name: Face the Facts
description: Start to the right of Jake said Ouch beneath a flake. Climb up the corner to a set of shared anchors with Jake said Ouch

name: Flatlander
description: Start with small crimps on a slabby face and move into a short vertical crack.

name: Jake Said Ouch
description: Some slightly tricky footwork near the bottom will get you to some larger holds and an easier finish.

name: Liberal Line
description: Starting near the tree work up the corner,then move right through the short crack section.

name: Metastable
description: Starting directly beneath the bolts move over the bulge on thin holds and climb through the overhang to chains.

name: Monolithic
description: Climb the overhung corner staying on the downhill face to a set of shared anchors with #3.

name: Slab-a-licious
description: A low crux on slabby face climbing leads through three bolts to shuts.

name: Campfire Direct
description: The obvious, usually chalked climb that is nicely overhung on phenomenally generous holds. Crux at the top (first part of climb to huge jug before left facing rail goes around +/- V2/3) like a mega-classic like this one should have.     Top rope through old shuts (careful now!) at the top or highball for fullest value.

name: The Chip
description: Found left of the chimney of the partially lichen covered wall. An easier crux makes this a nice introduction climb for someone new to the area. Start underneath flake, moving right around flake to ledge, to a nice finger crack crux. Easy finish to chains.

name: Steelworker
description: A tricky face climb that requires solid footwork and balance.

name: Taking It Easy
description: A slabby climb that requires some solid footwork. Obvious start at bottom, move left and follow bolts to a layback crux after second bolt with an easy finish to chains. Can easily be toproped with direct access to chains.

name: Darwin's Dilemma
description: Start off on the horizontal and move up and right through three bolts and a fixed pin. The crux is   after clipping the second bolt.

name: Flake Accesss
description: The easiest line up the Main Attraction which can be lead wiggle up the crack and face

name: I Just Can't Wait to be King
description: Stay on the face around the corner from Piton Crack. Thin holds, but its slabby. An easy route to the top of Main Attraction.

name: Levitation
description: A great route that follows the obvious line near the corner.

name: Piton Crack
description: Follow the crack up to the roof and keep your balance as you pass this crux. Nice trad line...

name: Power Play
description: Sit start low on the corner. Climb through 3 bolts and some sustained climbing to some chains.

name: Tree Line
description: Starts beneath the obvious large flake.Trend up and left following the left side of the flake.

name: Walking Wounded
description: Follow three bolts up a nice corner line to shuts. fairly sustained climbing.

name: End of the Pulpit
description: Climb the steep and aesthetic little arete towards "Lichen Wall."

name: The Shakes
description: Start down and left of obvious flake, climb straight up through tiny crimps to a "bomber top out."

name: Jigawatts
description: Sit start under the small roof on nice mini-jug, follow rail out to lip, and finish on the beautiful slightly overhung face.

name: The Lacoon
description: Sit start low and right. Move up and left around through some crimps and slopey rails. Top out straight over the middle.

name: Chipper
description: This route starts underneath the overhanging boulder just right of the Main Boulder. Move through some sharp crimps to good jugs through to the topout.

name: Dark Necessities
description: Sit down start on a good jug then move through a couple good crimps. Prepare your tendons for the quarter pad crimpy crux move with finicky feet then move into the jug before the bomber topout.

name: The General
description: This was the first route established at the Boone Run Crag. Located to the right of Uncle Phil it starts on a good jug then follows through a crimping seam, finishing on good jugs and a bomber ending hold. *this route does not top out

name: Ghost Monkey
description: Start on a sloping jug then move up and left on jugs to the same finish as The General.

name: Hump De Bump
description: On the front of the far right boulder this route starts low on an obvious jug. Move up and left till you’re on a good left hand crimp and a high right foot then bump through a series of nearly invisible sloping crimps to the sloping topout.

name: Parallel Universe
description: Start seated under the small roof with a triangle shaped undercling. Bump up into good crimps, bring the feet up then bear down on the half pad crimps before you can grab for the sloping rail. Ends on good jugs and an easy topout.

name: Raindance Maggie
description: Begin on the same start as Hump De Bump then move out right to a juggy ledge. Grab the two finger side pocket then bring your feet up high and lunge up to a good left hand before using the ending jugs to topout.

name: Scar Tissue
description: Start on the far right of the Ridge Line under the roof. Travel out the roof and up to the lip on a combination of good crimps and jugs. Move along the lip with plenty of toe and heel hooks to an obvious jug on the face that will take you to the topout.

name: Screamin Eagle
description: This is the left most problem on the Main Boulder, start on a pair of crimps with good feet then continue up the arete on good crimps to the sloping topout.

name: Seamstress
description: This route traverses the entirety of the Main Boulder. Start on the crimps of Screamin Eagle then move quickly across the beginning jugs to save energy for the cruxy crimpy middle section. Finish on a sloping rail to a jug finish.

name: Shaddow
description: Start down low on the back side of the Arete Boulder. Move through a series of crimps, jugs and mail slots to a semi sloppy topout.

name: Shindig
description: Start about chest height on good crimps then climb up the front face of the Arete Boulder to a semi sloppy topout.

name: Tit Toss
description: Start on the back side of the far right boulder. Go low under the small overhang and pull through a couple good jugs to an easy topout.

name: Triple Threat
description: Just left of Tit Toss this route also starts down low and moves up through good holds to a deadpoint finish.

name: Trust Fall
description: This route goes right up the center of the detached boulder. Start on a hidden but bomber undercling to a short series of crimps before you hike up the feet and make a throw for the topout.

name: Uncle Phil
description: Located about five feet to the right of Screamin Eagle this route starts on a low obvious jug. Move through a series of crimps and jugs to small slightly sloping finishing hold. *this route does not top out

name: Zepher
description: Just right of Dark Necessities on the Ridge Line this fun easy highball moves through a good series of jugs and ends with a nice topout.

name: Beginner route
description: Climb what remains of the left end and begins the corner of the right end.  “Crux” is visible from the ground. Gain ledge, easy sandy book stairs up to top. Small gear down low, could sling the chock up high but just walk it off instead

name: Camel Head
description: Ok, I admit I haven't climbed this route in a long time. Not that it's not a good route - it is. But it's mostly for a beginner and someone learning trad. Since I like the harder stuff and have a very limited trad rack, it's not my cup of coffee (I don't drink tea :)  The first half of the route is the 5.7 part, the second half is pretty much a cakewalk - literally. It's like walking up a tiered wedding cake! I would say it's even a Class 4. Once up and over the dihedral on the first half is where the cakewalk begins.  Oh, one thing fun about this climb is a rock feature at the lower half of the first half. It's a feature that resembles the upright stature of the male reproductive organ! :D  Don't let it distract you! Many a climber have handled it, hugged it, and even sat on it in order to ascend the route! Lol!

name: The Shield
description: Named for the feature near the bottom that resembles a shield, this climb, like the other ones here, is short but sweet. The “real” part of the route is basically a 25’ straight shot up to the top of the lower wall. After that you have an easy class 4 send to your top rope anchors. Note: To make this route official you need to engage the shield.

name: Damnation
description: After months of research and on-site consultations by veteran climbers, we’ve pretty much determined that this line is the famous line and namesake of this upper wall - Damnation. I write “pretty much” because with so much time passing since the ‘60s ‘70s era of climbing here, it's really hard to nail things down to an absolute. Yes, some routes are so well known and have been climbed so many times by the veterans that the names and locations are solid. This upper wall was less popular back in the day so also less remembered.The line here is pretty obvious as it runs up the vertical crack to the right of the bolted Shark’s Fin line. Follow this crack to a little dihedral with a tiny roof-like top. That area is most likely the crux as it’s a bit tricky. Once up above that, the next block is tricky too as you have to lean back to engage it, and like the bottom, it’s all overhung making for a potential pump fest.This route can go top rope or trad. If TR, you have anchors at the top but you’ll need to allow for the off-direct angle.

name: Pillar Front Face
description: I'm sure this has been climbed before but who knows when, it was pretty dirty, but a fun solo.Climb the front face of the (almost) freestanding pillar to the right of damnation. Start between the trees and the pillar, working your way up mostly good holds, about 8 feet from the top trend right around the corner to access a little ledge before stepping up to the summit. Not a lot of gear potential and currently no bolts.

name: Salvation
description: I just recently discovered the whereabouts of this classic ‘70s route! Part of the upper wall trifecta: Damnation, Salvation, and Loose Women (which has yet to be located/confirmed). ‘60s/’70s Donation climber Ken Decker verified this sweet line, and then only days after, my friend Alex led it on trad. He found it challenging but fun! Here’s his beta on the route “Work up the obvious easy crack to the small roof over a corner. Take advantage of bomber placements under the roof (pink or red tricam helpful) before moving out to the right. Layback the crack and make your way through the crux (a 0.2 cam offers peace of mind). Climb onto an awkward ledge, with good protection for the rest of the climb”.This route is a Donation-Must-Do. Try it on trad like Alex and imagine yourself (guys only of course) with a huge mustache, sideburns, tube socks, and if summertime, awkwardly short shorts! Oh the ‘70s...

name: Shark's Fin
description: Named for the awesome flake that sits out away from the wall about 20 feet up and looks just like a shark fin, this pumpy sport route runs up the face between Damnation and Salvation. It can also easily be done on top rope as those anchors are on top and easy to set up. Just take the trail up on the far left.Like Triple Play, this bolt line can service at least three route paths - left, direct, and right. I personally like to run all three but the classic line is direct and engages the Fin dead on. Do it direct first, lock on to the fin and pull hard and up to get set for bolt four. Get ready though, the next block is right in your face and no picnic. The ledge you'll be standing on is big enough to rest and shake out before you send to the anchors. Double hard clip into the Wave bolts and use the quicklinks at the ends of the chain for lowering. That way your belayer can make a run on top rope and clean the draws and be lowered, or you can pull the rope for the belayer to lead and lower. Nice and easy - no fuss no muss. This is important because this wall is really overhung making it difficult to clean draws on the way down.

name: Inside Corner
description: Climb the wide crack in the corner up to an awkward roof. Pull out of the roof into a smaller crack. Climb up onto a huge ledge. From here you can choose to make your way through a narrow chimney (very easy), or climb the face to the left (5.7 pg13).

name: Triple Play
description: I’m calling it Triple Play because it has three really nice route possibilities from one line of bolts. Because it has three lines, it has three starting points (rather than go into detail on that, consult the photo).  Now I know I’m not the first ascensionist - as the history reads, I’m a very late comer to this place. Who knows, Royal Robbins or Henry Barber most likely did this 45 years ago - Barber probably free soloed it - and hundreds have done it since including me! However, as a sport route, it’s new and I made sure to lead the three possible lines as soon as the glue cured!   Line 1: To the left and 5.9, takes on the beautiful arête. My personal rule on this route is that at least one extremity must be on opposite sides of the arête at any one time. Simply scale the arête, clipping right, pull the nose, stay on track and scoot right at the anchor and you’re done. Super fun!  Line 2: Direct and 5.8ish straight up the bolts. This is basically a face climb but you can easily grab the arête to the left for security if needed. It has small feet and hands between bolt 1 and 3 but after that you have better of both but it gets a little thin again on the upper big face. Stay true to the line and you’ll arrive dead on to the anchor.   Line 3: To the right and 5.9 runs the center of the lower face, clips left, pulls a nice little roof, and is a bit trickier than line 2 at the upper face. But just breathe, find your feet and keep moving. Grab the “goiter” (a big bulgy thing) with your right and scoot up left to the anchor. Very fun!  Lead all three in a row and you have a Grand Slam - Hat Trick if you’re a hockey fan like me! :)

name: TBD
description: !ATTENTION! There was unauthorized removal of the top rope anchors above this route (sport anchors are still there). Please Note: NO UNAUTHORIZED PLACEMENT OR REMOVAL OF FIXED HARDWARE IS PERMITTED AT DONATION ROCKS. Name is To Be Determined till I find out if there's an historical name.This is the second sport route here at Donation to accommodate beginning climbers - especially the young campers at Stone Mountain Adventures. This is why the bolts are placed within easy reach and from solid stance ledges. They are far apart but that’s because more are not needed due to the simplicity of the climb. The first bolt is easily reached by a short climb or stick clipped.For the beginner: The start is far right at the belay spot then up an easy 4 ft to a left shelf traverse. This gets you to the first bolt and then up to the big platform ledge at the base of an overhanging dihedral which is the crux. This is a bit tricky but the secret is feet - stemming between the opposing walls into small pockets. Hands are few so take what you can get. The second bolt is near the top of the crux and offers good protection from the platform ledge. Beyond that, it’s an easy walk up through the inside dihedral of the gully. Near the top there’s another shelf traverse to the upper left and voila, you’re at the anchors. They are big a$$ mussy hooks designed for super easy clip in and lowering without knowledge of anchor building or having to untie - clip clip and go.For the experienced: Start lower - closer to the big boulder, and once passed the first bolt and the crux, stay left of the gully and more on the face. Bolts will all be to your right.

name: Aurora
description: !ATTENTION! There was unauthorized removal of the anchors on the top face of this climb as well as above Spider Woman. There are a set of glue-ins over the top to use but you must carry the proper gear to do so. Please Note: NO UNAUTHORIZED PLACEMENT OR REMOVAL OF FIXED HARDWARE IS PERMITTED AT DONATION ROCKS.This route was originally a top rope listing by Kristin Waldkoenig in 2017. Since then it has become the second bolted route here at Donation and designed for the beginner sport climber. Bolts are many and close. Clipping stances are solid and accommodate shorter climbers. A great route to experience and gain confidence in sport climbing!Seven bolts to the anchors. The crux is getting up and over the slab next to the bigger of the two trees growing right out of the rock - between bolts five and six. Use the tree’s trunk at first if needed but aim to not use it eventually. Don’t go too far right on the slab though as it becomes much harder. Stay as direct as possible.

name: Triceps
description: !ATTENTION! There was unauthorized removal of the anchors above this route. Please Note: NO UNAUTHORIZED PLACEMENT OR REMOVAL OF FIXED HARDWARE IS PERMITTED AT DONATION ROCKS.Scramble up the easy beginning before making it to the obvious crack. Lay back to the left and watch out for hollow rock in the crack. There is an exposed tree root crossing the top of the crack. From the ledge above the root, climb on top of a small block and work your way up the ramp to the left.

name: Thin
description: This is where most newbies cut their climbing teeth and a route that’s been around since those high-cut gym shorts and tube sock wearing 70’s. An all time Donation classic! Thin offers you TR (top rope) as well as Trad (traditional). It’s a sweet little thin line up Africa Wall that you gotta do and will enjoy.  Start it wherever you like - some approaches are easier than others so test yourself and try a harder start each time. Anchors for this are on top of The Buttress and are the wide-set glue-ins to your left when on top. You will need two double length slings or a standard cordelette to make it out over the edge with your biners.

name: The Flake
description: I love this route! Especially now that it’s sport! Sure you can still top rope it but now you not only up your game, you eliminate the wicked swing if you come off. The 10+ rating is based on leading it. I would say it's more like 9+ on top rope fyi.  The main route is the same - sport or TR, the only real variation is at the start. When I was first doing this route I was instructed to go up the right side of the gully, up on a broad platform, then proceed to the skinny platform (what I like to call “the plank”) against the face. The problem is, that first platform gets super dirty because of debris washing down the gully. It’s dirties your hands and shoes. Not good for the next phase which happens to be the crux. I now start where the bolt line is and proceed up on clean rock avoiding the dirty platform altogether. This also sets me up to pull up and over the plank which I enjoy. Once on the plank, just spin around and get ready for the fun part!  Without getting too detailed, the premise of this section is to reach up to that diagonal flake (aka rail) above your head, and go hand-over-hand up it while working your feet between the face and the arête. The key to begin all this is mostly nerves. If you can let your mind go free and focus on the moves, you can release yourself from the plank and smoothly go into lay back mode and Git r Done. Pulling up to the last move to gain the top of this section is tough but you’ll figure it out. Hint: look for the awesome heal-hook on the arête near bolt five.  The next big phase could be considered a crux and is my favorite part - engaging and pulling the gigantic roof that looms over this entire bottom section. Again, I won’t go into detail so you can discover it for yourself, but there are holds above the roof that are bomber! After that, it’s a breeze to the anchors and a good stance while there. Here it’s best to run your rope through the bottom quick links and be lowered down or rap if you like.  Note: If you’re sport climbing, it’s best to use an extended draw at bolt seven to get your rope out from under the roof. Also this one’s really tough to clean on the descent. Have your second clean it on TR.

name: The Gully
description: Easy 4th/5th class gully. No real point in doing it on TR, but it's a fun place to practice short-roping, or could be a super low-key 1st trad lead. Also fills in nicely with snow and ice in winter, could be a fun, easy mixed climb?

name: High 5
description: This is basically a V5 boulder problem 25+ feet off the ground! Hence the name High 5. Only three bolts to the anchor but the first one is a test of nerves since it's not stick-clippable. If you're an experienced climber, getting there and clipping in is the easy part - after that it’s a completely different story! This is the sixth sport route at Donation and the hardest so far. And although it's a relatively short send to the anchors, because it's overhung and scarce on feet, it makes for a muscle and heart pumper for sure!  The grade is based on my 5' 6" frame and reach. You tall people might find it to be different and I ask that you please comment below if you do. I'm cool with a grade change if the consensus is something different.  Ground start off-belay with a scramble up to the huge ledge/platform at the base of the buttress. Once there, have your belayer at the ready and work up to the first bolt on the underside of the buttress. I get there by climbing the block to the right then left hand on the Screaming Mimi rail and clipping with my right. I recommend an 18cm/medium length draw here to come out of the slight roof but you can use shorties from there.  The anchors are quick-links and chains so once you're hard-clipped to the Wave bolts you just need to thread the quick-links, un-clip, and lower.  Back Story: Chris Winters of the Access Fund Conservation Team and I worked this one on top rope together in the fall of 2019 and it took both of us multiple times and lots of beta sharing to construct a doable path up this beast. I can still feel the excitement belaying Chris as he took my last suggested beta to successfully pull up and out of the crux. I gave out a rebel yell that could be heard all the way to the town of Huntingdon! We had finally unlocked the crux! Since then I’ve worked it, refined it, and added a couple new moves to better suit my smaller frame and reach. Regardless, I don't always make it and I'm always out of breath at the top. The FA on lead was a redpoint and my first .12 lead!!!

name: Magic Mushrooms
description: I had been eyeing this beautiful south face on The Buttress for some time looking for a path up. I could see these mushroom-like protrusions coming out of the smooth face but at the time I was not advanced enough to get to them so I looked for alternative routes. I came up with an approach that took me up and far right. Then, locking a foot into the huge crack at my feet, I reached far out to my left with both hands putting my body at a 45 degree angle. Now the scary part - cutting my anchoring foot loose and hoping I could hold on! After several tries I did and was then able to use one of the mushrooms for a foot and go from there! That was the crux for sure, but getting up, balanced, and completing the next moves to the top can be tricky for sure.  That was all on top rope. Now the route should be trad-able with a bolt on the main face and the use of a bolt from High 5. Plenty of gear placement opportunities from the ground up till you get to the crux. There is where you need to clip the draw and to be safe, clip into the other one then finish at the anchors and chains above (same as High 5).  For top rope: Either anchor off the top with cord or sling, or safety yourself into one of those anchors and use the quick links of the sport anchors.

name: Jam Crack Overhang
description: NOTE: My mind was recently blown when, in my research, I found that this classic route, formally known as Shark’s Tooth is actually named Jam Crack Overhang - climbed and named by guys back in the ‘70s! My plan in doing this historical research was to rename routes back to their original ones due to the long climbing history and to honor those who climbed here long ago. I must say that this iconic route was a tough one to rename so please forgive me of this seeming travesty. Now though, try and embrace the new/old name from a position of respect for those intrepid climbers - some who are now legendary icons in the climbing world! Seriously. Thanks.Since this was originally intended as a trad route, the line is up the obvious crack in the second layer block so the start is directly below. The lower block is a good mini warm up that works its way up to the overhung second block which gives this route part of its name. There you encounter protruding horizontal rock features that can be tough but offer great hands and stances. Once on top of those, you take the crux, the “Jam Crack”, straight on with hand jams or lay it back (which I find to be the most fun) to achieve the top of that block. Once there, the rest is a light challenging climb up the next two blocks to the top. Something to note: If you’re top roping, the anchors are to the right of the crux making for a good swing to the right if the climber comes off. Keep in mind, this is a classic trad route so bring your rack!

name: Keep On Truckin'
description: Note: For now drop your rope to the right of the tree below for a left side start at bottom.I’d like to say I discovered this new route but, according to my Oracle friend Mikey G, “There are no new routes at Donation''. So, given he’s right, let’s just say it’s a “reclaimed” route - probably from the '70s due to the amount of lichen all over it. And if it's a classic from the '70s, I named it after a classic image from then of a guy stepping out big and “truckin’” along (see photo). With crimps, cracks, good hands, solid feet and flowing moves, you're going to love it and... "truck" right up!The current start is to the left of the tree and a bit tricky, but with some cleaning work the right side should be an option too and should prove an easier start. From the left go up and around the backside of the tree and continue right to the vertical crack above (see photo) which is the crux for sure. Engage the crack and power up. Look for the baby pine tree (please don’t pull out), stay left of that, and continue up from there. The higher you go the better the hands and feet.This route has great potential for gear placement so will not be bolted for sport. You tradsters should love it! Also please brush or peel away any lichen you can as you send or lower. Thanks!

name: Calm On The Surface
description: Left hand starts on a small crimp, with the right hand on a far out pinch. Top out to the left, which is only 4-5 moves depending on beta.

name: Daytime Creeping
description: Start bunched up at the very left end. This problem is just a lip traverse, ending on the right side of the boulder.

name: Fairy Tale
description: Will update.

name: Handy Moss
description: Start is the crux, feet are very important. First move is up to pinch, then  up to sloped ledge, up to bread loaf, crappy crimp then up to obvious two finger "pocket" surrounded by moss and traverse on side of boulder up to the very top. DO NOT use rocks beside the boulder or obvious large ledge on boulder for your feet.

name: Ice World
description: Utilizing the same jug start as "Moncler Coat," this problem slaps out left for a few very slopey moves. Not sure of difficulty since I haven't been able to do it.

name: Moncler Coat
description: Start on the underside with both hands on a well chalked jug. Slap out right to the ticked hold, and the continue up the right side of the boulder. The crux for me is the top out.

name: My Heart
description: Start bunched up with both hands on the slopey lip to the far right of the boulder, and traverse leftward. Very fun problem with interesting beta options.

name: Off the Radar
description: Start matched down low and shoot out right. Crux is the first few moves, the upper part is juggy but very fun (with a rocky landing).

name: One Your God Chose
description: Start far to the left, traversing right. Avoid dabbing on the protruding rock about halfway through, then top out to the right after the big deadpoint.

name: Popping Out Of Nothing
description: Start low with a left hand side pull and right hand on the sharp crimp on the underside of the boulder. I topout to the left, using a knee bar to reach the upper pinch.

name: Rose Bud
description: Extremely low start inside the cave with a solid left hand and small, slopey right hand. Traverse right across the whole bottom of the boulder until you reach the good edge at the far end, then there's a big move to the top of the formation before topping out.

name: The Celery Roof
description: Start under the roof, right hand around the bulge, big move left out to a pocket where the bulge meets the left feature, then right hand around to a pinch, hold the swing, then up to the slopers at the lip of the bulge and match.  Top out with high left foot.

name: Something Bad’s about to happen
description: Start under a roof on a good crimp or jug if you can reach. Get a sneaky heel hook and move up the arete to a dropper.  Move up the face to a far away jug. Traverse right on jugs and some slopers.  Top out to the right.  I’m not sure if this was a first accent but a lot of holds broke. Let me know if it’s been done.

name: Asana
description: Sit start low on the sharp juggy pockets on the right side of the cave with feet pointing out of the cave. Bump up to the next pocket, then make the long dynamic throw to another pocket near the top edge (this may be near a full dyno for very short climbers). Get well established on the pocket than traverse the slopey (and dirty) lip to the right to exit the cave. Getting around the corner is a tricky balancing act.

name: Glass Hovercraft
description: Low to the ground, long lip traverse on rock sharper than most of hunters due to coarse crystals. Start with your but basically on a rock near the back, hands on the obvious rail and a heel and toe further back on a good (but sharp) lip rail. Work hands along the rail and get creative with heels and toes to not come off. Before you reach the end, swing feet under and around and move hands on good holds up the face and work for a mantle topout. This would be a 4 star climb if not for the sharp quality of the rock.   Note: The top of this thing has its own microecosystem of ferns, moss, and lichen so if cleaning please leave the topout alone and take off as little vegetation as necessary. Once you're standing on the end of this thing the climbing is really over and a true topout is a mossy slippery sketch fest.

name: Gold Dust
description: This fat flake is smattered with iron deposits, thus the name. Sit start as low as is reasonable and walk your hands up the arete/flake edge. Use heels on the left and smeary feet on the right to work for an awkward topout.

name: Goth Girl
description: Start far back in the cave containing Troglodyte Exit and Asana on a rail on the left side (same as troglodyte exit) and traverse out to the left on rails and slopers. Topout via the same "skylight" as Troglodyte Exit.

name: Grab the Throne
description: This route begins on the opposite side of the same boulder that "rho" is on. It lies directly behind a tree which makes protecting it difficult, but it is not a difficult route and you can stem with your back on the tree if you panic and need to get down. Work up through juggy sidepulls and topout at the tallest corner of the boulder. Take a moment to sit in the natural saddle or "throne" at the top corner and take in the nature. Have a spotter move the pad for a drop off or straddle the corner and slide your way down bit by bit.

name: Hemophilia
description: Follow the iron band crimps from left to right in a laidback traverse until you can reach up to a couple surprisingly good mono pockets. Do a dynamic throw to the juggy seam on the tip of of the boulder then work for the topout.

name: Horizontal
description: Haven't even tried to pull onto this thing so I'm not going to assume how it goes. Its an entirely horizontal roof a couple feet off the ground only featured underneath with tiny pockets and crimp edges.

name: The Opposition
description: Use deep juicy pockets on the arete for hands and oppose the force by pressing into the face with your feet. The pocket on the face is off. Great easy route, toupout is a bit dirty but that's Hunter's for you

name: The Prower
description: Start deep underneath this overhanging beast with one hand on each side, work out to the front on pockets, than through a cruxy crimp section to gain a juggy pocket on the tip. Campus up a couple moves on jugs to topout. Be careful of a hollow wiggly block at the start, it can probably hold body weight but don't pull too hard.

name: Rho
description: Balancey and Slabby climb different than the rest of the garden. Sit start with hands on obvious jugs at about hip height (be wary of pulling outward on these holds very much, some of the edge has already started breaking off), and pull up to work through crimps and pockets for a classic Hunter's topout (slopey and mossy).

name: Scraping By
description: The crux is not scraping yourself on the rock in the landing if you fall. Easily protectable with a pad and yoga mat though. Start low in the back to the right. The deep hueco is where your feet start. Traverse up and left on pockets, crimps, and slopers, then go up for the deep seam and hueco and step off to the right to "top out" and avoid the forest of moss and ferns on the proper top out.

name: Seeing Red
description: Start low on the juggy right facing flake, and work your way up, using an undercling and jug on an iron plate halfway up. Be prepared for a classic slopey insecure Hunter's topout.

name: The Troglodyte Exit
description: Start in the crack and work you're way up and out the "skylight" at the top of the cave. It has been cleaned but because of the nature of the skylight and the slope above it will soon refill with sticks, leave, and debris. There is a length of cordage fixed to a small tree to the right of the topout to assist with getting down as the rock is steep and slippery.

name: American Pansy
description: Start same as S.A.A. Left foot up to small knob and throw left hand up left to sloper/dish (below Incredarete), match left heel to sloper and bump left hand sloper sidepull (optional: go again left to really sandy handlebar hold one foot above), right hand to sloper in the middle of the S.A.A. topout...topout as S.A.A. This is a really fun eliminate problem.

name: Cockblock
description: Stand start on the right arete with a high right-hand undercling and a left-hand crimp on the face of the wall. Climb all the way to the top using pockets, gastons, and slopers.  Top out at highest point on boulder.    Fair warning: This boulder problem is tall and scary at the top.

name: Daughter of an Offwidth
description: Originally sent with only the right climbing shoe on. Its the second "crack" to the right of vedauwoo dropout. Start on wide hands and fists and work up to off width,

name: Garage Door
description: Pull off high holds at the lip and continue over steep rock to the top. I threw a massive reverse flag to the horizontal, but you can be more static if lame is your game.

name: Hillside Attraction
description: A fun arete and face climb.    Sit start on a good left hand pinch and right on the arete, pick some feet at toss right hand up to a unique pinch on the arete. Then toss out left to the jug in the middle of the face and top out up and left.

name: The Horsepens Boulder
description: Sit start at the middle of the sideways 'y' formation, left hand on the shelf-like hold, climb up and work left up the sloping face, walking your feet over on the rail below.    (v3 variation: start matched on the crimp below the 'y' formation.)

name: Incredarete
description: Start on pockets on the left arete (sit start optional).  Move up the arete using pinches and slopers.  The crux is at the crest of the overhang.  Topout is tall, but juggy.

name: Levitation Complication
description: Start low on Incredarete at obvious break/jug, long reach right to rounded small crimp with bite, cross left hand to the round pocket (the start of Standard American Accent), right hand to break in middle of boulder below the Standard American Accent sidepull pocket, square up feet, right hand up to sidepull pocket, finish as S.A.A..

name: MDSF
description: start on two pocket and a big throw to a rail, then work the rail and stand up to grab big jug and high topout..

name: mickey's 40 throw
description: on the way to mushroom tattoo... just as you start down the backside of the hill... veer right and find the egg like boulder with a great jug start... throw for the top... to the left of the start you can see some highballs... that face downhill towards the road..

name: Mr. Grumpers
description: Climb the slabby left side of the boulder - to the left of Incredarete.  This might be a bit mossy - it doesn't get climbed very often.

name: Mushroom Mantle
description: Sit start below the mushroom shape roof, climb up through the hueco's to a good hold on the lip of the roof. Now work up to a sloper and mantle over to the top.

name: Mushroom Tattoo
description: Stand start right hand at the brown hold at head height, left near the tree up high.  Slap and bearhug your way up sidepull slopers and muffin crimps to the top. The topout is easier than the beginning and middle sections, but the consequences of screwing it up are much higher. More like V5 if taller and conditions make a big difference on this one.

name: petunia
description: traverse the lip of the cave just down hill from incredarete...left to right. step off when you can.

name: resin run
description: walk through the cave below the mojo... large wall on the right... traverse from left to right... can end on teraplata (v4) on the uphill side of the cave.

name: Saddle Burr
description: Climb obvious face, steep but juggy. Topout is pretty tall and not quite as easy as the rest of the climbing.

name: skin flick
description: small boulder behind resin run... start on two crimps low and under the overhang, throw right to a crimp and work the lip of the boulder till you can grab the pinches under the point of the overhang... then throw for the lip

name: Son of an Offwidth
description: Start in the gulley to the immediate right of Vedauwoo Dropout. Walk/shimmy your way up. Unfortunately the crux comes at the very top of this thing where it narrows considerably. Throw a pad down if you like but because this thing goes so far IN as it goes UP, the worst of a fall will likely not be protected by pad. A bit contrived maybe, but good fun and a stiff test of your mental game. Do best not to hang on the tree.

name: Standard American Accent
description: Most Popular version (v7): Stand start (may need to stack pads for shorter climbers to reach the starting holds), left in obvious round pocket out left, right in sidepull pocket, right heel up and cross left hand to crimp, top out straight up.     Original start (v8-9): stand start in the middle of the overhanging boulder, left hand in break, right directly above in sidepull pocket, right foot up, cross left hand to crimp...helps to be really strong, really flexible, and shorter for this variation. Can also start matched in the break for added difficulty, but this makes one feel like a human cork screw and it is very seldom sent this way.

name: The Sweet Arete
description: Highball arete that faces the firepit clearing up the hill from Standard American Accent

name: terraplata
description: just down hill from the mojo.... the right hand wall just before you walk through the cave... highball... good finish for resin run.

name: Vedawuoo Dropout
description: Tape up, wear long sleeves, and prepare to do battle with some off width. The crux is getting off the ground up the first ~6 feet of the crack until you're secure. Then get ready for the inch by inch wiggle/struggle fest to finish. Super quality rock and climbing very unique for Hunter's.

name: Verbing
description: Verbing, v6: This problem was a v4 before a crucial hold broke.  Same start as Cockblock. Climb until you can traverse left to the good crimp on Standard American Accent... top out the same as S.A.A.

name: Welcome to Hunters
description: A neat little problem that's quite different from the standard Hunters fare.  Start on the obvious start hold with bad feet, move to the horizontal crack, traverse right, and top it out.  Fairly blank rock on this one.

name: Wonderbread
description: Start right hand just above head hight on crimp near right side of boulder.  Left hand on either of the slanting side pulls.  Smear right foot on high, throw left hand high to the pinch above.  Slap up the boulder with your right hand (avoiding the boulder to the right) and work your way to the jug to top out.

name: Civil Disobedience
description: Start low on nubby holds with feet in the big hueco. Slap up to get good hands and maybe a heel up as well. Climb up and top out. Not to tricky.

name: Disobedient Arete
description: Start on the obvious sloper on the arete left of civil disobedience.Workup through sidepulls for a slopey insecure topout.

name: The Forest Child
description: Start with arms stretched around opposite sides of the roof each near the lip, heel up on the right side. Do best not to dab on the "cheater blocks" at the bottom for full value. Bump each hand to get secure holds and then swing feet up into the perfectly sized horizontal crack for a bat hang. Get your hand sup to your feet and then muscle around for a slopey topout.

name: Sit and Reach
description: Left side of the face of the boulder. Start standing at the large surfboard-like rail at chest height. With your left hand on a flat crimp, step up and grab a smallish sidepull with your right hand. Top out straight up using the slopers above.

name: Tremble and Reach
description: Sit start as The Tremblings and traverse boulder from right to left.  Step off after rounding the arete or continue up through the corridor for some sketchy fun!

name: The Trembling
description: Start sitting, matched in the obvious jug on the right side of the face. Climb up and just to the left of the 'bulge' feature.  Top out using flat slopers above the bulge.  Yes you have to go all the way to to the top of the boulder.  It's worth it!

name: Agape
description: At the far end of the boulder, start sitting with your right hand in an undercling bucket, left on whatever works.  Move up left to a small but good edge, up right to a sidepull pinch, then left into a two-finger "bullet hole" pocket, then right hand under-cling pinch. Avoid the crack leading up the boulder on your right (the jug holds). Move up left through a good sidepull pocket and a small right hand sidepull before topping out just above a small boulder (perched on the stone slope).  Technically an eliminate but a good one.  The v7 version of this line was the original version before the good pocket high and left was discovered and cleaned.  Very few people climb the line this way now, but if you feel like a taste of the past feel free to avoid the good pocket before the topout.

name: Agathon
description: Start in crack on the opposite side of the boulder than the topout of the Hunger Artist, throw left to tiny edges to head underneath the boulder, then follow holds staying tight as to not dab on the boulder underneath you as you keep to the side of the boulder with the rock underneath you (stay to the right of the hueco jug for the original variation of this climb) and head to slopers and a slopey mantle topout (same topout as Hunger Artist).  Large dab factor present at all times on this climb.

name: Alcoholic Recovery (aka Recovery Cave)
description: Start low in the cave, with an uncomfortable rock basically right under your butt.  Start on the large chalked hold right in front of your face and head up and slightly left.  Move out left to a pinch, right up to a sloper, left to a diagonal slot, right to a diagonal crimp rail, left to a crimp above that, and up to a jug and top out.

name: Baby Boi
description: Start low on good holds and follow them up the little pinnacle.

name: Beer Milkshake
description: Highball. Stand start to the left of Electric Arete - starting holds at ~7 feet up.  Climb the face to the left of the arete, up and near the top head right, topout using the arete.

name: black snake boogie
description: to the right of agape...

name: Blockhead Traverse
description: Start pinching low on the corner, work up the arete until you can reach to the huecos on the left face. Follow the diagonal line of huecos up and left to an uncomfortable insecure topout. No easy way down off of this one, best to put pads near the end of the climb for a controlled drop off the top after.

name: Calathon
description: Start as for Agathon but climb up and right, staying left of the crack (eliminate), topout  straight up face. Fun problem.

name: Coral or Quarrel?
description: The interesting small overhanging quartzite face to the left of Looks Like a Turtle. Start on the obvious juggy edge at the bottom. Pull up to a crimp, then throw for a high right crimp. search for hold to manage the top out.

name: Curse A Real Sword
description: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wlc6KlHOIkA https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SaWaZq9dTKMStart on the obvious orange rail in the cave, with feet in the horizontal roof out left. I moved right hand up to sloping nub. A hard heel on the rail and toe scum in the roof marks the crux (for me) to a left had crimp. From there opposing gastons to sloper pinches up and left. Give it a go and let me know what you think, I hate grading routes. I did not use the detached boulder at the start in the cave.........The first video is not the beta, the second video is

name: Electric Arete
description: Highball.  Sit start under the large arete directly in the power cut on the right side.  Climb out from under the "roof" section and up the arete of the boulder.  Highball but great holds.

name: The First Church of Appliantology
description: The main line on the Church boulder - starting on the Southern side of the boulder (the side closest to the road and the powercut) - sit start left hand on a 2-3 finger pocket and right on a bucket. Left toe and Right heel hook, move right up to an ok pinch, big(ish) move left to a bad pocket-edge/gaston formation, match, then follow pockets left and around the corner until the large diagonal crack on the west face, topout. The last moves are eliminates and also the crux.

name: The First Will Be Last
description: Extension which adds ~12 moves that climb into The First Church of Appliantology. Power-endurance traverse...more like a route than a problem...should feel about 5.12c/d  depending on your beta. Start on the Eastern (most downhill) side of the boulder on the far right.  Traverses left and around the corner into the 3rd move of The First Church, then continues to the same eliminate topout.

name: Glorious Holes
description: Start far left and low on a bowling ball sloper jug. traverse to the right across the openings in the rocks until you gain the ledge at the top of the Wave boulder. Optional R rated v1 finish to the top of the spire part.

name: Golf Girl
description: Climb up the right side of the face of the rib cage boulder.

name: Hunger Artist Stand
description: Start from the hueco jug of Hunger Artist and finish as normal.  Awesome movement, but a bit short.

name: The Hunger Artist
description: Most obvious problem on the boulder...start on crack/break under the large suspended boulder (same as Agathon), left hand to a small gnarly pinch and right hand to a good but small incut crimp, long right hand move to shallow pinch then the crux - go again to hueco. Or throw from pinch & crimp to hueco...avoiding the dab is the crux this way. Slopers and/or dishes to the mantle top out (same as Agathon).

name: Induction
description: An overhanging, long, easy, lowball, classic climb. Start on the juggy rails under Electric Arete. Traverse up and right following the line of holds, then reach up and left to a full hand hueco. Finisher move and crux is throwing for a slopey edge with a seam in the back. Match and manage the weird topout.

name: Leaving the Den
description: Start low on the iron plated huecos, and work up the line that follows the "gulley" in the rock. Slopey weird scary topout, but a clean fall until you really commit to pulling over the bulge...then don't fall.

name: Looks Like a Turtle
description: This boulder is low enough to the ground that you can go padless if you want. Start low and to the right with your feet and legs under the boulder. traverse left and eventually swing a heel around the corner. Getting up can be a struggle but work on it.

name: Low Risk
description: Sit start on a good pinch and go up. Pretty straightforward for this one.

name: Lowering the Bar
description: Start matched on the obvious undercling on the lower left corner of the arete. Bump left hand up to the arete with the thumb catch pocket. Reach into the slopey underside of the arete to find a decent crimp/sidepull. Bring your right foot the the protruding corner of the underside of the boulder and secure a knee bar, then use pockets/sidepulls and the arete to pull up and top out.

name: Magnetism
description: Start on the obvious yellowish jug/pocket. Go up for a move or two and then traverse left on pockets. Pull up to a crimp or slopey jug to gain the face of the climb. Drop off or step off the boulder to the side if you don't want the top out be warned it is a very tall topout and a serious no fall zone. Its dirty and sandy up there as well. A classic climb just be careful.

name: Mariarete
description: Climb up the right tilting slightly bulged arete. Start with hands all the way at the bottom. get creative with toes and heels on the arete to prevent swinging off the first move or two. Fairly easy topout.

name: Mehrete
description: The overhanging left corner of the ribcage boulder. Start on a sidepull at waist height and work up through more sidepulls and pockets.

name: MiniTraverse
description: Easy low to the ground boulder. Beta: Route itself has a "crux" reaching around the rock to a right hand that is marked with an "x" in the photos. I wedged my heel into the crack on the side. Topout is flat and awkward but very do-able. Other people have definitely climbed this before (Theres youtube videos of people doing different routes) but there's probably an extra 100 routes at hunters not posted yet, so post away.

name: Repulsion
description: Start matched on the slopey rail down low. The crux is pulling off the ground through the first 3 moves. Finding tiny feet is important to not dabbing the start. The end lets up a bit in difficulty but is not trivial.

name: Ribcage Boulder
description: This is a large boulder face with many routes up, all of them between V0 and V2.

name: Seaweed
description: One move wonder. Start low and right on the the boulder with feet underneath. work hands left along the rail. Put a toe or heal near the start hold, then mantle and lunge hard for a pocket edge. Top out.

name: Shibby
description: A fun problem to warm up on or if climbing solo.  Start on the obvious jug, feet scrunched up on the shelf close to the ground.  If you're feeling spry, you can start on some crimps even lower and feet spread out, bumping this to a V2/2+.

name: Streussel
description: Start with the same to moves as "lowering the bar" then use the arete to turn yourself over and grab a pocket on the face. Easy finish to topout, but watch for crumbly rock. Knee bar shelf is off.

name: The Three Amigos
description: Those three stacked bulges...climb them. Use slopers and edges to pull through the awkwardness.

name: Trevor's Traverse
description: Start to the right of The First Will Be Last, traverse right to the good face at the top of the 'hill.'

name: triangle roof
description: from the top of the hill at the power cut, walk right past two formations to the warm up boulder with the nice start rail on the right... below this on the down hill side facing the road... climb up the overhang on the right side....

name: Un named v6
description: The line starts underneath the boulder in the cave. Two hand start on an undercling, go left hand to a perfect shallow pinch and work upwards trying not to dab on the boulder at your back. This line exits on the right side of the boulder, there is a line that starts on the same hold and goes left, likely V10. Skeptical of if either have been climbed, due to how frail most of the rock was underneath. Took a long time to clean off broken/loose rock from very obvious holds. Please let me know if they have been climbed prior. Both are great lines.

name: Wave Center
description: Start the same as wave left but blast up through the center for a slightly easier topout.

name: Wave Left
description: Start low on jugs and traverse left before going up avoiding the worst of the overhanging curve.

name: Wave Right
description: Start the same as the other wave problems but stay along the right arete throwing to good pocket edges, than manage an absolutely ruinously slopey topout

name: Welcome to the Powercut
description: Nice lowball for the timid virgin outdoor climber. start on the nice flat starting hold and bump hands up onto slopey crimpy edges. Not bad but not worth spending lots of time on.

name: You Into This
description: Start on two underclings and toe hooks, bop out to the large pinch then to a small hold on the lip and top out over the scary slab. Another Randy Burks problem and an eliminate...if you see him ask about the name....

name: Blood orchid
description: down with sand castles sit or stand start off the platform... stand starts on a couple pockets... to another pocket for the right... reach high for the flat ledge... highball topout..

name: The Ear
description: Start low on the ground on the right side of the steep over hanging cave. Traverse to up and left towards the center of the over hand, make a big right hand move to a crip rail. Cross left to a shark tooth. God speed on the top out. Make sure it's clean up there.

name: knob gobblin
description: down hill from the mojo... start under the uphill side of large boulder that forms the cave... traverse out the overhang and up the far side of the boulder...

name: Mojo
description: start under roof and out the lip on bucks then up-up-and away.

name: project
description: traverse left from sand castles, throw high for a drop in pocket and work the slopers for grim topout.

name: smaller than your momma
description: large face just down hill of resin run just above the river boulder... left side, highball above slab...

name: something i didn't name...
description: under the sugar cube... right side start crossed on a sloper just under the right most jugs... throw for a flat crimper then throw for the jug... topout same as sugar cube..

name: High Noon Sit Start
description: The High Noon boulder sits next to a waterfall in a tranquil setting. This is the only boulder found in this area (plenty in Rock Run as a whole) but it is worth visiting due to the setting and that the boulder has 5 distinct climbs on it. Perfect for a mid-day retreat. Climb and have lunch next to the waterfall!    The crux to the sit start is the 2nd/3rd move. After repositioning higher up on the starting left hand rail make a big move to a sharp jug with the right hand. From here make another large move with the left hand to the arête (sidepull). Reposition feet, drop the right hand into the sidepull closer to the middle of the climb and move on through the stand start up obvious features.    The setting is great, the climb is fun, but the starting foot is high and the second food is a bit polished.     I feel it is a v5 or v5+ (I've seen v6 for the sit on other sites as well as v4+). I give it this rating because I struggled with the high foot for the start. A more flexible person may rate it lower. A long reach helps. Regardless, it is a very fun climb in a setting not often seen in PA.

name: Unknown Soldier
description: One fun move then the top out. Stand start using a polished crimp and the obvious rail, "pop" to the nice lip then mantle it up and out.

name: Captain Howdy
description: SDS on a obvious flake and make a big, super fun move to the lip then top it out.

name: White Spider
description: Stand start on the arête and move diagonally right through not many features to the nice juggy rail and the top out.

name: Human Pony Girl
description: Start on an under cling and a good crimp, climb straight up.

name: Mother Earth
description: Around the corner right of the main face of the Heavy Petting Zoo Boulder (if the main face is roughly East then this would be the North face)is an obvious seam that runs the length of the face; traverse this seam right to left.     Slab and usually dirty but fun!

name: Punks that Purge
description: Using the same start as Human Pony Girl (under cling and crimp), move up and over to a solid pocket out right then to the top out.

name: Pursuit of Insanity
description: In my opinion the hardest line at rock run. Start with right hand on a very small and sharp crimp, left hand on a barely usable tiny edge. Paste your foot on the slopey, glassy foot and try to pull through to the half decent edge out left. Continue up and right to top at the highest point on the boulder.  Video of the FA: https://vimeo.com/243213836

name: Unicorn Princess
description: Sit start same as wailing wall sit. Climb into the stand start and then finish as human pony girl. See this video of Wailing wall sit to see the starting position: vimeo.com/243213836

name: Wailing Wall
description: Starting on solid crimps (one is two fingered) move up to a pinch and then the top out

name: Wailing wall SDS
description: In my opinion this is the best route at rock run. Nice holds and very interesting and cool movement. Video beta: https://vimeo.com/243213836  Sit start on two not very obvious crimps (see video for clarification) with a pretty good foot. Climb into the stand start and then go out left to a super cool pinch and top as the stand.   The first ascent was done by matching the first hold you go to (the better of the two crimps used for the stand start). I did it with some rose move beta that improved the quality for me, but also forces you to stray slightly off route. Both methods seem about the same grade.

name: Crowbar
description: Start on the lip and traverse across to a nice jug then mantle it out.

name: Mosquito
description: On the Northeast side of the boulder. Sit start and climb the arete.

name: Tuxedo
description: SDS utilizing a wonderful gaston and nice crimp, pop out to a nice sloper on the arête then mantle it out.

name: West Nile Virus
description: A couple of cool moves to the topout.

name: Glass Slipper
description: SDS on the right side rising edge and a side pull. Use the arête and a solid crimp to the top out.

name: Achilles Heel
description: Start with left hand on the arete, right hand on a slopey dish/pocket. Paste your right foot on a very bad pebble, and throw a left heel around the arete. Make a couple tricky/desperate moves to gain the lip and then the easy top out. Feels like gritstone arete climbing.   A sit start just down and left is feasible but would be heinously hard and probably not great quality. Could be in the v13 range?

name: Bad Voodoo
description: Start at the obvious flake and climb up and right utilizing a few pockets to get up to a sloper and top out.

name: Velociraptor
description: Climb the arete left of the Wave

name: Wave
description: Start at the obvious flake and move up and left to several pockets and slopers to the top out.

name: Unknown Cliff-1
description: Stand start with hands on the vagina looking feature, move up through nice crimps then make one pretty freakin big move to the lip/horizontal. Make one move to the lip of the small roof then mantle it out.     The dyno and top out are exciting for sure!

name: Unknown Cliff-2
description: Stand start on the arete, using features on both faces take the arete to its top, traverse to Unknown Cliff-1's top out through the tiny roof.

name: Unknown Cliff-3
description: Start on the horizontal under the roof, make one big move to a jug out on the face, then a little big move to the lip up right and the mantle top out.    Super fun problem, just short.

name: Unknown Cliff-4
description: Sit start back of the roof matching hands on a jug, make one move to a tiny seam above you and set up for a big move out onto the face. From this obvious jug/hole traverse the lip out left through some positive holds, then move vertically through a couple of crimps to the top.

name: Unknown A-1
description: A really fun problem! Some more powerful climbing down low, then some delicate climbing up high on a beautiful arete.     Sit start on a really nice jug, climb out the obvious rail to the lip, then move out onto the face and the wonderful arete. Take the arete to the top.     On the right side of the arete, just above the lip there is a nice slanting rail to help.

name: Unknown A-2
description: Sit start on a big rail, make one move to the horizontal crack out left then make one somewhat big move to the lip and the mantle top out.

name: Witch Doctor
description: Sit start matching hands on a nice rail, move into a nice crimp then a somewhat big move to a really awesome (and distinctive) jug. Using the arete out right climb to the top.     The first three or so moves are money for sure, fun problem.

name: Unknown B-1
description: Sit start using a two finger pocket and crimp, climb the thin seam to the horizontal cracks. At this point most climb/jump down.    If you do take it to the top through cruiser but dirty terrain, the down climb is on the blocky holds/feature about 10 ft right of this problem. Be careful.

name: Unknown D-1
description: Sit start at the very bottom of the arete on the lip, move up the arete and onto the face, using positive rails and crimps take it straight up then diagnol left to the top out.

name: Unknown D-2
description: Sit or stand start and climb the obvious corner crack to the top.

name: Diamonds in the Rough
description: Start matching hands on the obvious seam in the back of the roof, move out the seam to some jugs and the big finish.    A really nice roof for the area and some solid stone for sure, very beautiful!

name: If 6 was 9
description: Slightly overhanging for the first move then a slab top. Sit start matching hands on a horizontal rail, move up to a positive hold just above the lip and start up the slab top. Crimps, side pulls and pinches on the slab with good feet (some smearing, some features).

name: Red House
description: One fun dynamic move. Stand start using the obvious right facing side pull/flake, pop to the nubbin then match. That's it, no top out; just the dyno.

name: Voodoo Child
description: Sit starting on/in a horizontal crack, move up through a really nice side pull crimp making a big move to a juggy sloper at the lip. Match.  There is a slabby top out that hasn't been done yet.

name: Approach Shoe Lip Traverse
description: Start at the beginning of the crack, heel hooking and campusing use the crack to its end then follow the juggy, lichen covered but still good lip around. Drop off whenever the jugs end.    A good warm-up that is a tradition to do in your approach shoes.

name: Hello Boulder
description: Right hand starts on a pocket ledge at the roof of the cave, left starts in a pocket ledge just above and left of the right start. Both hands then go to the big slopery ledge. Big move for the left hand out to a small crimp and then bump it to a pocket right above it. Right hand to a full pad pocket and left up to a big ledge under an overhang diagonally left of the right hand. Right hand to a sloper ledge diagonally right of the left hand. Match on a big crimp ledge right above the right hand to finish.

name: Black Madonna
description: Left hand starts on a crimp along the bottom ledge, right hand on a pad and a half crimp a bit higher up. Left hand bumps to a big slanted ledge and right hand further down the ledge. Left hand crosses over to a half pad crimpy pocket and right hand moves to the top of the arete, then top out

name: Pride Rock
description: Left hand starts on a half pad ledge on the left side of the arete, right hand starts in a pocket sloper just above the left hand. Right hand goes to the big sloper ledge. Left hand to a pocket crimp and right hand to a sloper under a small overhang. Left hand to a pocket and then top out

name: Silverback
description: Both hands start on a sloper ledge below a small overhang. Left hand crimps on the raised bump of the ledge on the left side of the large pocket in the middle of the boulder. Right hand to the L shaped pocket. Left hand to a small pocket and right hand to the top for the top out.

name: Zebra Block
description: Left hand starts on a 3 finger pocket and the right starts on a sloper ledge-pocket. Left hand bumps up to a pocket and the right hand goes to a small slopery ledge. Left hand goes to a half pad crimp. Right nad to the top and top out.

name: Jaraiya
description: Sit start at the crimp slot make the move out and then right to gain some good holds, do some foot work to gain the slower jug that feels like a nice boob.give it a gentle squeeze and put some loving on that top out...named after the Pervy Sage.

name: Jonin
description: Sit start on the first problem you see as you walk up hill? Yep. Great little warm up on cool holds, top out is a little sloppy but there are some holes up there.

name: Yellow Flash
description: Sit start in the crimp slot and make a big move straight back to the ledge, cruise out left along the ledge and gain the arete, that’s where your pump shows, make a couple good slaps to the top.

name: Bear Trap (stand)
description: Stand start at the arete for Bear trap low on good holds and cruise up the arete.

name: Bear Trap Low
description: Get your ass down in that whole, watch out for bear traps now...but seriously....then get ready to slap some sharp rock. Start on the horn, slap out right to the crimps on the face and then gain the arete and cruise out of there. Super fun, but beta intensive.

name: Heart of Darkness
description: Get ready to earn the grade. Start the same as bear trap low and work directly out to the face through some heinous crimps...have fun with that.

name: Alf
description: Starting all the way right use some heel hooks and good jugs to gain the ledge by the tree and top out the same as Gnome. All disconnected feet are off...

name: Bear Grylls
description: Start the same as Gnome but traverse right by throwing out to a pinch with a big lay back with the left hand, a hard hand-foot match and tighten the core to swing out to the jug with your right hand. Tops out on Elf...super tough for a moderate.

name: Bootstrap
description: Start on a great jug of the left side of the roof. Gain the crack and traverse right to the top out.

name: Elf
description: This is a real dirt burglar, start all the way to through of the gnome block left hand on jug, right on a side pull with a heel hook. Climb straight up.

name: Gnome
description: SDS on a couple good holds under the roof. Climb up to an easy topout.

name: Big Kids Meal
description: SDS on the spike at the back of the roof. Climb up and (right) out from under roof to finish on Happy Meal (V3).

name: Happy Meal
description: SDS on good edges, climb up and left to the top out.

name: Royale With Cheese
description: SDS on the Spike at the back of the roof. Climb up and out of the roof left via an undercling to a jug and top out at the center of the roof. (Pa bouldering Description)

name: Death to America
description: Stand start on the rail to the right of the tree over Woman King. Proceed to bump right, either campusing or trying to keep your toes on Woman kings rail. Heel hook and make few more hand bums until you can mantel onto the bloc.

name: Kaah Powww!
description: SDS on the jug to the left of a tree. Climb up and slightly left to an enjoyable topout.

name: Thin Mints
description: Makes a great warm-up for other problems on this bloc. Stand start on a good edge and go up. Classic!

name: Woman King
description: Start under the roof at the left end of a good rail. Make your way right until the roof ends at a small arete. Swing over onto the face and top out via good horizontals. Mega-classic for the area and a bit stiffer than its neighbouring V3's, making a test piece for the grade.

name: Hard Carbon
description: climb the easy face on the right side of Carbon boulder (described in the boulderingpa.com guide under the area Carbon Run).

name: squeek
description: thuggy boulder  that starts from a sit start on the arrete of a small overhanging boulder.

name: Bail Bondsman
description: Starts on the far left of the Cave Boulder. Sds, hands on the large jug and feet on the block below. Work up through good holds to the large protruding block near the top. Make a large committing move to the block and top out to finish

name: Chad
description: Start as Tree Line and climb up and right to finish via jugs to the left of Heather.

name: Dead Homies
description: Climb the arete on the left of the "D" boulder in the guide.

name: Echo Base
description: Stand start with a crimp on the left and a weird side pull on the right. Head up and slightly left.

name: Goldfish
description: Start on the right hand arete with a side pull and mybe something else if you can fid it and then either gun it for the top or climb it static. Tricky floppy top out.

name: Heather
description: Start to the left of the tree that is growing out of the boulder. There are some good moves to the big undercling and then some jugs. The top out is scary on this one. I hope you are ready to flop.

name: Rising sun
description: This is the climb to the right of the tree growing out of the rock. It is kind of tricky and crispy, but on great rock.

name: Tree Line
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Vagabond
description: Do the first moves of Word is Bond and then keep right to many medium size crimps

name: Word is Bond
description: Start with your hands matched on the horizontal move out from the roof with an under cling, a jug, a crimp, and then a big move to the ledge. Heel hook it and pull up on some crimps.

name: Bone Crusher
description: Start under the roof with some good hands on a horizontal and reach back for a side pull crimp on the flake. Some foot work and a good reach will get you out to the triangular jug at the end of the flake that is now flexing as you hang on it. Reach out to the roof throw up a heel and do some pull ups to top out.

name: Yoga Pants
description: Sit start with your hands matched on the obvious chalked up flake to the left under the roof. A heel hook and some toe cams with get you along the flake to a crimp and a sloper. Pull straight up to jug, mantle over your sloper to another jug to your left and top out.

name: Dish Face
description: Sit start with a good left hand and a right hand crimp.  Move up through the crimps to a jug at the lip.

name: Wrath of Roth
description: Stand start on a good left hand sidepull and right hand crimp.  Move right to good holds and top out.

name: 10 Minute Abs
description: Sit Start with hands on the incut side pull crimp and the sloping edge which appear to be the remains of a flake.  Utilize any usable feet on the little boulder, which the main boulder rests upon.  Move your knees up to set a double kneebar, and make a big reach to grab the pair of usable crimps on the face.  Move the feet up and go left hand to a good edge around the arete.  Make another set of big reaches to another set of crimps high on the face, then top out easily.

name: Imidazole
description: Sit start on a low crimp rail for the left and a side pull for the right, move up to jugs and top out easily

name: Peace Sign Roof
description: Start at the back of the roof underclinging a hole, and move out the roof on pinches and crimps to the jugs at the lip of the roof.

name: White Trash Renaissance
description: Start on obvious jug on the right side of the cave. The kick plate stone is off for your feet. Climb out the lip of the boulder moving left through gymnastic moves.Top out the left side of the boulder through a high dihedral.

name: Dyce
description: Sit Start on the two low flat jugs and a high left foot. Slap up the cube feature and top out easily.

name: Fully Strapped
description: Sit start as for ratchet strapped, once you get the pocket transition onto the shield feature using crimps and a sidepull. Do a dance and figure out how to gain the jug/Gaston up left then top straight out. The jug in the crack for ratchet was not used and should be considered off although may not take away from the final moves difficulty.

name: Ratchet Strapped
description: Start sitting on the stone that rests under the shield.Use a flat deep jug for your right hand and a moderate side pull hidden under the roof for your left hand. Climb up the shield using all the holds on the face to help you access the crack feature which forms the right side of the shield. Enjoy!

name: Acid Drop
description: A classic of the South Mountain area, sit down start on the sloping rail and a high right foot.  Move up to an incut right hand side pull and match on the sloping rail with the left hand.  Cross over and grab the small flat edge and dyno to a jug at 3/4 height of the face.  Utilizing the flake and some big reaches top out the boulder.

name: The cost of lichen her
description: Step up onto the shelf make a reach move to a deep crimp then follow the holds up and slightly left for a heady mantle

name: Hanger Sit
description: Sit start on a good left hand crimp and a decent right hand pinch under a steep section of the boulder. Throw left hand to a good edge and continue up the sharp crimps to top out.
Climbs up and right past the 1944 inscription.

name: 2 Flights
description: This route is an extended version of Winding Staircase. Start with hands matched on a sloper, and make some moves until you reach the arete. Use the rail to traverse left into the start of Staircase. Reset your feet, and make some easy moves to the top.

name: Ben's Ankle
description: Start with good feet, and reach for jugs! The crux is probably topping out, due to the small footholds. This is where I took a fall and badly sprained my ankle (hence the name).

name: Birdshot
description: Start with hands matched in a crimpy pocket and good feet. Reach up to another crimp, and pull your way to the top.

name: Daddy Long Legs
description: Starts on shelf, with feet in the small crack. Work your way up the face and top out.

name: Delilah
description: Start as low as you can on the right overhang. Reach to the lip above, then mantle to the top.

name: Der Riese
description: Start on the big, juggy shelf on the right side of the wall. Traverse left, through the cruxy midsection using crimps and small footholds. Continue until you reach the start of Birdshot. Reach up to a few more crimps until you reach the top.

name: Elevator
description: Climbs the chimney crack

name: Escalator
description: Starts on the sloped shelf with awkward feet. Work up the arete, to the overhanging face. Set your feet, throw a heel, and top out.

name: High Hopes
description: Overhung start with a sloper and pinch. Follow the horizontal finger crack, and mantle up to the slabby finish.

name: Muzzleloader
description: Climbs the center of the face. Start with some crimps and small footholds. Work your way up to some bigger, friendlier holds and top out.

name: Ravioli Ravioli
description: Start with hands matched on the low shelf. Move up, and shoot your had into a nice pocket. Reset your feet, and make a few easy moves to the top.

name: Samson
description: stand start. reach up, and mantle to the top!

name: Shadow People
description: Sit-start with hands matched in the pocket. Reach up for some jugs, and make some moves up the arete to top out.

name: Staircase
description: Start with your hands on the big flake and walk your feet up the staircase! Top out however you want. I was tired and couldn't get it.

name: Sunshine Daydream
description: Sit-start matched on a low jug. Make moves to the small crimps on the face, until you reach the juggy top out.

name: Warm up Arete
description: Climb the right arete, up and around the corner. Avoid using the boulder next to it.

name: Winding Staircase
description: Fun, overhanging problem in the Staircase area. On the bottom right corner of the boulder, start with hands matched on the sloper. Make some moves to left until you reach the arete. Using the slopey shelves of the arete, PULL hard and top out.

name: Enigma
description: Climb the obvious wide crack at the left side of the Skooch Wall.  The vertical stretch at the top is the most challenging.  Use both walls for some corner / chimney skills.

name: Topography
description: Start at the crack to the right of the lower face.  Up the ramp to the crack to the right.  Straight up to the top.

name: Wet Willie
description: Climb straight up the center of the face.  The slightly overhanging rocks at the top are the most challenging.

name: Zipper
description: Start on the dirty ramp, avoiding the crack to the left, climbing the face.  At the vertical part, traverse right and go around the overhanging rock to the top.  Easiest route up the face.  If you are taking beginners out for a first TR experience, send them up this route!  Nice and easy, does not feel too vertical.  Comfortable beginner route.  Great for kids!  Cleaned pretty well.

name: Teardrop Buttress (PG-13/R)
description: Start on the pedastal at the base of the low-angle prow. Top 30 feet of climb is full of loose blocks, be very careful what you grab and where you place your protection. Rappel from tree at top (single 70m is just enough to reach the ledge below).

name: Tears are Falling
description: This route climbs the left facing wall of the buttress. Start 20' left of Teardrop buttress and climb a clean slab past ledge, then step through the left side of the ceiling at mid-height. Continue up slab past broken ceilings to the top.    Bring extra webbing. Rappel from large tree at the top.

name: Boca Roca Grande
description: The well protected right-facing corner with two large roofs. Begin on a narrow ledge 15ft above the trail with rhododendron and a maple growing on its left end. 30 feet downhill and left of this is a flat spot in the trail at a boulder with a finger crack (Henry's Hangout 5.11) Dougher and McMahon originally graded this route 5.5. With more traffic, this route would be excellent. Can be done as one pitch.     P.1 5.7+ 120ft   Up the corner past two trees to large roof. Finagle past the awkward roof and belay just above it on small to medium sized gear.     P.2 5.6 60ft   Move up to the second roof and pass it on the right. Up a short wide crack (only need .75s) to a tree. The tree blocks the way, so we swung left onto the short white slab to the top, with better exposure. Belay at a horizontal with finger sized gear.      Descent:   There is no rap station.
