Walk off up and left and descend down the power lines, or rap off one of the hemlocks 30ft to the left (not recommended).

name: Drifting Arrow
description: P1 Move easily up the bottom of the practice wall, following a jagged crack to an indistinct groove to a belay on some trees.   P2 Move the belay 10 feet to the right below a left facing corner with a tree growing out of the base.  Climb the left facing corner and face above, past a grassy ledge and slab above and belay at the obvious ledge.   P3 Climb straight up off the belay following a flaring hand crack which peters out onto a slab.  Angle right and climb through a tree/shrub on low angled rock with poor gear aiming for a small ledge below the long roof system above you.  Once on the ledge move right and place good gear in the crack and pull over the roof on good holds.

name: Espresso
description: I haven't managed to complete this route yet, I'll update this when I have. Here's what i know so far:    P1 - Move up the bottom of the practice face to the ledge by whatever means you want. Set up a belay halfway between Drifting Arrow and High Falls.    P2. Head straight up, aiming for a weakness in the roof above. There are a series of scary stacked blocks that you pull either directly over, or around on the right.  If you step left you will gain a long ledge. At this point, I went left and up to the high falls belay. However, the proper move is to head right to a finger crack and follow it straight to the end of the roof traverse of High Falls. There is currently a small birch tree/bush growing out of the bottom of this crack. Semi-hanging belay at the end of the finger crack and right edge of the High Falls roof.    P3 - Finish High Falls or do the Drifting Arrow Linkup.

name: High Falls
description: P1 - Move easily up the bottom of the practice wall, thru a short hand crack an past a single pointless bolt to the ledge. Optional belay from here, but it's a straight shot to the next belay.    This pitch is often skipped, you can traverse in via the catwalk ledge from the base of Pussytoes.  You can also do this to drop a TR on P1.  P2 - Follow the path of least resistance up the face above to gain the large left facing corner. Either go left of the rotting tree up a small right facing corner then traverse right into the bigger corner further up, or go right of the tree and up some lichen covered rock directly to the bottom of the big corner. Stem up clean rock in the corner to a small belay ledge atop the corner below a long roof.  P3 - Traverse 15 feet right till the roof overhead ends, then move up the face and right facing corner (crux, well protected) to the next roof. Traverse right under this roof with great gear until you can pull up a weakness at it's right end. An optional semi hanging belay here (V1) with your feet in a wide horizontal crack lets you see the second thru the crux and keeps rope drag manageable, otherwise continue up 20 feet to and pull a notch onto a ledge on the right w/ an old tree anchor and belay there. Rope drag will be bad if you opt for the ledge.  P4 - From this final ledge, move up the corner or face to the left of the corner to the top and belay off some trees  V1 - Drifting Arrow Link-Up - from the semi hanging belay, diagonal right up the face to a small ledge and pull the thought provoking crux moves on Drifting Arrow . Makes the route really worthwhile, protects well throughout.

name: Pussytoes
description: Climb the middle of the cat wall starting right where the "Cat Walk" traverse to the practice face begins. There is a bolted belay next to a medium size tree directly above, halfway up the wall. It is 5.5, but you may have to hunt for the 5.5 moves, a direct line will be a bit harder. Gear in the beginning seemed sparse, better up high.     For P2, the crux is right off the belay ledge. Start just left of the belay/tree and move up in an alcove, Get good gear and pull the overhang, then sprint up 70' of easy terrain to a small tree and second set of bolts.

name: The Great Escape
description: The obvious 3-foot wide chimney that is sometimes a fun, mixed ice climb. Can be loose and vegetated.     Pitch 1: Climb the chimney, then pass through a ceiling at a notch. Belay.    Pitch 2: Ascend a left facing corner, traverse right, then up and left through the clean ceiling at a crack.    Bring extra webbing since there may not be a solid rappel station. Plenty of good trees at the top though.

name: Chieftain
description: PG/R. Make sure you are skilled at placing protection before leading this one.     Pitch 1: Six feet right of Surprise's open book, climb the face, passing the right side of small ceiling with a serrated lip, then pass the left side of a second ceiling, and finally pass the right side of a third ceiling. Now climb the face at a crack to a belay ledge.    Pitch 2: Move out the center of the large ceiling above and into a left-facing corner system to the top.

name: Crackpot
description: Follow a series of 3 well spaced bolts up the prow. Use gear for the next 20-30 feet until reaching a final bolt, then continue up to a ledge From the ledge, option to rappel (tree to the right) or continue up another 35 feet on white clean rock to a bolted anchor on a ledge.The rappel from the tree should go with a single rope to a raised platform with a dead tree below.  A 70 will def make it. The rappel from the bolt anchor requires double ropes.Be careful of loose rocks on lower bolted section.

name: Point of No Return
description: This route follows the outside of the arch of the land of the giants wall.  The first pitch is moderately runout on easy 5.4 terrain to a delicate 5.7 traverse (swing potential) ending at the belay in the corner under the roof.  The second pitch continues to traverse left, following a finger crack on perfect clean quartzite, then heads abruptly up at 5.8+, or continues at 5.6 if you keep traversing.    Pitch 1 - 5.7 PG13 - Begin almost as far right as possible on the Land of the Giants Wall, at the only spot the clean rock extends to the ground.  Follow the path of least resistance up the rock to small ledge above a notch at about 60 feet (some loose rock, not much pro)..  make a few moves to the right up a groove, then angle left up an easy slab, towards the arete of the arch.  Get gear in a short diagonal finger crack.  Either go around then up, or up then around the blunt arete to a slabby face with very little gear (I found a blue ballnut handy here).  Continue to traverse across the delicate face (crux) for 15 feet to the left facing corner below the roof.  Hanging belay on ample fingers sized gear.    Pitch 2 - 5.8+/5.6 G - Follow the finger crack above the left side of the belay around the outside corner (exposed, wild), and continue to traverse for 25 feet to a right facing inside corner above a small alcove.  (V1) Move awkwardly up the corner (crux, huge reach, 5.8++), then diagonal left and belay on gear or trees above the rappel tree on surprise.    V1 - 5.6 G - Continue traversing for another 20 feet, following the same crack (very small gear) to a left facing inside corner (top of Cheiftan).  Move up this corner for 15 feet to the top.

name: Surprise
description: Pitch 1: Climb a white open book for 55 feet to a small tiered overhang. Step right and pull the center of the overhang to an optional belay ledge.    Pitch 2: Step 6 feet left, move up through a slight notch, step back right, and follow weaknesses just left of the prow to the summit. Descend with a two rope rappel or two one rope rappels.

name: Voyage of the Damned
description: Just right of Chieftan, up typical dirty first pitch to belay at tree 20ft below ominous roof.     Up to the roof, lean out place great gear, take many deep breaths and go for ride. Clear the lip and immidiatly move right and up to good stance. Plug in the biggest piece you got and now to really go for a voyage. Move left navigateing a difficult and awkward wide crack. Hanging belay from tiny gear.     Pitch 3 goes straight up. Small gear (#1 camelot fits in a pocket protecting the giant reach). IMHO; the best route at the Gap.

name: Morning Wall
description: From the start ledge, step left around the arete.  Make a few tenuous moves up and clip the bolt above.  (*V1) Trend slightly right up a shallow and steep corner with small holds, sidepulls, and small gear (wires).  Continue up to and past a large horizontal (Crux, a not very well protected, possible large cam, maybe 4 or 5?).  Continue up slightly easier and better protected ground to the right end of the roof, which is passed in a steep open book with a finger crack.    Continue up to a second corner 15 feet from the top.  Either traverse hard left approx 30' (sparse looking pro on questionable looking rock) to the Morning Sickness anchors, or continue up the corner (difficult, but protected) to the cliff top (very heavy foliage, get ready to pull on rhododendrons) and belay at a tree.    From the morning sickness anchors, descend via a 2 rope rappel.  From the cliff top, carefully work up-hill to a faint climbers trail and hike to the surprise anchor tree.  Descend as for Surprise (one 35m rap, or stop at a mid wall bolt anchor)   V1 - Some guidebooks describe this route as following morning sickness to the roof, then traversing 12' right under the roof to rejoin the route as described above.

name: Captain Hook
description: Directly below Osprey. Instead of following the trail up along the face to start Osprey and Heroine, go left below the small buttress.

name: Heroine Hypnosis
description: Pitch 1: Pass a low roof on the left and climb a flake 45 feet to belay below a small roof to the left of, and slightly higher than, the long, larger rook of Blue Sparks from Hell (5.10).    Pitch 2: Move left around this small overhang, then right around the ends of tow other roofs to a large corner system with a large, grassy ledge and rappel rings.    Pitch 3: Climb the corner (actually the right face of the large corner). Your see a tree and a grungy corner above you. Don't go here. Weave to the left and finish moving left under the large roof that forms the finale of Osprey. Use the same belay tree as Osprey.

name: Osprey
description: Pitch 1: Climb up easy terrain to a small indent with a roof. Pass the roof on the left (5.6) and belay on the flat ledge above (80-90 feet).    Pitch 2: Follow the obvious line straight up, passing three small roofs on the way. Use long slings to avoid rope drag as this pitch is 120 feet. Rope management is critical here. There is a roof with a crack that is known to jam ropes for both leader and follower. At the top of the climb there is a huge roof that you skirt underneath to the left and finish on a dirty, loose ledge with a good tree (Same as Heroine Hypnosis).

name: Pain Builds Character
description: Same start as Osprey.  At 35', trend left, staying on the arete and face, staying 10-20 feet away from the crack system that makes up Osprey.  Pass a small overhang.  At a steep headwall, climb the obvious, right slanting crack to a stance below the intimidating final roof system.  For the full 5.10 value, finish on the roofs above, toping out by pulling on clumps of grass to reach rap station, shared with Osprey

name: Pleasure Feeds Addiction
description: Start on the left end of the High Wall on the arete, 30 feet left of Osprey and 20 feet right of "Dragon's Lair".  On the left end of the low roof where a rock bench can be found.     P1: Climb straight up the arete on clean rock with good gear, passing a large ominous looking block on the right (avoid).  Belay at a 2 bolt anchor (5.8G)    P2: Continue straight up from the belay to the largest part of the overhang.  Pull the hang on good gear, 10 feet left of where "Pain" pulls the hang.  Continue up on clean rock above until you reach a very thin seam (10 feet left of the upper crack on "Pain Builds Character"). Unlock the sequence and finish at a 2 bolt anchor.  (5.10G)    V1. It's possible to diagonal up and left from the belay, around the arete and climb the second pitch of "Dragon's", bringing the grade down to 5.6G    P3: A third pitch is possible but very loose, scary and not for the faint of heart.  Most will rap after the second pitch.    2 single rope raps or 1 double rope rap will put you back on the ground.

name: Sleeping Beauty
description: Climb the low angle rock passing 1 bolt to a grassy ledge.  Continue on good holds past 2 bolts to the crux at bolt #3 find the incut pinch and get high feet and make another move on thin holds to reach the low angled terrain with good holds.  Plug some gear (I used a .5 camalot) and continue up to the small roof with a bolt (kinda runout).  Pull past the roof on the left and past 1 more bolt ending at the chains.

name: Snow White and the Seven Dwarves
description: Also Known just as "Dwarves" - Start as per Snow white, but at the ledge after the first bolt, head left to a runout second bolt. Follow a line of bolts up to the chain anchor shared with Sleeping Beauty.

name: Full Tilt
description: Scramble up to a large grassy ledge below the Screaming Eagle roof. Climb to the left. This is the "full tilt". Turn the corner and continue up the face. There is a lower rap tree, but it's best to continue to better trees further on up.    Best for the belayer to tie-in to a tree. The "tilted" section of rock is at least 50 feet from the ground and if the leader fell and blew a placement, they could easily take their belayer with them.

name: Alumni
description: Start matched on the loose dinner plate jug. Make a couple powerful moves following the left trending overhang and top out up the face/corner. Great movement and quality rock, but the start jug does tend to seep.  The start hold doesn't seem to be going anywhere despite how loose it is. If it ever does rip out, the problem could be started from the same position with no change to the sequence.

name: Beelzebub
description: Begins with vertical wall of small delicate holds with good crimping. the crux consists of a ledge with 2 hand holds that you have to swing over with one hand and foot on small hold. After the ledge slight overhang to use some hand holds and minimal foot holds.

name: Lower North Wall
description: Large vertical wall with many good sized hold, crimps, and cracks. First 50 feet of the route is dominated by less featureful rock with decent sized crimping holds with good placement for both hands the feet. Upper parts of wall is some of the most exposed climbing on the Devils Pulpit and require more technical hold placement with multiple kick maneuvers, friction holds, and overhang problems that create an exhilarating crux on the final pitch . The route ends on a 10 foot ledge that expands outwards beneath the Upper North Wall.

name: Finding B-MO
description: Start on a flat edge and a sharp crimp at face height, bump right to a good side pull, toe in hard on an edge and move the left hand to a sloper, then bump to find the good bump hidden from view.

name: Sharks Tooth
description: Sit start on a good right hand jug and a small left hand side pull.  Move straight up to the big sloping rail.  Bump left hand to tiny sharp crimp and move your feet up the sloping ramp.  Throw left hand to a small pocket in the middle of the face then top out.  The edge of the boulder is off  until the top out.

name: Bar Hopping
description: Sit start on the Yvly starting flake, and once you reach the jug, throw to the next flat jug about 4 feet to the right and control the swing.  Top out either straight up on small edges,  or move slightly right to the crack.

name: Breast Flop
description: Route starts right of the cave area and traverses left to a juggy rail. Step up to a good edge and top out. An exit from the rail moving left feels natural and is a tick easier alternative finish.The details of the line are a bit limited but assume the left block supporting the main boulder is off.

name: Def
description: An extension to the obvious route of ‘Shoe Lace’ on the the west face of the boot-looking block starting at the arete.

name: Graffiti Face
description: Right face of the fire dihedral on the boot block connecting to the arete. Sit start.

name: Leafy Sit
description: Sit start with a flat side pull and a right hand jug, make big moves to small edges before a deadpoint move to a jug.  Continue on big holds for a few moves, until all holds disappear, trust the mantle to top out this great problem.

name: Low Traverse - Left to Right
description: Sit start below grunt dihedral, and move right using the low holds, finish on the low jug on the right side of the overhanging face.  This problem has some long reaches and requires some flexibility.

name: Pulp Friction
description: Stand start on a good low left hand edge and a bad right hand crimp.  Bump the left hand to another small edge, then throw to a sloping edge.  Reset the feet and throw left again to a good incut flake.  Easier moves on bigger holds to topout.

name: Shoe Lace
description: A good warmup route to the area. Right facing jugs to large left hold up top with interesting feet.

name: Twitch
description: Two routes to the right from Yvly. Sit start, hand on a low flake, to a moderate edge, then work the crack. Topping out might be the crux.

name: Yvly
description: Sit start on a flake and move up to a side pull, then to a flat jug.  From the jug work slightly left on small edges and top out.

name: Honda Civic Blues (Brad's route)
description: Start underneath the triple roofs. Pull through all three roofs then make your way left and onto the face. Finish on easier climbing to a 2 bolt anchor above the arete. Between the first and second bolt is a detached block that seems to be jammed in pretty well but worth being heads up!

name: Rabbit hole
description: Climb the clean fingers to hands crack in a left-facing corner. As the corner ends move right and go the top. The last section is a little heads up.  Short but pretty nice rock

name: Rabbit hole direct
description: Climb the finger cracks and laybacks just to the right of rabbit hole's corner. Same finish

name: The Buttcrack
description: Short, fun problem requiring only a few moves. Start with one hand on a small ledge next to the middle crack(yellow circle in the picture) and feet on the rock. Make a few moves as you go up the crack and top out at the top of the crack by the piece of a metal pole.

name: F*** you!
description: Fun line, lots of good options for holds, start on the big flaky jug below the namesake graffiti, make a few of the harder moves up to the big horizontal crack then traverse around the corner and continue to traverse/climb and top out just left of the large metal pole sticking out of the rock.

name: High Heels
description: Really fun low Hanging line to practice your heel hooks on. Start with your hands in on the ledge near the corner hook your heel, the start making moves up to the left, until you get to the corner/peak of the boulder then just climb up and push yourself over the top. Footwork is the key on this so you don't slip off and touch the ground because of how low the line is

name: Low Exposure
description: Fun boulder on a lot of solid Jugs, a few sloper and crimp type holds but relatively easy with good feet all the way up with lots of variations. Start either on the left side of the boulder near the corner and traverse around the corner and up the face. or start lower on the face of the boulder and climb straight up.

name: Stourbridge Slab
description: Fun Slab rock with a lot of different routes and variations, start near the right of the slab on top for an easier ~V0 climb  or start underneath the slab face near the left and climb over the edge up on to the slab for a more challenging start and slab climb.

name: Porkus Non Grata
description: Climb to a short vertical crack 25 feet up, then climb two ceilings to the top.

name: Alli's Crack
description: Few different problems on the different faces of the boulder , this one specifically starts in the inside crack between the boulder and use the small crimps to get a start. Once off the ground you wanna stem your legs or keep them on the same wall and use your back on the opposing wall to offer balance.

name: The Bat Cave
description: This is the steep chimney on the right end of the Gorgeous wall. Going inside the chimney is much more physical and grungy, but less technical (hence 5.5)  If you hang out of the chimney on the jugs and stem between the two walls, the route is much more fun and technical (5.7), plus you can clip the bolts on the right wall (Party at Tim's) and climb it as a sport route.

name: Blap
description: This route has a fun crux right at the first bolt, making it a very safe fall.  The route name came from the sound you will make trying to stick the crux!

name: The Gorgeous Arete
description: Start on the slabby face to the right of the arete for a delicate start, or on the steep face to the left for a bouldery start. Half way up you will get to a good ledge/rest.  From here, traverse left to "Too Many Tacos" (5.7) or continue straight up the "Gorgeous Arete" passing a bolt (5.10a).

name: The Gorgeous Crack
description: This hand crack goes up up a steep overhang early on, and is harder than it looks. After surmounting the overhang, the original route finished left on Too Many Tacos.  For a harder finish, continue straight up the face above to finish of the Gorgeous Face (5.10b), or move right to the bolt and finish on the Gorgeous Arete (5.10a).

name: The Gorgeous Face
description: This route starts on the bulge just to the left of the Gorgeous Crack.   Climb the bulge to a cool small slot (gear). Continue up, clip the bolt and crank through the crux.  After the crux, traverse 5 feet right, crossing over the Gorgeous Crack and continue up the blank face above. Use delicate moves and long reaches to gain the horizontals above.  Finishes on the same anchors as the Gorgeous Crack and Too Many Tacos.

name: Guano (Bat cave alternate start)
description: Start up the slab (5.6-) to the over hanging section to a nice undercling. From here, a big move with the right hand straight up the face to a knob style hold on a round rock that stands out. From here either left hand to a flake above or match hands and move out right to the upper triangle shaped jug on "the bat cave". From this point finish on the bat cave

name: Mixed Bidness
description: The crack and arete on the right side of the left wall at Gorgeous Rocks.

name: Monkey's Fist
description: Hop up blocks in a big open book and chimney in the corner, past the first roof. Work up the next two roofs to the nicely exposed end.

name: Party at Tims
description: The thin overhanging face/arete to the right of the Bat Cave.  Better warm up those fingers for this one!

name: The Partys Over
description: Cruise up some easy terrain to the first bolt above the break, move gingerly on some loose but solid flakes to the second bolt, then fire off a v9 boulder problem to the anchor.

name: Separate Reality
description: Follow delicate moves over small crimps, passing 2 bolts to an anchor shared with mixed bidness.

name: Too Many Tacos, Not Enough Toilet Paper
description: Start at the bottom of the crack below the tree that is growing out of the wall about 15ft up.  Climb up and to the right, following the obvious crack all the way to the top where there are two anchor bolts.  Decent jugs and cracks for the entire route.  Some areas have awkward opposition holds when placing gear.  Top out is great and there are plenty of places to build an anchor if you don't want to use the bolts.

name: Variety Crack
description: A grab bag of crack widths on this one. The start is the crux. Very safe and easy to protect. Located to the right of Blap (first bolted line on the cliff) and sharing the same anchor.  This safe mellow lead is often used to TR Blap.

name: Welcome Crack
description: First crack reached at Gorgeous Rocks.

name: Brass Arete
description: Start up the corner/arete. Finish up the corner/arete past two bolts.   Variation (easier): Start on Brass Monkey face, then move right to the arete and bolts.    (One print guidebook gives the name of this route as, "5.10b")

name: Cornflake Crack
description: Climb the crack starting just to the right of Grey Face. This is a great beginners climb with great gear placement.

name: Flamer
description: Between the two trees, this spectacular face climb follows three bolts.

name: Great Expectations
description: Climb past two bolts to the crux at the third bolt.

name: Grey Face
description: Climb over a bulge just right of the previous route and follow the left side of the face to an easy top out.

name: Lavwelle Latte
description: Start to the right of Easy Day for a Layback and climb the face past 3 bolts. Decent face holds to an easy top out.

name: The Murky Way
description: Interesting moves -- not so murky.    If only this were longer.

name: Warm Up Route
description: Climb the face past 3 bolts at the right end of the wall. The start is about 10' to the right of the Cornflake Crack.

name: Nose Drops
description: Balancy footwork takes you through three bolts to the top. Grabbing the arete keeps the climb 11ish, staying strict to the bolt line makes it twelvish.  The rock is clean with a touch of lichen.

name: Nuclear Arms
description: Deceptively hard climbing takes you past the first two bolts, the crux is passing the drilled pocket.  No individual move is harder than 11+ but the pump and commitment adds a bit.  Can be done statically but its probably easier to huck a couple dynos.  Veering right at the last bolt keeps it 12ish, heading straight up past the last bolt ups the ante a bit.

name: Phazers on Stun
description: Up the sustained-overhanging crack, then a short arete to the top.

name: unnamed
description: A good route for library standards.  The rock is solid but a little lichen covered on the last third of the route.  The crux is a hard pull up high but the balancey second clip may deter some.

name: Unnamed 5.12
description: A fun route that works through a right facing flake into a system of horizontals.  The reachy crux after the second bolt goes static with the right foot placement.

name: Urine Over Your Head
description: Climb the fantastic finger crack at the edge of the big chimney. Stepping over to the chimney makes this route a 5.3.

name: The Bitch is Back
description: Up by the indented overhanging nose to obvious ledge. Next angle six feet Right-ward, then up to finish just left of obvious notch.    . (the Holzman print guidebook 2011 edition has the difficulty as 5.10a/b).    Upper sections sometimes dryer than other routes on the Rear Wall.

name: K.B.
description: Good climbing with a dominant crux after the second bolt, may seem a little harder until you figure out the sequence.  The first ascentionists named it after Kevin Bein, one of the climbing greats who died on the Matterhorn.

name: Lightning
description: Crux is low and with a big reach.

name: Pine Line
description: Sustained climbing with a dominant crux after the second clip.  The first bolt might seem a bit high off the ground but the climbing is easy.  The crux is is a touch painful, incorporating the left jug is true to the grade but going direct seems more natural.

name: Ryan's Crack
description: Up the crack and through the roof, up the left-facing corner.    . (the Holzman print guidebook 2011 edition has the difficulty as 5.10b).

name: Sad, Sloppy, Worthless, and Weak
description: Up the rounded right-facing corner, next by a vague left-facing corner, then right-ward to a ledge. Then up and left to finish 12-15 feet right (east) of the mature pine tree at edge of cliff.    . (the Holzman print guidebook 2011 edition has the difficulty as 5.10a).    Sometimes dryer than other routes on the Rear Wall.

name: Stairway to Heaven
description: Climb the crack to the right of the Bitch is Back. Short climb but very fun.

name: Thunder Stud
description: Some balancing skill takes you to the third bolt crux, can be done statically but a tricky dyno gets the job done. The climbing eases after the crux but is still sustained. Coerce your partner to lead it first to brush off the spider webs.  "The route Thunder Stud that was put up by Albert Pisaneschi who led it and bolted it. He is not on social media and asked me to have someone change this on the web. I have his phone number if you need to speak to him to verify this. He has quietly put up many routes without writing guides and other people have taken the credit." - nancy savickas

name: unnamed (rear wall)
description: Follow the bolts.    . (the Holzman print guidebook 2011 edition has the difficulty as 5.11a).     . (sometimes dryer than other routes on the Rear Wall).

name: War and Peace
description: Follow the bolts.    . (the Holzman print guidebook 2011 edition has the difficulty as 5.13a).

name: Book of Four Words
description: Up the arete.    . (the Holzman print guidebook 2011 edition has the difficulty as 5.11c).

name: Leave it to Beaves
description: Start at bottom of face next to detached vertical flake - (or could start from top of detached flakes).   Follow the bolts, roughly up the middle of the face.

name: Southeast Descent
description: Up the obvious two-feet-wide left-facing corner.    As of 2015 there is an old worn + faded nylon sling hanging down from above the top of the corner.

name: Beginner's Crack
description: Easy enough for kids except the last 10' at the top. Traverse left and roll over the top for the 5.6. If you go straight over the top it feels like 5.8R.

name: Beginner's Slab
description: Easy, fun slab until the last 15' where you have a tricky face to the same anchors as Beginner's Crack.

name: Bullseye
description: Good protection with cams up slabby start. Figure out the fun moves past alcove and roof to top.

name: Double Wave
description: Follow the bolted line to the left of the Pizza Crack. At the second bolt move right to a bulge and follow two more bolts to the top.     The anchors of Pizza Crack to the right can be borrowed.

name: Iodine
description: A fun route on the upper tier with some good finger to hand jamming.  Traverse into the crack from the left, head up the crack to a fixed pin, and then traverse out left to a couple old pins.  The crux is low on the route but the pump may get some people.  The bolts and fixed piton are easy to supplement with good gear.

name: Mercury
description: A fun spicy route that climbs past 3 bolts.  There is a substantial gap between the 1st and 2nd bolt that would likely result in a ground fall if you're just clipping bolts.  A couple marginal small cams can be placed behind a flake after the first bolt that substantially minimize the pucker factor.  The 11ish crux is well protected after the second bolt.

name: No Name Crack
description: A short but high quality crack.  Work up and right to gain the attractive finger crack.  Then head up the crack and traverse slightly left to the tree.

name: Pizza Crack
description: Great juggy climb on the center of Main Wall. Doesn't protect very well, but can be set up as a top rope from the top access trail. Has some really fun moves.

name: Razor Blade
description: Make techy moves through the beginning seam past a bolt.  There is a second bolt on a bulge, and after that easy climbing through some cracks where you might place some gear will lead you to a thin face with two bolts.  Climb onto a ledge after the face, and hope you're tall enough to clip the 4th bolt. Pulling up over the 4th bolt is fun too.

name: ZigZag Crack
description: Small holds to jugs about 10' up to left facing flake. Lie back to ledge and 1' wide dihedral about 10' up to pine tree. Move left and up to next ledge. 5.8 goes to left up steep blocky dihedral or 5.10+ straight up the middle. Also known as Whaleback Crack in Holzman's book and S.O.B. The start is a little harder since a flake broke off in 2011.

name: Birds Fly High
description: Very cool roof, start stend on two crimp just under the roof, rich the crack under the roof then traverse out and fight the top out.

name: I Fantasmi Camminano
description: Sit star on a big crack bottom right then climb up the cool arete to slopey open hands on the lip. Final hold is a jug in line with the tree, mantle up to finish.

name: Mythical Petting Zoo
description: The best problem of this area, sit start then follow the obvious and very cool line up the dihedral crack to a dyno finish.

name: Show Me
description: Start sit on the left side of the boulder, traverse right then go straight up on the center of the boulder.

name: Agent Orange
description: Holzman calls this one of the best 12s in PA and I wouldn't argue, especially if you like crimps.  The splashed orange color and rippling feet add to the enjoyment.    Angle up a left slanting rail to some small but reasonable holds to make the first clip.  A fall here wouldn't be fun without a boulder pad (stick-clipping is for pansies).  After the heinous clip blast through a thin section of micro-crimps and small feet.  Another powerful move awaits after the second clip (also tough).  Once established on the horizontal above the second bolt, take a deep breath and climb some easier ground to the anchors.

name: Astro Projection
description: Power through a bulge approx 10 feet off the ground at the first bolt, then follow the bolt line straight to the last bolt of I-beam.  The top of the route is sustained and fun but the crux for me was definitely at the first bolt.        There are multiple ways to finish this route but I feel this is way makes the most sense.

name: Broken Finger
description: Crux seams to be right off the ground since you need to stabilize using the finger cracks as you smear on the adjacent slab. once you finish the slabcrack you need to get around a protruding feature and traverse up and right then out on to the face at the top of blackbeard ending at the anchors above.

name: Direct Drive
description: Though the roof is a little intimidating, the crux is probably on the lower face.  Layback the roof flake to a welcome jug.  Missing the third clip would be a safe but "uncomfortable" fall.  After the roof, easy run-out climbing leads to a nice two bolt anchor.

name: Eye Brow
description: Mild overhang 30 ft up. Crack offers great protection.

name: First Blood
description: A surprisingly fun route on solid rock.  A bouldery move just off the deck is the business and a fall wouldn't be recommended until you get gear in the first horizontal crack.  The climbing is straight forward once you hit the horizontal but gear is a little sparce.    Undoubtedly someone else has lead this route before.  If anyone knows the FA then let me know.

name: Hickory
description: Climb the arete on the Hickory Wall just to the right of Maple. There are a few good crimps and a nice ledge at the crux near the top of the route.

name: I-Beam
description: Look for the mineral deposits and chalk running down the wall, step up the the incut in the rock below the bolt. follow the route straight up, first crux between the first two bolts. (Hint: finger lock) after that continue straight up to the the second crux below 3rd bolt. after that head up, pull through the over hand and head up and left to the bolted anchor. Enjoy

name: Maple
description: Climb the center face of the Hickory wall. This route has some cracks and good ledges.

name: New Generation - 5.12a
description: Double roof route. Original route was considered 5.12, may be a little easier now.

name: Oak
description: Climb ledges to a small roof. Work your way over the roof to the anchors.

name: Pine
description: Climb small ledges to the crux mantle about 15' below the anchors.

name: Rambo
description: Follow a corner to bolt with a horizontal capped ceiling. Move up to another bolt then into a shallow corner, then to the top.

name: Rambo Direct
description: Start just to the right of Rambo under a bolt and a small ceiling. Fly to a horizontal under the ceiling and then move left to join the Rambo route.

name: Roofing Madness (Reefer Maddness)
description: One of the best at Moc.  Climb straight through the bolt line passing two roofs.  The final roof is excellent and consists of a jug haul out to the final roof crack.

name: Tricks
description: Enjoy techy moves through the first bolt (easier if tall).  The crux (significantly easier if tall) is at the obvious blank section, where moving to the right is on the next route and will drop the grade.

name: White Water
description: A few feet right of Black Beard lock into a short crack to a horizontal and step right and up to a good ledge. Then up a slabby face to the anchors.

name: Anti-trypophobia
description: DWS route that deserves respect. Traverse down at the far side of the waterfall from the trail. Nice landing area to sit and tie shoes/chalk up. From there traverse low right for a few feet before finding good jugs and heading straight up, trending right. Harder moves lower down can be avoided by going up, then traversing. Topout at the obvious ledge or take a swim!!

name: Blue Velvet America
description: Sit start with a good edge for hands and a smear for right foot, go to a sloper for the right hand and thin edge for the left, left foot up and rockover to shallow edges for hands above, match and go for the top.

name: Corrupted Brow
description: Begin at the right-hand extreme of the previous problem, ledge for left hand large pinch for the right, high step to a good edge then press to reach upper break (hard for the short) thence to the top.

name: Danielle
description: Located past the treehouse wall going towards the Bridge. Take a left at a smaller trail and then a right going down hill towards the river. May be a little tough to find the rock. Area shows no sign of climber presence so I just tried some real easy problems. It is the crack that almost is the shape of a nose.

name: Hard Very Scranton
description: Climb the juggy wall then top out

name: Hope
description: Stand start on good edges, top out

name: John
description: Same boulder wall directions as Danielle. It is the slabby face next to the crack.

name: Leaving Buenos Aires
description: Hang the edge on the left and the higher crimp on the right, dyno to the good hold and then to the top.

name: Mini-prow
description: Stand start using good sidepull flake, go up to a variety of edges and incuts

name: Punctured Beauty
description: Stand start with fingers in the horizontal crack, foot on a low ledge, move up to a good hold and then the top. FA

name: To Have and Two Hold
description: Sit start with two hands on ledge.  Make way towards top out which juts out further than rest of ledge.  Top out feels like it leans back more than others on wall so use spotter

name: Tree House Traverse
description: Right to left traverse along the ledge, mantle to finish.

name: Try Not
description: Hang minute edges, then dynamically (or statically for the tall!) go to an edge immediately next to the sidepull flake. Top out.
left cliffs of the rim cut into the woods on your left before hiking up and around right to the rim

name: Cresent moon
description: One of many free standing boulders just off the trail in to your left

name: Gift of Gravity
description: For full value start on the left side of the long horizontal at about 10 feet above ground level. Establish yourself and then traverse the horizontal until you can dead point up to a good enough hold to pull yourself up onto the face. Follow up to another roof the follow a horizontal seam left and then up. Top out.

name: Alligator
description: A tall, fun problem. Climb the face directly next to the roof.

name: Astral Projection
description: Start in the back corner of the roof, matched on a small slope. Using crimps and large slopers, traverse out of the cave until you reach the start of Alligator.

name: Inspiration
description: Start on a jug under the roof, keep pulling jugs until you top out.

name: Ben's Ass
description: V2 or V3 depending on how low you start. Climb the left side of the face using the shelf, and mantle the top section to top out.

name: Bigfoot
description: Start low on some jugs, move up to the big shelf, then reach up to the slopey top-out.

name: Blaze Orange Required
description: Pretty easy vert problem. Start with one hand on the arete and another on the obvious crimp. Bump your hand up the arete & throw to the top out jug. Top out is a little weird but not too sketchy.

name: Crystal Crusher
description: Climb the face. Start with one hand low on the arete and the other in a small fingercrack along the dihedral. Move to one of the small crimps on the face, then shoot for the lip.

name: Jump Skip and a Hop
description: Start with hands matched in the huge under cling. Launch to the lip, and top out.

name: Squeeze and Pinch
description: Start low on the 2 aretes. Move up while pinching and squeezing, until you can launch to the lip.

name: Squiggley Wiggley
description: Start with the right hand to the right of the obvious block that protrudes in the middle of the boulder, and left hand towards the arette on some kind of slopey hold. From there, get your feet on and wriggle your way up.

name: Up, Up, and Away
description: Prone start. You basically start this problem laying down. Haha. Anyways, start with hands matched on the low jug, reach up and use the marginal holds to get a good crimp on the arette. It was making sounds as I was climbing it so be warned, it might come off. In any event, once you have this, its just a hop, skip, and a jump to the top. Enjoy.

Sit start on the meaty sloper and left heel. Head upwards for the cracks between the layers of the rock.  The end is a niceish jug about midway up the face. This route DOES NOT top out - simply match hands for the send.

name: Miriska Hargitay
description: Sit start under a plethora of holds and trend left to climb over the lip of the boulder for a super positive grade slab finish!  Look for the little nubs!

name: AntiGrant
description: Sit start on the left side of the boulder and work your way up the narrow side to a slopey-but-goody mondo top out.   Note: Grant has yet to get this one but if he does, the name will stay the same.

name: Around Grant
description: Looking for a fun warm up?   Start on the top of the small flake to the right and head to the large pocket above it.  From here, head left towards the crest of the boulder.  From here, anything goes to get to the top so get creative!

name: Philly Cheesesteak
description: Hey, remember that overhang we were talking about? It's here!    Start on ya bum and reach up to all solid holds leading up to a sloper on the crest of the boulder.  Trend left for that mondo top-out!

name: Birdman!
description: If you're into some gnarly crimp action and overhung goodness, this is the route for you!  Also dodging the tree... that's important.

name: Clap of Thunder
description: Crunched sit start with some pinches and a small dyno if you're vertically challenged or related to the Baggins'.

name: Iron Bridge
description: One of the quintessential climbs at Beartown!  Work your way across the bridging part of the boulder with a few sequence options for the middle section.

name: Troll's Traverse
description: A crimpy traverse through the tunnel of Bridge Area.  Good for warm ups or beginners and is very close to the ground.

name: Melman... from Madagascar
description: This is one of those problems where the crux is the start.  A few burlier moves up to jugs to top out!

name: Ross... from Friends
description: Looking for some overhung fun?  Here's a longer and fun route with solid hand holds and heel hooks for days.  The vertical face of the boulder is OFF for feet in the roof section of this route, however, a softer rating climb can be made out of this if you use the vertical face.

name: Becoming the Figure Head
description: Just a heads up, the top out for this problem can be rather sketchy.  Use the steps on the lookout to walk up and check if it is dry and clear of moss/lichen.   Sit start at the bottom of the prow and work up both sides.  The top out is on the left side of the point.  Look for a solid right-handed jug near the top and then beach whale it secure the send!

name: Incubus
description: In about the center of this face is a feature that juts out... Start below and to the left a bit of this. Work your way up by using said feature and then trend right for the top!

name: Succubus
description: Sit start on the large rail and then continue upwards using the many rails on this face of the boulder to a higher but easy top out.

name: Quite place
description: Start as far down in the over hang as you can. Starting hold is left hand pincher and right hand sloper. Start with right foot pressed under ceiling and left heel hook. Work hands along edge then move up over the ledge and finish matching on jug just below moss line.

name: Golden Monkey
description: Sit start on the arete and then trend right to enjoy the beautiful golden sandstone.  There is multiple ways people have done this route so play around and find what is the ideal beta for your style.

name: John the Octopus
description: Sit start.  Trend left off of the start and aim for the bulging feature at the top of the boulder.

name: Something About a Slug
description: This V-Fun is a really fun route for new climbers!

name: Walking Taco
description: Sit start on a left-hand jug and right-hand rail to get to have a slabby-good time up to a great variety of holds.  Vertically challenged individuals may have a super slight difficulty with one or two of the moves.

name: Animaniacs
description: Start on the bottom left on a great hold and reach out around the small roof.  Work your way up the front face of the boulder to a solid top out

name: Picking Berries
description: Start on the bottom left on a great hold and work your way right under the small roof.  Then on the right face of the boulder, work up the semi-slopey holds to a solid top out.

name: D Squared
description: First move is the most difficult; moving from the slopey start to the sloped rail.  But once one works up the rail and moves up to the turtle's eye  or the smaller hold intermediate climb up through his hat on the right side to top out.   Suggestions on names for the turtle?  Jason, perhaps?

name: One Big Triscuit
description: A longer version of "Triscuit to Risk It" due to a different start.  Tricky transfer to middle of the original route with the same ending

name: Triscuit to Risk It
description: Slope start to a series of crimpers and the top out through the turtle's hat!

name: Baldface Liar
description: This is a very sparse boulder with tiny crimps and jibs.

name: Bear cub
description: This is a slight overhang boulder problem.  Bring a brush for cleaning.

name: Emperor's new clothes
description: Boulder problem with lots of huecos to choose from.  Top-out is dirty.  Bring a shovel for cleaning...

name: Fat lip
description: This is a large boulder with a vertical overhang before the top-out.

name: Ice cube
description: This is a traverse route on the "Ice cube" boulder with a top-out on the right side of the picture

name: So you wanna fight
description: This is a knobby boulder problem with lots of options.  Bring a brush.

name: Tenticle
description: Fun for everyone!

name: Thing 1
description: No route yet.  Looks very sparse.

name: Thing 2
description: No route yet.  Slight overhang. Bring a brush.

name: Thing 3
description: No route yet.  Overhung huecos. Bring a brush.

name: Arrowhead
description: Sit start at the bottom of the large crack in the boulder and get our feet out wide to the right. Pulling the peak of the arrow is a thrilling move.

name: Big Iron
description: Utilize a long iron deposit to traverse along the length of the boulder. Readily available features get you up to the seam.

name: Overnight Oats for Desert
description: Easy climb up to a great view of the boulders. Start either at the south tip of the boulder or the flake in the middle of the face.

name: The Sex Lord Elect
description: North most boulder of the north cluster. Start on the right of the boulder looking north and climb left, variety of good holds for feet and hands. route finishes at the center of the boulder after climbing under the outcropping.

name: Up For Grabs
description: Climb up from the end of 'Sex Lord Elect'. Use easy jugs at the beginning and trend left to top out on the other face of the boulder.

name: Orange peel
description: Climb beautiful sandstone to a lip near orange sandstone top out

name: Iron Bow ("30 Feet of Pain")
description: Holds down low are super sharp and at risk for breaking, recommend stick clipping the first bolt in case one pops off. Very well placed bolts for clipping positions. Crux is the last move, can be accomplished via intermediate or one big dynamic move. Chains have surface rust but are solid, probably a good idea to rappel rather than lower off to save your rope. Once a leader sets up the anchors it can be top roped to work out the moves.

name: Last of the Mohicans
description: "Super fun and moderate route.  Great TR or you can lead with big gear.  Follow the crack to the top"

name: Solo
description: "Fun and casual way to get on top of the boulder to set up top ropes for other routes.  Good route on its own"

name: Arachnaphobia
description: short three move problem.start on slanted crimp on arete, and half pad on the roof.bump with your left to a small odd sloper, use a good pocket right above the edge with your right and make strong bump to the top with your left. top out    Beware of fairly large wolf spiders here during early summer, accompanied by extreme heat as the sun bakes this rock all day, so its also dry pretty quick. High tide makes this problem inaccesible.

name: Dancing with the Stars
description: sit start awkwardly with left hand in decent slot, and a low three finger "pocket". move up with the right to a good lip, and out left to a "seems like its gona be bomb" slot. right hand up to a crappy jug, match and make a big move to the top. downclimb the opposite corner of where you are.

name: Elephants Have Dreams Too
description: short little problem with good holds, and a fun top out. Start in "mouth" towards the far side with the obvious only clean top out spot. make a big move out right and stay close to the arete, grab a sharp small jug then go for the top out.

name: Gingers Don't Dance
description: Sit start with a good hold low and left, and super cool positive three finger hold on the arete, stand up to a sharp half pad side pull above your left hand, follow suit with your right hand, then find a way to the huge ledge slightly below the top. Top out can be sketchy and dirty, but the top corner is good, and theres an exposed root to assist. or you can just jump back down    (may be height dependent, I`m 6'1" and probly have another 4-5" before im fully extended on the biggest move.)

name: Headbangers' Ball
description: Start "underground" on two perfect horns, make static moves to good edges and a sloper making sure not to crack your dome off the rock below. Move through good edges and pockets to a dicey top out in the opposite corner of where you started.    slightly contrivedvariation cuts out the underground start

name: hepC
description: project

name: Leprechauns Need Love
description: sit start below elephants,on two jugs, stand up to a positive slopey edge, then share the arete hold with elephants, but stay wide to another sharp deadpoint slot, top out.

name: The Beginning
description: A neglected route in the heart of the lions den area. Climb past huecos and a bolt to a 2 foot roof (crux). Clip another bolt and navigate over a roof to easier climbing above. Great route in a secluded location!

name: Frosted Flake
description: Great moderate climb.    Crux is the undercling traverse.     Flake is often wet, but holds are juggy and super positive.

name: Unkown
description: Surmount the roof that starts straight off the ground. Commit to a good undercling to gain the slab with a crack in it. Chuck a piece of gear in if you can find a placement. I gave it PG-13 because if you can’t find a placement here, the next good gear isn’t until you continue up to find a great horizontal crack at 15-20 feet up. From here continue up towards the short dihedral. The crack in the dihedral takes nuts and passive gear well. Layback and stem your way up the dihedral, and find a dirty ledge up high that allows you to exit the dihedral. Continue up using roots and whatever else you can find to top out. Also, not sure what the name of this route is, but if anyone has more info, I’m happy to update it.

name: The Vibrating Rabbit
description: nice crimps and crux is in the middle. Starts as low as you want. I found a nice foot underneath the roof and two nice crimps to start on

name: Red Bridge Overhang
description: The crux is probably the big bump (for me at least) around the arete to ascend.

name: Dew Point
description: Burly route overall, best part is that the hardest move is the last. Missing the last move means a solid whipper. Very overhanging so relatively safe to go for broke. Would recommend taking a couple of extended draws to make clipping positions more efficient. Also when cleaning don't pull the last draw or you'll send yourself and the belayer flying off into the woods like some redneck cirque du soleil acrobatic nightmare. Just pull it with a stick clip after getting to the ground.

name: Beginners' Face
description: Climb up the line of least resistance just to the right of the arete to a ledge. Climb a few more moves to top out.

name: The Total Newbs Climbing and Rappelling Training Route
description: Your cousin Joe heard you rock climb and now he wants to go. You don't really want to take him, but you kind of feel like you have to give him a chance at least.  So you show up on Saturday with all your gear eager to get some climbing in.  Of course Joe's standing there in his athletic shoes.  Plus Joe has a slightly American physique and relationship with food, health, and fitness.  Also, Joe hasn't done a pull up in years.  Still, Joe is tough and everyone starts somewhere.  Perhaps this could be the beginning of something new.    Unfortunately, juat like every Saturday there is a line forming at Beginner Face.  You Name It just came open, but that can be quite tricky without a little technique and proper shoes.  In fact pretty much the only route a total beginner in athletic shoes might be able to climb is Beginner Face which is why there's now a 3 hour wait for it.    Suddenly you think, "Hey, let's rappel while we wait.  It's fun and kind of rock climby.  Doesn't need special shoes.  And a climber needs to know how to rappel eventually anyway."    So you set up the nice big overhanging rappel for Joe.  You connect up his ATC, wrap up his auto block, and then tell him to just lean back into that 40 feet of open space.  "Don't worry, you can't fall, just don't let go with that right hand!"    Joe's looking at you with wide eyes and letting go of the rope to cling to the rock even though you just told him to never let go of the rope.  You realize that a big overhanging rappel might be a little bit too much too soon.  Maybe you just need to get in line for the Beginner Face.  You've done it 1000 times, but it is the only Rim Road climb a completely inexperienced climber in athletic shoes even has a shot at.  Or is it???    As you're standing around near the Beginner Face you spot another line.  Someone could scramble the chimney 20 feet to the right of the Beginner Face, up to a big wide ledge.  From that ledge it might be possible to climb a short face and top out on top of the Beginner Block.  It looks possible...  maybe even in athletic shoes.    So you run up top, jump the gap, set up an anchor, jump back across the gap, run back down again and voila...  You have an alternate beginner route established. Joe can climb the chimney to the ledge at least.  Maybe he can even make it all the way up and out in his athletic shoes.  Plus the wide ledge half way up the climb offers a great place to teach someone how to rappel.  With the ropes hanging from above, transition onto a rappel is a breeze.    So much more than the cobbled together mess that is might seem to be, The Total Newbs Climbing and Rappelling Training Route offers an alternative to the always busy Beginners Face.  Then there are those folks who find even the 5.4 Beginners Face a little tricky or exposed.  This alternative route offers many starting options and can be climbed quite easily up to the ledge, even by beginners in athletic shoes.  Being largely in a chimney adds that false sense of security which nervous new climbers crave.  Once on the ledge you have a perfect place from which to practice rapelling techniques.  Or the bold new climber can take a shot at the second half.    This route can in fact be climbed all the way in tennis shoes.  However above the ledge there are a few tricky moves and sketchy moments that earn the route a 5.5 overall grade.  Up to the ledge it is a 5.2 or 5.3, above the ledge is solid 5.5, noticeably more interesting than the 5.4 Beginner Face just to its left.    While the chimney on the lower half offers easy lines, as you progress out around the left arete and onto the main rock face some interesting and more challenging lines can be explored using the same top rope set up.  You essentially get to protected boulder on the arete and main face, while Joe gets to climb and rappel at a modest grade.

name: Birthday Boulder
description: Start in the middle of the boulder. Start in the lower letterbox and the make two moves to the second letterbox. Continue up to the left on a weird, pockety crimp. Get your feet up, and make a balancey cross-over with your right hand to a flake. Then a few easy moves to top out.

name: Cakewalk
description: Climb up good ledges & positive crimps on the right side of the Birthday Boulder. Topout can be a bit awkward, make sure to have pads & spotters below. Great, smooth route

name: Happy Happy Joy Joy
description: Start in the second letter box of the main birthday boulder problem, set up with high, poor feet, and think happy thoughts about dynoing to the lip,and not ripping off the top.

name: Jail Bait
description: Follow the awkward moves up the left arete and face to the top.

name: Middle Edge
description: Locate the sharp line of edges up the left side of the boulder 5ft to the right of the arête. Follow these up and lunge for the jug.

name: Playing with a Full Deck
description: Follow the only visible route up the middle of Casino Boulder, using barely there crimps and sidepulls facing the wrong direction. The crux comes about 2/3 of the way up, holds thin out almost entirely before the top. Plant your feet, spread your weight, and pray that you have a good spot if you don't make it.    I've bouldered up to V5 in a few other areas in the NE, and can't make an ounce of progress on this bad boy at the crux. So, with that said, I don't know how accurate the V3 grade is but that's what the old guidebook has it as.

name: Five Finger Arete
description: The opening moves are the fun of this route and also the crux. A cheater block is often placed for the start of this climb, feel free to move them out of the way and enjoy the opening moves. The rest of the route is straight up with solid large holds. Overall this is a fun little route, one of my personal favorites and one of the better routes in the park.

name: Five Finger Traverse
description: Start on the right edge of the West face of Five Finger Block, traverse left across the lower face towards Five Finger Arete Route, the opposing arete.  Avoid using the ledge system that forms and keep to the face.  The crux is towards the end of the traverse.

name: Trigger Finger
description: High ball boulder problem with incredible jugs.  Start with the ticks marks. Climb up the middle and shoot for the ever-so-slightly overhung crown to top out. Nice grip on the crown, ladder walk your feet to get over the edge.

name: Grafiti Traverse
description: Starts on the left arete of the side facing Rim Road and move to the right. Sit start with a high left foot and both hands in a slot then up to a decent jug, across to a good crimp, on to a corner with a small overhanging ledge over it, then to the corner of the overhang, two more crimps and then reach around the corner to another crimp then bring your left hand to a slopery crimp on the arete, and finish by moving over to a jug and then topping out.

name: Alt Access
description: Alt Access is a fairly easy climb located just to the left of Rigging Route near the southwest corner of Island Block.  Because of its short length, moderate grade, and ample protection opportunities, this route provides an alternative way to access the top of Island Block.  With some Trad gear/experience it may actually be the safest way to access to top of the block since protection opportunities are rather abundant.    This route is obviously a good place for a beginner to practice Trad.  While not spectacular, it may also be worth a climb on top rope if you are already on "The Block".    It should be noted that this route had been previously identified as an unnamed 5.6 on another website.  Since nobody cares enough to name it, I'm calling it Alt Access.  I'm also downgrading it to a 5.5 since it is straightforward and clearly easier than another appropriately graded 5.6 (Lean Across) on the same face.   If you do lead this, remember to take your rappel gear since there is no easy way down from Island Block.Also, anytime you're climbing on Island Block think about climbing order.  To avoid having to re-climb an access route, always send a capable climber up last to clean up or move anchor.

name: Prenuptial Taste Test
description: Climb the dripping buckets on the far-left side of the wall as high as you dare.

name: Rigging Route
description: Located on a short arete on southwest corner of Island Block.  This route seems to be the best way to access the top of the large freestanding Island Block in order to set up top ropes for other climbs.  There is another tempting line made up of moss covered, sloping ledges about 20 feet to the right of this arete.  Don't be fooled.  Climbing this short overhanging corner is the easiest way up onto the block and the holds are solid jugs if you take your time and feel them out.   Just remember to take your rappel gear since there is also no easy way down from Island Block.Also, anytime you're climbing on Island Block think about climbing order.  To avoid having to re-climb an access route, always send a capable climber up last to clean up or move anchor.

name: Boulder Dash
description: Right of a left leaning crack, start between the face and a large boulder.    BAD LANDING

name: Center Route
description: Start to the right of the left arete on Ross' Boulder.  Climb straight up using obvious flake and finish at just right of the arete.

name: Ross' Boulder
description: Ross's Boulder (left arete, V0).

name: Sit Start
description: Start at the two low pockets to the left of the right arete.  Move up using the arete edge, pockets, and side pulls.

name: You Name It
description: Follow up the slappy faces in between the moss.  Large edges and big holds.  A great beginner TR climb.

name: Don't Drink the Koolaid
description: Climb a series of pockets to the top. Twenty feet or so to the right of Sunshine.

name: Post and Lintel
description: Simple Route on the backside of a flat boulder east of a large, graffiti covered rock face.   Sit start and reach large ledge of rock. Good holds to the right help with topping out.

name: Girlish Figure
description: Begin by climbing an offwidth crack to a sloping ledge. Either make a small traverse left and up over a small overhang to another sloping ledge (5.8), or as a variation follow the crack straight up and over the overhang to the ledge (5.10a). From here move onto the face and up to an overhanging block at the top.

name: Marriage license
description: Thin and sequential through the middle good route finding will aid in the send

name: Slippery When Wet
description: A spectacular overhanging lieback. Start by scrambling up to a ledge about 15 ft up. Follow the finger crack as it gradually becomes overhung, until reaching the top. A challenging variation continues right once reaching the top, and requires a pro placement just before sending the roof (5.10b).

name: Stepping Stones
description: An awkward start on a near vertical offwidth crack. Climbing becomes easier as the crack widens, and good features lead to the 1st of two large ledges.  Not far above is the 2nd ledge, and from here youll need to move right onto the face until you reach a sloping ramp. Follow the easy ramp to the anchor.

name: The Arborist
description: Behind the tree lies a few pockets, which give way to a comfortable flake and some sizeable ledges.

name: The Atheist
description: Sit start on the large jugs in the open seam, and use a few iron crimpers to pull into a jug. Ascend to the final hold where nothing awaits. Located on the left of the gently overhanging face, just right of the The Nihilist.

name: The Buddhist
description: Simply one of the best at Rim Rock, this problem is sure to help you on your path to ego loss. Sit start on the jugs in the low seam right of center, and move up through iron crimps to a ledge and some slopers. Calm your mind, and either commit to a long pull or let all attachments go and fire for the top.

name: The Optimist
description: Sit start low on the iron seam with a crimp and pocket, on the edge of the small boulder that faces your back. Believe in the thin iron holds as you move to a few slopers before making a slightly committing move to the top. A bit of an eliminate to avoid the better holds out right on The Jihadist, but the moves are sure to satisfy.

name: Cobra Bubbles
description: Sit start left of the arete, climbing up and through the ledge, finishing to the right.

name: My Friends Need To Be Punished
description: Start as for Cobra Bubbles, traversing low and right. A series of crimps and pockets leads to the ledge on the right side of the boulder and the topout.

name: Arleerette
description: Up the right arete and top-out. Easy climbing after the crux in the middle. Meaty ledge for resting if you have zero endurance. Closer to grade than many other climbs at the Duke. NOT A WALK-OFF DESCENT. MUST DOWNCLIMB. Definitely a do not fall zone 3/4 up and beyond, and hard to protect with pads.

name: Catherine's Traverse
description: Start stemming at Shot in the Back. Traverse left on the horizontal, often one-knuckle, cracks and generally bad feet, and finish stemming on the left. Fun for a traverse, tentatively graded V2. Hard moves close to the ground!

name: Coroner's Corner
description: Crux is 3/4 up the climb, most climbers dyno to nice, positive hold from a sloper OR a two-finger pocket, and a crimp. A Bilger's classic. This is probably the hardest climb in the Duke, a true 5.10a grade. Rated it V2 as it's a true V0+ move with highball consequences and to keep it relative to the surrounding boulders. Those with weak head game or short reach may find Arleerette (V2) harder.

name: Dusti Chaps
description: Start left of Ten Gallons, straight up.

name: Fire in the Hole
description: Fun for the grade but dirty. This boulder is rarely climbed.

name: Flexible SOB
description: REALLY mossy, good lip in the middle.

name: John's Belt Buckle
description: RIght arete and top-out. Slabby on the front side, and some good holds. Walk-off descent, but you have to scramble around some.

name: Raw Hide
description: Mix of slopers, crimps, and horizontal cracks. Crux 3/4ths of the way up. Good feet for resting, but the slopers near the top are evil if not cleaned well or wet.

name: Round Up
description: Straight up the middle of the route, just left of the bigger lip (Flexible SOB)

name: Seven Shooter
description: Felt crimpy for a 5.6, it's the middle line. If I graded it, I'd say ~5.8. Quite dirty, but could feel true to grade if cleaned better.

name: Sheriff A.N.
description: Stand start in the middle of the boulder and ride the beefy ledges up the slab to topout. Easy, but chossy. A good clean and it would be a great TR problem for munchkins.

name: Shot In the Back
description: Stand start on the left arete. No stemming, quite slabby, and definitely hella soft for the grade (V4). Walk-off descent, scramble around boulders until you're near the entrance of the Duke, and then scramble down.

name: Shot in the Back (Stem)
description: Start on left arete (#12) and top-out. Mix of stemming and slabby climbing on horizontal cracks. Great first highball.

name: Ten Gallons
description: Strechy crux and a nice crack.

name: Treadmill
description: One my favorite lines at Bilgers. Start on the roadside of the entrance slab and work up to the horizontal crack. Traverse left using the horizontal cracks, overhead flakes, small pockets, and smears until you reach the arete, and then head up and out.

name: Lil Roof
description: With a sit start it’s a V0 until the roof to me, it’s a fun little pull up and top out.

name: Lowgistics
description: Crimpy endurance traverse. Start right and move left, or left and move right. Better yet go back and forth!

name: Murderball
description: Start lower left on the overhanging face on a shelf, follow the shelf up to its end then move up to the juggy top and top out.

name: Spade
description: Stand start right in the middle of the Spade Boulder's North face and climb straight up through some fun crimps with bomber feet.

name: Spade Arete
description: Stand start on the arête left of Spade and follow it straight to the top.

name: The Undertow
description: A very crimpy route that’s super fun! A good landing place and a classic spot for the area make for a great boulder. Start in the middle near the small crack at the bottom and head straight up. Great 3 finger pocket a little from the top adds some variety to all the pebble crimps.

name: The Apprentice
description: Classic bolted line. Crimpy with a few, various, small features to use on the way up.

name: Autumns Child
description: Crimpy and requires some solid footwork.

name: Birthday Girl
description: Fun face climb through 2 bolts. Start in the left facing corner, move up to the horizontal and diagonal left to the first bolt; straight up from there.  Hunt for the amazing finger tube above the small roof.    Two bolts for a top anchor.    This is the easiest bolted/mixed route here.

name: Cobblestoned
description: Climb the thin crimpy face straight up to the top.

name: Curt's Crack
description: Classic (for the area) splitter that goes from fingers, to thin hands, to hands then is fist and/or offwidth(y) above the horizontal.    You can climb the fingers to hands crack to the horizontal then instead of continuing onto the fist/offwidth above, crawl (an average size human can fit) through the passage/tunnel and build an anchor. Just an option.

name: The Great Train Robbery
description: Crimpy, exciting face climbing

name: Headstone
description: Climb up the Margies Curves crack but instead of following the crack left or right, go straight up onto the face and to the top.

name: Keneissiology
description: Nice introduction to Boxcar.    Up the obvious crack. Interesting crux sequence mid-way. Fun moves below and above.

name: Margies Curves - Left
description: Fine, fun crack. Third splitter on the Main Wall.    Above the horizontal at 35 feet, you can finish up the offwidth (5.6) or climb the face to the right of the crack (5.4R), to reach a 2 ring anchor at 50 feet.    Well protected with plenty of options for feet outside the crack as well.

name: Margies Curves - Right
description: Climb the same crack as Margies Curves Left however at the split (bottom of the Tombstone) follow the crack right.

name: Moby Neil
description: Start at the flake, move up through some jugs to a ledge (5.4), then into an left facing dihedral/corner to the top.

name: Pebbles and Bam Bam
description: A near vertical face with some fun crimps and pinches. Climb the thin face straight up.

name: Please Don't Pop
description: Start on a shallow, red, right facing flake.  Climb past 5 bolts to a 2 ring anchor.  Crux is at the roof.  Try to find the fun no-handed rest, mid face!

name: Russell's Ruin
description: First splitter crack on the Main Wall. Climb the crack straight to the top.

name: Snap Crackle Plop
description: Climb a bouldery right facing flake to a bolt and a rest.  Delicately climb the face above past 2 more bolts to a horizontal.  Clip a 4th bolt and pull the small roof using nice finger pockets. Finish on the fun face past a 5th bolt to a 2 ring anchor.

name: Halcyon Days
description: Start at the bottom of the outcropping at the end of the spine in a sit start. Climb under the prow and pull it until you top out. Bonus points if you find the sit rest in the middle.   Easier for smaller climbers. Starts out as a lowball almost. Dodge the trees and avoid nearby rocks for support.

name: Out of the Maw
description: Start at the base of the off-width roof crack. Interesting feet as you move out. Fun route to practice inversions (pretty rough on the knees), off-width jams, and a few chimney moves. Find the number hand jam before pulling the roof.

name: Ape Call
description: The is the climb directly up the center of The Block above Riverview Ledge. I've led it 30-50 times over the last decade, I'm sure other people have done it, but I don't see it that often.

name: Bellyflop
description: Pretty straight forward. The only weird part is getting out from the overhang, especially if you are tall.

name: Paul's Pop Off
description: The lead up to the crux is pretty easy and straightforward, lots of holds and jugs. The crux is climbing through the overhang. Above the crux is less than vertical and pretty chill.

name: Riverview
description: Start at the far left of Riverview Ledge. Climb the overhang, and climb the broken rock and crack in a gully to the top.

name: Zig
description: Slight overhang, upper section has some slight slopers

name: The Exorcist
description: The Exorcist is THE classic boulder problem at Chickies. Actually, it's the only decent boulder problem at Chickies. It climbs a 60 degree roof on textured, high quality pinches and crimps. Drop off at the high jug.

name: Foops Simulator
description: Sit start.  Long steep boulder problem.  Mostly larger, smooth holds so you won't have to worry about tweeking fingers or running out of skin.  The crux for me came after the sit start getting to the long up and left traverse.  The second crux is moving past the finishing jug of the exorcist.  Once the second crux is done, you can climb higher and to the left as shown in the picture and walk off, down climb or jump down.      If anyone knows who the FA was, the grade, or if this is the correct name, let me know.  Thanks!

name: That Roof Crack
description: P1: Climb the obvious roof crack that traverses the wall just to the right of the cave.  Climb to the end of the roof and pull over the roof following the crack straight up to a small tree below a ledge, belay from the ledge. 60ft.    P2: Climb up and angle left across the grassy gully.  Past the gully reach an arete and follow that up right towards the large pine tree.  Cross under the left side of the pine tree and up another face to the summit, belay from the a rock pinnacle at the summit.  150ft.

name: Unknown
description: Start in the center of the cave.  Right hand on a large pinch and left hand undercling feet on the block right of the crack.  The crux is pulling out of the overhang.  Good holds, burly moves.    This area has a lot of spiders.  Knocking out the webs with a stick is worth 2 minutes of your time.    If anybody knows the name, grade, first ascenionist, let me know and I'll add them.

name: [Redacted]
description: This route starts halfway between the dihedral for Main St. and the smaller dihedral towards the Library where Madmen start. You should be looking straight up at the left facing ramp/open book of the upper part of the library, you'll finish on the outside(if truly straight) of this; so you should start under it. Climb straight up face to Riverview Ledge.  Route used to start over graffitti "Patty lester" according to Sue Hartman; lichen now dominates start.

name: Hollywood
description: "Start: At the base of a small black face, below a smooth white face, 5 feet right of the graffiti 'Bob 1986.'    Pitch 1: Climb the face, then the small crack, using no holds on the right side of the crack. Climb to the overhang and through the V-notch at the lip, and up the face to a small ledge. Climb the center of the face on the left to the Riverview Ledge. 110 feet.    Pitch 2: From the entrance of the Riverview Ledge, traverse right 7 feet. Climb the face to the right. Climb to the top. 50 feet."    - Sue E. Holland, "A Guide to Climbs at Chickies." 1988. (out of print)

name: Josh's Hump
description: Main Street Crack ends below a small tree/bush where most people escape right to Riverview Ledge. Josh's Hump continues straight up short slabby section of rock below The Great Roof to a stance in the left corner under the roof. Microstoppers or a #00 Camalot buys you some protection here before a scary traverse to the left out on a prominent, light-colored arete. The is the arete where Josh Laudermilch (seconding my lead) stopped to hug and/or hump the arete. Use a long runner on the gear in the corner to avoid rope drag on The Great Roof above.   We regularly do this route in one pitch with long slings, especially under the roof. Communication with your second is difficult when you are on the summit and your second is under The Great Roof.   Note: You can also start on Witches Brew, and move right up under the Great Roof before you head into the Chimney.

name: The Library
description: Look for the large dihedral at the base of the cliff. The Library climbs the first dihedral then moves left into the upper "open book" just below the left side of Riverview Ledge. This second dihedral is one of the best features at Chickies Rock with slabby feet on the left, and spaced-out feet on the arete to the right. It is stemming magic with a continuous vertical crack at the back of the dihedral that takes solid gear, and a final horizontal crack to protect the crux roof moves at the top. Because of the traversing nature of this climb, most top-rope climbers miss the stem moves of the final dihedral, and instead finish with the large broken crack system called Snowflake.

name: The Lower Undercling
description: Same start as Sunday Morning, and the Undercling. 15 feet to the right of the Library dihedral is a smooth orange and black slab broken by a left-to-right trending crack. This is the Sunday Morning Crack. Follow the crack up a short way. Before the roof/overhang, follow the lowest obvious flake/undercling, and traverse left (crux).Follow the arete up and trend right on the next two horizontal ledges. Finish the climb with bouldery moves in the vertical crack on the black face on the center of the south-facing wall.

name: Main Street
description: The Main Street Crack is the most obvious crack system just to the right of Witches Brew, and left of the face climbs Lester the Molester and Madmen Only.
