It's a great climbing crack system but does not extend all the way to the ground. If you are leading, the crux moves are just off the ground. You'll get your first piece a .75" Camalot while standing on a prominent light-colored ledge/notch 12 feet directly above the start. The best part of the climb is an obvious diagonal finger crack in a block near the finish of the climb. The crack ends on a small ledge near a small tree/bush. From the bush, you can move left into Witches Brew, finish straight up on the climb Josh's Hump, trend up and right and finish in the notch at the right side of the Great Roof, or you can traverse right and escape onto Riverview Ledge. Main Street is one of the great trad climbs of Chickies Rock and cannot be top-roped. You must lead it. It needs to be climbed more often, please climb this frequently and help clean dirt and grass to keep it climbable.

name: The Notch
description: "Start: between Snowflake and Sunday Morning.    Pitch 1: Climb the obvious long narrow notch. Climb through the notch and on up to the top."     - Sue E. Holland, "A Guide to Climbs at Chickies." 1988. (out of print)

name: Nuts
description: The route starts around the southwest corner of the Main Wall. The first pitch has three distinct sections. The slab at the bottom leads to a scramble which leads  to a vertical face with lots of cracks. There is a live tree and a wide ledge at the top. This pitch is about 60'.    The second pitch starts directly behind the tree and continues straight up the vertical wall to another wide ledge. On the ledge, there are two sets of bolts located only a few feet from one another. There is a steep walk off to the right which leads all the way down to the start of the climb. The route can also be toproped by scrambling up that same path from the bottom to get to the bolts. This pitch is about 30'.

name: Nuts Corner Wandering Variation G
description: Start similar to nuts amongst the trees on the slab around the right of the main wall in the shade. Slink up the slab around the tree and scramble to rock face with two parrallel, trending right, vertical cracks. Climb and sow up right crack to small living tree (not dead tree). Second pitch from the small living tree. Climb the obvious corner up to either set of bolts in buried around loose pebbles. Start in the corner and run up to roof, pull out right of the roof and traverse right to a notch and run that up as far as you can and then make the obvious traverse left back into the corner. Finish up the corner and mantle onto the loose pebble top out. Crux is top out due to loose pebbles and pulling to right of the roof (just a little awkward).

name: Snowflake Direct
description: Start where ever on the broken up section under the first right facing dihedral/open book of the Library.  Climbing straight up, or trending right, when you reach a height level with the roof and dihedral entrance on your left, look for your pro (#1 cam) at the very start of the snowflake crack, you get another #.5? Just a little off to the right in a vertically faded splitter (beta image). Both are good to run it out up the huge easy ledges to a big horizontal crack for more gear. Stay in the snowflack crack and rock it out.  Big, easy holds for beginners. Maybe PG in the beginning, then G all the way home.

name: Snowflake Variation 1
description: This is a fun climb that begginners could make it up.  There are plenty of big holds that don't require fancy body positioning to use.  Also some good hands free resting places to sort gear, take a breather or a picture.

name: Sunday Morning
description: Once you climb past the overhanging section (crux) the climbing is basically over.  It becomes more of a scramble to the top.  This would probably be an ok climb for first timers or for those who are looking to practice placing gear on a safe/easy route.

name: The Undercling
description: The 5.7 grade applies only to the crux(es) which are the undercling move, and at the top, following the vertical crack in the black face. You can easily maneuver around these cruxes to arrive at the same place. An easy top-rope version would probably go 5.5 due to the roof (i.e. Sunday Morning).

name: Witches Brew
description: I have seen different descriptions of Witches Brew and Witches Brew Direct. In my opinion, "Direct" is the only version worth considering. Any escape to the left or right does not make the climbing any easier, and you miss the best part of the climb.    Due to the length of the climb, the first time I did this I did it in two pitches, setting up a belay on the loose ledges at the base of the chimney. Don't do this. There is tons of loose rock on these ledges, rope management here sends showers of rocks down on to your belayer. I strongly suggest leading this climb in one long 160-foot pitch. the climbing is very easy, use some longer slings.    Climb the crack system using larger gear to the base of the Witches Brew Chimney (5.3). Climb the chimney--the key piece of pro will be on the south wall of the chimney--horizontal crack takes a pink Tri-cam or small C4.    Do not climb to the top of the chimney. You will get trapped under a chockstone. Instead, climb about 2/3 way up, then exit the chimney by stepping around the north corner onto the sunny exposed face to the left of the chimney (5.3). Easy climbing to the top.    PS. Please do not tie two ropes together and use this climb as a top tope. This is a nice easy lead for aspiring trad climbers. It doesn't make sense to tope rope such an easy climb.

name: Drop Out
description: The start is the same as Ivy League. Follow the large vertical crack until you come to a crack on your right. Follow this crack to the corner. Climb the corner to the to top.

name: Hit and Run
description: Cruxy start, smaller holds that get better.

name: Ivy league
description: Large dirty crack on the NW Buttress. Follow the vertical crack to its end then make a short scramble to the top.    Fun & well protected climbing

name: Solution Crack
description: From Michael Hartman's guide :  "The crack starts around 12 feet from the corner. Climb the crack through the crux and then easy climbing to the top."

name: Chickies Direct
description: P1. 70 feet. To find the start of the climb, walk north and downhill from Witches Brew. The climb starts in a corner at the base of the hill, right where the path levels off. June 13, 2020 we arranged a log near the base of the climb to act as a bench to putting shoes on/off. Climb the wide open corner aiming for a small tree. Climb the steep black face just 5 feet left of the tree (crux 5.7) and you'll find a bolted belay station about 20 feet directly above that small overhanging tree.  P2. 80 feet. take a long romp up and slightly left through easy grassy ledges until you find a new belay station on the roomy ledge with two very fine bolts and rappel chains. Thank you to South Central PA Climbers and the Access Fund!  We need more people to climb this pitch and beat the weeds and grass down, so please take a lap! The new belay station makes it safer and easier.  P3. 60 feet. Climb the overhangs directly above the belay. it's easier than it looks.  Move left and climb the left edge of the arete. The moves are hard 5.8+, very steep. The are many opportunities to escape to the tree gully farther left making it substantially easier. You can also escape to the right by climbing up to the rappel chains at the top of the cliff. But then, you aren't on Chickies Direct.  Make the final moves of Chickies Direct below the summit in the middle of the face where you'll find deep horizontal cracks for gear. This pitch is one of the best at Chickies, it's clean, steep and climbs the highest point of the rock. Be aware that as of Friday May 29 there is a new rappel station on top of Chickies Rock just 10-15 feet to climber's right of the finish of this climb. You can use this rap station to rappel down to the next station (at the top of pitch 2) but if you climb the final pitch and go directly to the chains you've missed the final arete and face climbing of Chickies Direct

name: Chickies Traverse
description: If you're climbing solo this is a great warm-up for the boulder problems in the cave. There are a few cruxy spots and some long sections of sustained climbing. Working from right to left seemed to be a little more difficult. Route can be made much more difficult using eliminates or staying under the heavily overhanging sections.    Great for an after-work solo/no gear required workout.

name: Steppin’ Out
description: P1: Same as Yo YoP2: Climb the corner up and just past the overhang.  Traverse right 10’ over the overhang, then continue up face to ledge then continue up the face and corner to the top. ~100 ft

name: Algae In Your Eye
description: Start on the near vertical face covered in lichens. Work your way up the face, staying left towards the top. Do not use the dihedrals directly under the roof. Once you get to the top work left and the pull the roof. Finish the slabby upper portion to the topout.

name: And Now For Something Completely Different
description: Start below the Pyramid Formation. Head up and right to the right-most base of the Pyramid. Get into the left leaning corner (that is the right side of the Pyramid) and climb the hands to offwidth crack to the pinnacle (obvious) end and take the arete/face to the big belay/rappel tree.

name: The Gun
description: P1 - climb up easy, slabby terrain to the bottom right side of the corner    P2 - traverse left and climb the inside of the overhanging corner.     Tip: on P2 there is a obvious feature you can sling for pro.

name: Heel-a-Peel
description: P1 - climb up to a block below an obvious slighly overhanging crack    P2 - use the crack and with some fancy footwork (HEEL-a-peel) pull the overhang and continue up to the top.

name: Hugh's 11
description: P1 - climb to the bottom of the obvious West (right) facing wall.    P2 - climb the clean(er) crack (there's several features but this crack you can clearly make out with the naked eye from the ground, its the obvious clean(er) splitter on the West facing wall).

name: Metamorphosis
description: A wonderfully fun climb. The second pitch is the "money" pitch for sure.     P1 - climb straight up (make your way up) to a two bolted belay that sits just below the overhanging rock.     P2 - you start immediately pulling the first overhang (protected by a bolt) and climb straight up through two vertical sections to the top. There is a large evergreen +/-15ft back from the cliffs edge (probably slung with webbing but don't count on it!) to belay and rappel from.    Use your best judgement for the descent. 1 60m won't make it in one rapp. Use the bolted belay as a second rappel point. Two 60m will make it in one rapp.

name: Monkey See, Monkey Do
description: Traditionally done in two pitches but could be done in one.    P1: Climb the corner (+/-25ft) to the obvious ledge.    P2: traverse all the way left to a Pine Tree. Belay and rappel from this tree.    Second pitch is unique but fun.

name: The Point
description: AKA Get the Point AKA Joint Point   Jam, cling, and swing out the crack to the top. The crux is making the first move. Don't look down or it becomes 5.9

name: Raven
description: Start up & right past tree, then aim for notch & overhang. With careful pro and creative footwork, move up through the notch. Finish at the good tree to the right.

name: Under the Gun
description: From the belay tree, traverse left on big ledge, then up the exciting and exposed vertical section to the tree.

name: Warrior's Way
description: Start by following the crack up to the overhang. Traverse right onto good feet, then up. Finish by angling up and right through the overhang.

name: Baited Breath
description: Great little shorty slab. For this variation, use the left arete

name: Bucket Seat
description: A 3 move wonder, start as low as humanly possible

name: Clam Shell
description: Start under the clam shell roof and mantle to the top. One move, hard

name: Firestone
description: Same as Baited Breath but you only get the little dishes

name: Wild Trader
description: Big moves between shelves on the right side of the cove

name: Heed the Harpies
description: Open project behind the Siren Song on the overhang, terrible landing

name: Siren Song
description: Very relaxed warmup climb, just bring chalk and don't fall, the landing is not flat.

name: Dingbat Swing
description: Sit Start, Top Out Start with hands in the horizontal. Move out to a small crimp on the right side of the roof. Balance to bump the right hand up to the good square cut hold (use an undercling under the roof if you need to). Use holds over the top of the next roof to topout. There’s neat leg beta for this route.

name: El Dabbo
description: A variation of Take a Stand, start sitting with hands in the large horizontal crack just right of the arete. At the first crimp/sidepull go up and left and up through a crimp to 2 very large pockets. Go through the pockets and ledge above them, find the mondo meat hook jug over the top and left and top out. Try not to dab on the back wall. Note: For the sake of not dabbing it might be easier to only use one pocket for hands, and yes not dabbing is hard and is probably the crux of this route.

name: From East to West
description: Climbs surprisingly differently to its companion route. Depending on how you do it this route can be a one move wonder. The best sitting position for the start of this route is probably on the rotting log. Start with hands on a good hold on the arete, get feet on the face and make either a long move or a couple short moves up to the point. Top out over the point. Do not use surrounding rocks for feet, do not use the left arete (until the top out because you have to grab over the point).

name: From West to East
description: Use the rock under the point of the climb to start. Start sitting using hands on the lowest part of the left arete just above the roof that holds Scarab and a heel hook. Lay back and follow holds on the left arete and a good sidepull to the point. Top out over the point. Avoid using holds on the right arete for the duration of the climb (until the top out because you have to grab over the point).

name: Headless
description: Start standing with hands on the obvious formation. Move up through a horizontal and good holds to the slopey top out.

name: Holden Miup
description: Start using the horizontal on the arete for hands with a distinctly shaped foot below in whatever position is most comfortable for you. Move up and right through a crimp/sidepull/pinch/sloper(options from bottom to top of the prominent left facing sidepull) and then left up to a sloping ledge. Do the crux press move to get good feet for the top-out just left of the top boulder in the boulder stack.

name: Horseman
description: Start sitting with hands on the obvious flake. Go up through sidepulls to the top out.

name: Loftie Awkies
description: A sharp awkward arete climb. Start sitting with left hand on a sidepull and right hand on a slim sidepull flake. You may have to uncover the foot ledge. Stand and get a right hand on a triangular feature. Choose any number of good holds on the left, find a good hold on the right and top out straight up the arete.

name: Obelisk
description: Start sitting (squatting if your butt doesn’t reach your pad) on a high right pinch and a low left pinch. Do compression moves up slopers/slimpers on the right arete and underclings on the left arete until you can get a position where you are able to reach over the top to flat holds (prominent flake that’s over the slopey lip) top out straight up scooting your way over the lip. Any surrounding rocks that are not attached are off (Including the rock that makes up the right side of the crack to the right of this face).

name: Pinchotchaun
description: A one move wonder route. Start matched on a deep staggered pocket on the leftmost end of the horizontal crack that goes the whole way up the boulder. Find feet and move up to a crimp. Stand up and top out. All of the surrounding detached blocks are off.

name: Scarab
description: Start underneath the boulder under a wide roof, starting as far down as your wingspan allows. Make some compression moves straight through the cave and top out using a conveniently located horizontal. Detached Blocks are off for feet.

name: Take a Stand
description: Start sitting with your choice of good holds at the bottom. Undercling and horizontal ledge are the major options. Find a way to stand and move through good holds to an easy topout.

name: Warden Arete
description: Start sitting at the arete using the small flake system on the left of the arete and an undercling on the right. Using cramped feet find a way to stand up and throw right, then on to a slopey topout

name: "23 Project"
description: Grab the lip above the dihedral and exit.

name: "Trailside Project"
description: Slopers and small feet lead to mantle exit

name: Exhibit A
description: Any first time visitors eyes will be automatically drawn to this line.  Two obvious holds are the only features on the 45 degree wall, the first boulder one encounters on the walk into Mt Gretna.      Not quite 45 degrees, this problem begs to be climbed.  Begin on a sharp right hand undercling and the three finger pocket for the left hand.  There is a large foot to start on.  Heel or toe hook the ramp on the right and move up to the gorgeous slopers at the lip.  It is possible to go with either hand.  Topout on the Fabulous finishing rail.  It will  help if the conditions are sticky.    There is a great video of the first ascent on the 2001 film Hard Gret.  Dynamic movement on finely grained slopers makes this a must do.

name: Fabulous
description: Farthest right problem on the 45. Sit start low on small pinches and make a big throw over a slopey lip to a small seam. From the seam hit the huge obvious jug then cross into another seam, mantle up and it's all over. Really fun.

name: The Adjustor
description: The Adjustor is one of the better known problems of it's grade at the main Mount Gretna area, but is not one of the best quality problems.  The name comes from holds breaking on the upper half after the first ascent, which required an adjustment in movement and beta and how to use the new and different handholds.  The sequences and handholds went through changes for the first couple of years.  Today, and for the last nine years or so, everything has stayed solid.      Begin by sit starting with your butt on the ground or on a single pad.  The right hand is in a large, incut triangular tooth down low and the left hand on a gaston three-quarter pad edge.  The starting footholds are large and flat, especially for diabase.  The hips should be in close to the wall.  Pull on and rock up hard on the right foot to grasp the main hold of the climb; a gaston that is held with the right hand and contains a contorted thumb catch underneath.    Perch the right foot on the right hand starting tooth and shove in a marginal right knee scum beneath the diagonal roof to keep you in close to the wall for when you release a handhold.  Bump the left hand to a undercling on the roof feature with the elbow sticking straight up.  Shift the right foot up a few inches to a good foothold.  Release the right hand from the gaston to reach the right hand again high to a sloping edge feature.  The middle, index and pinky fingers should go on a three finger tiny diagonal crimp that lies over a subtle sloper, while the index finger alone grabs a tiny edge that faces  diagonally but at a 90 degree angle change from the other fingers, kind of like a star.      Keep tension and reach the left hand to a broken, third pad left facing sidepull edge with a bit of an incut.  This hold is one of those that broke, but what is left now is fairly solid and good.  Stand up high and run the feet up and left a bit so you can bust the right hand to the good flat lip.  From here it is over, get the left hand up to a hold just beneath the lip and mantel with the right leg.      The whole idea of this bloc is tension.  The holds are poor and none of the moves are particularly long.  It is just about making intermediate movements between bad holds that all face the wrong way.  If one of your appendages does not execute correctly or loses contact with the rock for more than a second, you are off.    All in all, this is a cool problem and you will feel great if you can figure it out.  It seems so simple upon first glance, but is much more difficult than it appears.  The slash grade comes from it being V8 if the features and length between the holds fit you, which seems to be about 5'11'' +/- one inch.  If you are shorter like me at 5'7'', it seems harder.  I don't know about tall guys over 6 foot.  They may have an even easier time on it.

name: Long Dong
description: This short problem climbs the protruding boulder just left of the Adjustor boulder with it's climbs Equilateral (V7) and The Adjustor (V8).  It is a short compression climb that is the only lie down start that I know of at Mt. Gretna.  Lie/sit down under the roof and grasp the opposing aretes.  Slap one or two moves up to the flat lip with some frustration and then mantel.

name: Great White
description: Start matched on a positive sidepull on the left-hand side arete of the boulder.  Follow the slopey arete to the top utilizing some crimps on the face or huck off the marginal feet.

name: Slopey Feature
description: Its all in the first move with this one. Start low on odd sloped feature, figure out your feet then pull hard with the core and pop to the good hold up high. High step and top out.

name: Teen Spirit
description: Scramble up this surprisingly fun arête but dont expect any edges this is friction climbing territory.

name: Cheap Shot
description: Start under the roof right on a good undercling. Using detached block for feet, traverse left and reach for the edge of the roof. Pull up and grab a spine like feature that leads to the jug and mantle up.

name: Pickin' the Bone
description: Starts with a low left hand, right hand on right slopey feature. Smack up and left to a good slopey edge. Top out from there.

name: Ping
description: Sit start in corner with good side pull then move up to positive lip. Shimmy to the right a bit before topping out.

name: Pong
description: Sit start at base of arête on solid crimps and pull to positive holds directly above. Reach for a positive crack and pull to top.

name: Triangle
description: Pretty cool little problem on the side of the Ping Pong boulder. Start low on a giant triangle feature and move up through edges and slopers to a tricky topout

name: Corporate Strategies
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Omega Zen
description: Clean rock, good edges and fun moves make this arguably the best in grade at Gretna.

name: Scarlet Lady
description: Fantastic slab dancing.  Find the sequence up the face and keep it together at the top.

name: Beautiful Day
description: The reason you'd come to this area.  Start matched on obvious high start hold and work your way through crimps and gastons to a jug, then make a long reach high to a side pull and on to an easy top out.  Great Problem!

name: Brady Arete
description: Another great problem ascending the arete of the boulder to the right of Beautiful Day.  Start on obvious holds and work your way up the arete then transition onto the slab and top it out.  It's possible to bail onto the beautiful day boulder if you get sketched, but i think the hardest moves are lower.  That being said it's scary as hell up there.

name: Finger Fun
description: Obvious hand crack to the right of the tall slab of the central boulder in the cluster.

name: Right Arete
description: The area warm up.  Start sitting on the lower block, move out the roof, mantle on the boulder, and up the mossy slab/arete.  Just put your feet where the green ain't.  Not as scary as the rest of the problems here, and not a bad beginner route.

name: Sick Slab
description: I'm not 100% sure about the grade on this one.  If you go straight up the slab and stay away from either arete, which are both their own seperate problem, then i think it's not only hard but horrifying as well.  Get's 800 comp points if that's any indication of the grade, which i'm not sure it is.  If you bail out right toward the top it's a little more managable but still has quite a pucker facctor.

name: Feel My Pain
description: Locate a line of ultra thin crimps in the center of the boulder.  Start in a tiny horizontal seam with virtually no feet.  Crank up to two ridiculously thin crimps.  Maybe get a foot up to a miserable smear.  Launch for the flat one pad edge directly above and mantel it.      Hideously thin, one of the crimpiest in the forest.  Quite miserable, ultimately rewarding when sent. One of those problems I just had to do, because it made me so frustrated.

name: Hero
description: Start on a crimpy seam with marginal feet.  Gain slopers at the lip and mantel.  Finish up the slab.

name: Left Bookend
description: Layback finger crack on left side of boulder. Move up to positive holds at lip then smear your way onto slab and finish. Bring a brush to clean face.

name: Right Bookend
description: Follow edges up the right side of the boulder.

name: Bashista Yo Sista
description: A cool, powerful, intricate climb. To send this climb specific beta is what you KNEED.     Sit start or squat if you cannot reach the starting holds. Start right hand in a good single pad undercling and left on the sloper rail. Move up the narrow block compressing with your whole body until you hit the good hold on the lip, from here climb around the right side of the block to a tough top out.    This would get 4 stars however, the close proximity to the rocks on either side make it less than classic because of the dab potential.    Also apparently on the FA it was topped out fairly straight on but that feels very contrived and after talking to several locals the new standard and most natural line is to top out on the right side. When I climbed it I found this to be the most natural way, topping out straight up takes away from the quality of this great line.

name: Squeezematic
description: Sit start with a left hand on the left arete, and right hand in a good ledge on the right side of the bulging feature. Wrestle your way up the boulder to a good gaston crimp, pull and top out from there.

name: Slice
description: Stand start on a low foot rail and use small crimps for hands. Step up on the crimp rail and move out left. Slap up the side to reach a small crimp. Topout from here.  Note: the crimps will wear on your fingertips - the name says it all!

name: Clutch
description: Start left on sloping on the left side of the boulder. Right on crimp (Freshly broken 11-2018). Move feet and hands to big seam--then finish with giant undercling.

name: "15 Project"
description: Thin holds to slopers at the lip. Exit via an engaging mantle.

name: Body Snap
description: Start on the prow of the boulder around the corner from Colflesh boulder. You'll walk across a log to get there.Start with a decent right hand and a low left hand crimp, make the first move to the pinch and move to the right hand out to an edge, from there work up to the top out.

name: Body Snap Sit
description: An area classic, one of the most tried in all of Gretna!    Sit start with a good undercling and a crimp. Pull up and snag the side pull, pick some feet and make crux long move out left to good crimps. Follow the crimps left up to a big sloper. Then make a tension move to the lip to a causal topout.    Although this is called Body Snap Sit the only move it shares with Body Snap is the top out.

name: Energy
description: Sit start low then climb little arête and move right at top to finish out on easy slab.

name: Havit
description: This problem may be over in just a few moves but figuring out how to get into sequence can take some time. Stand and match on good edge then move up to top of shallow scoop. Pull through and finish.

name: Bacon
description: Shares a start with Homefries (V0) and Ham (V0) - all good warm-ups. Stand start and climb left side of steep slabby face to good holds and left exit.

name: Green Eggs
description: Gird your loins for this one! A fall at the top is definitely a bad idea.  Start on easy holds to fun mantel then reach for sloppy rail high above. Man up (or woman up) and smear blank face to reach jug at top.

name: Gumdrops
description: Short problem on dirty face. Move up on good edges to top, mantel and finish.

name: Ham
description: Another great warm-up between Homefries (V0) and Bacon (V0). Stand start and climb center of steep slab face straight up to top.

name: Homefries
description: Homefries is a great warm-up problem but hardly the give-me V0 you might expect.  Stand start and climb right side of steep slab face to jug and right exit.

name: Pancakes
description: Great moves on positive holds. Start on side-pull and stand up to large horizontal then move to nice finger jam in crack and crank up onto better holds above. Finish on easy slab.

name: Scrapple
description: Climb this little guy for a quickie ride on a surprisingly fun V0. Sit start on obvious holds then move to lip and jugs above. Setup for a high step and finish.

name: Colflesh Direct
description: The obvious hard line up the center of the Colflesh boulder, left of Jenn Savage.

name: Jenn Savage
description: Start on head high crimps, crank to positive edge then move up to lip and easy slab above.

name: Malcolm X
description: Starts to the left of Colflesh, climbs straight up the face to about 16 ft.

name: Oh Shit
description: Sit start on low holds then move up to rail and match. Move out to crimp in middle of scoop and then finish on slab to the top.

name: Path Less Traveled
description: Work your way up the slab with long moves between good holds

name: Poison Ivy
description: Great sustained bouldering on long traverse. Good footwork required. Start far left on large hold then traverse right and up diagonal crack to nose. Finish straight up on good holds and easy slab.

name: Terretti
description: Start on head high sloper and low side pull. Move left to positive edge before pulling lip and finish.

name: Balance Issues
description: Start foot in crack and use crack under-cling. Balance to shallow crimp and top out right. Short but fun.

name: Inner Light
description: Fun little warmup. Start on left side of slab and climb straight up using small edges and smearing.

name: Outer Dark
description: Left of Inner Light. Two variations.    Variation 1: Start by compressing the bulge. Head left out to a great ledge and then straight up the finger crack to top out.    Variation 2: Start by compressing the bulge. Traverse right using bomber underclings and finger jugs. Climb over the arete onto the slab and finish out on Inner Light.

name: Nectar Vector
description: Sit start at arete and follow obvious edges and jugs to top. Fun.

name: Sweet Nector
description: Stand Start with your left hand in a high "pocket" (where two seems create a small gap) and right hand on a crimp. Gain high right foot and grab far right undercling. Top out on slopers. The top is a wrestling match but there's probably some good foot beta that will make this part easier.

name: Sur La Pointe
description: Sur La Pointe is a Joel classic.  He was all about this problem at the time and it has a very nice name (look up the definition).  This is a challenging and tricky one move wonder dyno from a perfect one pad edge that accommodates eight fingers.  The right toe frontpoints in a small, shallow pocket, smear the left foot and launch for the sloping lip!      Surprised you only gained a few vertical feet?  It is difficult to generate any pull with the hands at all, everything is about leaping with the right toe pocket.  It very much helps if you have a new edge on your shoes.  I tried this probably 50 times before succeeding.

name: Goofy Foot
description: Stand with hands matched in the seam. Move feet up and toss to the top. Find good feet and top out.     There is also a lower start with a tiny crimp and the arête. It doesn't add much but it could be fun to play around on. Have fun.

name: Hang Ten
description: Gain slab via step up to large jug.  Match crimps then grab a jug and throw to the top.  Kinda scary.

name: Maverick
description: Stand start with hands matched on good holds. Find your feet and stand up to a good crimp. Bring your left foot up to the big foot and throw up to the arête just under the lip. Move your feet around and go for the top. Top out the problem.

name: Agrobat
description: start on the right side of the lowball rock on the side of the trail. work your way around and left using heel hooks, snag a crimp and mantle.

name: Every Saucer Has A Silver Lining
description: Sit start on the left side of the boulder on a jug below the lip.  Move up to the lip and traverse the lip and top out on the far right side of the boulder using a jug.

name: Mini Saucer
description: Sit Start on the right side of the boulder with hands on the lip, traverse the lip and mantle.

name: Momentary Lapse of Reality
description: Sit start on crimps and move right through more crimps towards the tree, slap the slopers at the lip and mantle.

name: Rainbow Goat
description: Stand start using a sidepull and undercling move up the the slopers at the lip and mantle.

name: Brady Arete
description: The Brady Arete is the prominent steep arete to the right of The Original Route and connects with "Original Route" at the Thank God jug 3/4 the way up the boulder. It is certainly the most serious highball in all of Mt. Gretna.  Joel Brady caused quite a stir among us locals when he completed this long eyed project during a visit around 2004.  Not only is it incredibly highball and proud, but a pointed rock lies embedded in the ground directly underneath the fall zone.      Start standing and climb up to a flat jug on the corner around ten feet up.  Take a deep breath, then begin the horrifying journey up the next fifteen feet through rarely traveled terrain.  The right face is flaky and not the best rock quality.  On the plus side, it is peppered with tiny flaky edges.  The upper portion appears to utilize the arete for both hands in some spots, and the left hand on the arete with right hand on edges on the right face in other areas.      It would be prudent to clean the rock on toprope before attempting, as I am certain the climb has not been tired in quite some time.  Better yet, work the boulder on a top rope before bouldering it out.  Think of it as a headpoint.  Or the best idea may be to skip this climb and move on to a problem that will not risk broken ankles or worse.      If you send this boulder, you have serious street cred in my mind.  I imagine it has seen only a handful of ascents in the ten years after its first ascent.  The Brady Arete is one of the most risky undertakings that I have seen out of all of the diabase areas, save for a few of Char's creations at Haycock.  Only The Yosemite Crack (V10) at Haycock comes to mind as a rival in terms of height and fall potential.

name: Delerium Tremens
description: Delerium Tremens is the alluring east arete.  Begin on the sidepulls at head height.  High step, lock off on the gaston and reach to an edge.  Get established on the face and climb up crimps leading to the obvious pinch on the arete.  Snag the lip with the aid of a crimp on the other wall.  The topout is easy, thankfully.  The crux is the first move and gets progressively easier the higher one climbs.  Until 2003 or so there was a tooth on the initial gaston that make it easier but more painful.

name: HighBall Crack
description: climb the crack on the back of the highball

name: The House of Cards
description: Stand start right of center on a large hold.  Climb up on small crimps, trending slightly left, then back right.

name: Kundalini
description: Sit start the technical and physical sloping arete, using small crimps on the left face.

name: No One's Getting Any Younger
description: Stand start the right side of the north arete and go up using delicate smears and edges.

name: The Original Route
description: This line begs to be climbed.  There is a tempting jug a few feet from the summit.  Climb up thin, incut crimps and sidepulls on the vertical face to reach said alluring hold and the final flake.  In 2000 it was more like V1 but holds have broken.

name: The Squeak
description: start left on the small foot ledge on the back slab of the highball, and work your way right and up on smears and crimps. very tricky.

name: Trickle in Time
description: Trickle in Time is Chet Gross' first masterpiece and probably the most revered problem in all of Mt. Gretna.  It climbs the subtle sloping lip of a steep roof and in true diabase style; surprisingly finicky and technical despite the severe overhang.  A testament to Chet's ability to envision problems from seemingly unclimbable features.      Start sitting on the rail.  Heel hook and head for the triangle shaped hold, which is more of a feature than a hold, that you will utilize for both hands in the near future.  This problem will work your right hamstring.  Get established on this hold (will help if it is cold and not humid), match with a gaston-ish meat wrap grip and make a dynamic move to snag the two and a half finger crimp.  Now you need to attain the sidepull/crack/fingerlock thing with a go-again.  A tiny foot lies far under the overhang for the left foot to aid in the transition between crimp and crack.      The crux is over, toe hook the left foot on the starting rail which will allow you to hook your right heel over your hand (probably the only time I have ever had to do this on diabase) to grope the right hand up your choice of a blank wall around the corner or a sharp arete, aiming for the apex of the arete with the top of the boulder that forms a nice pinch.  A right knee scum is possible.  Pull around the right face, traverse the lip and topout.  This problem has been done as an eliminate without using the crack and is most likely V9 that way.        Trickle in Time is the problem that almost everyone considers the benchmark for V8 at Mt. Gretna.  It is a problem that feels impossible until one works out the subtitles.  In optimal conditions with low temperature and humidity, this problem feels easier. (in my opinion it could be a sandbag V6 at one or two granite bouldering areas I can think of).  A guaranteed full body workout.

name: V6 Slab
description: Start on a large high right foot and move up using friction and intricate footwork to a final dynamic move to a flat edge, then top out.

name: The Breadloaf
description: This problem sits front and center and just begging to be climbed! Stand start on far left of the boulder and traverse across finger crack topping out at the far right.

name: Crazy Game of Poker
description: Start in the hole and climb out on surprisingly good for Gretna holds.

name: Lonely Boy
description: Stand/Squat start in an awesome corridor down from "Crazy Game of Poker". Follow the only pure holds all the way up and out of the corridor WITHOUT touching the rock behind you for the full value! If you "DAB" the top out by touching the rock behind you, its like the rock has your spot, but makes it a little easier! Another CLASS-SICK Problem for the already cool Lower Matrix Area, F.A.'ed by John Carriere!

name: Spring Chicken
description: There are several excellent cracks in the lower Matrix, but this one is the longest, the hardest, and the scariest. I am not sure what you call a sit start below ground level in a cave, but suffice it to say you start quite low.  Jam your way up to where it gets wide and you can jam no more; them layback the offwidth until you can top out through the hole in the roof.  The jammy part is pretty casual because the ground follows you up as you climb out of the hole so the fall isn't much of a concern; the layback however has the potential to dissect you in half should you peel off.  It is suggested that a pad be used to cover the obvious giant axe feature. The rating is debatable, a crack climber would probably call it 5.11. A visiting climber from the Czech Republic for example flashed it and said it was the funnest thing he had climbed in Pennsylvania, while local bouldering mutants were unable to get off the ground.

name: Jolie
description: Sit start matched on a flat jug, make big moves left onto crimps and use tricky beta to move around the blunt arete.  Reach up and grab a hold the forms the corner with the porcelain slab and top out, it is a little spooky near the top.

name: Needle to the Vein
description: Fun one move wonder near Porcelain. Start on bad hands and a bad foot and make a long move to a not great hold. From there, hit the jug and top out

name: Particle Man
description: Use flakes and crimps to move up this short slab.

name: Porcelain
description: A beautiful problem and a slab lovers dream. Climb straight up center of face on delicate holds.  Fantastic!

name: Reunion
description: Route shares boulder with Needle to the Vein. Start with right hand in the seam and left on the arete. Go up.

name: Shroom Star
description: Sit start on crimps, move up to sloppers then high step and pull for top. Good diversity for a short problem.

name: Crouching Tiger
description: Start matched on a big flat side pull with feet wide right to a vertical edge. Drop left to the crimps and reposition feet to shoot to the top. Various options--tiny u-shaped micro-crimp, slopers wide left and on top. A little contrived.  Good practice for diabase top-outs

name: The Green Marble Arete
description: Climb the left arete of the Green Marble boulder.  Start by stepping up onto a rock at the base to gain jugs.  Make long moves to grab the left facing flake and then the flat top of the flake.  All of the holds are huge.  Then a big move to the juggy lip.  This problem is in my opinion the best easy highball in all of Mt. Gretna!  It is characterized by long moves to big gym style holds to a tall but easy top out.  The grade is about 5.9+ or easy 5.10.

name: The Green Marble
description: The Green Marble (Direct) route starts on the left arete of the Green Marble boulder.  Climb the start of the Green Marble Arete route (the left arete) by stepping up onto a separate small rock underneath.  Gain the left facing flake low, then bust right to the hanging jug rail that lies over the bulge.  Go right for another move to a finger bucket with the right hand and highstep the left foot and mantel to the juggy lip.  A real hair raiser!

name: Year of the Dragon
description: Year of the Dragon is a bit of an anomaly for Mt. Gretna.  It climbs a slightly overhanging face on, gasp, actual holds!  Plus, the sequence is not cryptic.     Start sitting on two crimps.  Backstep and work up solid, small crimps to the obvious, beckoning sloping pinch.  This hold is one of the best in all of Mt. Gretna.  Slap out left around the slight corner to a sidepull.  Keep it together and squeeze the right arete to topout.      I always felt that it helped to be tall for this problem.  I could never keep my feet on while moving from the pinch, while I watched Ernie have no problem with it over and over.  I consider this a benchmark problem for V6 at Mt. Gretna.  Of course, that is assuming optimal conditions.  The pinch will feel impossible to hang onto in the summer.  There is an excellent video of this problem on the 2001 film Hard Gret.

name: Downramp
description: Good climb for little kids or good way to downclimb off the boulder.

name: Modest Man
description: A jug-o-licious romp whose only problem is its over too quick.

name: Mojo Inhibitor
description: Start by sitting and grasping a sloping edge with the left hand and an opposing sloping feature pinch with the right hand. Bust up and left to a sloper. If you're short--come right back into the right crimp on the middle of the face.  Work up and perch on a right then transition to a left heel hook on the left hand starting hold to reach sharp holds up on the angle change of the arete.   OR   Dig left toe under the roof on left collection of nubbins. Throw hard to the left crimp, then deadpoint toss from there straight to jug on arete.  Follow the arete up an easy low angled finish. This is an amazing compression problem.  *Start beta - People have started this boulder with a right heel and a right hand on the starting hold--The guidebook suggests starting with only the hands on. Do whichever, great pebble.

name: Transform
description: Slightly harder than its sister climb Transform but soft for the grade. Start in crack then slap out left and then up.

name: Crimptonite
description: Stand start the two lowest crimps in the diagonal seam. Bump up to a decent crimp and get ready and toss up to the slopers at the lip. Pick some feet and go for the crimps up and left. Throw a heel up and top out.    There is a low start on a left hand crimp and a sharp right hand crimp throwing up to the rail that has been done.

name: Roller-coaster
description: Squat start with hands matched on a good hold. Pick some feet and pop up to a good crimp with your left,  bring your right hand up and match. Swing up to the lip and pull over for the top out.

name: The Shadow Gallery
description: Stand with your hands matched on a small but good crimp. Pull up and rock over the good foot out left, lock in your core and reach up and match on a good set of crimps. From here get ready to commit to the crux, gently move up to the slopers while moving your feet up, just when you think you are going to pop make a quick move to the jug at the lip.

name: The Zipper
description: Stand start with a good left hand and a slopey right. Work your right foot up to a good smear. Zip to the top with your right hand and latch the good lip. Bring your feet up and top out.

name: Fury Road
description: Sit start as for Mad Max. Work your way up and right to top out to the right of the roof, on good holds.

name: Mad Max
description: Sit start matched on a big jug with a heel hook and throw right to a good sidepull. Move your feet around and toss to a decent left crimp. Bring your heel in closer to you and reach up for a small right crimp. Relax yourself a little and bump your left to a higher crimp. Find some good feet and prepare to shoot up to an ok hold with your right. Once you are here work your way left into the top out of Mad Max Direct.

name: Mad Max Direct
description: Stand start on two incut crimps above head height. Throw up to a good hold with your right rearrange your feet and grab the good hold with your left. This is where it gets a little spicy. Pull up and lock off with your left and reach up high for a good crimp above the lip. Find the feet and rock up to two more crimps. Climb the slab to the top.

name: Astroboy
description: No beta spray here. Just a big offwidth/ squeeze chimney on clean rock that beckons to be climbed. Stand start on the microwave sized blocs in the back of the crack. Traverse out the crack to the jug and pull the lip.

name: Chets Children
description: Stand start and climb face to good hold at top.

name: cousin IT
description: same start hold as IT, reach out right to crack. work your way out the crack to the lip. mantel on the lip and top out. keep feet to the left on IT. **right wall is off**.

name: Dark side aka Teachers Pet
description: Squat start with good holds and a decent chip for your left foot and big rail for right. Pull up to a gaston grab a crimp and reach for the top.

name: Islander
description: Definitely worth a mention in any conversation debating the best route at Gretna, and could stack up against any area classic anywhere.  Both the sit (V8) and the stand (V7) are amazing.  The sit used to be V9 but a hold broke and brought it down a grade. No matter how you start it the top is tricky and there are a few different ways to do it.  Whether you go with a heel hook, match, or all out dyno is up to you. No matter what you chose you'll be happy you stuck it.

name: IT
description: On your way up the hill toward Islander and The Prow, don't miss this little beauty.  Okay maybe beauty is going a bit too far, as i've heard it described as "the best ugly problem ever."      Start low under the roof on huge holds.  Work out through on pinches and in-cuts gradually setting up for a sweet meat wrap.  Work the face on some crimps then top out.  Loads of fun.

name: The Prow
description: Jutting out into the air like a ship's bow, enshrouded in mystery by the cryptic elephant skin diabase texture like a vessel in the mist, sits The Prow.  Technical, physical, involved and committing, this problem embodies everything of Mount Gretna and the rock type.  The sit start to the Prow is my all time favorite diabase boulder problem out of all areas in Pennsylvania, a state I was born in and never left until the age of 20.  I grew up on Mount Gretna Road, just a ten minute drive from the main boulder field.  I have a special connection with this problem. The stand start at a stiff V5 was one of my first V5's.  I completed the sit start to The Prow on April 1, 2003.  I remember that day vividly.  It was one of the first advanced boulder problems I had ever completed, both mentally and physically.  It took me probably 7 to 10 visits to do the stand start, and by the time I was working the sit start full line a season later I was doing the stand three to five times in a day in preparation.    I understand that now a hold has broken and it is most certainly the crucial left hand half pad three finger sidepull crimp that has enlarged.  The stand start is a sandbag or solid at the grade at V5.  Right hand up anywhere you want on the arete, scrunch up, and highstep onto the blade.  The right foot will be smearing on a downsloping feature, if it blows you will graze your shin on the underside of the roof.  A large deadpoint for a one pad left hand sidepull immediately follows.  It is the largest hold on the problem but is utilized for a very short period of time.  Delicately balance your way around the right arete after more slapping, 1/3 pad sidepulls and a high right foot smear.  There are at least three ways to get to the lip; technical and in control, shouldery and barndoorish, or all out dyno.  I prefer the former.      For the full V7 or V8 sit start line that nearly doubles the length and quality of the problem, start underneath the roof blade in a true sit start and work around left on solid, almost one pad crimps.  Make a very strenuous pull from a three finger three quarter pad left hand sidepull and grope up and right on the arete to a veiny pinch and swing both feet up and to the right.  It may help to be short on this sequence because it is so scrunchy.  High step like you would off of the ground to begin the stand start then execute the above.

name: Serenity Crack
description: Follow large crack traversing left a few moves before moving up on large holds to top. A good cool down or part of an endurance circuit with other area problems.

name: Testicules
description: Testicules climbs the blunt right arete on the main face of the Warm Up boulder of the Prow area. Begin by pulling onto a large foot with a small left crimp and the right hand squeezing nothing around the blunt corner. A right heel in this same blank, chalky spot will allow both hands to move into a crimpy seam around the left side of the feature. Delicately transition to slopers at the lip, then snag the incut hold. Pull onto the slab and topout. You may want to scope the topout slab before trying. A cold weather problem.  Testicules is a Gretna classic with great movement. It can be frustrating until one figures out the subtleties. I believe that name may stem from a combination of testicles and Hercules.

name: Vigilante (aka Warm-up Crack)
description: Start with hands high in crack and step up. Follow crack as it tends left and finish on good holds and slab.

name: Vigilante Direct
description: Start as for Vigilante which some call the Warm Up Crack.  Get off the ground and where the crack turns left head straight up and onto the slab above.  The holds are not obvious from the ground and will most likely have no chalk but they will appear upon closer inspection.

name: White Dwarf
description: Grab the obvious jugs in the crack pull up for a good crimp and grab the undercling in the crack. Reach up high for the top then go left for the top out.

name: Beat Box
description: Sit start on a left hand sidepull and a right hand edge. Fire up to a good crimp and bust to the sloper lip. Either mantle there or traverse out left and top out on the arete, either is acceptable.

name: Bow Hunter
description: Start on big jug/crack on blunt arête and move straight up to positive holds above, step up and mantel.

name: Deer Hunter
description: Sit start far right in good horizontal. Move left to good jug then crank to positive holds on rounded lip above and finish.

name: Fugitive
description: Stand Start with a left sidepull on the face and the highest crimp on the right arete with the right, pull on set the left foot and huck to the left arete.  Pinch the top saddle and fight to keep the right foot on as it inevitably slides off due to the dirt and moss covering the right face of the boulder and top out.

name: Ninja Gaiden
description: You dont have to be a Ninja to climb this one although it would help. Start on crimps and move to a good hold at base of left trending crack. Then establish your feet and follow the crack left around arête to easier ground and top.    The guidebook rates this a V4.

name: Profile of a Fugitive
description: The low start to "Fugitive", start low on crimps and a solid right toe hook. Pull right into better crimps, then prepare for a big dyno to the left lip.

name: Shady Flake
description: Start about head high on razor crimps. . . get used to them because you fight your way up many more directly up the face.

name: Sumbitch
description: An easy warm-up problem with a fun little finish.  Start on right side of boulder and ride the arête to the top.

name: Tony Danza
description: Like Tony Danzas talk show, this slab problem is mediocre and short lived. Climb straight up easy slab to top.

name: Balance or Power
description: Balance or Power is one of Dr. Torretti's top ten contributions to Mt. Gretna, and that is saying a lot.  He has put up many of the best problems-especially the technical ones- (like 50-100) in this main area and at the surrounding satellite areas.      The climb begins sitting or crouching with hands on a large hold on the left end of the boulder.  Some people will do a kind of standing start but with hands still on the hold.  For full value, start sitting.  Mantel this hold and reach up with the left hand to a huge sloper on a bulge.  Slap around on this large feature and lean way right to grab a crimpy, inset seam which shoots straight right for ten feet.  Getting established with both hands on the seam from the basketball sloper is probably the most difficult individual move, but every following move requires nearly similar exertion.  Tick tac right along the crimpy seam with zero footholds.  Your feet will be pawing on a steep wall for worthless smears with your butt out.  After a handful of moves, you will have gained the right side of the boulder where you can mantel on a sloping lip.      Joel used to make this problem look graceful, and I made it look thrutchy.  So the question is: balance, or power?

name: Capacitator
description: Sit start with left hand on slim crimp, right hand on sidepull pinch under the crack. High foot, slap out left to a sloper than pull through to jug. top out from there, about 7-8 ft.

name: Help Meat
description: Several hard moves in a short space with nearly the perfect landing below, a great problem to get on if you are bouldering alone. Stand start on crimps and move up to next set of crimps then to slopers on edge. Bear down, find your feet and slap to the rim above. Top out.

name: Josh in the Box
description: This rig looks casual as approaching it due to it diminitive size and straight forwardness but don't be fooled this little line packs a punch!    Sit start on the same hold as you would for The Box (v8), put your left foot out on the large foot hold out left and press your way up to the obvious crimp 3 feet above, match the crimp and top out.

name: Knuckles of Evil
description: Sit start on left edge and right seam edge. High heel and reach up to crimp and mantle to the lip.

name: Sneaker Crack
description: Sneakers are optional, falling is not! Climb obvious wide crack up slabby face. Either layback the crack or take it straight on. It will not present any problems.

name: Choppy
description: Sit start, left on sloping edge, right newly broken flat crimp. Find the toe, hit the pinch sloper (hold it son), then kill it. One move wonder to good hold. Right crimp broke November, 2018.

name: Free Time
description: Start on a flat crimp and an incut crimp under the roof.  Reach the side pull in the rough crack and jump for the coarse jugs above the lip.

name: Baby Signs
description: Scramble up this easy arête.

name: Decepticon
description: Technical, tall and terrific! Start on thin crimps and find your way up steep slab to finger crack then top out high above.

name: Heaven
description: Heaven climbs the striking seam on the Shamoo boulder.  A longtime project due to its location and just beg to be climbed line.    Begin by pulling onto the wall with a miserable opening in the hairline seam with your left hand and right on a tiny (1/4") crimp).  Cam the right foot into the bottom, wide part of the crack.  Lean left and reach high to hook your right middle finger into the mono.  This hold is not so much of a mono as a tooth for one finger.  Left foot on the most miserable foothold imaginable.  Stand onto it and reach high left hand to where the crack offsets.  Begin strenuous, delicate laybacking to the topout.      The mono is notorious for injuring fingers, and I worry that if my left foot would skate off the smeary edge, one could lose the finger.  Do not let this scare you away from the problem.  The tweakiness can be mitigated by listening to your body.  I have seen this climb flashed.

name: Scary Face
description: Left of shamu, obvious roof. Start on left-most jug and traverse right and top out. Slightly harder variation--dont start with the feet on the block at the bottom.

name: Shamu
description: Shamoo is one of the top ten boulder problems of Mt Gretna.  It embodies all of what diabase climbing is about: small holds, balance and most importantly technique.  Shamoo climbs the striking seam and left arete on the most prominent boulder in the area.     Begin easily enough by laybacking up the left arete whilst smearing.  Work your way into a position where you will be spanning between the arete and crack with your hands and no feet.      Hike the left foot up to nearly nothing, perch for all you are worth and reach up high left to a tiny, nearly unusable sidepull.  Stomp the right smear up, no up further.  Then fire out right for the opening in the crack.  Hug the features for another move, then topout easily.

name: Shamu Dihedral
description: Climb the dihedral to the left of Shamoo, on the same boulder.  Start standing and lieback or stem up the slippery dihedral using a thin crack for the hands to a tall and delicate sloping lip encounter that is guaranteed to raise the heart rate.        Often overlooked due to the popularity of the adjacent Shamoo arete.  I highly recommend this problem if you are looking for a scare similar to that of Shamoo.  With good technique, this climb can be performed without much difficulty.

name: Pet Goat
description: With your hands out left on sloppy edge, climb the long slanting slab to top.

name: Talking to Myself
description: Sit start on low incut jugs, then follow the right arête to the top sloper edge of the boulder. Throw a high right heel and do a hard mantle to finish.  Variation:  Don’t use the arête and go straight up the face on crimps for an increase in difficulty (about 1 grade).

name: Overlord
description: Atypical for Gretna, steep and juggy.  Sit start on the obvious jug and follow the line to the top.  Fun stuff.

name: Overlord Face
description: Low start on two crimp buckets, up to crimp islands, gastogne  and finish to the knob; top out. No arete, finish straight up, dope moderate.

name: Multiple Personalities
description: Multiple Personalities is a unique climb for Mt. Gretna.  It is a traverse which is quite long and involves more than a handful of moves.  Begin by pulling onto an obvious two hand start hold near the right side of a rectangular shaped boulder.  Traverse left across to a slab with delicate feet.  Make a reach into a sharp crack and continue left to the far arete and top out.    There is an addition to the start of this problem.  Start near the right arete and heel hook and traverse into the normal starting hold.  About the same grade.

name: flatliner
description: s.d.s. with a left hand side pull and a seam for your right. move straight up to crimps and then follow the seam out right. top out as you would for "tony's roof".

name: Happy Camper
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: The Outlier
description: Sit start matched on a obvious jug and pick some feet. Pull on and cross right hand to a sloper crimp, then work your way left to the arete. Figure out how to reach the crimp way out left from the mediocre holds of the arete. Once established on the crimp toss up and top out on jugs.

name: Rocky Horror Mantel Show
description: The single most obvious dyno at Gretna. Start on massive horn with a perfectly placed foot hold. Hit the gritty sloper. Hold--maybe cut feet. Grab onto the multitude of jugs up there.  Crux: Top-out. Muscle-up, gripping--ripping--hooking on either the left or right side of the roof.  V8 in the guidebook--difficulty varies vastly with bodytype/strengths.

name: Soul Assassin
description: Start low with bad feet, good left sidepull and poor right hand crimp. Go big up to sloper, and fight your way to the top.

name: Tony's Roof
description: Sit start back in the roof on large, sharp underclings.  Toe hook and utilize a crimpy sidepull to go again to a sloper over the lip.  Other hand on a crimp over the lip, then go for the jug to an easy mantel.  Used to be considered V hard but the discovery of new beta (toe hook) has made it more reasonable.  Tony's Roof is one of the steepest problems in all of Gretna.

name: Wrestling Whales
description: Start matched on a crimp seam all the way to the right of the boulder. Move left and up on the slopers, crimps and seams all the way until you round the corner to the crimps and side-pulls on the arete and mantle up using the big ledge as foot.

name: Paula
description: Sit in the hole match hands in the crack. Get the huge foot below you and a good smear. Smear your heart out and pull up to the good finger lock with your right. Once you get there grab the arete with your left and work your feet around. Get into a layback position to bring your right hand up high and bring your left foot up onto the arete. Rock over to your left and work up to the lip. Top out the climb.

name: Seamstress
description: Squat start with hands crossed and good feet. Pull up to a good crimp with your left. Bring your right up to the crimp just under your left hand. Move your feet around and Reach up high for the good crack. Stand up high and top out.

name: Skate Shoes
description: Stand start with hands on a sloper. Pull up and into the crack to work your way along. Make sure to use the giant ledge bellow you for your feet. When you get to the end of the crack find some good feet and toss for the big jug then top out.

name: Candy Button
description: Stand start the obvious arete to the left of 'Nose Picker'. Start left hand on a good side pull on the left of the arete and right on a small crimp on the right side. Pick some feet and make a long move to the good hold up and right, work your way to the good holds on the top.    Looks like a sit start is possible starting in the corner left of the arete. Im sure it has been done, I have not tried it however.

name: Light Your Mind
description: Light Your Mind climbs the tall vertical face left and around the corner of the Smiley problem.  It starts standing with a tricky long move to small crimp, which is the crux.  Pick your way up crispy edges to a high top out.  The rock quality on this portion of the boulder is not the best on this line, the start hold has broken since the first ascent.  It may be necessary to "Light Your Mind" up with a certain substance to get into a head space where the height is not an issue, if you're into that sort of thing.      It is possible to avoid the tall top out by swinging around right onto the Smiley slab top out by using the large jug on the arete mid way up.  Or add some length and a V grade onto the problem by starting the Smiley problem and moving left around the arete.

name: Nose Picker
description: Stand start matched on the sloper and move right using two crimps before slapping the top sloper of the nose feature.  Continue moving right to a good undercling, set the left foot and heel hook the right foot and go for the jug at the lip of the boulder.

name: Smiley (Left)
description: Boulder is left of smiley, between rock and cheese grater.  Start: Right on diagonal sloping edge that points right. Left on sharpest little crimp @ gretna. Feet on the bar below you. Move deep into the cheese grater, gastogne on edge then very high right foot on sloping seam. Rock right and up and catch small 3 finger intermediate or if you can reach, straight up to great bar. Multitude of tiny edges and sidepulls if you can make it work. V3-V4 climbing on awesome incut crimps as you flow up past any hope of a decent landing, so send it  Would be a fantastic climb if it werent for the chance of potato peeling at the start. V6 if you can just reach the bar.  (Infrequently climbed..)

name: Smiley Face
description: The areas namesake and a must do. Start on rail then find your way out left to positive hold. From there move up face on progressively better holds to easy slab top out.

name: Smiley Right
description: Starts on Smiley, bust up and right to a slim gaston crack. Get your foot up on the start and top out straight up.

name: Smiley Slab
description: Climb up the moderate angle slab on the backside of Smiley boulder.

name: Bisquack
description: Bisquack is the acute corner crack that is formed by the intersection of the Doughboy's Throne boulder on the right (containing the leftward traverse Yeast) and the smaller boulder to the left (containing the rightward traverse Knead It).  Start low and climb the corner crack then top out.

name: Bread Box
description: Bread Box climbs the narrow face that is left of the main, tall Breadloaf boulder face.  It begins with hands in a rectangular slot feature at chest level (the bread box).  A loaf of bread would fit perfectly into this starting hold.  Climb up the vertical face using crimps to reach knobs near the lip and then mantel.

name: Bread Slab
description: Walk up this nice little slab.  This would be a great problem for a first time climber.  It is secure and fun.

name: Breadloaf Arete
description: A classic to end all classics!  High and spicey, Breadloaf arete is a must-do problem at Governor Stable.  Start low on the arete of the giant boulder that looks like a breadloaf i guess, and make delicate moves toward an exciting finish.  Not to be missed!

name: Breadloaf Arete Traverse
description: Start in the center of the wide, tall Breadloaf boulder face on top of the rock at the base near a tree.  Pull onto the rock and traverse rightwards along a horizontal crack with decent edges.  After eight feet or so, climb into the sloping crimp crux of the Breadloaf arete, then finish up the standard problem.

name: Cobra
description: Cobra is widely regarded as one of the best problems at Governor Stable.  Ignore the scary landing and give it a burn, you won't be disappointed.

name: Doughboy
description: Stand Start on a three finger left hand crimp and a small right hand crimp, either dyno or pull on small crimps to grab the lip.

name: Keg Stand
description: Keg Stand starts off of a raised flat boulder at the base.  Hop up to a flat two handed jug hold if you are of normal height (or grasp it with your feet planted if you are very tall) and work up a short bulge to the lip and top out.

name: Knead It
description: Harder than it looks, sit start with good holds and huge foot ledge.  Make a couple hard moves to good holds, then bust up for the juggy lip and make a fun topout.

name: Party Right
description: Party Right starts in the same place as the problem Keg Stand (V2).  Begin by jumping to a large flat jug from standing on a flat rock.  Campus traverse leftwards along a steep wall with poor feet and hands working good edges on "elephant skin" rock features.  Gain the arete/apex and then engage the crux.  Heel hook the right foot on or near the starting jug hold, and then make an insecure and slightly frightening mantel with the left hand meat-wrapping the corner.  There is not really a hold for the right hand on the blank bulge.  Balance and rock up hard and high on the right heel hook perch to reach the sloping lip with the right hand.  Breathe and top out.  This is a challenging problem for the grade but is well worth it.  It is a steep face on good holds which is a rarity on diabase.

name: Pop 'N Fresh
description: This short problem will catch your eye.  Sit start and paw the arete.  Think about it, reposition, pull, and go for the lip!  A novelty problem at its finest.

name: Quickie
description: Great little one move wonder on the boulder in front of Cobra.  Sit start on two sharp crimps, figure out your feet, and fire for the lip.

name: Slap Me
description: Sit start using opposing crimps, slap with the right hand to a sloper, then move up to the crimps and mantle.

name: Soul Face
description: This project will climb the center of the tall face on the downstream side of the Breadloaf boulder.  This tall, alluring face has been contemplated by every visitor to the Stables, since the late 1970's or early 1980's I would imagine.  It is the most obvious project at all of Governor Stables, partly due to it's proximity to the entrance, and also the fact that it is the proudest line on one of the best boulders.      Start off of the flat rock at the base.  Begin on the good holds in the horizontal crack.  Move up to a solitary sidepull, then somehow span the five or six foot blank vertical face to the top of the boulder.  The only feasible way to work this project would be with a top rope, because it is a tall boulder.  The grade is merely a guess, as I had to put something to enter this into the database.  The problem does not seem that hard upon first glance, but believe me, it is a very long reach from the good sidepull to the lip of the boulder, and it is very sloping as well.  Someday, someone very tall may complete this problem.  This is one of the last great projects at Governor Stables.

name: Ungreased
description: Ungreased is a neat little steep slab with smeary feet and some cool subtle handholds.  It would be a perfect problem for a rank beginner, but even I find it very enjoyable.  The movement is sublime, with great rock quality and incredible friction.

name: Vulture
description: In the corridor downhill from Cobra is a 20 degree overhanging face.  Enter the corridor from the Huck face around and right of Juggernaut.  Pull onto two thin crimps at head height.  Get a foot onto a small chip and snatch a slanting one pad crimp with the left hand.  Move up into a large right facing sidepull flake with the right hand and then mantel easily with the aid of jug at the lip.  There is a tall steep slab paralleling this overhang with a horizontal shelf near the bottom.  The landing is precarious in a narrow slot corridor.  It is a poor landing, so bring a good spotter or two and pads.

name: Yeast
description: Another awesome GS traverse on small holds.  Start on the far right side of the boulder just down the hill from the Breadloaf boulder and traverse left, topping out just as you run into another boulder on your left (that one's off).

name: Cave Prow
description: Climb the acute arete to a horizontal crack 3/4 of the way up, then to the top of the boulder.  Navigate to the top of the cave boulder pile or find a way off and down via adjacent boulders.  The difficulty is perhaps 5.8.  I can imagine a young man climbing this prominent, easy prow on the dare of his chums whilst hanging out at the cave before the 1950's.

name: Cave Wave
description: Stand Start using the square crimp on the steep face, the sloping ramp is off for the feet, dyno to the left flat jug and mantle.

name: E Flake
description: Climb up the center of the vertical face on big holds, one of which is a large flake.  The right problem climbs the right side of the face, and the left problem starts on the left and joins the aforementioned climb.

name: Entrance Arete
description: The Entrance Arete is a cool little problem that climbs a sharp, hanging arete that faces inside the cave as you enter the cave from the upstream (entrance to Governor Stable) corridor.  Stand start with hands in a horizontal crack, move though a cool slot, and perhaps grasp a textured pinch on the arete to make a big move to the flat lip.  Mantel here or use the flat shelf above and back to get on top.  I believe the guide has this as V3, but I think it is easier.  This problem is one of the best of it's grade at the Stable, but is mostly overlooked.

name: Entrance Face
description: This is a thin face climb on tiny edges with long reaches on a hanging, steep face.  Start in the center of the blank face crouched or sit if you can on a one hand edge.  This is also the starting hold for Finish Line (V10).  I do not think that the original problem started at this height, rather it started much higher at very thin edges at head or higher height.  Either way, the new school way is to start lower.  Reach to the thin edges described above, then pick your way up a super blank face with almost no footholds to the lip and mantel.  This is the crux.  This is old school problem, hard V5 or most likely even harder.  Good luck.  This thing hardly ever gets climbed.  I have never seen anyone even attempt it.  I have spent too much time trying to get from the tiny edges up high to the lip, and I have not come even close to topping it out.

name: Finish Line
description: Finish Line starts on the Entrance Face hold and traverses left to finish on Entrance Arete.  Crouch or sit start if possible on the flat basically one hand edge in the center of the steep face.  This problem may appear V8 at first, but the dearth of footholds will prove otherwise.  Make a long reach left to a five finger slot.  It will help to have a long ape index to make the reach and skinny fingers to piano match in the slot.  The holds are fairly okay.  Put three fingers of your left hand in the slot, shift the feet, take one out to put the right three fingers into the slot, the surge left to the horizontal crack that marks the start of Entrance Arete (V2 or V3).  Finish up and mantel on Entrance Arete.  This problem was one of the last hard projects to fall at the Stables, and Tony dispatched it in a short time with minimal effort after it had received serious attention by many suitors.

name: J-Crack
description: I can picture a bored or boozy young man venturing up this obvious crack back in the 1920's, 30's or 40's, perhaps on a dare from him chums.  The J-Crack climbs the letter J shaped wide hands/fist crack in a corridor, then exits up and right through a chimney on the tall Cave Boulder.

name: Tissue Issue
description: Tissue Issue is a tall, thin face climb that is in a tight corridor near J-Crack.  The landing is hideous with a pointed immovable rock at the base.  Any fall will land you square on this obstacle.  It is shaped perfectly to snap an ankle.  I would seriously suggest headpointing this problem with a rope prior to bouldering it, and I almost never even consider this option.  It negates the point of bouldering, but considering the difficulty and danger of this problem, may be prudent.    The problem climbs a steep, thin face on diagonal edges with prickly rock and tiny foot chips.  The first couple of moves are very crimpy.  Exit up and to the right.  Prior to the first ascent by Dr. Torretti, it was a long eyed project.  The difficulty and danger kept mortals off of it, until Joel committed to it.  I doubt that it has seen more than a couple of ascents to this day, ten years later.

name: Two Step
description: Stand Start using the square crimp on the steep face (same hold as Cave Wave), the sloping ramp is off for the feet, dyno to the right incut jug directly above and mantle.
A few different problems exist on or near the central arete of the 45 boulder, all are good. The guidebook will be helpful in discerning which is which. All are fairly difficult, ranging from V6-V9.

name: 45 Arete
description: This is the hardest line on the boulder.  For the stand start at V8 pull onto the wall and use tiny right hand sidepull veins to reach a slim slanting edge up and left.  Figure out a way to get up and over the bulge to an impossible looking top out on a steep slab with and finish with a path that is independent of the 45 Left problem's finish, preferably.    For full value and 9 points, link the strenuous sit start into what is described above.  Groping up to the incut flake at the terminus of the scar which forms the starting hold for the 45 stand up problem is hard on the shoulder, and that is the largest hold on the climb.  Getting up into the stand start is difficult as it uses a very thin right hand sidepull crimp and is probably the crux for most folks.  Then the top is a mental battle.  For full disclosure I have not really come close to doing this problem.

name: 45 Center Face
description: Old school B1: crimpy, tall and technical.  I would rarely see this problem attempted.  The line is obvious and intimidating.  Begin by grabbing two thin and bitey crimps which are at the same level.  Highstep and reach way up to the really cool undercling above.  Match and stand up, then deal with the slopey topout which practically guarantees some shivering.  A bit of a sandbag perhaps.  This problem shares a lot of full value characteristics with the Breadloaf Arete.

name: 45 Degree Stand Start
description: Most people stand start towards the right side of 45 wall on obvious good holds and throw a heel on rail and rock up to crimp. Throw for jug and top out.     Alternate start. At one of the GS Comps this problem started further left on crimps and moved right to the two obvious holds. This required extra moves and foot work and made the problem a bit harder (7+). It also made the it a better problem.

name: 45 Degree Wall Sit Start
description: Sit Start at lower right of boulder at the arête, straddling arête, with right hand on good sloper and left hand on crimp under the 45 wall. Work way through decent holds and fire for the jug. Top out.

name: 45 Left
