description: The rock between the 45 Arete and the tall 45 Center Face problem is covered in an intricate pattern of diabase "elephant skin", revealing sidepulls and gastons leading to a cryptic top out.  I am sure adding the sit start into this problem makes it V7 or V8.  The stand start is V6.  This was a really fun problem to figure out and piece together.  Most people put more than a few tries in just discerning body positioning and how to use the holds that are provided.

name: 45 Right
description: Vertical problem to the right of the proudest line on the face which is the 45 Center Face.

name: 45 Traverse
description: Start on the far left side of the 45 and traverse to the high point above the arete.  A little contrived since it's possible to exit early, but still very good.

name: Apex
description: Sit start on a slightly painful small flake and work the left side of the face using the arete up toward the boulder's apex (whodathunk?) and top it out.  Good stuff, kinda hard for the grade.

name: Bigfoot
description: On the side of the boulder opposite planet of the apes, find the triangle jug and the big foot and launch up and right, aiming for the sloper.

name: Butt Crack
description: Neat little thin crack flake overhang on one of the Butt Crack boulders.  It is to the left of Apex and Low Ride on that same boulder.  Sit start and endure a surprising amount of pain compared to how short of a distance you need to climb.

name: Circ Mantel
description: This is a neat little old school novelty problem.  Either jump up to the dish at lip of the boulder bypassing the blank face below, or for an even cooler experience, leap across the chasm from the lower boulder four feet away and hit the face with your feet and the dish with your hands.  Press out the mantel either way you do it.  This is a challenging little 5.9 mantel, perfect for a beginner or a first timer.

name: Dom Don't Know
description: Rated V3 in the guide but hard for the grade. Lie down under the boulder and grab the lowest slot with your left and the high nub with your right and fire a precision deadpoint to a higher slot jug.  A few more easy moves lead to the top

name: Domino
description: Sit start on good left facing edge and right arete. Top 'er out

name: Domino Face
description: Climb the short mellow face left of the arete starting from a large and flat two-handed right facing sidepull.  Pull up to the slightly sloping flat lip and mantel.     For an added challenge, sit start near or on the arete on flat holds and climb up into the sidepull at V1+ or V2.

name: The Gathering
description: At a place known for tricky mantels, The Gathering stands out as one the better, albeit more difficult ones in the preserve.  Start sitting on obvious chalked slopers, fire to the jug, and mantel it out.  Great line.

name: Low Ride
description: Long and slopey, this is one of GS's best. Start down in the pit opposite Apex and climb toward the top.

name: Open Circuit
description: Great problem, long and pumpy with the business coming at the end.  Start matched on huge sidepull jug with high left foot.  Traverse the lip of the boulder, eventually topping out around the corner on the huge foot hold.  The only thing keeping this problem from classic status is that it's a bit contrived in the fact that you could mantle and exit early, dumbing the grade down to about V3/4.  Resist the temptation to do so, going around the corner is worth the struggle!

name: Planet of the Apes
description: Possibly the best V2 at GS. Start sitting with right hand on big jug and left in good slot.  Climb up the arete and top out left or right, either way it's super cool.

name: Slopey Circ Arete
description: Climb this arete from a stand start via super thin crimps and tiny sidepulls on imaginary feet to a slopey lip.  Super balancey.  It will help if the conditions are cold and sticky.  This is one of those problems that seems impossible until you figure out the correct body position.  A shift of the hips a few millimeters can make all of the difference.  Bring some fresh edging shoes like a brand new pair of Miura's.

name: Slopey Circ Mantel
description: This is the mantel escape described in the problem Open Circuit (V7).  Start at the beginning of Open Circuit (aka Slopey Circ), grab some cool veiny jug holds, and mantel on them with your feet under the overhang, onto a slab and top out.  The key is a strong left heel hook perch.  This is one of my favorite mantels at the Stables; in an area full of quality frictiony mantels!

name: Thin Circ
description: Climb the face on the Slopey Circ boulder that is left of the Thin Circ Arete via thin crimps and balance.

name: Unknown Lowball
description: This problem is one of the coolest lowballs at the Stable, on par with Buttcrack at the same Circuit area.  Sit start right of the arete on the face with your back downhill to the stream.  With hands in juggy diabase elephant skin crack features, perch a foot up, make a hand move and then mantel up onto the slabby boulder.  On this problem, a shorter stature is a real boon.  I have seen six foot foot climbers struggle with this little gem, and I have seen ten year old kids absolutely cruise it.  This thing is just plain fun!

name: Banana Split
description: Sit start w/ sidepull & arete. Crux is in the middle topout is friendly

name: Creekside Throw
description: Start low in the middle of the creekside boulder and throw for the lip.  An awesome video on this problem can be seen in Kevin Catlin's GS Beta Series onchetroy.com

name: Creekside Traverse
description: There are a couple variations to this thing, and the V6 version of the problem is probably the most contrived of the bunch.  That being said, it's really, really good.  To do it the hard way, start on the far right hand side of the creekside boulder and traverse left staying low on the boulder and aiming for a prominent gaston crimp and sloper then mantle it out.      For an easier line that probably checks in around V3, instead of traversing low and left go up diagonally from the start, using the handholds of the harder variation as feet.  The moves on this are nowhere near as fun as the harder version.

name: Split Decision
description: Stand Start using the arete and an undercling, dyno/deadpoint to a good edge then top out.

name: Split Lip
description: Start with left hand on arete and right hand on a crimp. Climb up following the arete to top out. Balancy start to easier finish. Kinda techy fun problem.

name: Split Pants
description: Tricky, balancy little mantle on the side of the left Split boulder. Sit start on righ facing sidepull jugrail for your right hand and high good crimp for your left.  Mantle it out.

name: Split Pea
description: Stand Start using the seam at head height, mantle the boulder.

name: Split Personality
description: Awesome slabby warmup.  Don't worry about the moss, everything you need is free and clear.  That being said the aesthetics of this problem could probably be improved with a brush.  Stand start on the big foot rail using whatever works for your hands.  move up the delicate slab and top it out.

name: Split Tips
description: Sit start matched on big obvious edge, traverse and ascend the crimpy face to top out above the boulder's left arete.  Fun but make sure you have fresh skin for this one.

name: Cave Wave
description: Terrifying to look at, but not all that bad.  The trick is to commit, because if you don't... well, just commit.  Start with your left foot in the seam and your right hand on the crimp in the  middle of the face.  Launch for the lip with both hands, then top it out.

name: Fisticuffs
description: Fisticuffs is unique to Governor Stables, and diabase rock in general, in that it is a parallel hand and fist jam crack, and on a horizontal roof to boot!  If you like these kind of challenges then you will not be disappointed.    This roof crack is down low in a sort of cave opposite of the tall and sweeping face which contains the V6 dyno problem Cave Wave.  Look down and underneath the roof to locate the crack.  It is easy to miss if you are not looking for it.    Burrow as far back as you can in to the beginning of the roof crack and start jamming.  After a couple of moves turn the lip to vertical territory.  Once standing on the vertical face, you may step off, of continue upwards on grungy but easy rock to a top out.  Taping may be prudent as the insides of the crack are quite gritty, but taping is not a deal breaker.  The crack is hand as well as fist sized with good, solid jams for hands and feet.

name: Herr Center
description: Trad climbers rejoice! Offwidths and chimneys do exist on the East Coast, they're just boulder problems. Climb the chimney on this one to a high and exposed topout above Herr Right.

name: Herr Left
description: Herr Left's grade is entirely dependent on height.  If you're under 5'7" it's V3.  If you're over 5'11" it's V6.  V5 seems to be a good compromise

name: Herr Right
description: Tall and proud, this line has a little bit of everything.  Start with easy enough moves utilizing the arete to gain a high crimp, then bust out the crux toward a flat lip.  Don't look down.

name: Lieback Crack
description: Climb the tall crack that starts wide, goes to a horizontal break, then narrows to a 3 or 4 inch crack which can be liebacked on the right side or jammed securely straight on.  This is one of the nicer easy cracks at the stables.

name: Nestling
description: Nestling is an overlooked gem.  Start in the cave/corridor on large rails.  Climb up for a couple of fun moves on large holds and pull around the right arete delicately to reach the lip and mantle.  Be sure not to blow it up high.  This is my favorite V1 at the Stable, a place that is stacked with quality climbs at the V1 grade.

name: Rosie
description: This climbs the steep overhang above and to the left of the roof crack Fisticuffs.  Start on the jug of Fisticuffs. Climb the short finger crack to a horizontal break underneath the overhang. Load up the roof seam with gear and bust a move or two out to the huge horn at the lip. Wall on the left side (that cave wave is located on) is OFF unless you want to bail. Plug in some more gear here (threaded sling and #3 camalot) and pull the lip using the arete. A couple insecure slab moves lead the the top. You can set up a belay off a #1 and #2 camalot.

name: Barnacle Bill
description: Mantel the ledge to gain the interesting vertical and horizontal seam intersection.  Like all the other problems on this face, after the ledge is left the rock surface is flawless and the only option is smears to reach the lip.  This is the easiest of the four distinct problems on this side of the boulder.

name: Beluga Blues
description: Perform a delicate mantle to get started.  Lean into the rock and with blindly stand up with no handholds.  Once you are established on the legde, deftly smear a move or two to the lip.

name: Birth of Chuck
description: Something of a novelty, you either love it or you hate it.  Might be a little easier for the vertically challenged, but it's doable for all.

name: Captain Ahab
description: Right of Minky Mantle is a large foothold to start on and undercling the roof.  Stand up and reach high to pock seams.  Smear on the blank section to snatch good holds in the seams.  It is possible to top out slightly right or left.  This is one of my favorite of the grade at the Stables, an area stacked with classic V2's.

name: Dorsal Don
description: Climb the left arete on the narrow side of the Humpback boulder between Killerette and the Humpback face with it's variations.  Either climb the low angle right side with the corner in your left hand on the arete or on the opposite side with the arete in your right hand and your body on the vertical Humpback face.  Either way is perhaps 5.7 and highly featured.

name: Huck
description: Right and round the corner from the Juggernaut crack is an overhanging face with three large juggy rails that beg to be swung on.  Low start on a massive flake.  This is one of the largest flakes that is solid that I have encountered on diabase rock.  Push with your legs (some people will want start swinging and make a few false starts to gain momentum), and huck to the rail above.     Now the business begins.  The holds are hard to see and it may be helpful to have someone verbally guide you.  Reach up through a small incut flake that accomadates both hands to crimpy seams hidden in the rounded, beach ball like top section of the boulder.  Keep feeling around and delicately climb up with your heart in mouth.  The landing is flat and is stone as it is the top of the slab below.  This problem and Huck Left are part of the original old school B1's, joining Breadloaf Arete and 45 Center Face.  Some people may feel sandbagged, but everyone will be challenged.

name: Huck Left
description: Start low on the huge flake and make the huck move.  Instead of topping out straigt up as for Huck, make a shouldery move left to the middle of the three large rails.  Then top out the beach ball straight up above this center rail using more of the same crimpy seams as are found on the Huck top out.  Much like Huck but some say it is a bit harder.  This problem is highball and full value and has existed since at least 1980.

name: Humpback
description: On the shorter uphill side of the Humpback boulder is a fun face to play around on.  There is a central, right and left line.  Basically all of the variations start on a jug with smeary feet, go to a pair of edges then up to a sloping lip and mantel over.  It's just too bad they are so short.

name: Jaganath
description: Jaganath means "lord of the universe".  If you can complete this bloc, you may feel that way.  This problem is the king line in all of Governor Stables.  During the yearly competitions in the early and mid 2000's, this was a toprope.  If any boulder problem deserved an "R" rating, it is this one.  Jaganath is one of the most intimidating moderate problems I have seen on diabase, even including the massive boulders at Haycock.    Jaganath climbs the diagonal shallow finger crack in the center of the downstream side of the huge boulder that shares its name.  Negotiate the blank bottom of the hanging, ever-so-slightly slabby face and pull into the shallow tips crack using crimpy flakes.  Navigate up this crack type feature which climbs more like a face climb than a crack to a very high top out.     I imagine Jaganath has seen few ground-up, no top rope inspection ascents.  I think this is the proudest problem at Governor Stables.  If you try this climb, remember there is much more to this one than just the V grade.

name: Jugarete
description: Not to take away from Seth Derr's description of the Jugarete Traverse, I would like to add more to it.  This problem has it all: history, a striking feature, adequate holds, height, continuity of movement and a bit of spice!    The Jugarete can be climbed two ways.  The right (direct) way is to hop up to the wide horizontal rail on the hanging arete and slap up to two small finger bumps at the lip of the beach ball slab above while squeezing the arete with your feet or using a tiny chip to keep the feet from swinging off.  Claw your way blindly up to a crimp edge or two mid way up the bulge.  Get your feet underneath you on the starting rail and mantel with your heart in your throat.  This way is V5 or perhaps a tad harder, but probably not V6.  This is a standard sandbag at the Stables.  It would be prudent to get on top of the boulder and locate and chalk the holds prior to launching off, and the holds are hard to see.    The left version of Jugarete is to hop up to the rail, get the bumps at the lip of the slab, and then start working the hands left along the rising sloping lip rather than topping out directly above.  After slapping away left, you will end up with the left hand on a sloper and the right on a faint edge on the sloping lip.  There is a foothold far below on the face that may be used if you are lengthy.  Get the right foot up as a toe perch or heel hook and mantel, again in terror.  The intended problem is to not traverse all the way left into the huge horizontal jug that is at the top of the Juggernaut dihedral crack, though in theory this is possible.  This variation is about V6, but probably not V7.  Both ways of doing this problem are high quality and climb quite well.     The Jugarete traverse sit starts with hands on a huge plate on the overhanging wall eight feet to the right of the arete.  This is the start to Huck (V4).  Make long moves, traversing left to a wide rail, and then again left to gain the starting rail of the Jugarete.  You could top out on the right Jugarete problem for the traverse, but the intended path is to top out on the Jugarete left variation.  The full traverse is about V7, probably not V8 and is one of the longest overhanging problems I have seen at any diabase area.  It might be neat to traverse all the way into the finish of the Juggernaut crack and top out on that problem, adding a few feet but perhaps subtracting some difficulty, as you would avoid the crux mantel of Jugarete left.  My above description sounds contrived, but there are almost no extraneous holds and all of the variations are relatively easy to decipher.           I have always thought that a sick lower standing start could be done on the hanging arete.  It would be necessary to pinch the arete at a nice, acute depression and undercling the right hand underneath the roof of the boulder far below.  You would be very stretched out with the hands, and there are virtually no footholds, save for one measly wart.  I suspect this obvious start to this classic, tall and proud line would be no easier than V11 and perhaps even V12.

name: Jugarete (Traverse)
description: Included both problems as one submission.  For Jugarete, hop up to the big rail on the right side of the arete and bust up left and top out above Juggernaut, V6 and pretty cool      For Jugarete Traverse, start on the Huck jug and traverse into Jugarete via big moves on good jug rails.  V7 and flippin' awesome

name: Juggernaut
description: Another awesome problem.  Ascend the finger crack just screaming to be climbed in the dihedral below the Moby's boulder using typical diabase feet.  In other words they're only there if you believe in 'em.

name: Killarete
description: At the far corner of the Moby's boulder, near the mantle problems. Start standing on super juggy short arete and make an easy move or two to gain a ledge.  From there negotiate the blank bulging slab to the top of the boulder.  The new guide gives it a V0 but i'm sticking by my guns that it's a little harder than that.

name: McJump
description: A little party tick located to the right of Mushroom Crack on the arete.     Start on any of the tiny little crimps and the giant foot, pull on and pop up to the sloping pocket above your head. match the pocket and top out up the fun little flake. This problem gets more difficult the shorter you become.

name: Minky Mantle
description: Awesome problem, looks improbable but it goes.  Start on the obvious jug rail at chest height and work your feet up until you can grab the tiniest of nubs, then stand up and top out.

name: Moby's Dick
description: One of the most popular problems at Governor Stable, and for good reason. While no individual move is all that hard, you will most definitely have to work for the send.     Sit-start matched on the huge ledge/jug sidepull under the roof.  Make a tricky move to gain the front of the boulder (watch out for that root), then traverse all the way around the corner and top it out.  Awesome.

name: Mushroom Cap
description: Scary.  Start on the large block feature near the corner, move up past the slopey ledge, there are good holds farther back, then make a few ballsy moves to pull the roof and top out.  If you blow it you're probably going to introduce your tailbone to the tree, no matter how good the spot.  Awesome problem.

name: Mushroom Crack
description: Great problem at a very doable grade, if only this thing went for another hundred feet or so. Climb the cool crack on the west side of the Mushroom Crack Boulder, squeezing under the cap itself to top it out.  Fun.

name: Number Two
description: Squat start using double opposing gastons and fire up to the unique crimp on the lip.  Move up and left on the awesome crimp rail using some unique beta to gain the hollow jug.  Topout on the slab.    NOTE: The original starting crimp broke on 3/19/17, making the crux move noticably harder.  The line still goes using a higher portion of the seam.

name: Pimp Slap
description: Short V5 slab.  Tough.

name: Plankton
description: Left of Killerette is a low angle slab.  Leave the security of the lower boulder by making a slightly committing transition onto the slab.  Smear and palm out a cerebral mantle.  If only this movement and friction went on for a full rope length...

name: Shitake
description: Slab bouldering at its finest.  Figure out what the hell to do with your feet then stand up.  Pretty tricky.

name: Simulclimb
description: The slab's mossy but the important holds are there clean. Great problem straight up the tall slab

name: Tasty Flake
description: Tricky guidebook V2, a bit sharp, but a fun, satisfying little problem. Start on a face height undercling/thumb catch flake and work your way up through the short slab. Typical blankish diabase topout, gain using small crimps and remember your feet.

name: Twin Face Left
description: Cool smears for the feet with edges for the hands lead to a rail beneath the lip and then a mantel.

name: Twin Tips
description: Either make the fire for the huge rail or work the arete. Tricky either way

name: Gin & Juice
description: Gin & Juice is in my opinion the best hard problem at Governor Stables.  It is also one of the best problems at any diabase area in Pennsylvania, including Mount Gretna and Haycock.  I think it is one of the top five V9's in Pennsylvania, encompassing all rock types and styles.      Begin this challenging problem on the right side of the 45 degree overhang on a good underclings with smears for the feet.  Bust the right hand up to a flat hold that is exactly vertical just to stall on it, finagle the left hand into the best part of the undercling starting handhold, and then slap the right hand again to the sloping lip.  Toe hook so you can release the left hand and attain the lip.  These are very powerful moves.  Keeping the feet tight so you don't dab on the ground that parallels the overhang is difficult.    Now the real fun starts.  Heel hook with the right leg, and figure out how to mantel the extremely sloping lip.  The mantel is the crux alone and is at least V8 or even V9. You will need some serious strength and skill to get on top of this boulder.  Prepare to scrape the inside of your right ankle, perhaps many times.  This mantel is far more difficult than the crux mantel on Two Pop (V9, initially rated V10) at Lost Cove, in Boone, North Carolina.  In fact, it is the most difficult mantel I have ever encountered outside of Pawtuckaway, New Hampshire and Little Cottonwood Canyon, Utah; and those were rated V10 and V11.  Many folks will feel sandbagged by the grade.  To add insult to injury, I think Dr. Torretti thought the problem in it's entirety was about V8!  Good hip flexibility will be a boon on this mantel.     Pull, press and rock over onto the flat top.  This is a full on mantel.  Congratulations, you have just sent the best hard problem at Governor Stables...  The name comes from Joel and his wife Jennifer sipping Gin and Juice on the day of his first ascent, like the gangster he is.  His day job is merely an orthopedic spinal surgeon.

name: No Bedlam
description: No Bedlam was the second problem to be completed on the Pedal boulder, formerly known as the Project boulder.  Anthony DiSanto used his incledible strength and reach to put up this classic hard boulder problem.  Start off of pretty good underclings low near the center of the 45 degree overhang.  With smeary, bad footholds, make a loong reach to an incut crimp slot on the vertical face above.  Match on this two handed hold using a bicycle move with the feet (the pedal move) and then grab up to the lip and mantel.  This bloc is demanding, powerful and quite obvious.  It is a great short power problem and is an exceptional example of how good diabase rock can be.  It will help to be tall and have a positive ape index on this problem.  If you are very tall, the grade could be as easy as V7.

name: Pedal Extension
description: The Pedal Extension is an extended start into Gin & Juice.  It starts on the left most underclings low on the 45 degree overhang.  Dance the feet using foot switches and step throughs rightwards with hands grasping the underclings to set up on the starting undercut of Gin & Juice.  These moves are taxing, though the holds are positive, the footholds leave something to be desired, making it harder to set up into the  Gin & Juice (V9 in it's own right) start hold.  Conserve some power to slap out to the sloping lip on the right hand side of the boulder.  Now fight your way through the incredibly bald V8 finishing mantel of Gin & Juice and belly flop onto the top of the boulder.  Gasp for breath and then pour yourself a drink, you have earned it!

name: Buck Dance
description: This problem climbs the left side of the Dish boulder starting with the left hand on a circular dish and the right on a slanting ramp.  Pull onto the wall and you can use an edge.  Stand up and reach to the horizontal seam and there is a tiny finger pocket that you can use to balance.  Then make a big committing move way up and left, the best place to aim for is a basketballish shaped area on the lip perhaps 3 feet right of the left arete and then mantel.  The left arete is off and should not come into play anyway.  The way I always did it was fun and dynamic.       A fun variation called Buck Dance Direct at V4+ is to head straight up the even blanker scoop just above the start holds to a even slopier top out that is directly above.  There are even fewer holds to aid in the stand up.  Top out maybe 4 feet right of the regular problem spot, about 6 feet right of the boulder's left arete.  Do not use any of the jugs on the lip like can be used for the Dish problems.  You will be groping and reaching way back from the lip onto the rounded top to mantel.      The left arete and face can be climbed as a layback at about V0.

name: C's Problem
description: Wanna get away from the crowds?  Check out this hidden gem in the top corner of the preserve, near The Dish.  Take a short walk through the woods on a not so obvious path until you round the boulder.      Sit start low using the slab for feet then fire out to a gaston jug and gain a positive rail.  The crux is down low but the problem's not over unitl you're stanind on top of it.  Awesome stuff

name: Casanova
description: Good problem even though it's a bit contrived.  Start the same as Cassablanca, matched on the giant jug rail.  Make the same first move to the right handed jug, then instead of going straight up bust out left on bad slopers eventually aiming for a big jug on the arete.  The big juggy dish up and on your right as you move through the slopers is off.

name: Cassablanca
description: Not many moves, but tons of fun.  Start sitting and matched on the giant jug rail.  Hook a heel and bust up through a couple small holds to an easy top out.  Dont miss this one if you're nearby

name: Cleopatra's Waltz
description: Start to the right of the Pyramid start and climb the tall expansive slab to the right of the Pyramid problem.  Avoid using any of the extruded knobs on that problem and dance up smears following the prominent left leaning veiny seam with your fingertips.  Make your way to a thin crack beneath the overlap, stand up tall and mantel over.  Secure stances but a bit airy.

name: Dish Arete
description: Climb the right arete and face of The Dish boulder.  Enjoyable movement and interesting iron rock like extrusions which gives the arete an interesting texture and are a dream to stand on with your toes on the steep slab.  The grade is perhaps 5.9 with an easy top out and is a great climb to put beginners on before you goad them into scaring themselves silly on The Dish problem and it's mantle which is to the left.    It is called Dish Tree if you climb the face near the arete but avoid the arete entirely and is V0 or so.

name: Dish Right
description: Dish Right is an independent slab problem that is between the standard Dish climb and the Dish Arete on the right hand side of the boulder.  IT starts on the same hold as The Dish.  Climb up the slab on decent holds, worse than those on The Dish, to a juggy lip.  This problem uses holds that are not on the standard Dish problem.  It is a tad more difficult than The Dish, but it is still a steepish slab.  I think this way is on par, as far as quality is concerned, with the more popular Dish.  It is more thought provoking but similar.

name: The Dish
description: Awesome V1, the top-out is fantastic.  Lunge for the lip and throw a heel.  Exciting stuff

name: Eggsocentric
description: Eggsocentric is a neat little problem.  Sit start on a flat sloping lip beneath a bit of a roof.  Pull out and over a blank bulge with a hand pawing for purchase above.  Toe/heel lock in the gap between the starting hold and the roof above it.  Figure out what to grab on the sloping lip on top of the bulge and then mantel it out.  Though it is short, the large bowling ball-esque slopers and challenging mantel make up for the length.

name: The Foo
description: Cool line but sits in the middle of a swamp.  Start low on the obvious jug rail and fire for the slopey lip, then top it out.

name: King Tut
description: King Tut is a king line.  The attractive overhanging arete and face makes a spectacular boulder problem.  Start sitting with your butt on the ground, not crouching, left land on the arete right on a undercling.  Just getting off of the ground those few inches is hard.  Fight the barndoor, lean right and start slapping.  There is a thin sidepull undercling for the right hand to aid your efforts.  Reach the left hand to a diagonal pinch on the arete around head height and sag into the small but incut crimp on the face.  Now you are in the stand up start which is called Tut and is a nice V3 on it's own.  Scum the left toe or heel and try not to abrade your calf and shin.  Reach way up to a ripple, work the arete to get established on lesser angled ground.  From here follow the tall arete which in itself is a good V0 named Mummy March.  On a busy day you can sit on the rock nearby and almost hear a rusty door creak as people line up and barn door off the first few difficult move.  This problem is long (by diabase standards) and produces a pump.  There is a lot of compression involved in climbing King Tut.  I think it is one of the best problems of all grades at the Stable.

name: Mummy March
description: Mummy March starts standing on the face right of the King Tut arete.  Begin on a left juggy flake that leads to the arete of were the face and slab meet.  Make your way up to a high top out on a protruding, left facing large flake.  This part is the mental crux.  Delicately balance and layback a move or two to the lip and mantel to safety.  This problem is a bit heady for a beginner, but is perfect for someone who wishes to test his mettle.

name: Mummy Right
description: Climb the 70 degree slab on large flat hand and foot holds.  This problem is the left side of the easy backside of the Pyramid boulder.  A first time climber would have no problem on this climb and it would inspire confidence.

name: Mummy's Walkup
description: Climb the vertical face on nice jugs just right of the flake and arete.  This problem would be perfect for a rank beginner.

name: Open For Business
description: Start low on an incut jug and traverse left to top out same as Rick's Cafe

name: The Pyramid
description: THE classic area highball.  Fortunately it gets easier as you get closer to the top.  Establish low on the slab and climb through edges and slopers then top 'er out.  Must do!

name: Swamp Foot
description: It's a little messy back there, hence the name, but this is a great problem nonetheless.  Start low on decent edges and fire up through jugs to a strenuous top our on the right side of the boulder

name: Tomb Traverse
description: Great route, the crux comes at the beginning but the end isnt too easy either.  Start on the obvious crimp rail and move up through slopers and crimps to finish on the spine of the boulder.  This was V5 in the old guide but downgraded in the new one.  Some grumbling has ensued...

name: The Tooth
description: Stand Start and utilize opposing jugs on either side of the boulder to ascend.

name: Balarete
description: There's a sit and a stand.  The stand goes at V3, the sit at V4, although in my opinion the sit isn't all that difficult.  The problem itself is a little contrived, as the giant jug out left is off.  Apparently you have to stay near the arete.  All that being said, it's a fun problem with some interesting balance.  Try it.

name: Captain Prow
description: Ride the prominent prow to the top that is on the left of the two Twin Soldiers boulders.  Climb up the overlaps with underclings and sloping footholds.

name: Corner slab
description: Easy slab climb on right most side of boulder

name: D-Day
description: This overlooked problem lies in the corridor between the right and left Twin Soldier boulders.  It is to the right and around the corner from the problem LT.  Lock off diagonal slots on gritty rock to an easier top section with smaller holds.  This problem has good movement.      A nice variation is to start around the corner to the left on LT and climb into this problem at the same grade it just adds a few moves.

name: Dirty Sanchez
description: Sit start under the roof on a flat ledge and pull out the roof on chossy jugs to the lip.  The lower wall and footholds are crumbly rock.

name: Glass Arete
description: Stand start with two good underclings. Move up the arete choosing from a variety of holds and body positions. Get to the good holds near the top, and top-out with a heel. There are a ton of ways to do this problem, and it's a good warm-up before heading to the other areas.    You might want to avoid trying to smear on the glassy face, because this part of the rock is not your typical diabase frictiony smear.

name: Glass Menagerie
description: Start standing at the arete and top out to the right.  Great problem.

name: Karmic Power
description: On the steep face right of Balarete is a line of decent but widely spaced holds that is very popular.  The arete is off for hands and feet.  This is an independent line.  Start as low as you can on a sidepull/gaston, crouched or standing and a left hand crimp.  Reach up with the right into the unique seam for a perfect half pad crimp.  Get the feet up and make a big deadpoint to the obvious one pad 4 finger flake.  The left hand probably travels 5 feet to reach this hold and is the crux.  The top out is relatively secure.

name: Left Up
description: Climb the left blunt arete of the Upstream Arete Boulder using large holds at perhaps 5.6.

name: LOC Up
description: Lovely faint left facing flake, a few feet left of The Scoop with sticky footholds.  It is possible to top out the same as that problem or a bit more independently if you so desire.

name: LT
description: This is the right line on the left Twin Soldier boulder.  It is right of Private Slabby.  Stand start on obvious holds, or with hands lower if you prefer.  Make nice moves on consistently large holds through the elephant skin textured rock to a very incut rail ten feet up.  One more reach leads to a fantastic jug top out.

name: Mexican Hat
description: Climb the easy, chossy face from a sit start and top out.

name: No Moss
description: Slopey power test piece.  Stand start on two thin slots with a good little left foot.  Make a long move up and a bit left to a OK sloper.  Edge on some bad feet out right to find the next, bad sloper at the lip for your right.  Rock up and fire for a jug finish.

name: Parkour
description: jump past holds on the scoop (Vo) and grab jug rail and top out.

name: Private Slabby
description: Classic warm up in the warm up area.  Tall, slabby, with good holds the whole way.  Very enjoyable

name: Royale With Cheese
description: Royale With Cheese is named after a scene in the cult classic Pulp Fiction, and climbs much like the movie feels-insecure, ballsy and dangerous.  Grab the sloping dirty break midway out the roof in the burger shaped boulder, pull onto the rock above a chasm where the ground slopes away downhill beneath you, and dyno high up to the sloping lip.  Grab what you can up top and try to top out and mantel onto the burger bun.  This climb is more scary than it is difficult, but it is still hard.  This burger has some spice to it, you ordered jalapenos on your meal!  This problem was a project until 2005 if I recall correctly.

name: Satellite
description: If this were all one block i feel like it'd be better, still pretty cool though.  Sit start on the low block then use it and whatever else you can find to work your way toward the boulder's pinnacle. If V1 is your limit, this should be a good one to work.

name: The Scoop
description: Climb the obvious scooping face however you'd like. shares a boulder with Ballarete and Karmic Power,

name: Sergeant Crumble
description: Climb the face starting on large footholds to an undercling overlap, then reach through a thin section to the lip of the boulder and top out.  This is a nice beginner problem.  Once established on the face, a bit of thought is required to reach the lip from the prominent down-sloping overlap.

name: Sombrero
description: Sit start down & left on jug. Go for small holds out on the ceiling & use the arête to top out.

name: Grape Fingers
description: Start sitting with medium-sized crimp about two feet right of the crack. Climb straight up through small pebbles until reaching a sideways jug near the top. Top out on fairly good slopey jugs.

name: Honeycomb Moray
description: Start at the very bottom of the right arete on soft right-hand crimp and left and on protruding jug. Work up the arete until topping out at the highest point of the boulder. Be ready to engage that heel hook!

name: Social Distance
description: This is a dyno that starts on the first of the two large shark tooth shaped outcroppings. High foot on the feature to the right with a small left foot in the middle of the face. Throw for second shark tooth while avoiding the small tree to the left of the finish jug. Can be either a two or one hand throw. If your reach is above 6ft you most likely will be able to keep the start hand.

name: Twilight Arete
description: Start low on a long rail with a heel hook. The first move is out to an obvious bulge on the arete. Either meat wrap up the arete or use left hand on crystal crimps to move. Finishes at the same spot as Twilight Crack.

name: Twilight Crack
description: Start low on huge crack, following it all the way to the top out. Top out is crux.

name: Twilight Ladder
description: Fun problem with a scary landing. Start on obvious mega jug low and left. Work up through shelf jugs on the left of the large crack. The crux is the final hold which is a large left-handed crimp. Lock-off the crimp and pull to crystal jug finish with an easy top out.

name: Odin
description: Nicely overhung, 18 ft. long, with some really gritty stone offering a variety of holds and with just enough to keep it moderate.  Start on the obvious horizontal at the bottom, follow the seam to its end; once the seam stops move through a few bomber jugs and the top out.  An absolute quiet classic in the woods for the area.

name: Chimney
description: This is a standard chimney climb.  It has the usual dirt.  Just because the gear fits doesn't mean its good.  Check the quality of the rock.

name: Crack II
description: The crux pulling through the overhanging crack.  There is a large flake in the center of the climb that vibrates when you hit it.  It looks like it takes plenty of gear but I wouldn't put anything in it.  Fun & protects reasonably well.  Make sure you have some long slings for an anchor at the top.

name: Unknown Ceiling
description: There a couple exciting moves on this climb.  Climb straight through the overhanging blocks.  The crux is moving past the first block.

name: Arettissima
description: Start on North Face left, traverse left over the roof until you straddle the arete.  Climb up and left onto the face in the rear of the pillar.

name: Big Mama
description: Start nine feet left of the north facing corner.  Climb center of face to start, midway break left for 5.8 or right for 5.9.

name: Born to be Wild
description: A beautiful 20ft splitter finger/off finger/thin hands crack (crack itself is very condusive to climbing, its a treat for sure) that leads into a left facing corner/roof; pull onto the face to the right (don't pull the roof rather go out onto the face in the corner, to the right); crimpy with some thin side pulls. Veer left (crux) following thin seam to obvious left facing corner and top out.

name: Chimney
description: Climb up the gap in the rock.

name: Five Star Crack
description: One move up to a horizontal crack, traverse around the corner bumping your hands until you arrive at the amazing vertical hands crack. Land sweet, sweet, jams all the way to the top. Last couple of feet the crack narrows to perfect hands/off fingers.    This can be lead or bouldered.

name: Hopper
description: Start left of hooked tree. Climb up face into the branches.

name: The North Face Left
description: Start at left hand corner, traverse left over roof, then up face.

name: The North Face
description: Climb the right side of the face.

name: Puppy
description: Start on a small outward leaning ledge just left of dead 	tree in chimney.

name: Puppy in Heat
description: Outside corner eleven feet right of Chimney.

name: Rezerection
description: Route put up in spring of 2012, by myself,(Luke Bollinger) and Joe Snyder. Very solid rock, needed almost no cleaning, other than a small pine tree that was growing out of shelf near top. Route located on face to the right of 5.2 Chimney. Bouldery start leads to an early crux. Climb past shelf on left up the tallest part of the wall. Very fun movement. One of the best routes at Brown Rock.

name: Southern Comforts
description: Climb right side of face and corner.

name: Sundown
description: Located on the front face, climb left face.  Pull small overhang (crux) then onto the top.

name: Unknown
description: Climb straight up through the small roof to the ledge. Get in some gear, and figure out the fun moves up the seam in the overhanging prow. Watch your shins: there isn't much gear in front of your face while you work out the crux, and the jagged ledge below could be a shin basher.Top out.

name: Simplicity
description: Straight forward (straight up from the bottom through some positive holds) slabby fun. Wonderfully funky and on solid stone.

name: Grumpy Bear
description: Start with left leaning crack (left center of wall) step over to second left leaning crack at tree 20 feet up. Follow crack to slab exit to the right. 5.3/4G. Needs cleaning.

name: Pur-plex-ploration
description: Start directly under small roof with a short overhanging section and a crack just above it. Once you pull the roof follow the broken crack to the ledge then its a very short traverse to a crack in a bulge. Take this crack in the bulge (couple moves, short) to the top out.

name: Sunday stroll
description: Starts in the green corner under the triangle shaped small roofy bulge. Maybe 15 left of pur-plex-ploration. Boulder up to the first small cam placement then make move to a jug. Follow the crack up and right to quartz boulder.

name: The Arête
description: Start on the North facing side of the arête.  Climb straight up the slightly overhanging arête through a ½ inch finger crack to the top.  Stay on the face proper, around the corner of the arête is off limits.    Note:  If you stick all of the holds in sequence it is an excellent 5.7 climb, otherwise it can be very hard!

name: Crack-R-Jack
description: Start in the inside corner of the West face and the huge block in front of the face.  Climb up the inside corner, then continue through an offwidth crack to the top.  The crux is the transition from the inside corner to the offwidth crack tending to the right.  To make it a bit sporty, try not to step off onto the top of the huge block!

name: Crackin Up
description: Start on the North facing side of the arête.  Climb up the face angling left to a slightly overhanging fist sized crack that angles to the left, climb the crack to its end and then finish by climbing straight up to the top.

name: Green Jeans
description: Start on the West facing side of the arête.  Climb straight up the arête to the top.  Stay on the face proper, the arête and the corner is off limits.

name: The Vulgarian Highball
description: Stand start bottom right of the West face, left hand on the face, right hand on the arete. Follow the arete/rail up through some positive holds moving up and left. Climb diagnol left until you hit the obvious ledge about 13ft up and go straight up through cruiser terrain to the top from the ledge.

name: The Alley
description: Start at the base of a small slab, climb the inside corner crack up through the bulge to the top to a good ledge.  Finish by scrambling up to the top of Pillar #2 or walk off to the right into the sandy gully that separates Pillar #2 and Calvins Slabs.

name: Bolt Left
description: Start at the corner just right of The Great Chimney.  At the ledge, climb the face left of the bolt to the top.

name: Bolt Right
description: Same start as Bolt Left.  At the ledge, climb the face right of bolt and through center of overhang.

name: Chimney Route
description: Start up the left side of Pillar #2 halfway up the sandy gully at a large ledge that goes out toward the southwest outside corner of Pillar #2 and is the top of the arête on The Alley.  Climb the chimney up to a large ledge and the top of the right side of Pillar #2.

name: Chriss Corner
description: Start just right of Easter Bunny at the far left of the west facing corner and climb straight up.

name: Down Climb
description: Start at the top left of the sandy gully at a root system of a large pine tree high overhead.  Climb up and over the roots into a chimney, up through the chimney stepping out onto the top of the right (south) side of Pillar #2.    This is a popular descent route for all three (3) of the pillars.  It is easily accessible and offers security for the novice descender as well as a quick path down for the more skilled.    Caution:   There is some really loose looking stuff on this route.  A simple word of caution, so be careful.

name: Easter Bunny
description: The start is the bottom center of the north-facing wall of Pillar #2. Climb straight up the middle using pinch and crimper holds angling left up the narrowing wall to a ledge on top (stay on the north facing wall), either step off to the left and climb up and over the roof to the top, or walk off to the right side of Pillar #2 toward the descent routes.    Note:	Both sides of this wall are off limits for the full effect.

name: Mister Gut Wrench
description: Start at the bottom of a great over fist sized crack angling to the right, climb up through the crack to a ledge.  Finish by scrambling up to the top of Pillar #2.

name: S__Face
description: Start at the base of a small slab, just to the right of Mister Gut Wrench.  Climb the left wall of a right facing corner just left of the corner crack.

name: T.P. Corner
description: Climb the right face of the corner.

name: The Wanderer
description: Start in the middle of the narrow west facing wall of Pillar #2.  Climb straight up to the top.  Easier to the left, harder to the right.    Note:  The beginning of this route is hard to protect and is the crux, and a bit scary to boot (lots of balance and friction moves).

name: Well Groomed When Pruned
description: Use one of the main starts (the right side corner crack start is a classic) climb up to the start ledge.  On the right side of the start ledge is an awkward monster offwidth chimney / crack.  Climb up through the chimney / crack (hint stay outside so you dont get stuffed into the top of the chimney / crack). To an outward sloping ledge below the roof, step up right to a good ledge, step 	off to the left and climb up and over the roof.  Or from the ledge you can also climb straight up to the top (this is a less than vertical option to finish on), from either choice continue on to the top.  Or you can walk off to the right side of Pillar #2 toward the rap chains.    This is a classic line of Pillar #2 with a roof of only moderate difficulty.

name: Arching Route
description: From the far left side of the large ledge, climb straight up the face, then angling right across the arched face toward Thin Crack.    There are several large lunges to positive holds!

name: Boulder Problem
description: Start around the right side of the Jims Wall, about five (5) feet left of The Great Chimney start.  Step up in the pocket and start traversing to the right into the cave.  Undercling the large flake working right and up.  Climb till you get stuffed tight up into the chimney.  Enjoy!

name: The Cave
description: A dark, sometimes wet route exists back in the deep recesses of The Great Chimney.  Walk about twelve (12) feet back into the cave to a left side ramp work up to a right side cavity, then work your way to the top climbing up ramps, ledges and the final flared chimney moves.    This is a good non-roped descent route.  However, the top section (fifteen (15) feet of flared chimney type moves) is a bit scary, so if you are unsure of your abilities go ahead and rope up and enjoy the experience!  Caving gear is optional.  Head lamp is nice!

name: Classic Corner
description: Use one of the main starts (the middle crack start is a classic) move left to the large ledge (this can be used as a belay station).  Climb up the classic open book corner to a nice belay ledge on the right, either step out left and continue to the top or walk off to the right towards the top of The Great Chimney and The Cave routes.    This is a great classic and can be climbed in three (3) real micro-pitches.  An excellent beginner route to start those aspiring new climbers!    This area of Jims Wall can become quite crowded at times.  Be patient with fellow climbers learning the ropes!

name: Gonads
description: Start at the left facing but right slanting flake 6 feet left of a pine tree.

name: The Great Chimney
description: A classic located between Jims Wall and Pillar #2.  Start climbing in the cave, were it is possible to get a foot on each side of the chimney, stay outside and chimney all the way up to the top.    Placing pro up through the chimney is scattered and not real apparent at first, a real challenge to find and place good solid placements from a chimney stance.  Be creative, its all there!

name: Jester
description: From the right side of the large ledge, Between Classic Corner and Jims Throne climb straight up to the top.

name: Jim's Throne
description: At the obvious crack fifteen feet to the right of the chimney. Climb crack to notch and then up small ramp that splits the face.

name: Nasty Crack
description: Start around the right side of the pillar, about five (5) feet left of The Great Chimney start.  Step up in the pocket and climb the excellent finger crack (hint: try laybacking the upper section) up to a fair size outward sloping covey, setup a belay or, continue up the right side of the pillar using the knobs all the way to the top.

name: Pine Tree
description: Start just left of the prominent northwest corner, climb it to the top.  Great friction start, moderate climbing beyond!

name: R.H. Crack
description: Same start as Thin Crack, but when you get to the ledge above the big ledge climb the face between Thin Crack and 	Classic Corner.

name: Reach Around Boo
description: Start five feet left of Gonads.  Traverse under the overhang to the right.  Finish in the corner.

name: The Sea of Grunge
description: This chimney is located to the right of Angulation and the extreme left side of Jims Wall.  Climb up the vegetation-infested chimney towards a left leaning chimney (there are some great pocket holds on the left side of the chimney), climb / crawl to the end, and step out of the chimney and continue to the top.

name: Seven Percent Solution
description: Start about ten (10) feet left of The Sea of Grunge.  Start way under the overhang, pull the lip and climb up working left towards a horn and a small ledge to stand on, step up onto a blank smooth section work up the left seam to the top.    The section above the horn feature is smooth and unprotectable.  A bolt was added just to the left of this section of the climb sometime before Memorial Day 2011.

name: Sign of Zorro
description: Climb outside corner of the main wall (west face), just left of the chimney.  Joins Jims Throne later on up the face.

name: Thin Crack
description: Use one of the main starts (the left side start creates a nice testy start) move to the middle of the large ledge.  Climb the small crack that splits the face above the ledge to a blank section, continue up to a deeper larger crack farther up, and continue on up to the top.

name: Angulation
description: Start about ten (10) feet from the left side of the wall, climb up onto the ledge running the length of the wall, go straight up through two (2) bolts.  Continue up and left to holes for slings.  Top out onto a small rounded ledge, climb on up to the top.

name: Super Crack aka Wise Crack
description: Start below the obvious off-width crack, climb up onto the ledge running the length of the wall, climb / jam the crack up to an outward sloping covey, continue on up to the top.

name: Surf The Boogie
description: Angulation wall.  Climb up onto the ledge running the length of the wall, climb the right angling crack, then straight up past two (2) bolts and trad gear.  Climb the scalloped face towards a bulge (lots of balance moves), pull over the bulge and top out.  A set of rap bolts were added on top of this route somewhere around Memorial Day 2011.

name: Eves Rib
description: Start at the extreme right side of the crag, follow the rib (stay on the west face) up and left, traverse left under the roof, stem up into Glens Roof and pull the roof (hint: right hand into the crack, a bomber is in there, trust me) and continue to the top.    Note:  Two (2) Bolts have been added to ease the ground fall potential.

name: Eves Rib Direct Finish
description: Start at the extreme right side of the crag, follow the rib (stay on the face) up aiming for the right side of the roof, climb up over the right side of the roof to the top.    Note:  The roof corner is very hard to protect.  However, you can do some pre-climb help by going up before hand and place a sling and biner to clip when you climb.

name: Flying Snake
description: Start at the left side of the crag, climb up through the flakes and broken face to a  two (2) tiered blocky overhang, pull the roof on its left side (go for the knob hold high on the left outside corner), continue up to the top.

name: Glens Roof  aka Linda Screams
description: Start in the middle of the crag, climb the awkward crack straight up to the roof, stem up into and pull the roof (hint: right hand into the roof crack, a bomber is in there, trust me) and continue to the top.

name: Overlooked Overhang
description: Start in the middle of the crag, climb the awkward crack angling left to the left side crack in the roof.  Pull the roof and continue to the top.

name: Copper Heads
description: Start around the middle of the wall at the obvious off width crack.  Climb straight up through the large off width crack to the bottom of an overhang, pull the overhang on its right side.  Good holds if your sequence is right, if not it could be a scary roof.

name: CP Face
description: Start at the base of a small pine tree.  Climb up through some difficult face moves to the roof with a vertical crack.

name: Disjointed Apparatus
description: Start just left of a small pine tree at the left side of the slab.  Climb up and through the overhang at the top.

name: Lets Face It
description: Start between the left side and the large offwidth crack.  Climb straight up the blank looking face, there are a couple of good holds if you look for them.

name: North Face Crack
description: Start at the hands/finger crack at the far right of the North wall of Craggy Pines. Jam this to a horizontal crack. Take the horizontal into a vertical finger (broken a bit) crack and this into the right facing corner. Take this corner up and then you top out.

name: Piney Corner
description: Start around the middle of the wall at the obvious corner.  Climb straight up through the corner to the top.

name: Diagonal Crack
description: Start at about the middle of the face, 	follow the right slanting crack all the way to the top.

name: Last Sign Of Zorro
description: Start at rectangular shaped rock, climb the 	prominent crack to the top.

name: Lizard Bail Out
description: Follow Diagonal Crack about ¾ of the way up angling left then straight up to the top.

name: Disappointment
description: Start at the far left side beside a huge block and in a corner.  Layback under and up the left side of the huge block to a good size ledge (25 feet).  From the ledge climb up the left side of the flakes (saw teeth) to the top.

name: Sawtooth Corner
description: Right side of the huge flake is a two (2) foot wide chimney, climb the chimney up to the top of the block (15 feet).  Move left and climb up the left side of the flakes (saw teeth) up to the top.

name: Toxic Traverse
description: Straight forward warmup OR cool down at the end of the day. Great way to work endurance.    No strict definition for this route: just traverse back and forth.

name: Doowop Chimney
description: Climb the obvious chimney behind the pinnacle.  Located on the north side of Hard Scramble Corner.

name: Proctometer
description: Start under the bulge, climb up to the ledge.  Pull the overhang and continue to the top.

name: The Saddle  aka  Fists And Fingers
description: Start up the middle of the crag following the broken face features up and towards the right side of the pinnacle past a tree to the top.    The name, The Saddle, came from using the tree as a belay station, legs around each side of the tree with a hip belay and ya, you know it, using 7/16 inch hemp rope and flossed hemp slings as pro!  Those were the days.

name: Thriller Pillar
description: Climb the face of the pillar, only the face.  Work around (left) to the north side to avoid the overhang.

name: CramJam
description: Start on the north west corner and climb the left hand diagonal flaring crack to the top.

name: MeatHead
description: Start in the middle of the face just below the diagonal under cling.  Climb straight up to the top.  This route is traditionally well protectable.

name: SpamJam
description: Start near the inside corner, after a couple of face moves climb the inside crack to the top.

name: Digger O`dell
description: Climb the left facing `sawtooth` corner/flake. Use the flake and whatever the faces allow.

name: Northern Pillar
description: Slightly overhanging. Follow the hand/finger crack up to the top passing some horizontals. Obvious line.

name: Pigs in Space
description: Pigs in Space is the dominating (there are several, Pigs has a chockstone in it up high) left leaning hands to fist crack (face climbing last 10ft) that starts at average chest height and goes to the top. It is overhanging the entire way. Protection is plentiful but beware that there is potential to fall onto some boulders; mitigate this risk by placing ample pro.     Note: there are face holds along the way if you wish to use

name: Stomach Contents
description: Climb the inside left facing corner.

name: Cal's Ceiling
description: Climb the offwidth (for the skinny just about a squeeze chimney) and pull the roof. If avoiding offwidths the face also can be climbed then pull the roof and this goes about 5.5/5.6.

name: Calvin Corner
description: Climb the long left facing corner that is on the right side of the area. Gain this corner by using one of the starting routes (mix and match if you'd like) and you'll end up at the big ledge. From the ledge head into the corner.

name: Grumpy Gus
description: Choose your start (5.4 starter crack, Cal's Ceiling, or the boulder start) then once at the ledge climb up to and use the splitter crack directly left of Calvins Corner.    Follow the splitter to its end at a ledge with a tree (can't miss it) then traverse a short distance to finish on the last few feet of Calvins Corner.    Can be done in one or two pitches. No need for two but it'd be fun/good practice. Climb to the big ledge and belay second up or climb until you get to the bottom of the splitter proper and create a gear anchor using Calvins Corner and belay the second up.

name: Patriot Act
description: Climb the face on the far right side starting from the main ledge (choose a starter route to gain this ledge). Stay on the face until it ends at a ledge, step off the ledge to the left and follow the crack system to the top.

name: Buddha Traverse
description: Sit start far lower left of the West face, move vertical a couple of moves through a side pull and some positive holds, start traversing right on the obvious large flat to juggy holds to a nice positive rail, continue on the rail through a sweet crimp and end at the start of Off the Beaten Path.

name: Off the Beaten Path
description: Overhanging arete. Just around the corner, south and/or right, from the main overhanging face is a broken rail along with various pocket holds.     Stand start on a obvious horizontal lip that is on the main face, use good enough foot holds on the main overhanging face and south face to make your way up so you can throw to a vertical shallow crack high on the South face to the fun mantle top out.

name: Three-Fold Path
description: This is a mix of three problems. Start and follow the Buddha Traverse until your far right on the obvious rail on some super positive holds (theres also a lower rail offering really stable feet), instead of going for the crimp, dyno up to a really large slightly sloping ledge that is far right on the West face, match hands then finish out the last part of Off the Beaten Path.

name: Greasy Bastard Cluster-Crux
description: This is a very pumpy one pitch climb that doesn't provide many rest opportunities due to the negative tilt to the wall.  Start at the far south corner of the crag and work the dihedral up to the small ledge just to the left of the face.  Transition out from here onto the face and climb up the center of the two crack system.  Handholds are limited, but all there.  Continue up about 10 feet, using a left hand side-pull around the corner and a pointy flake on right (crux).  After moving through crux, continue up another 10 feet and traverse right towards base of chimney.  Continue up and through chimney to walk off (top rope can be set with gear and long webbing/cordelette).  Be careful of loose rocks.

name: Eaves Traverse
description: Start under the lookout view ledge. Traverse along the horizontal crack with bomber handholds but iffy feet. Crux is near the end at the finishing hold. Be wary of the rock in the middle and towards the end.

name: Foot Jammer
description: Start out with some foot jams and a hand jam. Short crack but good for practicing foot jams. Top out is a little sketchy for the grade.

name: The Once and Future Flake
description: For shorter people, the crux is reaching for the top hold. Tricky balance moves.   Otherwise the crux is the traverse right from the starting holds.

name: Pops in the Corner
description: Start on a muggy rail and work your way to a flat top out. Either dyno or utilize decent edges on this slightly overhung corner.

name: Slick Rick
description: Start out with a combination of hand and foot jams. Donut, hand, and fist jams can all be utilized on this short route. Top out is easy.

name: Western Toad Style
description: Sit start low with a side pull undercling combo. Reach up high and get your foot up on the first slab. From here pull the next two "roofs" to the top. Fun slabby climb with a semi burly sit start.

name: Wish it was Taller
description: Sit start low, solid right foot and a decent left foot stem. Work up the finger crack and try to find a bomber hand jam.

name: Campus Wall
description: Slightly overhanging edgy wall. Good for outdoor campus practice, albeit with a poor landing.

name: Chonkiness
description: Climb up the blunt and bulging arete to the top. Some fun footwork. Matched hands on a rail to start.

name: Coin Slot
description: Transitioning from the start to the hand crack midway up. Named after the crack that runs through the boulder. Watch for spiders and trash.

name: Exit Stage Left
description: Start as low as you can on the left lraning diagonal crack. Solid laybacking, juggy pulls, and foot jams up this short crack. The crux is transitioning from the face to the shabby side of the boulder. Avoid the smaller boulder that would make an amazing foot hold and reach high.

name: Nightcrawlers
description: Squeeze chimney or off-width practice. Short and sweet.

name: Tiger Style
description: The crux is close to the bottom as you pull on medium crimps. The lack of feet options make this climb harder at the start. Once you reach the largest crack there are solid fist and hand jams along with some delicate left footholds that are hard to find. Right foot can utilize the crack pretty comfortably.

name: Vemorkian
description: Start close to the corner and work your way up. Pulling the lip is crux, especially without using the pillar directly ahead.Red line on the photo on coin slot.

name: Hardbacked Cover
description: Start out with your hands on the pinch flake, feet under the overhang. Reach up and pull through some crimps to the top. Crux is going for the top hold, it's a blank section of the wall and requires balancey moves, trusting some iffy crimps, or a dyno. Crimps may pop off at any time so be wary.

name: Hydroxyloxyl
description: Start out at the base of this high ball and follow an intermittent crack/flake up. Crux comes in the middle where holds are sparse. Sink your hands in some messy side pulls and pray they don't pop. Top out is a little sketchy because you have to down climb the back side. Walk or shimmy down the spine until you see some good holds to lower on. Spectacular view from the top.

name: Lean wit Me
description: Start with your hands on a diagonal rail, left foot low, and utilize a toehook to keep from twisting if you want. Continue up left on good holds. Some interesting footholds can be used. The crux is moving off the start and keeping yourself from barndooring.

name: Poppa Layback
description: Avoid the slab boulder near the start. Layback up the chunky sidepull. Step high, watch your footing rocks pop on this one, and move on up.

name: Saving Flake
description: Start on a crimp and work the flake.  The crux is the mantle in the middle of the route. As soon as you pull it though it's an easy top.

name: Splayed Alive
description: Start with your arms wide on a balancey foothold and slap your way to the top.

name: Tortilla Chips Verde
description: Start with your hands on a flake. Do what you can eith your feet but they're just sort of there at the start. Work up through moss coated jugs and flakes.

name: Toss a Jam
description: The crux is in the middle of this fairly easy route. Typically involves tossing up a solid finger lock from some iffy footholds and a crusty side pull. Top out has a nice jug or hand jam.

name: Unnamed
description: Start on the ledge/rail. The crux is the mantle right after the start.

name: Unnamed
description: Start on the flake and either jam or layback your way up. Nice incut ledges to grab too.

name: Upended
description: The crux is pulling off the set start. Holds in the middle of the route may be mossy.

name: First Directive
description: Committing moves on this ledge highball. Ignore any thoughts of being impaled by the various downed trees below, should rot away soon. Slightly mossy rocks make this route iffy after it rains.

name: Toe the Vine
description: Crux is shortly after the start as you transition diagonally. The top section is a lot easier due to the solid holds and ledges with the added benefit of being slabby.Originally covered in vines and dirt. Remnants may still be found.

name: Dirty Martini
description: Start left of tree on easy ledges to first bolt. Next, move up to to right facing flake then move right to another right facing flake.

name: I am Groot
description: Start right of Dirty Martini, Move into over hang and traverse right. Pull 'hang and move up very thin terrain to shared anchors

name: Kettle Face
description: Left most route. Climb up pockets and crimps. Move right over last bolt to jug up and right. Mantle to anchors.

name: Left turn crack
description: Climb Rob's until a thin crack breaks left after the small overhang. Follow crack to top and I am Groot's anchors

name: Lover's Leap
description: Hard move off the ground. Use the rock sticking up out of the ground by base. Although it has been climbed sans the block. Tough lieback to very balanced stance. Move right and slightly down to holds and mantle back up. Clip third bolt and move back left to flake. Follow bolts to top.

name: Rob's old Bolt Line (Greenie)
description: Climb short dihedral to head wall. Make move onto head wall. Climb straight up over bolts.

name: Sunset Slab
description: Start below the first bolt on a ledge. Crimp and smear up pockets and flakes to the 3rd bolt. Pull the bulge and step right. Move to anchors.

name: Tequila Sunset
description: Climb to first bolt, then big under cling move to good holds. A bit PG to second bolt. After third bolt tend left to anchors.  Optionally sling a small tree before anchors

name: Viridescent Crack
description: Clamber around a split tree with boulder stuck in it. Move up slab. Climb crux through steeper terrain. Follow finger crack to anchors.

name: Campaign
description: Climb up a ramp move right to chains

name: Cato
description: Gave the PG  because the way its bolted the d is because the tough clips on the v2 problem clip the first two bolts on rattler move right figure out the arete and the bulge.

name: Concious lovers
description: Tough start tricky finish

name: Spectator
description: Boulder start pop up to ledge, casually scramble to 3rd bolt last section is good but short lived.

name: The Tattler
description: Clip the easy second bolt climb up to a side pull in deep clip the chains.

name: The Crown Jewel of Safe Harbor Climbing, Four Stars, Eleven B
description: Climb into small dihedral and the exit left over bulge to a stance. Continue up and left to anchors.

name: Cup Cakes and Beer
description: Climb easy ramp to right side of cliff and hidden bolt. Then up arete trending left to second bolt. Cliff face straight up over slight bulge to anchors.

name: ManBearPig
description: Climb easy terrain to overhanging arete. Lie back up arete to top and then move right to anchors.

name: Overlap
description: Start left of dihedral. Pull initial roof pinching on sugar cube sized quartz. Continue up fun and featured rock that becomes ever so slightly more than vertical.  From this anchor you can rappel all the way down to the enola (gravel) trail with a 60M rope

name: Pinch the Pebble
description: Climb a bulge right off the ground with a bolt and quartz pebbles. Continue up wind carved pockets and cracks to anchors.

name: 7 Slates of Gray
description: This route starts on a boulder under a blunt corner.   Finger jam up short crack (about 3 or 4 moves) that angles up and right to the corner (crux).   Swing around corner on thin face to more bolts with a lot of climbing.   Follow bolts and line of least resistance with good route finding skills to the anchors. There are some remaining loose chips up there.
A Crack in the woods just before 1.5 on a pillar

name: Bernie Plays Base
description: Start on the middle of 7 Slates buttress just right of a tree. The first bolt can easily be clipped from tree protecting difficult moves off the ground (but that would only count as pink point, wouldn't it. haha!). Climb steep right leaning crack to triangular alcove. It is fairly pumpy clipping the 3rd bolt. Perform powerful moves up and right on terrible ring locks to where the crack widens. In the back of the crack are great finger jams to clip the 4th bolt. From here move up and left to gain a rest and the next bolt. Beat the pump clock and fire the rest of the route at about 5.9+ on steep terrain with big holds that are sometimes far apart.  There is a lot of climbing in 50 feet on this one. Enjoy! Recently some holds have broken/shifted decreasing the difficulty to about 11c. It is still a fun route, so get on it!

name: Bio Hazard
description: This route is about 50 feet south (climbers right) of Chimney of Horror. Scramble up inside corner to high bolt. Climb steep face on crimps and side pulls following bolts to anchors.

name: Chimney of horror
description: Chimney,stem and squeeze the chimney just north of 1.5 mile marker.   Is the route horrifying or horrible?

name: Crack-a-lackin'
description: Struggle to gain a stance right off the ground. Stem, chimney and jam up the    crack, which goes from hands to fingers to closed and then hands again. Pretty good variety of moves for such a short climb.

name: Cushy Buns
description: Start on Chossy rock for a move or two until you reach the better rock with finger crack. Follow crack up and slightly right to a small tree then move left to crack-a-lackin anchors.

name: Die Fledermaus
description: Named after a bat (fledermaus) that was disturbed in removing a large loose flake.   This climb has a few interesting features, plus even though there are lotsa bolts it still seems spooky to me the whole time.   Start around the corner and right of "7 Slates of gray".   If you are not comfortable with chimneying you might want to stick clip the first high bolt.   Climb chimney to its top. Climb up over the bulging face(crux). Follow flakes and small stances on near vertical terrain to about the 9th bolt. Next, climb up and right for 2 or 3 more bolts to anchors under a large pine tree (90').   There is an optional trad/solo second pitch to trees (5.5 R/X)   Walk off Right(south)

name: Entrance Route
description: This route may be used to access the balcony rock routes.Start left of first high bolt and follow easy ramp up and right. Climb passing a bulge and then lower angle ledges. At Last bolt move left to anchors.From the anchor one may move left to another set of anchors. Then up to top of cliff  to trees and walk over to balcony rock climbs.

name: Finger Tingler
description: climb steep face to double crack. Climb right when able. Finish on right most crack to anchors

name: In the Jungle
description: weem-awop-a-weem-awop...    Start on north side of 7 Slates buttress just left of tree.   Climb steep corner with finger crack in roof to first bolt. Overcome temptation to use the trees at the start. Then a committing mantle above 2nd bolt to slab. Climb slab to small roof. Continue up thin face (crux) with many balance moves (i.e. use you feet!) and lay back the upper arete to anchors.

name: The Jungle Book
description: Climb stemming dihedral with some crack moves and/or lay backing to anchors.   A fun little climb easily TRed.

name: King of the Swingers
description: Start in the corner of Jungle Book moving up until you can undercling right to a high bolt. Pass bolt using the arete. then up a bit more (spicy) until you can move left to a stance. Place some gear then up tiny crack to another stance and set small wires, rps, etc. Climb up a move or 2 then go left to Jungle Book anchors.

name: Knuckle Dragger
description: Climb right to left rising crack until the end then move up on top of the nose to a bolted anchor

name: Kurz
description: Climb arete

name: Legoland
description: Start in the same dihedral as Biohazard, but move up and right onto arete. Cross right on slab to a bolt and gain a large ledge. From here continue straight up the route staying very close to the bolt line. Around bolt number 10 you will see Biohazard's anchor to the left (don't clip it). From here climb up and right unto naturally exposed rock passing 4 more bolts to anchors at the very top of the cliff.

name: Manky Corner
description: Scramble up to initial large ledge left of tree. Walk right to first bolt.   Climb fins and flakes clipping next bolt.    Minimize using the manky corner,    in fact avoid the chossy bits all together,     and climb left on crimps and sides pulls (crux) over next bolt arriving at another large ledge.   From here move back into corner(not manky). Climb remaining bolts to top.

name: Monkey Business
description: Start on flake below and left of first bolt. Lieback up corner thru 2 bolts. Next move right to rail just below 3rd bolt. Move up to good hands and bolt and then traverse right to anchors on "Crack-a-lackin"

name: Predator
description: Begin on the front face below the first bolt. Balancey lie back up corner and then flakes. Move slightly right and follow thin seam with pods to large hold. Far right is chossy. Move back left on jugs and pull on to low angle slab to anchors.

name: Sticky Wicket
description: Just right of chimney start climbing on thin steep slab. body tension and position help up high. At 30 feet pull left over roof (crux) with powerful mantle and continue to anchors.

name: Swinging Singles
description: Part 1:   Climb steep-ish slab with large hands and a few nice stances to a large ledge with anchors (5.6 40').   Part 2:   Hard moves to get established on the wall.   Continue beyond first anchors on ever steeper slab/face. Holds exist to the left of the first anchor (thin) to a bulge. Move over the bulge going slightly left and then back right.  The goal being the 4th bolt because better holds after that to top (5.10 40 more feet).

name: Take the Flake
description: Start on 7 slates of gray.   At 3rd bolt move left to flake/crack. trad to a lone bolt at top of flake.   easy 5th class up to 7 slates anchors.

name: When will it end?
description: Not sure yet ???

name: A Charlie Brown Christmas
description: Start behind a jumble of rocks. First bolt often wet.

name: Easter Beagle
description: Climb discontinuous crack on the right of slab. Move left at the top to a pine tree anchor

name: Good Grief! Charlie Brown
description: Start in front of Pole just right of exceedingly rotten rock. Make tricky move off the ground and clip the first bolt. Gain the very narrow slabby ledge. Following the slab ignoring  the wall on the left (questionable holds) and the cable. Move right on thin feet clip and then up passing more bolts. Gain a short fist crack and last bolt. Move up and left to anchor on thin feet.

name: The Red Baron
