description: Climb face right of Good Grief

name: Security Blanket
description: Climb steep slab on the right side. To be fair gaining the first bolt try not to use the grassy cracks to the far right. After clipping said bolt stay on or slightly left of the remaining bolts to the anchor.

name: Trail thru the woods
description: Climb the slab on the left side of the face, ending at either the anchor to the right or continue left on very sparse bolts to a large tree.

name: Upper Route 1
description: Climb large crack to a steeper section and to top.

name: Upper Route 2
description: Climb face on crimps to top

name: Upper Route 4
description: Climb steep face to the top of the cliff

name: Ziggerella's Day Off
description: Start with your hands on the face, feet under the rock and climb through the roof start. Balancey moves as you move up the face.  There are some other fun easy problems around here, like a nice finger crack, but a lot of questionable rock too.

name: The Corona
description: Start on the right side of the face by a small tree.  Climb up scoops to first bolt. Following remaining bolts to a large ledge. Continue up second part of cliff passing 2 more bolts

name: Lyme
description: Start above steep dirt slope. Climb wavy rock passing 3 bolts to a small ledge It is a bit run-out after the 3rd bolt. There is a crack that excepts gear (1"). Continue to large ledge. Another bolt is located in the back of the chimney. Clip that with a double (120 cm) length sling .  Move back out on the face and continue up steeper rock to another bolt. Climb up  and ever so slightly left (crux) to a hidden bolt above. Finish at bolted anchors

name: (Es) un yame
description: Just left of Namaste there is a small ridge about 20' tall to a crack.Move right on slanting ledge. Then follow a finger crack up and right to the anchors on Namaste.

name: Arrampicano
description: Large cliff at 2.0 mile marker on trail.   Climb flakes to big "V".   Move right on steep slab.   gain steeper rock with cracks.

name: Me llamo John, Me gusta mucho bailar.
description: Climb slabby edge up and right gaining stance. From stance dance up the crack to anchors

name: Namaste
description: Start left of first bolt. Follow ramp up and right to steep wall.   Move over bulge on good holds to inside corner. Follow Corner to its end and step left to anchor.   Put extended draw/sling on next to last bolt before anchors b/c that bolt is kinda far right.

name: Planet Derrth  -  formerly AKA "La vie en rose"
description: Climb slab starting on stance on Gusta Bailar's 5th bolt then stay on the right side of remaining bolt line

name: Samurai
description: Start on left side of face.    There are two starts either lay back corner to first bolt or move directly up to first bolt.   Aim for under cling horn/jug below third bolt. Lay back discontinuous crack on steep terrain with thin feet/swap. The climb eases off after 4th bolt. A nice test piece for aspiring 8 leaders.

name: Tashi delek
description: Begin with a bouldery move below 1st bolt (optional) right of Namaste. Pull up right onto a large ledge and 2nd bolt. A Few easier moves up and right to the third bolt. Powerful moves with tricky feet up the crack clipping 2 bolts along the way. Finish on Namaste (last 2 bolts).

name: Tsunami
description: Climb right side of face. Gain initial start edge and first bolt. Approach from right side of first bolt with high steps. locate mono and move over first bolt to the jug at the second bolt. The belayer must be VERY diligent. Move left to second bolt. Easy 3rd bolt then delicate moves up and left(sometimes damp). Pull small overlap and finish on Samurai anchors  Cutter Variation. Climb directly up to 2nd bolt. start about 5' left of the 1st bolt (10c).

42: The answer to the Ultimate Question of Life, the Universe, and Everything and my friend's 42nd birthday on the day we put up the route.  Clip first bolt and gain stemming stance. Move lightly left to good side pull then up to jug. Move right to clip. Then move up right to next bolt and again a clipping jug. Traverse up and left on steep terrain using small crimps and under cling to (you guessed it) clipping jug under bolt in the roof. Clip, make big move up and slightly left to a blunt point, match, and pull roof on good holds. Continue up steep inside corner. It gets chossy up high if you go too far left.  Variation: Direct Start from stem stance continue straight up dihedral (ignoring temptation to go left) 2 or 3 more delicate stem moves (10d/11a) to second bolt staying in corner.

name: Black Crack
description: This route starts at an inside corner left of Crap Crack. Climb easy 4th class up to first bolt. Continue stemming up corner, and cracks to roof. Jam out roof and pull through V notch. Move up to steep slab with pinches. From here pull over large bulge (can bypass left in short crack - boo!) to stance. Finish on thin slab to anchors, passing directly over to slight right of the last  bolt. Lastly, mantle on the sloped ledge just right and above the anchors. Bend down to clip.

name: Blind Leading the Naked
description: Start just right of Psycho Thriller at large crack/dihedral.   Move up right on lie back corners(crux). Then back left into crack. Follow crack and corners to large stance almost at the top. Climb left over bulge clipping last 2 bolts to anchors. FYI - Anchors are near Psycho Thriller anchors.

name: Comfort Zone A.K.A. Marmalade
description: Climb to first bolt on Easier said then done. Move left on feet with tiny hand holds to a mono pocket. Move straight up (Madam Bovary is off) Clipping next bolt. Move up again on non-existent feet. Clip then traverse right on non-existent feet and no hands to a key and hidden side pull. Clip. Move up and slightly left over steeper terrain with non-existent feet and tiny hand holds (crux). From here move up on 5.10-ish terrain following 2 more bolts. Finally mantling and continue on the remaining 2 bolts of Easier said than done.

name: Crap Crack
description: climb up large pinnacle type boulder, normally has bird crap on it. Gain large slanting crack that goes up and right to Power and the Glory anchors.

name: Easier Done Than Said
description: From the ground between 2 trees behind wooden pole, climb jagged steep rock. Get established on the rock and then move up and clip first bolt. go around bulge keeping the bolt to the climbers left.(easy). Come back left above the bolt and gain a small sloping ledge and clip 2nd bolt. Climb arete to more bolts and a large sloping ledge at 25' up. Go slightly left to next bolt(extend draw). Work back right to arete. climb left side of arete to another stance. Clip, continue lying arête on the left side. On a large stance clip bolt on RIGHT side of arete and head up thru dihedral to the RIGHT with off width crack. Stem, off-width or face climb to top (3 more bolts). Finish by moving up 10' from bolt (easy) and slightly RIGHT to anchors. The anchors are positioned on a nearly horizontal section of the alpine ledge.

name: Easier Said than Done (EStD)
description: From base of 5 5s Climb up right to thin finger crack. Follow crack over little roof (crux #1) to stance. Move up to large ledge and clip bolt on LEFT side of arete. Continue up lie backing left side of very fun arete following 2 more bolts(crux #2). Continue on, passing more bolts on low angle slab. End at anchors for Madam Bovary.

name: Fanagle
description: Pitch 1. Climb initial 10' slab to steeper corners. Lie back over-hanging corner and mantle up onto a stance and next high bolt. Continue up shallow bowl (stemming/crux). Then cruise to anchors.  Optional Pitch 2 (not recommended). A 110' trad pitch on moderate 5th class climbing above ending at trees. Find your own way up! A 2 rope rap or walk off south gets you back down.

name: kwaJimu
description: Start on vertical wall.   Move up on to ledge and clip high 2nd bolt.   Continue up steep wall clipping 2 more bolts.   Move left under terrible small crimps at last bolt.   Power up slightly left to top of cliff.    You can also optionally continue on What's ur Safe Word

name: Madame Bovary (FA's original name)
description: Pitch 1. Climb obvious 90' dihedral north of hand crack. It's an off-width crack. This crack is super rad in that vedauwoo kind of way. The crux is about 30' in length with a balancy stem section on top.  Pitch 2. 60' Climb corner/face to anchors.

name: Power and the Glory (FA's original name)
description: Climb crack on gear 1" to 4" through roof to old cold shuts (don't stop here). Then continue about 10 more feet to new stainless anchors.

name: Psycho Thriller
description: Climb slightly over hanging face to arête.   Lieback arete clipping 2-3 more bolts continue to a BIG stance. Resume liebacking up steep arête with hands on arête 2 or so feet right of the bolt line (don't go left chossy, bad fall potential and difficult to clip) to its end and another stance.   Move left over awkward pinches and oddly angling feet for a few more bolts. A sling is helpful on last bolt. climb right at last bolt up blind lieback flake to anchors.

name: Said and Done
description: These are 2 link ups.   Said And Done:   Do the first half of Easier Done then Said and finish on Easier Said than Done.   Done and Said:   You can also do "Done and Said", but not recommended. Start on Easier Said than Done and finish on Easier Done then Said, but take long slings for some of the bolts.

name: Shady Lane
description: On right (south) side of alpine wall starting from the ground on black rock   are 2 parallel routes. Of the 2 routes this route is on the climbers right.   (You walk under the rock fall fence and up a small slope to start)  Start at crack below 1st high bolt. Tending left and stemming corner on good holds gets you to the first bolt.   Move up to large slanting ledge with great feet to clip second bolt that is just out of view over head.   Continue moving over ledges and bulges.   Finish at bolted anchor.

name: Upper Level - Midas Touch
description: This climb starts 125' up the cliff on a large ledge.   You get there by first climbing Easier Done than Said or Black Crack.   Starting from anchors on ledge climb steep face 8' right of anchor and directly behind pine tree.   Follow bolts tending right, up to bolted anchors shared with Banshee

name: Upper Level -Banshee
description: This climb starts 125' up the cliff on a large ledge.   You get there by first climbing Easier Done than Said to anchor.   From this anchor walk straight right (3rd class) behind pine tree.   Go beyond Midas Touch and clip first low bolt on Banshee.   Move right again 5-7' to good crimps. Move up and slightly left to big pocket(jug). Prepare for exciting crux and head point.   From there following remaining bolts over steeper terrain to bolted anchor shared with Midas Touch. Stay close to the bolt line especially at the top (There may be some remaining loose blocks).

name: Wots ur Safe Word?
description: Start just right of "42". Climb crack to chimney. Pull out of chimney (quite awkward if your hand jamming is a bit rusty) onto slopey ledges with some bolts (to reduce rope drag either skip the bolt above the chimney [5.5R/X] or back clean). Then to another bolt and yet another bolt in the first roof and clip with 20cm draw. Pull first roof (clip with 60cm sling because there is a sharp corner that you do not want near your rope) and then a big move to slopey lip of second roof. Traverse right clipping 2 more bolts (recommend using a 60cm sling and then a draw) toward anchors. Mantle to top. Simple.

name: Arduous
description: scramble up low angle slab.   Basically climb the right facing corner.   There is hardly any stemming though.   Crux is getting to the third bolt.   The anchors are just above a small cap roof at top of route(bring slings for TR or seconding).   Or, at the next to last bolt climb left to anchors on Fus Ro Dah.

name: Arm-a-geddon, AKA WtB
description: Start 10' left of Nanny Goat on ledge.   Climb crack/flake until it pinches out.   Move right to left facing small triangular alcove.   Clip and make a reachy move left to side pulls then move up to crack that goes up and right.   Move up to hard under cling (cruxy if tall) and left hand side pull to clip. Make big moves up and right (cruxy if short) then up to anchors

name: Balance of Power
description: Start under small pine just left of ARMageddon.    Climb steep crimps and thumb catches to pine and jugs. The route steepens a bit more here. a very cool section with a blancey mantel with no hand rest. Lie back slopey pinches to jugs and bolt. Continue up and right following discontinuous seams through another bolt and then straight up to anchor from there.

name: Barely Legal
description: Climb straight up to 2nd bolt on slightly overhanging rock.   From here "wind up" and dyno (crux) to a small ledge by the 3rd bolt.   Go left at rail to 4th bolt. Hand traverse back right(pumpy, no feet - maybe heel hook) to last bolt.    Pull up to anchors.

name: Fus RO Dah
description: Crazy route up slightly overhanging wall just left of large dihedral. Climb beginning of Handle with care. Move right to ledge. Continue up ridiculous blank face. Make a dynamic move to large horn to climbers right and last bolt. Move to anchors.

name: Handle with Care
description: Scramble up easy slab to the business.   Climb up right side of the first bolt to slanting sharp crack/flake. Commit to face.    Make some big moves on small to non-existent holds. Find the clipping hold for the next bolt. From the last bolt make many nontrivial, but very cool moves to the anchor.   Balance and good footwork will pay great dividends.

name: Legacy route
description: Climb straight up bolts.   Crux is thin and tricky getting steeper up high.   On steepest part there are bigger holds, but they are far apart!

name: Malice
description: Start 20' right of Razor Flakes.   Climb up easy terrain to first bolt.   Make hard initial move (crux#1) into an under cling. Power up to pockets at second bolt. Climb through 3 or 4 powerful moves(crux#2) to small rail at 3rd bolt.   Tenuous moves follow to small flake directly above. Then make a very cool sequence of moves to the left and another flake at 4th bolt. Make 2 or 3 big moves up and right(crux #3) to juggy ledge and 5th bolt. Move right to another jug flake and get your feet on the juggy ledge and move back left then up to anchors.    Optionally at 5th bolt move LEFT and finish on Razor flake.  Nice moves with some sequential, technical climbing and some burliness.

name: Nanny Goat
description: A fun route. The rock quality is not as bad as it looks.    Follow discontinuous and sustained lie back flakes with some clutch jams to ease the forearms. Seems longer than it is and way pumpy.

name: Sugar Frosted Razorflakes
description: Left/north side of Eurowall. Start by power pole. Climb easy terrain to first bolt. Move up on large ledge. Climb flake by 2 more bolts. Next follow flake traversing right (Crux) for 2 bolts on steep terrain with bad feet. Move up to slopey hands and put your feet on the sharp flake continuing right for 2 more bolts then hard-ish big move up to jug then finally move to the anchors. Sweet line with much variety (lieback, slopers. crimps, side pulls, big moves, and an arm bar/jam). Pumpy.

name: The Warm Up
description: Start on Sugar frosted razor flakes, but when razor flakes moves right, continue straight up to anchor.

name: 2. Golden Bough
description: Follow nicely spaced bolts up amazing arete. An optional green alien can chill out the last moves.

name: 3. Medusa
description: Start right of Golden Bough arete in left facing corning. At top of corner move right across thin terrain. Climb up over slight bulge and continue following bolts to shared anchors.

name: 4. Flash or Crash
description: Climb up following bolts. In the middle of the route is a thin seam. Pull through this blank section which is quite thoughtful and very techy to a thank goodness jug. New Anchors.

name: Deserves to be Named
description: Follow bolts to anchor. Optionally. after anchor continue to the top of cliff via trad crack and build sling anchor.

name: Gold Line
description: Climb up gold colored face with small seam/crack to pocket and crimp. After it slabs out go up to old cold shuts.

name: Thing1
description: Climb Diagonal crack to a bulge by a tree. Mantle out and move up to a bolted anchor

name: Thing2
description: Climb tiny right face corner feature to a bit of undercling moves. Tend right to second bolt then up to tree and finish on the last 2 bolts on the route to the left.

name: Zizzer-Zazzer-Zuzz
description: Begin just right of Gold Line. Follow a steep dihedral, starting out on easy ground. Continue following dihedral with ever increasing difficulty as you go. Thoughtful. There are a couple ways to tackle the crux.

name: Ander's Onsight
description: Climb through 3 bolts to shared anchor.   Be careful not to go left around the corner, dubious rock.

name: Better than it seams
description: Start with a big move up to a hanging flake. Traverse right and mantle. Stay off the boulder behind you. Find thin fingers in the seam. Make tricky moves to a horizontal. More tricky moves to jugs and then pull a small roof to anchors.

name: Coming Soon
description: Climb to left facing corner to undercling flake, move left to left facing corner. Next move up and left over slight bulge to steeper juggy bulge and anchors.

name: Dasein
description: Climb easy dihedral to high first bolt. Make hard moves right on lousy feet eventually gaining a slopey pocket with your left hand. Gain a not-so-great pinch/pocket with your right, do a few more hard moves, then giggle your way through easy moves to the anchor.

name: Dopamine
description: climb face with decent holds to very short shallow left facing corner (crux), then up right to a bolt and then anchors.

name: Honeysuckle
description: Southern most route in  this area.   climb flake/crack to V-notch place small gear and finish to anchors

name: Layback
description: Climb left angling crack to corner then follow corner up right. Finish on trees or Levitation anchors

name: Levitation
description: Climb through 2 bolts(crux). Then a short hand crack with large stoppers and a #1 Camalot.

name: Missing Ethan
description: Climb up steep slab to first bolt.   Lie back tufa like ridge to second bolt and pull little roof.   Move to third bolt. Make thin moves to fourth bolt(crux) and then to anchors.

name: Mossy Pocket
description: Climb blunt arete 8' left of Honeysuckle passing 3 bolts. Place gear for second (big nut or small cam) and traverse right(easy) to anchors.

name: Packing Distracted
description: Climb bolts just right of Dopamine.   Cruxy from 2nd to 4th bolt.   Fairly steep for slab and crimpy.   The first ascent was missing the fist bolt.    It has since been retro bolted (obviously).   Continue to shared anchors

name: S. L.
description: Slab up to a new bolt at 25+' (instead of the 30+') with no gear. Under the route and slightly left is a right upwardly slanting ramp that will get you to the first bolt at about 5.6 or 5.7. Also a more direct start on steeper slab weighs in at 8+.  Climb crack to shuts. There are perma-biners up there for easy descent and they appear good, but they have been there since 2012.  I know. Before the flame war starts, we tried leading on trad. Falling on gear ripped the rock off the cliff. Luckily no one was seriously injured. One such failure did create a great finger pocket reducing the grade down to its current 10a.

name: Spoof Roof
description: scramble to first bolt at little roof.   Pull roof(crux) to stance at second bolt.   Climb over 2 more bolts to anchors

name: 1Looney Bin
description: Climb a mostly straight line up the left side of the face to a maple? tree sling anchor. Top out or rap. Optionally one could follow a right arching finger crack to a bolted anchor.

name: 2Lunatic Fringe
description: Start at small tree under the left most line of bolts. Although there are a few bolts on this route one might want a few trad pieces in between. Climb mostly straight up following bolts and placing gear when able to a right arching finger crack that leads to a bolted anchor

name: 3Bark at the Moon
description: Start under a bolt and climb straight up following bolts and placing gear when able to a bolted anchor.  Variation 1: Instead of using the first bolt, move up and right following pockets until you are about half way between the Bark at the Moon's start and the Obfuscation corner. From there climb up and then left meeting Bark at the Moon at the third bolt.

name: 4Obfuscation Corner
description: Climb the right corner of the face staying mostly on the front side placing gear when able. At 30 feet move left into a "crack" and move up and right to its own bolted anchor.

name: 5Dark Side of the Moon
description: Climb overhanging Wall on the southern face of the formation

name: 6Blue Moon
description: Climb right facing corner left of Mani and the wolves. Follow steep crack at top to anchors for Dark Side of the moon

name: 7Mani and the Wolves
description: Climb the center of smooth slab right of Blue Moon.

name: Aaron's Follies
description: Start left of Zero Wing.   Balancy and delicate liebacking on small corner.   Climb up to high bolt. Follow corner to stance.   Then a few easy moves to Anchors

name: Book End
description: Starting from the dirt ledge right 15' right of Zero Wing. Climb up face and bulge then move a little right and climb to Zero Wing Anchor.

name: Brad's Birds (open project)
description: Open Project, go get it.   If you've ever had a man on a bike with a fanny pack stop you near cemetery wall to talk to you about birds and show you pictures of them, then you've met Brad. He is a local and likes to help with the Fish and Game commission to help monitor the birds. Take a minute and talk to him if you see him stopped at a bench, he's a good guy.  Stick clip highly reccomended. Start on crystalline rock about 5 feet right of "granola in the gri gri". Go straight up into the alcove, using thoughtful beta to climb right of the hollow block on the left (crowbar couldn't move it, but I wouldn't go yanking on it). Move up and right out the alcove utilizing very thin holds and thumb presses. Find a way to make your feet stick to pop up to actual holds and follow to the anchor. Theres about a 10 ft runout to the anchors, but clean falls.Stays shaded until about 1pm.

name: Double Entendre
description: Climb slight over hanging rock past 3 bolts to a delicate slab and 2 more bolts to a 2 bolt anchor

name: Granola in the Grigri
description: Stick clip highly recommended. A steep sequential boulder problem gains you access to a slabby face and a good stance at the first bolt. Follow ample holds and steepening terrain through 3 more bolts before engaging in a physical crack crux at the fifth and final bolt. Clipping the anchors is made a bit easier due to addition of chain at anchors, but may still be difficult for short climbers.  The bottom of the route after the boulder start is quite licheny, but easy terrain and does not warrant scrubbing. Stays shaded until about 1pm.

name: Itza Slab
description: Easily climb to the first high bolt. Then make thin moves straight up to bolts 2 and 3.

name: Misnomer
description: Start under a large "V". Climb easy ground to first high bolt (5.3). Move up to second bolt by back stepping wall behind you. Next lie back the arête to the top. Pulling over the arête before the last bolt makes it loads easier (not recommended), not sure if you can clip that last bolt when doing so.

name: Zero Wing
description: Right most line. Climb thin steep face to slab. The intent is to stay over or just left of the bolt line. To the right is Choss! Too far left and it eases off.   Continue up easy slab to crack and corner to top.

name: Catfish Cleft
description: Climb to first bolt (crux if staying directly under the bolt). Scramble to second bolt.   Move left and move over bulge to large horn.   Mantle (crux) and move up. Follow easy slab up straight up from last bolt to the anchors.

name: Grim, The
description: Climb right facing corner to first bolt. Follow bolts up and left to corner and head wall with anchor. Cruxy and balancy getting to second bolt. Then a second crux getting to anchors.

name: How does eat food?
description: Start below small easy over lap to first high bolt.  Follow bolts straight up to crack and then continue up face to anchors.   Beware of potential loose rock right of 2nd bolt.

name: Likin, Lichen, Bush
description: Start below first bolt. Climb up to 4th bolt. After 4th bolt and above bulge to anchors up and left. Be nice to the plant that smells like mint!  Lower/descend down "TR route" to belay the second.

name: PSA: Fire Prevention
description: Climb to first high bolt. Gain large ledge and climb remaining face to shared anchors.

name: Reaper, The
description: Start with left hand side pull 6' up. Climb up slightly right on very small, sharp crimps to first bolt (crux, bouldery and hard!). Follow remaining bolts to top of cliff. Watch for loose rock on big ledge half way up.

name: Stegosaurus Rex
description: Locate first bolt. Climb to first bolt on fairly steep rock. It is easier if you climb in from the left. Mantle on big ledge and step right (balancy). Once over second bolt, follow good feet with side pulls (left and right) to last bolt.   Scramble up to anchors.

name: Stick Clip It!
description: Climb 8' to ledge. Probably first and only time I will say it but, Stick clip the first very high bolt. The crux is getting from the ledge to above the first bolt. The wall is slightly overhanging with sparse holds. Very Challenging!  Has not seen a "red point" yet. I only put 5.12 as a grade because I had to put something. It very well may be harder!  It may be possible to add a lower bolt and actually be able to clip it..

name: What am the sky?
description: Start under 'How does eat food?'.   Locate very high first bolt up and left on slab.   Climb line of least resistance to that bolt. Watch for loose rock! Finish slab to short head wall. Climb head wall(there is a crack of sorts)  eventually hand traversing right(about 5 feet or so) on a large hand rail to the last bolt then up to anchors

name: Austin's Pockets
description: Start on Slabadelic. Split right and follow pockets to corner. Then go up to share anchors with Slabadelic or traverse right to anchors on Dr Evil's cat.

name: Slabadelic Baby!
description: Climb left line on blank face.

name: 100th Monkey
description: Just follow bolts to anchor through a slight bulge.

name: [Redacted]
description: Scramble up slope from left.   Follow Bolts to anchors. The rock is friable so be cautious.

name: Fun Hogs
description: Climb bolts to cold shuts.   What does the name mean?  Maybe a play on 'Fote Hog' or bar in vegas?

name: Primal Scream
description: Bolts to anchors.   This route is the most challenging of the 4 routes in this area.

name: Battle of the Bulge
description: Start at belay on Schist for Brains.   climb RIGHT on slab up and over the bulge.   A fun cruiser

name: Schist for Brains
description: Begin on low angle chunkie rock. Move up left clipping 2 bolts.   Then move left again UNDER a roof all the way to the left side(PG). Watch for chossy rock at your feet.   On left side of roof climb crack to a tree and bolt on your right.   Follow bolts up and left to pine tree growing horizontally out of the cliff.   From pine, clip bolt and continue following bolts up steeper terrain with big moves to blind holds. Anchors are at the very top of cliff.

name: Sliding Board
description: Start on rock apron just above ground level. Follow line up slab about 50'    then turn 90 degrees left (there is a bolt protecting traverse) and go to the start of 'Schist for Brains' and 'Battle of The Bulge'.

name: The Way Up
description: Start just right of 'Schist for Brains'. Start below steep wall between 2 trees. The rock is a bit brittle for the first few moves, so move delicately and in balance. A 5 foot no fall zone to the second bolt on rounded hand and feet holds(shouldn't deck with attentive belay). A tricky mantle, following by an easy run out to a big ledge. The upper section is a little less steep and maybe 5.8 with good moves to the anchors.

name: Charming Snakes
description: Start in chimney. Follow bolts up and over bulge to anchors.

name: Fast Twitch Poety
description: Climb ever steepening slab to right side of roof.   Several years ago a large chunk of rock fell off near the top.  Don't recommend climbing until hardware is replaced.

name: Frustration
description: This first "pitch" is fully equipped and climbable. Lots of dirt vegetation and loose blocks have been removed from the opening gully, but there is still more to clean off so tread lightly. The opening gully is the only PG-13 section, G rated after that. The top of the slab is dirty and could still use some more brushing. Start up a chossy and dirty but easy gully, slinging a tree on your way to the high first bolt, then get established on the small foot ledge at the base of the slab. Climb much better rock up the slab, following the shallow right slanting corner to the anchors. Careful on lowering and cleaning due to the traversing nature of the route; the lower/rap line from the anchors currently goes through a nest of dead vines on a ledge that need to be cleaned up. Second "pitch" up the overhang is a work in progress, and not fully equipped for climbing.

name: It's a Fine Line
description: Start below and slightly left of first bolt. Move over slabby section. climb over small overhang on crimps and crack (crux). Move up to big over hang. Surmount overhang on far right. Follow remaining bolts to anchors.

name: Mindwalk
description: Just left of Charming snakes. Major rock fall has basically destroyed this route.   Some bolts exists though.   This route description added for historical purposes

name: Pain Lies on the Riverside
description: Climb ever steepening slab to left side of roof.   Several years ago a large chunk of rock fell off near the top.    Could now be called "Layin' on the Riverside".    Don't recommend climbing until hardware is replaced.

name: Power Surge
description: climb initial overhang to slab/seam and roof. Clip first bolt on roof. Move up right clip second bolt on roof. Make a move down and attempt climbing over the over hang on slopey feet and hands. Try and find the OMG hold.

name: Project
description: Start left of Power surge at a crack.   Follow low angle to roof, pull roof and follow two (directional) bolts with aluminum hangers.

name: Raptor
description: Climb bolts to roof at 50 feet. Cruise roof on left side and finish to anchors.

name: Recovering Festival Girl
description: This is a great route to practice/teach top belaying and rappeling as the anchors are above a sizeable ledge that fits two people comfortably. It is still a bit dirty with some vegetation on route, but the rock is super solid.Start either directly under the first bolt or start as for sagaba and move up and left to the first bolt. Climb up the slab with intermittent smearing and good holds, then tackle a small overhang at the last bolt. Mantle onto the ledge and clip the anchors. Difficulty is a bit dependent on how directly over the bolt line you climb but is generally in the 5.7 area. A fun short climb for the grade if you're uninterested in the spooky hold-less top half of chutes and ladders.

name: Sagaba
description: Start at the right edge of the low angle moderately featured slab to the left of the main "Fine Line Area" where there are some old names and numbers scratched into the rock at the base. Follow small but generally positive diagonally running cracks past three bolts (extend the third bolt with a sling) until you come to a notch in the roof above the third bolt. Clip the ring hanging over the lip of the roof then pull the roof and follow three more bolts through highly featured vertical terrain to a two bolt anchor. For full value and better climbing, stay on or just slightly left of the bolt line after the roof. In my opinion this climb is really a move or two of 5.10 at the roof surrounded by easier climbing. Note: Do not climb past the anchors, nothing but frightening choss.

name: [Redacted]
description: Route Name: "Drug a Virgin"Start left of Pause for thought. Basically, Follow bolts to anchor.The giant poison ivy patch was recently removed.

name: Afrosheen
description: Climb right facing corner/seam. At 4th bolt look for pinch (crux) on the left side of bolt line on bulging face. Make hard moves to rail and mantle up. Continue up slab to shuts.   Harder if short.

name: Buzz Clip
description: Climb steep face with some small crimps and open handed slopers to a lip about 25' up. Pull the lip left of bolt then slabby finish to anchors.

name: Chutes and Ladders
description: Look for 20' bore hole/chute up face to slab. Climb slab following bolts to anchor.   Crux is at 5th bolt. Staying slightly left helps!

name: Dry Bones Dance
description: Start as per Monk Gets Ripped.   At 3 or 4 th bolt. The line splits left. Follow the left split and bolts to steep wall and anchors.  There is at least 1 hold that is reinforced with epoxy.

name: Leap of Faith
description: Climb very slippery face past first bolt to right facing corner stance. Continue up steeper face to anchors

name: Monk Gets Ripped
description: Start on dubious rock. Move up to good rock and corner /roof. Pull around lip with thin moves to head  wall. Continue up steep wall to bolted anchors.   Staying right of last bolts is easier and scarier. Recommend moving over last bolt. A harder move, but safer.

name: Nini won't stay down
description: Just left of Smooth operator is a line of bolts called Nini wont stay down.   Follow the first few bolts to a small roof(5.9). Then go around roof on the left on steeper slab with an insecure stance to clip the crux bolt(5.10).   Next figure out how to climb a tiny right facing seem through the crux to the next bolt(5.11). From here, climb much easier terrain to a large roof exiting right then up to the anchors.

name: Nose, The
description: Start just left of the nose. Climb to the first high bolt. Continue to third bolt and pull over the nose.   Clip 4th bolt and then up and right and clip a bolt on 'Chutes and Ladders'. From here follow bolts up and right to semi-hanging belay.    Step off the anchor to the right and move up through two bolts. Follow remaining bolts staying on left side of nose. At some point a finger crack over bulge appears on your left. Follow that to anchors.

name: Pause for Thought
description: Start left of Rant and rave. Follow bolt to anchor. Nice balancy move at 3 bolt crux will have you pausing for thought.

name: Pity You
description: Climb flake through 6 Bolts to anchors.

name: Power at Play
description: Climb bolted line between Buzzclip and Pity You.   Not seen a red point yet.

name: Rant and Rave
description: Start on small overhange below a blunt arete.   Pull initial roof (right off the ground) and cruise slab to arete. At jugs on the arete traverse left onto the left face of the arete. Follow bolts to anchors.   One may also stay on the arete and then move slightly right under the anchors to up the ante (11a -ish)

name: Ruby Red Slippers
description: Begin on wavy rock and slanted rail up to thin seam at 4th bolt. Climb seam to anchors. Tenuous holds, thin and technical with a wild crux.

name: Smooth Operator
description: Start left of Ruby Slippers. Basically, compression problem with left hand on corner and right hand on side pull seam. Gaining the glassy slopey "ledge" to clip the second bolt is the crux!   At the 3rd bolt or so the route eases into nice face climbing.   At next to last bolt there is a thin bit of climbing and the head crux. Finish with a "harder move than you'd like" move to the anchors.

name: Beat Crazy
description: Climb up pinches and liebacks to stance.   Move up over small bulge/roof and then slightly left over last bolt and then up to anchors.

name: Corner Stone
description: Climb North west facing wall to slab and anchors.   the route is in need of cleaning and hardware upgrade.

name: Damnation 1992
description: Start below right facing corner and short crack. At top of crack move left to next bolt and then continue straight up to anchors.

name: Tonus Bonus
description: climb three bolts to top of cliff and move slightly right to 4th bolt then up to anchors.

name: Children of the Dammed
description: This route climbs the wandering slab just left of Dammed if you do. Be careful, chossy bits abound.

name: Dam it! Janet!
description: Start directly under high 1st bolt. Balance up onto "nose" at chest height. Walk up slab and clip the 1st bolt using a 60 cm sling. Heel hook/mantle over the lip and climb up and right on easy terrain. Pull small roof and then again up and right to a third roof.  Skirt this roof on right side or don't and then climb up and slightly right to anchor 10' right of "Dam the Torpedoes"' anchors.

name: Dam the Torpedoes
description: Climb the bore hole chute on left side of face. Exiting right at end of said bore hole and wander up to the right surmounting a small roof to the top.

name: Dam Yankees
description: Start just right of Damit! Janet! under a steep section to an alcove and first high bolt. Clip second bolt with 60 cm sling. Clip 3rd bolt (Roof) and move under said bolt. Make hard Heel Hook/Mantle move passing just barely to the climber's left of the bolt line. Clip and follow remaining bolts up and right to anchors, being careful to stay away from chossy corner to the right.

name: Dammed if you do
description: This route shares the 1st few bolts with Dammed with you don't. A chossy start to bolt #3. tend left following more bolts and better rock to the top.

name: Dammed if you don't
description: Same chossy start as Dammed if you do. Then tend right passing a PITA tree. Climb a steep section and then head up and right to a 2 bolt anchor.

name: A Ledged Crimes
description: Stem or face climb up to a ledge, clip high, then bust a few interesting moves up to better holds.

name: Fine-Apple
description: Pull out the notch in the roof and into easy slab climbing past bolts 2 + 3 to the technical face above. Follows a faint dike that trends leftward, just right of the bolt line. The last two bolts before the anchors are the business.   Watch out for loose rock on the slab when lowering.

name: Key West
description: Straight forward climbing following bolts to anchor.  Crux around 3rd bolt.

name: Blood Sugar Magic
description: One of the best at Safe Harbor. Granted it is short, but there is no fluff on this route.    Start at the base of the crack and diagonal up and left using underclings, laybacks and the occassional jam to a pair of cold shuts.     Use caution getting to the second bolt. From bolt 1 to 2 the climbing is mid to hard 5.11 and you could hit the ground if you blow it.

name: Blood Sugar Magic Direct  Start
description: Start directly under the second bolt of Blood Sugar Magic (a crash pad is nice). Climb straight up to 2nd bolt on small edges and sides pulls. Do remaining route of Blood Sugar Magic

name: Bomb Free Harbor
description: Bouldery start to the second draw, then pull the ledge and finish at the anchors underneath the bush

name: Copperhead Road
description: If only this was longer.  Start in a mini dihedral and follow a seam toward some horizontals near the top.  Moving toward the last bolt is the crux

name: After Thought?
description: Start at crack 10' left of "Safe harbor Direct".   Climb up diagonally left to bolt. Next climb up to fourth bolt on "Can't remember". From here traverse left to "clever retort" anchor

name: Birch
description: Start in wide inside corner right of Snake. Climb the inside corner slinging birch trees and occasional gear in cracks. Just before the top go left to Snake anchors or continue to top and tree anchor

name: Black Velvet
description: Start on a tiny ramp below and right of the first bolt. Climb up ramp to triangle pinch. Step left, to good holds. Move up clipping next 2 bolts passing them on the left. At overhang hand jam traverse right and up to Lost Boys Anchors

name: Can't Remember
description: Fun slab climbing. Hands get thinner at last 2 bolts. 8+ variation starts 10 feet right.

name: Clever Retort
description: Climb face straight up passing bolts. Follow new bolts over the top to new anchors.

name: Electric Co.
description: The steepest route on this wall, directly up the middle of the featured vertical face.

name: Left Birch
description: Start below and right of the first bolt Two Pines. Climb up to a pod (1-2" cam. Run it out up and right to left facing corner right of Two Pines (sling a birch tree move up left facing corner to a small pine and move left to Two Pine Anchors.

name: Lost Boys
description: 3 bolts up steep slabby face to a shared 2 bolt anchor.  Crux is reaching a 2 finger pocket above the first bolt.

name: Maggie
description: Climb arete starting below arete 10' right of Mia. Climb arete to Mia anchor. Many eliminates exist with a wide range of difficulties. The easiest starts in the hand crack to the right in corner and climbs left over the corner at second bolt(10d~11a).

name: Mia
description: climb up face to 2nd bolt, then diagonal right up slab. Tricky feet at 3rd bolt

name: Old School High Ball
description: Fun route on occasionally slimy footholds

name: Public Service
description: Easy big edge slab climbing up to the last bolt, crux seemed to be going from the last bolt to the anchors.

name: Right Birch
description: Start same as Birch. Move up inside corner and then right to birch tree. Climb up Steeper terrain along a corner to a pancake flake at the top.

name: Safe Harbor Direct
description: Similar to its slabby neighbors, but SHD requires more thinking and delicate balance for some moves. A pleasure to climb.

name: Snake Route
description: Straightforward warm-up route. A few slabby moves exist if you're interested in eliminates.

name: Sugar High
description: A somewhat overlooked albeit very good route.  The climbing features some cool sidepull and thin face moves on vertical rock.  Work a bit right at bolt 2 and then crank back up and left to a steep rest and clip (crux 1).  Shake and then work back a bit right (crux 2) and up passing one more bolt to the shuts.

name: Trad/Solo
description: Trad or solo the crack just left of Safe Harbor Direct. It's a nice cruiser that has fairly good gear.

name: Two Pines
description: It might be called One and A Half Pines soon. A natural warm up climb. Low angle slabs to a crux at the end. This held water the longest of any climbs in the Electric Co. area when we were there (a couple of days after rain), requiring some different moves than if dry.

name: Under Fire
description: Bouldery start from left (low crux), then up the arete.

name: Dancing Abi
description: Climb blank face over 2 bolts.   The arete to the left is off.   Too bad it's not longer!

name: Elevenish
description: start 15' left of tenuous on large rock at base. climb to first high bolt then right and up beyond 2 more bolts. At third bolt go right to fourth bolt. climb straight up black streak (few tiny finger nail pockets and ripples) to anchors. If you traverse further right towards "Tenuous" (resist temptation) there is a small pocket (boo!) that makes it much, much easier.

name: Good Enough
description: fun moves after last bolt, easy start

name: Grassy Ledges
description: Climb Slab between and around grassy areas on clean rock. Move up to small roof. Pass roof on its left. Continue to trees.

name: The Hanging Garden
description: Climb easy slanted ledge to 1st bolt. Continue past 2 more bolts and pull roof. Continue up slab past more bolts to anchors.

name: Hollywood Blvd
description: Climb straight up face over 2 bolts. Going left to the left facing jugs is considerably easier. Also, you can climb left from a stance on jugs up unto a blunt arete and get to the anchors @ about 5.9 R, but a fall will land you on the ledge and you'll swing a good amount as well.

name: Horizontal plaything
description: climb slab to roof flake. Turn lip to anchors.

name: Scott's Turf builder
description: Climb inside corner to anchors

name: Streamliner
description: Climb up slab right of Tenuous. Follow bolt paralleling Tenuous. Clip old button head and continue up blank slab with tiny fracture right of tenuous's crux.   At top of cliff move left to Tenuous anchors.

name: Tenuous Odyssey
description: High first bolt but fairly easy climbing to it.  Fairly straight route following bolt line.

name: Turf Builder Access Route
description: Climb crack between Scott's turfbuilder  and 11-ish. End at Scott's anchor

name: Under the Bridge
description: One bolt with possibility of gear at weakness on overhang.   Unsure of redpoint and grade.

name: Vine St
description: Climb three bolts. Arete is on! (5.7)   Or   Climb straight over bolts. Arete Off! (5.10b)

name: Between Rains
description: Scramble up low angle slab to first high bolt. Climb beyond second bolt. Go left to third/fourth bolt ( bolt on right is a different route) and power up face on small crimps and/or deadpoint, gaining cliff top, hand traverse right to the anchors.

name: Between Rains (Thunderhead Var.)
description: Start on Between Rains.   At third bolt move right and climb steep thin face angling right then back left to anchors

name: Ding-Dong the Wicked Witch is Dead
description: Approach the first bolt directly, going left to the "bomber" left hand side pull will feel harder than 5.5. Continue up the route climbing directly to second and then 3rd bolts. Move slightly left and up easy terrain to the last bolt. From the stance at the last bolt move up over bulge and slight LEFT to easy terrain to anchor

name: Fist Full of Schist
description: Climb just left of three bolts to anchor.   Balancy and technical. The crack on the right is unnecessary and often filled with poison ivy.

name: How Do Ya' Like Dem Apples?!
description: Climb the left facing dihedral passing 2 bolts. Climb right around the small roof then straight up please to 2 bolt anchor.Stay very, very close to the last bolt. Wandering right as some are want to do may result in chossy rock (and climbers) to fall!The rotten, junky crack way to the left is off - not that you'd want to use it anyway

name: Lynn's Chin
description: A long route for Safe Harbor. just follow the bolts. Thoughtful, thin crux at bolts 5 thru 8. Stay right of crux bolts for a touch more difficulty.   Nice Slab climbing followed by roof at the top.   Climb the roof left of last bolt for more fun.

name: Machismo
description: Thin technical climbing past the first 3 bolts (crux).  Continue up past a chossy hole to a drilled blasting hole for a good rest.  Finally up sloping holds that are pretty good to the anchor.

name: Pass The Dew
description: Climb left facing corner/slab on trad. Gain roof, move left under roof, clip 1st bolt at 25 '. Follow bolts to 2 bolt anchor. Crux is unlocking sequence to move beyond and just left of first bolt.  Direct Start: Start below bolt, scramble up to left facing corner and stem up to roof. Move right to first bolt. 5.9(R/X)

name: Too Cold Two Stroke
description: Climb thin pocket/seem straight up to first bolt and pod. Clip, move left and up to second bolt. Climb to third bolt and move LEFT over third bolt to arete. Lie back arete to top.

name: Virtual Reality
description: Follow bolts.  Crux is low getting to the second bolt. After that 5.11

name: Witness
description: Starts on a narrow face between a left-facing inside corner and an arete.  Climb the face using the arete (full value) or the insider corner (easier), then pull the overlap on the right (full value) or skirt past it on the arete (easier, more run out) to rap rings at the top.

name: Li 'l Jerry
description: The route's full name is,  "Li'l Jerry is a good name for a fat squirrel". Don't ask, had to be there.  Start under a short chossy band that is sometimes damp 20' right of Your Mother. Climb said band to first high bolt. Continue following bolts up corners and ledges to a blank head wall at the last bolt. You can use a small pocket out left about 3 feet from the bolt line or small side pulls out right about 3 feet from the bolt line. Or, you could go direct using tiny face holds and tiny feet ( 5.10)   Directly above the right hand anchor bolt is a decent clipping hold for the anchors.

name: Pro Bono
description: nice, easy slab

name: Quaranteenage Mutant Ninja Turtles
description: Move up the low angle slab to a crux bulge near 3rd bolt. Continue up fun, easy terrain to the finish.

name: Slab Master
description: Exciting slab with a couple of face holds. Start the climb about 8' to the right of Super Slab and go straight up the face. There are six bolts plus the anchors.

name: Super Slab
description: One of the best at Safe Harbor, would be a popular slab climb anywhere. Climb to the high first bolt, then to the super fun thin crux above the roof.

name: Through the woods
description: Start just right of Slab Master.   Climb to first high bolt. follow 2 more bolts then through a break in the tree (sling) ledge above. Climb 2 more bolts step left and climb right facing flake to top.

name: Who Shot Bambi?
description: Moderate slab climb between Pro Bono and Super Slab. Crux comes pulling the roof and a thin section right above it.

name: Your Mother
description: Simply follow bolt line. Tends to stay wet after rain.

name: Autumn Arch
description: This route is fantastic - varied between the upper and lower halves, long, interesting moves and great stemming! Nice view from the top too.     From the Rock & Ice guide published in issue #51: "Mega-classic corner with great stemming. Beware - A 165-foot [50m] rope is required to lower off this, and adjacent routes!"

name: Chillin' and Maxin'
description: Begins with easy climbing on face right of Wonderama on bolts shared with its neighbors. At third bolt move right, then straight up to the roof after the fourth. Find a solution jug to pull the roof, then climb through the crux on a blunt arete with some slabby mantle moves.

name: Doppelganger
description: This is one of the coolest routes Safe Harbor has to offer featuring good moves up a solid shield of orange rock. Start on either the first five bolts of Autumn Arch or on the first five bolts of Expose'. Make a few balancey moves past two bolts to a stance where the wall steepens. Make some athletic moves to another stance (crux) on a thin ledge. Shake and pull one more sequence moving up and right topping out on a large ledge.

name: Eminant Domain
description: Shares the first 3 bolts with Locomotion and Chillin' & Maxin'.  Move right at the 3rd and 4th bolts.  If your footwork isn't good this will feel harder, lots of stemming and counterpressure.  Ends with a mantle onto a comfy little ledge.

name: Expose'
description: A wild route. Climb past 6 bolts on funky rock to a stance. At bolt seven you have two options;  1) Follow the path of least resistance by underclinging out right and then work up the right arete feature.  2) Manufacture some difficulty by going straight up. This sequence is in the 11+/12- range and is worth doing.  From the top of the arete pull a somewhat powerful move to the shuts.

name: FR-Agile
description: Climb bulging rock, staying directly on bolt line for first 2 bolts.  Climb left facing corner using the right wall for a few choice stems to make it easier. At the top move left to anchor with out topping out in alcove.

name: Heart's Horizon
description: "Follow two bolts through a cruxy alcove. Climb past three more bolts on easier but enjoyable ground to a distinct crux past the sixth bolt to the anchor." [-Jonathon Clark]

name: Locomotion
description: If you climb 10's you should lead this, exhilarating exposure pulling the roof into a nice diagonal tips crack.    It's named for a train that passed by during the crux of Rich Romano's first ascent.     It's the next bolted route right of classic Wonderama.

name: Lycra Perversion
description: Start to the left of Heart's Horizon and climb past a funky section. Mover more easily up the corner and then make the crux traverse around the arete to the right. Continue up the arete passing one more cruxy section near the top. Use caution nearing the anchor as the rock qulaity is suspect in spots. The anchor has been lowered a bit due to the dubious rock quality in the vicinity of the existing cold shuts. [-Jonathon Clark]

name: The Schisting
description: Climb easy ground to third bolt (5.6R)    The crux is at the top.   According to Jeremy (he loves this climb), the beta goes like this, "You can't fall anywhere above or below the first bolt. You also can't fall anywhere above or below the second bolt. After that, the top is great and safe".   Also, clipping the anchor from any hold below the very top of cliff is desperate.

name: Static Cling
description: Static Cling is to the climber's right of Urban Daydreams, sharing the start of Autumn Arch but heading up the face instead of following the corner.

name: Urban Daydreams
description: "About 20 feet left of the obvious corner of Autumn Arch. Blocky start to get established on the slabby face. Based on the streaks, it looks like the face stays wet longer than other sections. Fun, delicate climbing; a little grungy in some spots but not bad.     It was wet at the top on Sunday but the left-hand pocket was still pretty good and there was a dry nub for a left foot to feel just secure enough to get to the anchors." [-Mojo Monkey]

name: Visionaire
description: Climb steep face left of Wonderama

name: Where Eagles Dare
description: Climb to first very high bolt(heady). Pull bulge and climb nice face to a stance at bolt 4. Follow finger crack clipping 2 more bolts to a left facing corner with a tricky move to last bolt. The crux is balancing to the anchors on decent feet.  "Eagles dive-bombing each other and there are no route names with eagles in them so she wanted a name with eagles - we settled on "Where Eagles Dare" - a double homage to the eagles that now frequent the cliffs, and the Clint Eastwood movie of the same name"

name: White Stripes
description: Climb the face past two bolts (5.11) to a ledge.  The corner is considered off route and is significantly easier.  From the ledge reach up, clip a bolt and try to unlock a baffling sequence (crux) passing two more bolts on the thinnest holds Safe Harbor has to offer.

name: Wonderama
description: The striking arete right of the large Autumn Arch corner. There were a couple of decent rest spots to shake the pump out of your right arm - that is getting most of the workout on this overhanging arete.

name: 18 and Life
description: Climb suspicious looking rock to first bolt.   It is quite solid though as long as you stay near the bolt line.   Continue up face paralleling 19s in the house to anchors.

name: 19s In The House
description: What the heck does this name mean?    The route looks blank at the bottom for a 10a, but the moves are all there and are not hard to do. Just a little tricky to find them, but it is a fun route if you're in to balancy.

name: AF in PA
description: Better than it looks, but needs some cleaning. Steep and kinda pumpy.

name: Avant Garden
description: This is better than it looks (but needs some cleaning).

name: Both Ends Burning
description: Better than it first appears

name: Both Ends Burning Variation
description: 2/3s way up "Both Ends Burning" move right up over little overlap/roof to pass the last 2 bolts on the right.

name: Final Cut
description: Clip first 2 or 3 bolts of 'Rocking Peacock'. Then move left on left facing corner. Follow bolts over bulge to Cold Shut anchors

name: Marriage by Napster
description: Climb sparse 3 bolt line right of righteous and the wicked. Above 3rd(last) a large cam may help.  Follow arete (run out) to anchors on Righteous.   Solid for grade.

name: The Righteous and the Wicked
description: A wicked, techy facea Bob Perna classic!

name: Rockin Peacock
description: Reachy crux past roof.

name: Bat Crack
description: Up blocky face to stance, then head straight up the thin crack (fingerjams) on the overhanging face.

name: Black Is Power
description: Crux is between bolts 1-2. Higher sections look blank but there is actually more there.

name: Crips & Bloods
description: Up the first three bolts of a face (shared with Bat Crack), then up the steep arete on the right.

name: Ellie's Belly
description: Two weeks ago we put in a new route at Safe Harbor, PA. We call it, in the spirit of Lynn's Chin, "Ellie's Belly."     Six clips, it climbs left facing corners and finishes on a low angle slab. We believe it rates 5.6 or 5.7. I see it as a warm up for other climbs in the area, a pleasant beginner's route, and a safe climb for novice leaders.     "We" is Dave Rosso, Rob Goldberg, and Alan Margolies -- longtime Safe Harbor climbers.

name: Numero Uno
description: Start laybacking/stemming your way through the corner, then up to a good rest then easy face climbing to the anchors.

name: The Other Crack by Numero Uno
description: Climb crack just left of T Bag.   End on Numero Uno Anchors

name: T-Bag
description: Up the crack/corner system

name: That Crack by Numero Uno
description: Start on steep crack 10' right of Numero Uno.   Follow crack unto its end at the last bolt on Numero Uno.

name: Tonga
description: Left past a little roof to start, followed by as many slabs as you feel like. Stop at the first anchors, or continue up more low angle rock to Wild Palms' anchors higher up.  Upper anchor is now equipped with drop ins (as of 2 Mar 2020)

name: Tonga Redirect
description: Climb Tonga to 3rd bolt (5.9).   Break left up to head wall.    Climb slightly overhung face (5.11) to shallow drill hole to Anchors

name: Tradatrocity
description: A few jam moves up high on this on.

name: Warthogs Can't Fly
description: Start right of T Bag. Climb interesting corners to roof with drill hole. Climb up the left dihedral to first high bolt and follow the rest to the top. The Anchors are about 10' above last bolt.

name: When Doves Cry
description: More sustained warm-up climbing than Econoline (that sports a single tricky move towards the top).

name: Wild Palms
description: Start left of the first bolt and traverse right using the lip of the small roof, pass the first bolt and continue right to gain the fin/ramp of Numero Uno and the second bolt.  Delicate stemming will get you to the top of the bulge and the third bolt, then easier climbing to the top.

name: Crumbledore
description: Start right and up on a ledge right of Flex All. Follow 2 bolts up thin holds and finish on Train in Vain anchors

name: Demon In My Semen
description: Climb up to a hanging block and clip the first bolt (high but easy climbing) thin face climbing past two bolts lets you gain a ledge.  A reachy move to gain the rail and this one is in the bag.

name: Econoline
description: Thin face climbing past 3 bolts to gain a dirty ledge then easier climbing past 2 bolts to the anchors.

name: Eight ... No. Ten!
description: Climb face through 3 bolts.   Then a bit run out to 4th bolt. There is a rotten, chossy section to your left. stay away! (goes with out saying, really)   Clip 5th bolt and roll to anchors.   Harder climbing right of bolt line all the way to just beyond the last bolt then immediately move left.    Stay away from the choss on descent also.

name: Flex All
description: Most start below and left of first bolt others start on mono directly below first bolt. Climb to second bolt. Move left to big crimp near arete. From there go up right to big ledge. Easier to top.

name: Flex in Vain
description: Scramble up to high bolt. Climb up to third bolt passing sketchy block on your left. When we attempted to trundle the sketchy block it wasn't budging. Just the same leave it alone. From last bolt finish up slightly right to undercling then tiny finger/layback seam that top out at jug and anchors.   There is a crack/corner far to the right that has lots of chossy stuff (stay near bolt line) - belayer beware.    The route is pumpy and sequential

name: The Sighting
description: Work you way up either side of the slaby face, then using big holds climb the overhanging face to the anchors.

name: Train in Vain
description: Perform an athletic sequence (12a) past the first bolt to an okay stance and clip the second bolt.  Climb up and right through a powerful boulder problem and clip the third bolt (which can be difficult to clip).  Pump past two more bolts to the anchor.    I'd recommend stick clipping the first bolt as the climbing is relatively hard right off the bat.

name: 5.9 crack
description: Discontinuous crack between Parabolic Corner and Ad 2 Vic. Follow upper crack to cliff top then traverse left to Parabolic anchors.

name: Ad 2 Vic
description: Climb thin face over 2 bolts to ledge. Clip third and move to anchor.

name: Adopted Son
description: Thin climbing, a little heady getting to the anchors, a 4th bolt might calm the nerves, but it was chopped and never replaced. Easy climbing above the third bolt, despite the runout.

name: Adopted Son Direct
description: Start right of Adopted Son. Follow thin white streak to a small mantling ledge. Maybe get gear to the left. Then up to pocket. Fiddle some gear into it. Straight up to horizontal crack and gear. Finally straight up to finish on Last move of Adopted Son  (optional gear right at top of crack).

name: Body Drama
description: Climbs the arete to the left of Mental As Anything. Harder version starts on the arete while the easier start uses a short ramp to access the large horizontal rail. Climb the arete using crimps, pockets, jugs, jams and kneebars. Don't be punter and cop a rest by rocking over to the slab to the right.

name: Crossroads
description: Climb delicate moves and possibly the crux of the entire route to a high first bolt.  Easy climbing through two more bolts lead to another crux with a deceptively good finger slot.  It's not over yet, as a fun boulder problem up high guards the anchors.

name: Deep V Crack
description: Climb obvious "v" crack just right of JSF.   Climb crack to tree. Then scramble to anchors on JSF   Route needs cleaned

name: Humpin' Somethin'
description: Climb easy corner/ledges to top ledge. Plug in Camalot. Climb face. There are pockets for left hand and corner for right hand. Stay left of nose for full effect.  Finish on thin seem thru V notch to anchors.  You can pull around nose to the right at first bolt dropping the grade to 5.10, but bad swinging falls.

name: Hydroman
description: The historic first sport route to get bolted in Safe Harbor.    Little pockets, sometimes sharp, and just enough holds for fun, thoughtful climbing. Left-hand pocket used to get to the not-as-good-as-you'd-like horizontal near the top had a piece break off on Sunday. Was a little wet/dirty inside, and somewhat sharp, but usable. Crux was right at the top for us. My partner worked up the arete to the right and had a tricky step left to get to the anchors. I stayed in the corner, eventually getting a hand out/up left, then a heel to get settled. I then came up and right to the anchors.

name: Incipient Crack
description: Climb face and cracks (which may or may not become apparent) to trees.   Route needs cleaned

name: JSF (Jay's Scare Fest)
description: Just right of Ad 2 Vic.   Start on small boulder.   Climb tiny left facing crimpy corner.    Follow crimp corner to its end and move up to decent left hand side pull. Clip first bolt and follow crack to big ledge.   clip second bolt and then up to anchors.

name: Le Eaglet
description: Intro to Safe Harbor 101. Starts on broken rock, then moves up slabs broken by tiny ledges.

name: Mental As Anything
description: Slabby face climbing with ample protection. Fun moves: chances for high steps, hand and foot matches, hidden fingertip pockets, tiny edges and nubs for the toes. A more sustained challenge than other Safe Harbor 5.9s like Adopted Son, Tonga and SH Direct.    I went with Eric Horst's grade of 5.9+, though a Rock and Ice article (from around the 1990s?) called it a 5.10a. Hard 9 or easy 10 are both accurate enough for the subjective YDS.

name: Old School
description: Start below Ad 2 Vic.   Gain small ledge and clip buttonhead.   Move up right to flake (gear).   Move again up right to crack and gear.   Follow crack to big ledge and move right and finish on Deep "V" crack or 5.9 Crack.

name: Old Trad Line
description: Follow right facing rap from below crossroad to Hydroman anchors

name: Parabolic Corner (high variation)
description: Climb up a steep left-facing dihedral most of the way to the top, then work around the arete on your  right to the finish.

name: Parabolic Corner (low variation)
description: Climb up a steep left-facing dihedral. Halfway up, move around the arete to the face on the right, and finish there.

name: There Goes the Hood
description: A diagonally traversing slab. Tiptoe up the ledge system, hop up to a tree, then work up the face to the anchors. Look for a big translucent crystalline formation on the last big footstep.

name: Tin Woman
description: Climb steep slab to a high bolt. Passing a clump of trees (they're on the climber's left) to second bolt. Follow remaining bolts diagonally up and left to anchors. Optionally, continue to anchors on cross roads.

name: RC Direct
description: Start three feet left of the corner. Climb the center of the face below the small ledge. Then, using solution holes, lunge for the right hand bucket and mantle to ledge.

name: Birthday Traverse
description: Facing the Cheese Grater Boulder, follow the trail upstream around some large boulders. Looking left you can see a large, gently upward sloping arete. Use a combination of good handholds and heelhooks to make your way to a vertical crack at the right end of the arete. Cool movement on a beautiful piece of rock!

name: The Cheese Grater
description: Many problems and eliminations on this boulder. Be creative.

name: Mantling 101
description: Located next to the trail leading from Cheese Grater Boulder to Birthday Traverse. Problem begins with two hands in a low quartz band. Pull on and ascend up the thin face to gain the slopey lip of the boulder. Get a high left foot and start squirming like a beached whale to the oft dirty top-out!

name: Unknown
description: About 15 feet uphill from the Cheese Grater Boulder, behind a large tree. Problem goes straight up the 10 to 15 foot nearly vertical slab. Underclings and crimps.

name: Barugon
description: Start same as Guiron. Traverse right into MonsterX.  Work up through sketchy undercling flakes. Top out far right

name: Guardian of the Universe
description: At the bottom on the far right of the face, start matched in the crack.  Go straight up into finger pockets and work left to the start of monsterX. Keep working up and left, to the crystal shelf on Guiron. Top out straight up.

name: Guiron
description: Towards the left of the boulder, start matched on crimps about 4-5 feet up. Dyno up to crystal patch. Top out straight up

name: MonsterX
description: Towards the middle of the face, start matched on obvious crystal patch. Work straight up. **V1-Use the monster jugs.

name: Monkey Face
description: Good foot holds and great for beginner or young climbers learning to send

name: Battletoads
description: Right of Contra. To start, left meat hook and right undercling feature below the crack. Work up and left, finishing into Contra. *Crack is off*

name: Contra
description: Start left hand on the arete. This is the only time the arete may be used. Throw up and out right to a bomber sidepull. Work your way up through the pockets and chips. Top out straight up.

name: Double Dragon
description: Starting on opposing crystal patches. Once feet are above the start holds, rock on the left is off. Work straight up through the crimps and jugs. **Both Aretes and the crack are off**

name: Clam Sandwich
description: Sit start in the corner and work towards the left (opposite of the crack). Two obvious holds hang from the roof then use your imagination and superhuman ability to get on top of the roof. I've heard this is the most difficult route at Shaffer (guessing upwards of V9) and a local climber has the first ascent, any opinions?

name: Low Roof Direct
description: Same start as traverse but move straight out roof to gain an upside-down no hands rest.

name: Low Roof Traverse
description: Start from sitting in the corner and use a leg hook to reach out to the crack. Follow the crack out around the crux to top out.

name: The Womb
description: About 30 feet towards the main wall from Smokie Boulder. Two obvious start holds that are always chalked. Problem goes straight up and over the lip. Area classic!

name: Beckys Roof Traverse
description: Same start as Beckys, but continue traversing right at the roof through some tough moves to a good ledge.

name: The Dark Room
description: This climb spirals up a cylinder formation in the rock. The river does some crazy things, this route is wild looking and possibly one of the more unique climbs you will ever do!

name: Bank Robbers Cave
description: Start at bottom of cave and traverse left in seam to small dihedral. Do hard moves into dehedral and top out.

name: Dark Crystal
description: Start on bank robbers, go out seam until you can come to the underside of the boulder. Crimp the crystals and continue out steep overhang till you can mantle onto slab. Jigs out right are off.

name: Psycho 78
description: Start on Rail, bust to crack and make it to the top.

name: Screaming Tanquility
description: Start on left side of block. Go up and right to the right arete and top out.

name: Heavy Metal Kids
description: First block you come to from Woodrow Rd. Climbs out the obvious left prow.

name: Pine slab
description: The slab on the side closest to the trail next to the think pine tree. Many variations.

name: Purgatory
description: This is the corner to the right of the tree. The next fin on the right is off route.     Sit start.

name: Stuck in Purgatory
description: Up the off-width crack between fins to the right of "Purgatory." Holds are plentiful.

name: Counterweight
description: Start under steep 45 degree overhang. Do funky move to jug on right arete. Follow the arete upwards and left to the top out.

name: Fire Wall
description: Stand start with left on small mailbox slot and right on undercling thing. Go up and work your way to a small two finger pocket with the left. Bust big to the jug. Top out.

name: Grease Lightning
description: Start on jug. Do moves to the next big jug. Micah Klinger has topped this out.

name: Malicious Intent
description: Start on underclings in center of boulder, go up short overhang.

name: Peace Arete
description: Behind Fire Wall. Arete climb with a peace sign drawn on it. Climb it.

name: Squeeze Me
description: Fun little chimney, less than vertical, with cracks for hand holds on the sides, and chockstones for footholds. Crux comes when you have to rotate your body around and find footholds at the top to escape the chimney.

name: Beginner Free Climb
description: Sloped hill with rocks for traversing and freeclimbing on that lead down to the Susquehanna river. Good for messing around on or warming up.

name: Epic Trundle.
description: This is the only sport climb I could find it seems to have had a few bolt chopping issues..    The climb is pretty easy and has chipped holds and a few friction moves but all and all it was kinda fun.

name: Kamakaze Crack
description: This is an excellant crack climb for beginners and shouldn't be missed if you are in the area. The climb eats gear and only has a few places where hand jams are needed.

name: Bob Dylan Did Drugs
description: This great problem climbs out a low, sculpted roof on good holds spaced far apart. It has a fairly intricate sequence but will reward what effort is put into it.    Sit start at the very lowest point on hard-to-find undercling edges. Pull on and move to a crimp further out the roof. Left hand to a crimpy horizontal crack, then right to a blocky hold higher up. Cross right to an excellent undercling jug (kneebar!), and consider the last few moves. With the right hand, move to an insecure pinch on the lip of the boulder. Shift some feet, and make a large move to a crystally sloper on the apex of the boulder. Top out, making sure to not hit your head on the limb above the boulder.

name: The Cranking
description: This difficult testpiece ascends the left side of a wavy, overhanging prow. Many climbers work this, few send. However, any time spend trying it is a reward, as it is a very smooth, challenging line.    Sit start on low edges. Move up a small bulge at the base of the prow using sidepull crimps and the arete. Once good feet are established, slap up the arete. Move the right hand out to a sidepull pinch. Slap left again and shift feet up until it is possible to bring the left hand way up to a crimp on the face. With difficulty, move right across the face under the prow until it is possible to grab the large slopey jug at the prow's tip. Top out over the right arete.    The block to the left is off. Apparently, the problem using the block all the way up is 'The Spanking' V7.    Video of the problem can be seen here.

name: Divine Order
description: Start matched on a high jug, move left over the sloper rail then up the obvious flake.

name: Pyramid Slab
description: A fun and delicate slab problem up a triangular face. Sit start on the left side of the face, right next to the ramp. Climb the face on small but usable crimps and small slopey edges. Top out at the apex.

name: Ten High
description: This proud line climbs the right arete of the Cranking boulder. Starting low, move through crimps and pinches to a long move to a poor crimp just right of the arete. Make several more very difficult moves on crimps to gain a jug right under the lip. A great line put up by a great local climber.

name: White Blaze Slab
description: Between the main areas and the Cranking are a number of low-angle outcroppings right on the trail. These make for excellent warmups, and a few are somewhat highball. This route is found where the AT jogs downhill between two rocks. An obvious featured slab is visible. Climb it.

name: Classic Arête
description: This problem, while not physically very difficult, requires a good deal of trickery and beta. Fire away!    Start standing on the arête with a left hand sidepull/undercling and a right hand in a thin horizontal. Smear and move left around the corner, grabbing a poor right handhold on the little shelf. Readjust feet, and move up left into a juggy pod. Top out onto the tricky bulge.    Climbs far better than it looks; classic!

name: Crystal Meth
description: Sit/squat start with left hand sidepull and a right hand crimp. Work right to arête, then up.

name: Entrance Arête
description: Tackles the juggy right arete of the overhanging Entrance Boulder. The original start jug was broken off in 2007, making the V0 much harder. Sit start matched on the chalked edge in the center of the face where the jug once was. Pull one hard move out right to a corner, then move up to a good flat jug. Follow shelf-like jugs up the arete to top out. Great warmup.

name: S.o.m.b.e.
description: Hard to find.  Start left hand on the arete and right on the undercling edge.  Move into the undercling jug and fire for the slopey lip, then match and make another big move for a huge crystal.

name: Spittle Machine
description: This fun slab problem climbs a perfectly flat face that appears almost featureless. The line lies in a narrow corridor above an angled landing- be careful!    Start standing on a right hand crimp and pinch some small crystals with the left. Move up and into a large, slopey pocket. Continue on small crimps that are difficult to see from below.

name: Changing Coroners
description: On the other side of the whiskey crack boulder and just above Mantle Man, find the chalked low shelf.  Start heel hooked on that shelf with a lower jug undercling and an edge for your hands.  Perform a difficult sequence to round the corner then climb the delicate face to a heady mantle topout.

name: Grand Traverse
description: The Grand Traverse moves across Vulture View Rock from left to right. The climbing is varied and features a nice rest. It is part of a very contrived larger traverse of most of the central area of Whiskey.    Start under the far left end of the enormous roof. Climb delicately rightward on small crimps (crux) to gain a wide crack in the center of the face below the roof. Jam or layback this 10 feet up and continue traversing on the juggy horizontal. A rest ledge can be found at the right corner of the roof where the horizontal ends. From here, the problem traverses a tricky slab. With sparse hands, walk your feet down and across the rail-like features. Once across the slab, climb the chimney to the top of the rock and enjoy a warm beer.

name: Hang On
description: Start matched on the huge shelf, then move up through crimps and slopers to a sketchy topout.

name: Platex Crack
description: This problem follows a blocky rail before entering a left leaning crack. Full of interesting moves, this is a nice warmup or intro to the area.    Start sitting with hands matched on the vertical rail. Make one hard move to stand up, then continue up towards the crack, liebacking it to the top and an easy mantle.

name: Whiskey Crack
description: This long, pumpy, left leaning crack is an area classic and will ensure that you have no skin left on your fingers when you leave Whiskey. Start as low as possible on the right end of the crack. Using positive pods in the crack, heel and toe hooks, and as many energy-conserving techniques as you can, follow the long crack to its end.

name: Wizard's Cane on a Mountaintop
description: This is a nice quick easy warm up and a good problem for first time outdoor climbers. Easy moves up the crack. The crux is probably underclining the flake but it's a pretty simple move. Use the features to the left of the crack and then focus on the flake on the second half of the lightning bolt shaped crack.

name: Stolen Delights
description: Stolen Delights tackles the corner to the right of Webber Seam. Beginning at the undercling on the face left of the arete (same start as W. Seam), move right around the corner to a jug on the rail. Post feet and stand up hard into a bad left hand undercling. With the right hand, slap up a good vertical groove until you can reach a jug out left. Top out and walk off.

name: Webber Arete
description: Climbs the arete left of Webber Seam. The moves are nice but the line is short and the landing is poor, so this isn't quite a classic. Start standing with the left hand pinching the arete, right hand on a sidepull, and a very poor foot. Move up to a bad right hand crimp then make a long move left into the sloping vertical groove. One or two moves lead to a topout jug.

name: Webber Seam
description: The classic area moderate. A striking, obvious line up a seam in the center of the freestanding Webber boulder.    Start matched on a thin undercling with good feet.
