Move left to the seam. Crimp and sidepull up until you can grab a perfect quartz crystal crimp on the face to the right of the seam. With poor feet, make a long move to the lip and ultimately to the jug 6" behind the lip. Top out with ease.

name: Zero Wall
description: To the right of Webber Seam is a featured wall with several V0s. The climbing is unique at Whiskey in that it consists almost entirely of slopers and pinches. Great way to warm up. The best line follows a groove on the right side of the wall, but harder problems and eliminates exist.

name: Camille
description: Two feet right of Maddie. Start straight up a triangular block to a small crack leading up to a fairly easy, blocky section near the top.

name: Maddie
description: Start about four feet right of Maddie's Dark Side.  Climb the prominent left angled crack that leads up then angles a bit right.

name: Maddie's Dark Side
description: Crux is the lower section directly up through, and just above, the dark smear. Continue up a fairly easy section above that.

name: Main Wall Traverse
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: White Rock to Whiskey Springs Endurance Traverse (link)
description: Start on the Main Wall at White Rock Acres, traverse (right to left or east to west) the main wall near the ground moving up or down as needed. Once completed (100+ft of climbing) move to the White Wall and traverse the entire thing (100ft+) from east to west (closest to farthest on the trail).     Once that traverse is complete hit the trail (heading west away from Main Wall) until you hit the Appalachian Trail (AT). Take a left at the AT and follow all the way until you hit Whiskey Springs (+/- 4 miles).     Traverse around the Vulture View Area (theres a V3 established traverse already if youd like to follow that, check out Whiskey Springs on Mountainproject.com for more details) and climb whatever routes you wish THEN hit the trail going back.    Total of 10 + miles and some great endurance and technique (variety) training.    Can be done solo very easily or with friends or dogs.

name: Bubba
description: Really fun offwidth roof crack.    Start upside down with your legs above your head heel to toe camming, work your way out from under the roof following the crack to the top out. Pretty straight forward problem.     If you use 100% traditional offwidth technique (knee locks, hand stacks, heel to toe camming, leavittation techniques, etc) it is harder than V3. If you use mostly offwidth technique but use some of the face holds it goes around +/- V3.

name: Uber Classic Traverse
description: Traverse one end to the other. 100+ft of solid 5.3-5.9 +/- climbing.    Super classic. Been done by many for decades now (according to local legend Stan Schoonover)    Great way to work on endurance + can be done solo of course!

name: Angry White Men
description: this climb is located between bye bye bolt and monkey boy. excellent warm-up to harder climbing. don't blow the third clip.

name: Arocknophobia
description: Beginner route

name: Balls Deep
description: Easy moves at the bottom and very top, but the route earns its name on stemming moves up a dihedral requiring careful balance.    WARNING... A significant hold fell off this route. Is is no longer a 5.9. Instead, the lost hold creates a difficult stem move at 5.10+ or higher.

name: Bye Bye Bolt
description: Great climb, fun moves near the top.

name: Corny (Dennys Route)
description: Crux was getting off the ground, afterwards all the holds are positive as you move up an indistinct right facing corner.

name: Corny Alternate Start
description: To do

name: Don't Faint on my Disco (Variation)
description: Climb up through the drilled pockets of Faint, but after the second bolt rather than traverse out right on the slopers of Faint, continue straight up to the ledge above passing a bolt. From the ledge head straight up following Don't Screw with my Disco through the overhang. Names for this variation include Fanisco and Don't Faint on my Disco.

name: Don't Screw with My Disco
description: First bolt is tough for me to clip. I think it's really reachy, but, I have seen other shorties make the clip. Okay, after the first clip it's pretty easy up to the roof. The move over the roof is hard.

name: Faint  (drilled)
description: Start on a steep wall with sequential moves on drilled 2 and 3 finger pockets. After the initial boulder problem keep the pump clock in check and climb up natural features until the end.

name: Fracture
description: This route is to the right of Faint and the hardest part of this climb seemed to be at the first bolt, afterwards the climbing is easy and there are good rests on pretty big holds.

name: Hog Nose
description: Goes up the prow just right of Itching to Climb.    This is a fun climb with two burly moves before the second bolt. Not sure if you would stay off the ground if you blew the clip at the 2nd bolt.

name: Itching to Climb
description: On the face before it gets steep with the overhangs.      This climb has a polished start, but, it's a great beginner lead. Clean falls, great hands/feet make for a fun climb.

name: Jingle Bells
description: On the other side of the tree next to Itchin to Climb.     A long climb on good rock for birdsboro, the top is definitely harder for shorter folk.    Crux is getting to the anchors. High clip them from the right if you can reach them (5.9) or do some hard work heading left and up under the anchors to a crack that heads back towards the bolts (5.10)

name: Monkey Boy
description: Start off on some decent holds then launch into the crux which consists of moving to and off of two sloping small crimps, the route then eases up to about 5.9 or 5.10 past 3 more bolts to shuts.

name: Monkey Girl
description: Easier climbing past 2 bolts leads to a pumpy lieback.  Take care clipping the 3rd bolt, if you blow the clip, you might hit the slab.  Easier climbing follows the 3rd bolt to the anchors.

name: Puss in Boots
description: Starts at the downward pointing flake. Wanders back and forth between the bolts. I think it officially ends at the shuts halfway up the wall, but I usually bypass them on the left and head to the bolts directly overhead.

name: Rain Check
description: Easy climbing with the awkward crux at the second bolt.

name: Rain Check Direct
description: Third route from the left on the main wall, 4 bolt line next to Arocknophobia, this is a short easy route.

name: Shark Bait
description: Short route which follows the slightly overhung face below the shark's tooth. If you use the broken rock and arete on the right hand side, the variation is a 5.8 climb. Really a well bolted high ball problem.    Note: Be sure not to z-clip between bolts 1 and 2!

name: The Sixth Element
description: Beginner climb

name: Slab Dance
description: Tricky first bolt, then an interesting climb after that. The top is dirty.

name: Tap Dance
description: The crux is at the second bolt stepping your way around the bulge, after that the climbing eases up to 5.9 and goes to bolt anchors with rap rings.

name: Two Bolts - No Balls
description: 2 bolts (see name).

name: UCGB
description: Start on the vertical face to the right of the slab start the start is marked by an old fence post, work up to the overhanging face making some awkward moves on sharp holds, the crux seemed to be making the last move before the rap rings. There are a few places on this climb where you don't want to fall, or you will be hitting the low angle slab below you.

name: UCGB Slab Start
description: Start on the easy slab to the right of monkey girl, work up to the overhanging face making some awkward moves on sharp holds, the crux seemed to be making the last move before the rap rings. There are a few places on this climb where you don't want to fall, or you will be hitting the low angle slab below you.

name: Bottom Feeder
description: 9. Orange Sunshine Wall

name: Bottom Fishing
description: 8.Orange Sunshine Wall. This is the blocky line just right of the steep 5.11. Continue past 2 easy bolts to a 3rd clip at the crux. Get over the bulge and to the anchor. Either come down from here or continue up loose blocks past 3 more bolts to a high anchor.

name: Dirty Swing
description: 2. Orange Sunshine Wall

name: Dirty Thing
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Gym Dandy
description: Harder if short, I imagine. The crux is the start, a couple crimpy moves to the good holds by the bolt. At 6', it was two moves for me and I'm not sure they felt 5.11c. The rest of the climbing is easier 10.

name: Iodine-125
description: This route has 3 bolts and shares the starting holds of Gym Dandy, then blends into Bottom Fishing. The holds by the 3rd bolt are dirty and there is a bunch of loose holds - even by Birdsboro standards.

name: Jay's
description: 5. Orange Sunshine Wall, This line is a steep jug filled adventure. The climb is near the center of the orange sunshine wall. Start on left side, up some large holds to a horizontal hand ledge 7 feet up. Continue straight up/a bit right of the bolt line. Route curves up and left to the anchor. It' essentially directly behind the tree closest to the wall.

name: Orange Sunshine
description: Orange Sunshine Wall's name sake. Better than Brown Moonshine :\

name: Rocky and Bullwinkle
description: 10. Orange Sunshine Wall (last climb on the wall)

name: Sultans of Swing
description: Climb easily up the left slab past 4 bolts to anchors with rings.

name: [Redacted]
description: None at this point.

name: Cheese Burger EC
description: A ledgy climb up good incut holds.  Some holds are still loose and the climb is a bit dirty.

name: Connor's Climb
description: Last climb on Slab Climbs wall before walking over to Zorro Face.     This is a convenient place to teach leading and cleaning, since you can practically touch the anchors from the ground, and the rock is like a big escalator.

name: Dancing Nancy
description: This is really a 5.6 with a tricky start if you go straight up the face. It's easier if you start on the crack and go right then back left to the 2nd bolt.

name: Matthew's Climb
description: Easy climbing the whole way, good beginner route.

name: Neophyte's Delight
description: Easy warm up slab.

name: Super Lube
description: None for now

name: Triple Boots Blithering Brisket
description: Slabby, balancy climb with decent holds. Easy for the grade.

name: Triple S
description: If you want to intro someone to lead climbing, go over to Connors Climb. While this is not a terrible climb its always very dirty and not really worth messing around on.

name: Turkish Delight
description: Using the inside corner, move past one bolt to a ledge.  From the ledge, clip the second bolt and move up on a side pull to gain the third bolt. Continue up to jugs and the anchor.

name: Whimpering Wookie
description: Good route for learning edging, small ledges. This route will give you an idea of what some of Safe Harbor looks like.

name: Bee Sting-Be Strong
description: Crux is at the second bolt. Stay on the line for the 5.7 moves as there are easy ledges to the left.    Or the crux is at the fourth bolt if you are shorter (in wing span). Stem your left foot out to gain a needed inch to clip high.   Nice belayer's tree on the ground.

name: Clown Face
description: Nice intermediate face climb on good ledges, with a small roof and tricky throw to pull said roof.  Using your hands (maybe feet?) beyond the arete to the left is surely off.  This route shares the third bolt and anchors with Clown Shoes (hence the name).  Climber can bail out to clown shoes if necessary after the first bolt.  Climb up the easy, low angle base and make your way up to the horizontal crack and underclung mini roof.  Use the arete after clipping the second bolt far to your right and throw up to some more good ledges before making the third clip to the shared bolt.  Climbing eases up as it shares the finish with Clown Shoes to the anchor.

name: Clown Shoes
description: Climb past 3 bolts to anchors.

name: Face is Great - Choss is Off
description: Good climb, well bolted. Good rest spots. Because you could potentially deck from the second bolt, this might not be great for a new leader.  Using different lines and the same three bolts, variations can include from 5.6 to 5.11 moves.

name: Face O Meter
description: Tricky little roof. Short, fun climb.  Just around the corner from Zorro Face.

name: Geronimo
description: Climb the face to the right of "Red Skin".

name: Got Choss
description: short

name: Jenga
description: Starts is right of the zorro corner, follow the bolt line to the roof, clip the bolt below the roof and pull to one more bolt and then the anchors

name: Jengaistic
description: Climb straight up blocky holds past 5 or 6 bolts to anchors.  Pretty consistent grade most of the way up. Didn't feel like there was a crux.

name: Liken' the Lichen
description: True to its name, very dirty route covered in grime.

name: Pinch Six
description: Overgrown seeping ledges throughout.

name: Red Skin
description: Technical balancy start.  Pass bolts to a ledge, clip another bolt then make the crux move to the anchors.

name: Zorro
description: Oral tradition says this was the first route put up at Birdsboro. Walking along the trail, you see it jump out as the cleanest looking face climb in the quarry.    I started to the lower left of the face in a corner and then moved right to the face around to get to the first bolt. From there I stuck to the face, even though the arete or cracks near it were within reach. Instead I stuck to the thin, horizontal cracks/features on the mostly blank face.

name: Zorro Corner (Son of Zorro)
description: Looks like it's loose and chossy, it's actually much better than it looks. This is a nice fun jug haul.

name: 11 If by Right
description: This route shares the first 3 bolts of 9 If by Left, then rather than trending left, continue straight up the overhanging face/corner using some cool corner climbing.  The crux is at the 2nd last bolt going from the undercling to a good jug.  Due to the grunge, getting to the anchors could be quite cruxy as well.  Ends at a 2 shut anchor

name: 9 if by Left
description: Climb the corner between the flat wall and the steep blocky over hanging route. Maybe you can sneak over and TR Click,Click, Boom

name: Click, Click, Boom
description: Start the route on a small sketchy looking flake and reach out to a good pinch and a bad crimp find some feet and move up to the good holds by the 2nd bolt.  The last part of the crux involves a balancy perch on the pinch, if one were to fall here, I'm not sure if the first bolt would prevent a ground fall.  After the second bolt the climbing eases up substantially past another 2 bolts to the top.  Note this climb will feel easier the taller you are, if you're short the crux will feel quite hard, if you're tall you could reach through some of the difficulty making it feel easier than the stated grade.

name: Crying Ryan
description: Fun little roof to climb through. Look for the foot options, the bolts are close enough together to calm your head; no need to cry.

name: Alpine Line (first pitch)
description: More loose rock than your favorite Alpine Route. Belayers beware!

name: Batman
description: Great climb, well bolted. Anchors were recently replaced. Nice line.

name: Broken Bit
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: CT7
description: Easy climbing diagonaling left leads up to powerful moves up two underclings with terrible feet to more powerful/long moves climbing on drilled pockets above.  The last bolt is a little spaced below the anchors but it shouldn't be a big deal as the falls are clean.

name: Flippin Gravity (The Big Dumb Link-up)
description: Climb "Flippin the Bird" into "Opposing Gravity", instead of clipping the anchor on flippin, clip the bolt on "Welcome" to the right, pull the redpoint crux of that, and continue to the first anchor of "Hinterland", get a good rest on the flake above, and head to the first fixed draw of "Opposing"

name: Flippin' the Bird
description: Powerful movement from start to finish. The entire climb is hard, but the crux is probably moving through the sharp edges guarding the chains.     It is possible to link this route up with Hinterland? for a much longer climb.

name: Groovin'
description: Angles up and right to a good rest below a short, left-facing corner.  Clip the bolt on the face left of the corner, not the old one on the right side of it.  Technical crux is getting up this corner to the good holds above (and a bolt near the top of the corner).    From there head out right on good hands.  Head up before working back left near the top.  The upper section has good holds and fun moves - don't get pumped out before the anchors.    I found the anchors tricky to clip, but maybe I'm missing something or was just too pumped.

name: Hinterland (first pitch)
description: This is the first pitch. There's a rap station 1/2 way up the wall before things turn steep. Two Cruxes and continuous climbing make this a fun pitch.  There are a few glued on holds, notably the jug at the 3rd clip which also features a big X.

name: Hinterland (second anchors)
description: Climb the past the fist set of anchors past 4 bolts, the crux is above the 2nd bolt, with some slight leftward traversing moves with bad feet.  The final move of the crux requires getting a high foot while holding a bad pinch and an OK sidepull.

name: Laid Back and Well Hung
description: Hard climb up to the thrid bolt, after that it's sustained but it's big holds.

name: Opposing Gravity/King Solomon
description: at the chain on The Streak either bust left traversing on the ledge towards Hinterland and go up to a very interesting roof encounter, or continue up the refrigerator block and head left immediately afterwords. Going left seems to be a bit harder, but continuing up the streak seems to be the most popular. from there work your way up some powerful reaches on crimps and side pulls. Avoid going to far right and using holds on the streak to skip the crux. This is definitely the best route on the wall and deserves more attention. The first ascent history is a little murky and it seems there are two accounts. It sat untouched for quite a long time with its original bolts and some manky fixed draws,but it was rebolted in the winter of 2014 and now has nice steel fixed draws. Since its revival its seen quite a few repeats, including a flash by Vasya Vorotnikov.

name: Opposing Gravity/the Streak (1st pitch)
description: The Streak (whose first pitch is the same as Opposing Gravity's) is an apt description of this butt stain of a route. The holds are large. Follow up the right angling ramp onto the face. Careful for loose rock on the ramp (even still in 2010).

name: Romania
description: A good portion of this route fell down recently, and is no longer climbable until new bolts are placed.

name: The Space Between
description: Start in a right facing dirty, short corner and move up the jugs past 2 bolts to a good stance.  Move up for 3 or 4 moves on Batman to gain the 3rd bolt on the right.  Move up and right on thin holds and a technical sequences (crux) past 4 bolts to a good incut flake for a good rest.  Continue up past 1 more bolt on positive holds to the anchor.

name: The Streak (second anchors)
description: One of the last routes at the big wall between Hinterland and Alpine Line. Starts on left facing ramp and follows the dihedral up towards the first anchors.  Follow the pocket and prow up and slightly right to the second set of anchors.  Careful as holds continue to break between the prow and the anchors.

name: Twisted Sister
description: Between Laid Back & Groovin. Up thin crack to roof. Traverse right out roof to anchors. Sustained.

name: Two Screws
description: Two Screws is a somewhat funky and worthwhile variation to Groovin'.  Climb past the first four bolts and technical crux of Groovin' to a no hands stance.  Continue straight up the corner passing two more bolts to the Twisted Sister anchor.  The crux is the sequence passing the last bolt to the anchor.  There is some less challenging, but non-trivial climbing to get there.

name: Vulgarian Pterodactyl
description: First two clips easily gained, then a difficult thing section crux to step climbing with better holds. And a final difficult section before the finish.

name: Welcome to the Bird
description: Start off the ledge 6 feet up and launch right into the boulder problem crux of the route, which involves moving right on small holds and then  up past the 2nd bolt to two small crimps.  The boulder problem culminates with a deadpoint up to a good flat hold at the 3rd bolt.  Big reaches to sloping holds deposit you at a wobbly jug for a good shake and a high reach to clip the 4th bolt.  Move left and pull a cool roll over move and continue up on small sloping crimps past 2 more bolts.  A second crux near the top involves pulling an the remnants of a bolted on flake and small sidepulls.  Moving up to the jugs on Hinterland is the last bit of this route and the difficulty backs off, its a bit run out when you are clipping the anchors but the fall is clean and the climbing is easy at this point.

name: Wrecking Ball
description: Move right at the fourth bolt. Then climb the off width to gain ledge. Next a boulder sequence, into a difficult roof.

name: The Dude Abides
description: Start off the landing and its the left most climb.

name: Nice Marmot
description: The climb just to the right to the Dude Abides. Just climb the approach route belay at the top off the bolts.

name: Pretty strict, UH, Drug regimen
description: This is the approach line to the upper ledge so you can climb the upper climb.

name: Crackalicious
description: This line follows the obvious crack system through the right facing corner on the left side of the West Wall.    Scramble up to the base of the corner passsing a bolt or two.  Consider skipping these or back cleaning to avoid rope drag.  Use caution as the rock quality is poor through this section. Jam and layback through a powerful sequence that is capped by a mini roof.  Your efforts will be rewarded with a stance after the roof.  Stem your way up to the anchors.    While eyeballing this line from a neighboring route, the crack through the crux has widened significantly since I was on this in 2010. Not sure if this is from aggressive cleaning or traffic, but I remember thin locks on razor sharp rock for a couple of moves below the mini roof. The top looks like it has cleaned up quite a bit.

name: Hot Pockets
description: Climb easy rock past two bolts to a stance below a shield feature on the right side of the West Wall.  Consider skipping these bolts or backcleaning to avoid drag.  The climbing to this point is trivial, but the rock is poor.  Using drilled pockets and sidepulls, pull a bouldery sequence (crux) to a stance.  Continue up using more drilled pockets and arete features through another crux (easier than the first) section to the anchor.    The rock on the face is very solid, but seems to stay quite dirty.

name: Precarious
description: Starting from below crackalicious, head up and left off the ledge, then straight up 8 bolts to rings.  Crux is 2 bolts from the top.  There are a couple of tombstone blocks on a ledge halfway up that look scary like they might pull out and hit your belayer.

name: Spit On It !
description: Straight up face move left onto ledge rest. Climb large left facing diehdral moving right crux to nice finish.

name: Where The Wild Things Are
description: Tallest Climb at west wall wet start 10d or you can start on precarious and traverse left.

name: Bulge Aria
description: This felt pretty hard for 5.9+, maybe I did it wrong, but the crux came after the 2nd bolt and involved some balancy moves on small features to move through a bulge. The rest of the climb was pretty mellow.

name: Cerca del Paraiso (first pitch)
description: Delicate slab climbing. the crux is just below the anchors. This is a newly developed wall so there is still loose rock. A helmet is recommended for this climb.

name: Cerca del Paraiso (second Pitch)
description: Pull 2 mini roofs and then one more bolt to the anchors. Enjoy the view. You can link this into 1 pitch if you have a 70 meter rope.   WARNING: I would advise that experienced climbers only attempt the second pitch; if you do not clip the second bolt you will likely deck out on the slab.

name: The Enso
description: Make your way up the blocky looking slab. bring a runner for the fourth clip or you can run it out if your feeling brave. You'll then reach a small roof, this is the crux. Once you pull the roof you'll eventually come to a small traverse over the top of a roof toward an arête. You can use the arête or make your way up the face to the anchors. This climb is one of the longest pitches at Birdsboro and will challenge you slab endurance, i.e. your toes.

name: Fear Factor Direct
description: Beware of lots of loose rock as is typical on this whole wall. Overcoming the roof is a bit of a mental crux, knowing how common choss is here. head up up to anchors shared with Fear Re-Factored. #92 in guidebook.

name: Fear-Virgin crossover
description: The topo says to start at Fear-Refactored (second bolt line off the ground) or Smear Factor (Third Bolt line off the ground).  Topo says 5.9+, but we felt the start off of Smear Factor made it 5.10+, can't comment about the other start.    The main part of the climb moves up a small right facing corner that diagonals right past 6 or so bolts.    If starting from Fear, move up and left into the brushy alcove, traverse left thru it to join up the corner.  I haven't tried this start so i can't comment on the difficulty.    If starting from Smear, head straight up directly next to and partly on the seeping moss covered face, make some balancy moves at the second bolt (crux) clipping 3-4 bolts, then move right to join the inside corner.  Runners, skipping, or back-cleaning are recommended for the 4th and 5th bolt.    Second pitch is much easier, maybe 5.6? It continues up to the anchor for the second pitch of Virgin Suicides.  There is alot of loose and dirty rock on this pitch, I had a few holds rip-out, take care not to kill anyone below on Virgin Suicides.

name: Ghetto Palm
description: Ghetto Palm felt pretty tame compared to Bulge Aria, the crux was one move above the first bolt involving a big reach to a crimp and pulling up on it, the rest of the pitch was pretty tame.

name: High Steppin'
description: As the name implies, high step your way up the slab, many, many high steps and hand foot matches get you to an overlap, where you pull through a vertical section and then climb the last bit of slab.

name: Like A Slabby Virgin
description: The sign at Giant Wall shows this starting at the second horizontal log on the uphill trail. Up a pitch of slabs to an anchor.

name: Nine Line
description: A long route, use a 70m rope for one pitch, or a 60m rope for two. A variety of wall angles are found on this route, starting with a face climb and ending with low angle slabs. You will get to experience knocking rocks loose onto every angle.    The belay station is thoughtfully placed out of the line of rockfall for both this route the one to its right (downhill) side. But learn from my novice mistake, and don't put your belayer here while someone is climbing the route to the left/uphill side (Will It Stay or Will It Go?).

name: Pennsyltucky
description: I thought it to be the best line at the Giant Wall, follows solid bolts reasonably spaced to chain anchors at the top of the wall.    A cool move off a fixed cable (easily protected) leads to thin and thoughtful face moves.     Belay is not so optimal, you want the belayer below the first bolt but there's a significant slope - until a ledge is chopped it may be best to rig a semi-hanging belay off the fixed cable.

name: Slabtastic
description: Up a pitch of slabs to an anchor.

name: There Will Be Blood
description: Up a pitch of slabs to an anchor, then drink your milkshake.

name: Uwe comes to America
description: climb up the dirty alpine stylish ramp to a small ledge with 2 trees and an anchor. For the second pitch, begin climbing up the face until you get to a fin like feature. you can either work your way around it or climb up through it like a chimney. you are now in the fun spot. work your way up a corner crack(varying in size from #3-#5 Camalot) about 20 feet in length. when the corner ends  make your way to the anchor making delicate moves.

name: Virgin Suicides
description: This delicate slab climb doesn't require much strength, but instead asks for and rewards precise footwork. The crux comes 2/3rds of the way up pitches 1, past bolt 6.  Master this climb and you'll be ready for inscrutable slabs anywhere. Yosemite and NH await.  While technically 2 pitches in length, the second pitch is so short that it is a bit unsatisfying.  Given how this may be many Philadelphia area climbers first multipitch, you should know that the belays are not at good ledges (semi-hanging belay at both anchors), and you should know the fundamentals of multipitch rope management and anchoring.  Enjoyable in late fall, winter and early spring. Probably to hot in summer.

name: Will it Stay or Will it go
description: Starts with a bolt right next to a tree halfway up the hill.  Moves up lots of bad loose rock on sparse bolts, turns into a slab after the 8th bolt.  Distinct crux between bolt 5 and 6.  WEAR A HELMET, I and my partner both dislodged lots of rock on this one, each of us taking down chunks the size of softballs on lead.

name: Afternoon Delight
description: Fun short route. To start you step right of a huge ledge onto tiny feet nice exposure.

name: Blankety Blank
description: New route very thin start possible crux, straight shot to the bottom of a roof then curves out roof.

name: Chief Crazy Bird
description: Climb up a short slab to a roof, bust out right and up. this is the crux. make your way up onto the slab to the anchors. strenuous fun climb.

name: Early Bird Special
description: This route starts with some easy 5.10 climbing past 3 bolts up to a small roof. Pulling through the roof is not obvious and feels around V6; and clipping the 4th bolt is very strenuous. Once established above the roof about 20 feet of technical 5.10 climbing in a fun dihedral guards the chains.

name: Eight.Nine.Ten.
description: This climb is a sloping low angle left facing diehdral. The start shares the first two bolts with Son of a Blankety Blank. And the finish shares the last bolt and top anchors with Totally Unacceptable. But can also be finished to the right on Son of a Blankety Blank's finish. I enjoyed this climb very much.

name: Eleven.Twelve.Thirteen.
description: New route starts with a left facing flake pulls small roofs and tops out at Magnanimous's belay ledge

name: Magnanimous
description: the obvious bolted hanging arete visible from the lower slabs to the big wall. a well protected burl fest. pretty easy moves off the ledge to the first 2 or 3 bolts. Once you clip the first chain your in the buisness, keep moving and try not to get crossed up. big dynamic moves on drilled pockets. Not a lot of footholds so don't bother looking. crux is pulling over the belly. 5.11 moves to the top

name: No Chance Of Escape!
description: This climb pulls through the stacked roofs and then angles up and left to finish.Havnt tried it yet just bolted it not sure of grade or crux! I will post more info when I try it.Or it gets Sent

name: Panty Cannon
description: This climb is 5.11 right away awesome rock leads to harder climbing crux is gaining and pulling first roof.

name: Poised for Peril
description: This is a endurance climb. With drilled pockets where needed. Some thin dirty climbing into a obvious roof that you climb out of the left side, crux. And some reachy moves continue to another smaller roof that you move left on as well. Pumpy to the finish.

name: Son of a Blankety Blank
description: This climbs crux is the blank crumbley start. Then it is an enjoyable 5.7. The easiest route on The Wall of Immortals, and a stright shot into Blankety Blank!

name: Totally Unacceptable
description: This climb is the approach to the belay ledge for all the great climbs at the Wall of Immortals area. It changes frequently due to chossy conditions.

name: Uncharted Direct Feed
description: A dihedral-ish gully slab that's harder than it looks, polished and slick, crux around bolt 3 or 4 is a blank section with bad hands and glossy feet... top section full of sand and gravel... as always with birdsboro, PLEASE wear a helmet as a belayer!!!

name: Uncharted Territory
description: This climb is awaiting a FA. Its prob a 13? in the beggining. There is 4 fixed draws with the crux at the top fixed draw. The rest of the climb is 11ish and spicy.

name: Battling T-Rex
description: Super fun climb. Very interesting start. The crux is 3/4 of the way up when you find yourself in a diehdral.Staying in the diehdral through the top is the crux, however you can move right to easier face climbing. After you leave corner much easier climbing to a great finish. Great exposure!

name: Birds Nest
description: Start in a small inside corner and stem up to a low small roof, pull out the roof and continue up to an overlap (crux) then continue up to the anchors.

name: Get Wet
description: Step out over the water on 3rd class passing a few bolts until you get to the base of a groove.  Climb up the groove passing some bolted on slings (wtf?) and bolts until you arrive at the belay ledge.

name: No Bama
description: Crumbly climbing up to a roof, undercling the seam in the back and pull over the roof to easier climbing up to the anchors.

name: Your Mom
description: Two thoughtful cruxes

name: Batmania
description: The second-to-last line of bolts on the ledge.  Has some suprisingly fun stemming moves.

name: Deep Six
description: Delicate moves off the ground to a stance below an overhang.  A very tall move reaches a jug past the overhang and a balancy move or two get you to the rings.

name: Depth Charge
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Ian's Climb
description: Follow the first line of bolts up to a 2 bolt anchor with chains. Easy terrain past the first 3 bolts, a distinct crux around bolt 5 or 6.

name: Loch Ness Monster
description: Sweet and short dont drop your gear or Nessy will swallow it.

name: Mya's Climb
description: Longer than most climbs on the Main Wall. Rock can be hot from sun exposure. Slight rope drag as you near the top.

name: Mya's Roof (variation)
description: Crux is at and over the roof. There are grades of difficulty to pull the roof. 10d if you stay on the bolt line. Easier (a little) on the left arete of the roof or to the left in the dihedral.

name: Slammin' Salmon
description: Fun in the sun

name: Swimming with the Fishes
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Assault and Battery
description: Another short face slab climb typical of this section of the Bird', which isn't as featureless as it looks on closer examination. A tricky little slab, gets pretty blank between the last bolt and the anchors

name: Belgian Blonde
description: Easy climbing (don't forget to stem) to the third bolt, pull one hard move and follow jugs to the anchors.

name: Black Stripe
description: A low angle climb with large holds. Obvious black lichen trough climb just right of the flat clean slab.

name: Blind Faith
description: Start climbing in the corner that eventually turns into an overlap/small roof, pull the roof (the far right crimp is very loose) and tackle the slab, the hand holds and feet are very small making the top quite tenuous.

name: Evil Twin
description: Start on sloping holds and continue up past 3 bolts.  Utilizing a sharp crimp  at bolt #3 and pulling up to the positive holds on the flake is the crux.  A few easy moves put you at the chains.

name: Gran Maharaja
description: Climb up some easy 5th, crux comes pulling through a bulge and some balancy moves around the 4th bolt.

name: I'm Lichen It
description: Follow the bolts up a slabby line left of a tree.

name: Ichor Sunday
description: This is no longer the 5.6 it used to be. A key hold broke, making this a 5.8 or so. Actually, I thought the bottom (where the hold broke) was still really easy. Tricky little move up the slab on top.

name: It's a Harder Line
description: This climb goes up the flat face.

name: Its a Nice Line
description: Fun slab route, have to look for holds. Worth repeating.

name: Mighty Midget
description: The route follows 3 bolts through blocky overhanging jugs to the chains

name: Mitchin' to Climb
description: Start on the concrete block, the crux is the first couple of moves going off the block, with small feet, and bad hands, after the climbing eases off.

name: Pseudo Slab
description: Enough good edges to get up. Avoid knocking the dirt and rocks up top and along the vein 1/2 way up.

name: Pseudo Slab (Right)
description: Blocky bouldery start, move to the left leaning diagonal that leads up toward the anchor.

name: Semi-Grand Traverse
description: Climbed everything else at the quarry and need something to do on a hot summer day? Solo up vienna lager to the last bolt. Clip that and sling the horn to the left and build an anchor. Bring up your second, then embark into the sea of bolts on the right. pull the crux of blind faith and then stay at about that elevation through some nice moves and comfy holds. it gets a little spicy towards the end as you have sort of a run out climbing through the crux of mighty midget, The second faces quite the fall if they blow it. Semi hanging belay at the Mighty Midget anchors. Easy when no one else is at the wall but logistically more challenging, and more fun, when the walls full of other climbers, clipping their hung draws as you go, well as long as you know them first.

name: Southern Tier Pumpin
description: Start on a steep and slick slab and climb the overhanging face on positive holds past 2 bolts.

name: Sunless in Seattle
description: Easy blocky climb. Might harder than a 5.7, probably a 5.8. A bit of a run out to the anchors on 5.5 climbing. Nice climb, thoughtful moves through the bulge.

name: Truffle Butter
description: 3 bolts, anchors with rings

name: U-Name-It
description: Easy climb to the right of Sunless in Seattle.

name: Vienna Lager
description: A chunky section with big holds and good feet lead up from the left to a jug by the first bolt. Pull past the jug to a slab with large comfortable diagonal cracks for hands and feet, then romp to the top.    This has to be the easiest climb on the lower slabs. Super easy and pleasant climbing, no more than 5.3.    A fantastic easy climb, it still feels like climbing even though it's very easy. Do it!

name: Welcome Direct
description: 3 bolts to shared rings with Welcome to safe harbor. 2nd route in from the left facing corner. Crux is at 2nd bolt.

name: Welcome to Safe Harbor
description: Vertical fracture line. 3rd line in from the left facing corner. Lots of small edges. left facing edge is crux after bolt 2.

name: Zorros Cousin
description: This route follows 3 bolts up an inside corner, to a roof use the face on the right for big holds, then step left and under the roof to the anchors.

name: Dirty Fingers
description: Start with a right hand undercling and obvious right foot, left hand in undercling in the crack. Work up the flake to your left, move right then top out.

name: Dirty Old Crack Rock
description: Lots of ways to go about this one. Sit start under the fat crack and work your way up. Its wide enugh to be hand jammed but featured enough that it really isn't necessary.

name: Apex Novelties
description: SDS with juggy arête on far-right. Follow the arête up, only hand holds on the arête are on. Large shelf on right near the top is off.  Beta Video

name: Cheap Thrills
description: Stand start with large jug at chest height. Head straight up to an easy top out.

name: Juicy Crucifix
description: SDS with juggy arête on far-right. Move up and left to large edge. Continue traversing left, staying low. Top out above jugs on the left. The middle of this climb can be pretty wet after it rains.  Beta Video

name: Mr. Natural
description: SDS with juggy arête on far-right. Follow the arête up. Large shelf on right near the top is off.  Beta Video

name: Snoid
description: SDS with juggy arête on far-right. Move up and left to large edge. Traverse left then move up to the lip on sidepulls. Topping out there isn’t really an option so drop or move left to finish over Cheap Thrills. The middle of this climb can be pretty wet after it rains.  Beta Video

name: Battle of the Bulge
description: SDS on far-right side of the lip. Traverse left until you reach the left face of the bulge. Move straight up over the bulge on small crimps. This route originally began matched on a chest-height ledge in the dihedral.  Beta Video

name: Battle of the Bulge Left
description: Stand start on ledge in the dihedral at chest height. Traverse left until you reach the left face of the bulge. Move left on small crimps to an easy top out.  Beta Video

name: The Bulge Direct
description: Stand start on ledge in the dihedral at chest height. Move straight up and over the bulge. A fall from the top could be dicey.  Beta Video

name: The Bart Man
description: SDS with large jug in middle of face. Climb up the right side of the face.  Beta Video

name: Like Gold and Faceted
description: SDS on right side of face. Traverse left around the arête to jugs on the left face.  Beta Video

name: Machop
description: SDS on far right of overhang. Traverse left as far as possible and top out.  Beta Video

name: Pinbacker
description: SDS matched low on the overhang. Traverse right to jugs, gain the lip and top out.  Beta Video

name: Seven Angels
description: SDS and climb the left arête. A fall on this route could be spicy, mind the chunks of quartz and try not to cheese grate.

name: Sunshine Arête
description: SDS matched low on the arête. Climb the arête, avoiding the tree dab.  V0 Variation: SDS with large jug in middle of face. Climb the face using the arête.  Beta Video

name: Sunshine Mantle
description: SDS with large jug in middle of face. Climb the face without using the arête.  Variation: SDS with large jug in middle of face, dyno to the lip.  Beta Video

name: Teeth of Lions Rule the Divine
description: SDS in middle of face. Climb straight up without using either arête. A fall on this route could be spicy, mind the chunks of quartz and try not to cheese grate.

name: Warm Up
description: SDS on jugs, climb up the easy face.  Beta Video

name: After Hours
description: Sharp crimps and some flakes at the top, topout is the crux.

name: Belly Flop
description: Start on an undercling and side pull. Reach for the lip and top out.

name: Business Time
description: The start of the problem is on the lower right hand corner of the boulder. Then you traverse to where the boulder and the tree meet, then you top out.

name: Business Time Direct
description: Start in the middle of the same boulder as Business Time on two crimps. Move up to a flake and traverse left to the same top out as Business Time.

name: Mini crack
description: The problem is a fun warm up to do. It is a crack with some pretty chunky holds on it.

name: Run Off
description: Sit start on a crimp and pocket and make a big move to a jug and top out.

name: Waterfall
description: You start with two wide underclings to get up onto the slab, which is the crux. Then climb the sob to the top

name: Big Easy
description: Climb the tall featured face, not all that exciting but its something.

name: Trail Headgame
description: Start low on positive crimps and then work your way up on small positive holds and top out, many ways about it all about the same difficulty.

name: Easy Friction
description: Start at the small gully in the rock just left of the cutout corner. Work up the face on easy smearing and dirty jugs.

name: Grit Hymnal
description: Start matched on an incut section on the left side of the lip above the cutout, feet on the overhanging section under the cutout (small wall to the right is off). Bump hands up and right to good hold, get a left foot above the lip and find holds to stand up on it. Finish by topping out a slightly delicate slab with decent holds if you look for them. Rock seemed solid but the edges of some holds on the bottom may crumble and round as it cleans up. Fun movement, goes at V0-1 if you use feet or hands on the right wall to start.

name: Line Drive
description: Start as for "Negative Space" But move straight up from the start

name: Mid-Atlantic Punter's Club
description: Start with wide hands on incut but small holds, small smeary feet. Press hard with the feet and bump a hand up high, then another bump for the other hand. Hard to describe beta. This thing is stiff.

name: Negative Space
description: Start matched on the left side of the cutout corner around the left side of the overhanging face. Move to the right wall of the corner and reach for the lip. Manage less than ideal hands and feet you cant see to move yourself up. Awkward exposed move up over the lip.

name: Questionable Mantle Health
description: Start on any of a selection of good holds on the lip of the overhanging face far left. Follow good holds traversing right along the lip with small feet on the overhanging face until you need to throw for the broken corner jug and let feet come loose. Get a hand heel match and mantel, top out.

name: Arachnoflake
description: Start with hands in the large left facing flake to the right of "Tripping While Dogsitting" and with good feet. Layback up and get some crimps to pull over the bulge. The crack is home to a myriad of spiders in the warm months.

name: Breakfast at Cliffany's
description: Start on a small left facing flake at about chest height work up on good crimps and small edges into a corner dihedralish feature. Top out and walk off. Tall and scarier than it is difficult. Really good quality rock, not sure what it is though.

name: Core Shot Club
description: Sit start with hands in flake and feet far left. Pull up to two good edges, find feet, and then pull up to a right hand on your choice of a glassy crimp, a tiny bad Gaston pocket, or a bad slope. Set feet and then launch for the jugs above the bulge. Try not to dry fire off the glassy crimp, it hurts.

name: Grippy Gully
description: Start up that the horizontal crack in the featured concave slabby rock. Trust your feet to smearing and work your way up the well featured face.

name: Neighborly
description: Climb the featured slab left of Breakfast at Cliffany's

name: Roadside Rabble
description: Start matching the large sidepull flake and move up to the left hand crimp. Afterwards move up to a solid righthand crimp before throwing to the top lip. A much easier version of this line is possible by using the large crack between the last crimp and the top, but it was much less fun.

name: Tripping While Dogsitting
description: Start as for "Breakfast at Cliffany's" on the left facing flake. Bump up and right to a far gaston, adjust feet and reach for the arching crimp rail above the gaston. Match the arching crimp rail and follow mossy slightly incut edges up over the bulge.

name: Misty Green
description: Start with hands spread wide in compression across the bottom corners of the overhanging block, get creative with feet. Bump the left hand up to a finger wide flare in the crack, and then either find a way to bump right hand to crimpy edges, or establish good feet and throw with the left for the top, and then head up and right to top out.

name: Clearcoat Arete
description: The best climbing in the clearcoat area, but by far the worst landing. Start with hands in chunky opening on the left face. Swing/slap up to an edge around the right side of the face. Heel hook wide right to allow you to pinch the polished arete and then bump your right hand to a bad 2 finger uncut edge. Open those hips and get a high foot to stand up.

name: Clearcoat Cut
description: Start matched on the large ledge that is the left hand start of Clearcoat Arete. Keep to the right of the crack. Do 3 or 4 small moves up small negative crimps and gun it for the top. Top move is scary, and may be harder for smaller climbers.

name: Clearcoat direct
description: Tiny negative holds until you hit the crack, and then they're still tiny. Be careful as you tend to lean right near the top and a fall could be very very bad if not protected right.

name: Clearcoat Left
description: Climb up the left side of the clearoat face. Big chunky holds lead to a sloped topout. Topout probably the crux.

name: Commitment Issues
description: Stand start with a hand on a big crimp/edge and one on the separated but still solid small block in the seam.  Work up on good feet and hands to a juggy edge shrouded in ferns: this is the commitment point. Work some slightly high feet up (you better trust them) and make a reachy move up over the next block to another juggy edge, and then repeat that sequence to the final jutting out edge. Walk off the slabby topout of clearcoat face to the left. Careful, that topout slab is more slippery than it looks.

name: Trout Erection
description: Contrived sit start that shares a finish with "Clearcoat Arete". Start with hands on large triangular ledge and high feet. Work up and left on small but mostly positive edges and top out near the arete.

name: Peace Out
description: Sit start low with hands matched on the obvious rail, pull up and get the right hand in the undercling, then match (I've tried many many times but it only goes if you match). Bump both hands up to the flake, and then campus or traverse left. topout where the ledge ends.

name: Peace Out Direct
description: Same Start as peace pipe, but mantel directly up over the top. The mantel move is on good holds however the ledge that you exit onto is small (about a foot and a half wide) and typically overgrown with ferns if not recently cleaned off. Would be an unpleasant fall if not committed to the move completely.

name: Boogie Man
description: Just an extension to heebee jeebees starting out to the left. Really no harder, just a little more pump.

name: Bring Your Protection
description: Sit start with your hands on the big flake and your feet in the crack. Move to the obvious side pull and then match on the rail above it. The rest is pretty much all small rough crimps until you get to the big edge just below the top. The crux is getting your left hand in up into a tiny negative crack thing without peeling off the wall. very fun problem once you work that out.

name: A Very Clever Ladder
description: Since the climb begins over a bench, be careful   choosing foot and hand holds for the first few   moves. About 1/3 of the way up the route is the   crux — an especially smooth section that requires   a high left foot and potentially dynamic reach to a   good positive horizontal shelf. Match hands here   before proceeding to the final sequence surrounded by scraggly vegetation but with a clean series   of holds. Use a recessed stone to the right of the   route’s trajectory for a final solid foot before topping out.

name: Gross Neglect
description: Be careful on the start of the climb to avoid   falling on rotten wood and rusted metal. After the first quarter of the ascent, sloppy   patched mortar makes a challenging second   quarter, with a few choice crimps pulling you   through to the cruxy third quarter. You will   have to traverse to the right of the initial   crack to reach a series of good foot holds   and a single high crimp for the top out.

name: Jugovick's Detail
description: Start   below the cavernous opening shaped like a downward-pointing arrow and work your way up the   large crack offering positive, if flakey holds for   the first 2/3 of the wall. At this point the quality   of stone changes dramatically to smoother, more   rectangular blocks with only small crimps for purchase. You will have to work your way to the left of   the crack to move past the crux. Beware of flaking mortar and active bird’s nests in the crack and   be careful when topping out - the jagged concrete   aggregate that forms the wall’s coping will draw   blood.

name: No Tidings of My Man
description: This crack starts generously at the bottom and   becomes narrower as it goes up before disappearing to liberally applied mortar marking an   especially challenging crux. Use the broken edge   of the mortar as a left side-pull to cross to a high   crimp and work your way through a forgiving final   sequence to the climb’s completion.

name: No. 264
description: The wall has a slight ledge   at its base which drops off to the right of the start.   Looks for gaps where mortar is missing from the   wall and reddish mortar revealed where some of   the pointing has crumbled. The coping is almost   completely missing from the a section at the top   of this area.   The Wissahickon Schist selected for this part of   the wall is especially jagged for the first half of the   climb. A large, lightly colored rectangular stone is   set back about 2” deeper than its neighbors near   the halfway mark. Following this ledge is a challenging series of distant crimps, zig-zagging a path   up to a sparse, dynamic finish.

name: Bondage and Discipline
description: Follow a thin crack from the left edge of the ledge at the base of Don Genero up the overhanging wall passing a ledge and into an offset overhang, then on to the top.

name: Central Buttress Direct
description: Climb up the center of the buttress beneath the obvious wide crack, move right into a thin crack, through an overhang about twelve feet off the ground. Go over the overhang at the crack. Continue to the top, finishing directly over the larger overhang there. Be aware that the last overhang, at least in the eighties, had a large block sticking out. When making the moves out and over, pulling on the block it "clunks" down. Bring spare shorts for this.

name: Dead Men Don't Eat Roughage
description: Climb the face passing to the right of a small evergreen. Continue past horizontal cracks and shelves. Exit just left of the small overhang at the top.

name: Don Genero
description: From the ledge five feet off the ground on the front of buttress #7, follow two parallel thin cracks up a short overhanging face. Continue up through a steep scoop facing right to the top.

name: EB, Phone Home
description: Behind the Great Wall you can scramble up into a vee shaped area formed by the two buttresses. EB takes a line up the center of the downstream wall side.

name: Flattered
description: Begin five feet uphill from the lowest point of the wall. Move up following a broken crack to a sloping ledge. Continue following a curving crack moving left through two shallow depressions before reaching the block on the ledge. Continue straight up to the top.

name: Fruition
description: This is the first route we did at the Edge, and perhaps the most obvious line. Pro is good,sting is in the tail. I think it's the best route here.     Climb the steep rock near the center of the wall into an inside corner facing left. Follow the crack over a small overhang to a cedar tree at the top.

name: The Great Wall (center - aka the Pumper)
description: Slick, Slippery, Polished, Pumpy, Fun!  Classic climbing on smooth red Lockatong Formation argillite interspersed with friable Brunswick Formation shale...

name: Great Wall (center trad line)
description: On the Great Wall, only the center 5.8 route was led, via headpoint.     As I understand it this route now sports four bolts.In which case the protection rating would change considerably.

name: Great Wall Left
description: Similar climbing to the pumper along the left side of the face

name: Harelip
description: The smaller chimney on the right, within the larger chimney of Would I? Follow chimney to top, passing a constriction.

name: Knuckle Sandwich
description: Climb the wall a few feet right of the corner,passing an overhang about ten feet off the ground,continue to the top.

name: Mel's Route
description: Start at an obvious 4 inch crack and follow to it's end. Move right into the corner and follow to top.

name: The Nose That Roared
description: This wall is broken by a large groove in the center. Climb the groove to the top.

name: Pro-found
description: Climb the left face of the pillar at a very thin crack past a small overhang and up to top.

name: Right Hand Drive
description: The right hand side of the leaning pillar to start, then up a crack on the main face.

name: The Rotwand Direct
description: This route starts with a crimpy boulder problem right off the deck, protected by small gear.  After reaching the horizontal, plug good gear move slightly right and continue up on decent crimps.  Pass a solid nut placement and run it out to the top!

name: The Rotwand
description: From the back of the V, hand traverse with little protection out the upstream wall to the nose. Clip a pin and move up to the top.

name: Shattered
description: Back in the corner, follow a thin finger crack without stepping off left. Climb directly over the flaky overhang to finish.

name: Simple Solo
description: On the right side of the downstream wall of buttress #6, near the entrance to the arch, climb the short harder looking open book, moving around the outside corner to the right at its top, then up to top.

name: Strapaducktome
description: The obvious groove in the middle of buttress #8. Follow the groove for ten feet, move left passing an overhang, up into an alcove, exiting left.

name: Thunder Road
description: The right side of the large overhang on the downstream side of buttress #6. Start at the left side. Climb broken rock to the second ledge, then attack the overhangs from the center of the ledge. Above the lip follow a short crack to the top.

name: The Tongue That Swung
description: Climb the face below the prominent tongue,then out to the tip of the tongue. Move left and up to the top.

name: Would I?
description: On Buttress # 7. Climb the chimney using all the shelves.

name: Flyguy
description: The problem follows the rightmost arete of the cave, starting with both hands as low as you can go. Luckily, these holds tend to remain dry when the rest of the cave is still soaked.

name: King Cobra
description: Probably one of the best problems I've ever done. Start in the very bottom of the cave with a left hand undercling and a slopey right hand. Follow the line of good holds up and to the left.

name: Moon Rising
description: Start low on the right side of the boulder, and follow the line up and to the left. The top out can be tricky.

name: Smidge
description: Start scrunched up with hands matched on the right side of the "boulder." After a few moves traversing to the left, topout.

name: Casual Corner
description: Climb up the corner using small holds and stemming technique.

name: Lofty
description: Start with hands on small but good holds just above the opening in the wall. Climb up and slightly left then back to center on small and sometimes slopey edges to the top. Top out and carefully walk off to the edge of the woods. Landing could be treacherous if you punted hard off the top as the remains of an old small wall are about 6 feet back from the base.

name: Cobra Strike
description: Start on the cobra hood with a compression hold, and move straight up. Rock on the left is off.

name: Crack Head
description: Start on the right side of the rock with an under cling reach for the crack. Crux is the first move into the crack

name: The Talking Snake
description: Start in the crack on the left side and traverse right and mantle on the right side of the rock.

name: Workin man
description: Start with your hands on the dish in the lower middle of the boulder and climb left working your way to the point at the end of the boulder. a fun sustained problem with great moves. the crux is where ever your anaerobic respiration kicks in.

name: Working Man sit (unemployed man)
description: This is the sit variation of working man, it adds an additional 3 moves. Start on two crimps a few feet right of the dish and throw a heel hook, cross right hand over to another crimp. Reach left hand out for the dish and lock in your core to match. Finish the rest of the boulder as you would for working man.  You could start even further to the right if you want, but starting here prevents the annoying butt dab.

name: 2 Beers Deep
description: Start on the right side of the south face of the boulder. make a few moves then make a small traverse left and continue straight up the boulder.

name: Turkey Hill hot dog
description: start low on the slab move up and left over the roof to a hard mantel

name: Half pump hump
description: Start with your feet under the lower roof with your hand on the first good hold. work your way up the face and mantel on the rock above

name: Crack ladder
description: stem your way up the crack in corner.

name: Easy street
description: Climb the slab face. watch for loose pebbles.

name: Muddy mud skipper
description: Climb the crack

name: no name
description: Start on the corner and make your way up  on the left side of the face

name: One pump chump
description: crux is the start. climb up into the roof. pull roof on right side of the arête and finish up the slab.

name: Ren and stimpy
description: Climb the arête.

name: Stupid white man
description: Step out on the ledge and climb the face

name: Thundercat
description: Climb the left side of the face on the arête.

name: Typical birds boro
description: Climb the slab face next to the roof on the left.

name: Cheese and Crackers
description: Climb the arete on small holds.

name: Cheese and Crackers Sit Start
description: Sit Start to Cheese and Crackers, start on a poor crimp and side pull and bad feet, move up to the stand start holds.

name: Garden Spider Party
description: Climb the arete starting on slopey holds and top out.

name: Garden Spider Party Sit
description: Sit start to Garden spider party, start on a large crimp and feet close to the dirt.  Move up to the slopers and reach way up to more sloping holds and top out.

name: The Goose
description: Sit on the boulder to start.  Undercling up to pinches.

name: Hugo Long
description: A one-move-wonder: dyno from the chalked up start holds of The Plug to the top.

name: Jungle Boogie
description: Sit down start.  Climb the overhanging prow.

name: Jungle Boogie V4 Var.
description: Stand start.  Climb the overhanging prow.

name: Nutmeg
description: Sit down start in the pit.  Climb small edges to the top.

name: The Plug
description: SDS on a low rail with tiny feet, move up and left to a small vertical slot, hand foot match the rail, than follow jugs to top out. A bit of a one move wonder.    Variation: Hugo Long - V4, Dyno from start hold to top out jug

name: Propecia
description: Climb the overhanging face.  The boulder at the base is on.

name: Rubbin the Nubbin
description: Climb the overhanging dihedral.

name: Tour Du Bloc
description: Start on the slab and traverse the boulder. Finish on the plug!

name: Viagra
description: Start on the underclings and climb the nose.  The boulder at the base is on.

name: Yohimbe
description: Start under the roof and follow the crack out.

name: Unnamed V0-
description: Climb the short hand crack in the dihedral.

name: Unnamed V1
description: Sit down start on the right side of the arete.  Climb the arete.

name: Unnamed V4
description: Start at the low jug just right of the tree.  Climb straight up to the slopey top.

name: Big
description: Find the massive wave like boulder just near the Mangler. Starting on nice crimps in the middle of this boulder, climb up and right towards the off-width that is formed by the adjacent boulder. Enter into the off-width and finish it up!

name: Broken Heart
description: Climb the big zig zagging crack system

name: Four Leaf Clover
description: Slabby jug haul. Follow the prominent crack up the slab. Careful as the landing has a bad ramp that would surely ruin an ankle or two!

name: The Heart of Haycock
description: Its a shame this line doesnt get more traffic. This is a great v4 with some very interesting and crimpy moves.     Find the vertical seam of the south facing face (see topo picture). Start with a high diagonal crimp and climb up on crimpy sidepulls. Find the faint gully like feature of the rock that appears when the sidepulls run out. High step up and press up onto the top section of the boulder.

name: The Hoagie
description: Start at the bottom of the pit with a RH sloper and a LH gaston on a good crimp. Make a few easy moves, then enter the crux by reaching out to a horrible LH crimp and continuing up to the lip via a bad right hand pinch. After hitting the lip, climb up the relatively easy slab to the top of the boulder.

name: Not The Mangler
description: Where to begin with this one! This climb has a somewhat sordid history. For an informative description of the many versions of Mangler, be sure to check out the entry in the paper guidebook.    Climb down into the small pit and start on both sides of the block. Climb up and out of the pit.

name: 3-Star
description: A Haycock classic highball finger crack.

name: Happy Herbert
description: Start matched on a prominent edge on the right and climb up along the rail.

name: Project
description: Start with a left side pull and a right rail. Find feet and fire for the top. Looks great but the feet are tricky, probably around V2.

name: Soft Serve
description: Stand start with a large foothold and slopers. Traverse left on crimps avoiding the lip until you reach the swooping arête. Move up with jugs on the arête and top out.

name: Bokow
description: "Start with a flat square hold and climb the prow up and right, finishing up in the dihedral on jugs to a nice top out. An amazing hanging prow feature."    credit to Char for the description as this was taken from the Haycock Guidebook.

name: Spined Micrathena
description: Start on large undercling jug with high right foot, power and finesse you way up right to a good slot in the crack and continue to finesse up the crack with insecure feet.

name: Wokob
description: Start on two crimps left (sidepull/undercling) right (sidepull) at about chest height, get a high foot and slap your left hand up a rightward arching arete with bad feet.

name: The Balrog
description: Start with your left hand on a sloping rail and your right hand on a good crimp sidepull.  Get a high right foot and dyno for the slopey lip, then mantle over.  This problem was originally climbed at V5, using the right hand side pull and a small left hand crimp up high.  The crimp now appears to be broken off, making the dyno significantly longer and more difficult.

name: Bouloutain's Arete
description: If sharp crimps are your thing, be sure to give this one a go.     Start on the very blunt arete on an obvious two handed crimp seam. Follow a few small crimps to a larger hold and then mantle up over the top.

name: Cave Crack
description: Its easy to locate this climb. This powerful yet somewhat short line has a really nice landing and is situated in the cave itself.    Start with two high fingerlocks in the crack. Using bad foot smears, power up and exit left around the roof.

name: High Jinx
description: Start on jugs at the base of the huge crack. Climb straight up into the scoop on bomber holds.

name: Honeybun Arete
description: S.D.S. climb the arete.

name: The Kind That Go Ding
description: Start on the right side of the obvious pit. Follow the rail leftward until you reach the large brick sized hold at the base of the sweeping feature. Stab up for the slopers at the lip and mantle over.

name: L'angle
description: Brace yourself for perhaps the hardest v2 on the mountain. Being able to crimp v-hard will not automatically mean you will be able to power up this arete. Be prepared for a fun challenge deciphering this technical climb.     Balance up the left side of the arete.

name: Low Jinx
description: stand start with a side pull for your right and an edge out left right above the chalked up slopey rail. get a high foot and carefully go for one of the crimps up high. top out straight above. a v3 variation exists starting from the slopey rail.

name: Pele
description: Start on the jug on the right arete and follow the obvious line across the 45 degree wall. Reach the crack in the dihedral and continue up to a triangular jug. From here, jump off.

name: Sumo Wrestler
description: Climb the ball. Start off with fist jams and trend rightward.

name: v1
description: Just to the left of Sumo Wrestler, climb the slab.

name: Yosemite Arete
description: Starting on the big jug on the left arete, follow the long arete up the boulder.

name: Yosemite Crack
description: This is a rather tall boulder with a somewhat relatively flat landing. Climb the small seam that splits the face of this boulder.     Start on a low pinch for your right and a pocket for your left.

name: Center Slab
description: Follow the thin line up the center of the boulder, do not use the crack to climbers left.

name: Left Side Crack
description: Follow the obvious crack up the left side of the boulder with a few locks, jams and jugs.

name: Right Slab
description: Follow good flakes up the right side of the boulder to a thinner top out with good feet.

name: Beckdu
description: A typical Haycock diabase route - start using an undercling at the base of the lip and slap your way up the lip then right top out in the center of the boulder

name: Dubeck
description: Slap your way up the left arete of the Dubeck boulder.  Start low on a jug and go all the way to the top.

name: The Scream
description: Smack in the middle of the Dubeck boulder is this fun yet short problem.     Start with a left hand on the lowest part of big sidepull and a right hand on sidepull down and right. Bump the left hand up and fire up and right to the arete. Follow the arete up.

name: Jug Arete
description: A few different options exist to crimp and slap your way up this one.     SDS on the jug at the base of the arete. Using crimps and a sloper, make you way up to another jug about 3/4 of the way up the arete. An easier top out awaits.

name: Little Fluffy Clouds
description: A classic atypical Haycock line following a featured overhanging arete before pulling onto the face and the topout. Sit start utilizing an under cling with feet smearing on the face, climb the jugs and pinches with big moves and turn the lip with a small feet cut move before slapping up for the lip.

name: Perpetual Dawn
description: short, but a good warmup for LFC; - sit start with a good left hand jug, low right hand compression sloper and feet smears - move your hands up into the good seams, eventually throwing right hand up to the amazing pinch jug. Get high feet, lockoff on that pinch, and balance your way up to a shallow seam. Easy top out after braving the less-than-decent fall potential.

name: The Magi Direct
description: Start under the roof on a good incut for your left hand. Using the below boulder as a kick plate, reach up to the good crimp at the lip of the roof. Pull up and over and top out directly above.

name: The Magi
description: SDS on the right side of the roof on the arete. Work your way up and left across the face to a good crimp at the lip of the roof. Pull up from here and top out above.

name: Fruit Basket Traverse
description: Start the same as Mo Mangos, but instead of reaching up for the crimps on the face, continue right past the big undercling to another undercling and continue out to the crack. From here, climb up the crack and follow the arete.     Dab potential on the boulder that is home to The Plum is very high on this one. Its quite scrunched.

name: Mo Mangos
description: One of the best v7's at Haycock. Definitely worth adventuring down the Caves Trail to find.     This problem (along with the few variations and The Plum) is somewhat tucked away in a cave type formation.     SDS on the hold that is continually chalked. Move right to the big undercling, then up the nice crimps on the face. Hit the arete and climb up and over.    Word of caution, the bottom of this climb is always always wet.

name: The Plum
description: Start on a low edge and climb up to the sloping rail. Follow the sloping rail up and right and top out.     Very mellow climb and very short.

name: Nadja
description: Start just left of the small tree and climb straight up the slab face on small crimps/seams and tricky feet.

name: Unnamed V0
description: Climb straight up the large crack that turns into a finger crack halfway up the boulder.

name: Unnamed V0-
description: Start climbing the large crack and follow the finger crack that trends left.

name: Unnamed V1
description: Share the same start as Nadja. Step on just left of a small tree and follow the scoop up and right.

name: Echo Belly
description: Interesting line (if its dry!)     Start the same as Rocking Chair Direct. Sit start on the obvious low ledge on the left side of the boulder. Traverse low across the boulder using the prominent seam. Link in to Rocking Chair on the right arete and follow the seam and top out.

name: Rocking Chair Direct
description: Rocking Chair Direct is the left side of the Rocking Chair Boulder. Sit start on the obvious ledge that is low on the left side of the boulder. Work your way through some crimps and slots to the lip. Mantle over the lip and on to the slabby arete above. Top out on interesting seams, crimps, and slopers.

name: Rocking Chair Left
description: Start as for the rocking chair (squeezing with left hand in a notch and right hand on the arete), but go left through crimps to a bulbous sloper and top out straight up the left face.

name: The Rocking Chair
description: The right arete of the Rocking Chair boulder.     Start with your right hand on the arete and your left hand in the notch near the lip. Pull on and trend rightwards up the prominent seam.

name: Middle V1
description: Center and easiest of the Three Seams. Highball - commit to trusting feet and go.

name: Novocaine
description: Start at the big prominent jug near the bottom of the arete. Climb the arete utilizing nice crimps to a solid top out.

name: Tooth Arete
description: Climb the right arete of the Tooth Boulder.

name: Tooth Traverse
description: Although unnamed, this is a pretty nice climb nonetheless. Starts on the same jug as Novocaine and traverse rightward, following the seam. Head for the notch in the top of the boulder.

name: Tooth Traverse Variation
description: Start on a curved crimp on the left and climb the face to the notch in the center.

name: Before the Storm
description: Start low on a sidepull and move up and right to finish.

name: The Bubbler
description: Excellent Haycock compression problem. Your right hand is low on a crimp under the overhang in the seam out right, your left on a good edge on the arete. Follow a few faint sloping edges on the seam and work you way out and up the arete.     Careful not to dab on the ground boulder that is awkwardly placed directly under the start.

name: White Top Overhang
description: Start on a large undercling and high jug, get a high, good foot and follow the crack up using another jug and mantle over the lip.

name: Bootleg
description: A very tricky and balancy arete problem! SDS on the left side of the arete. Work your way up the arete and top out at the peak.

name: Cooperazzi
description: Start on the v-shaped slopers in the center of the boulder. Go up and right to a crimp rail, then fire out for the arete.

name: Cooperazzi (Variation)
description: While Cooperazzi starts in the center on the obvious v-shaped jug, this variation starts on the left side with a small sloper on the arete for your left hand and the prominent low crimp for your right. Slap up the sloper and then lurch over to the v-shaped jug and then continue into Cooperazzi.

name: Egg Roll
description: Starts on an undercling under the roof. Move up and right and then top out. The boulder at the base is on for feet.

name: Jesus Calls for War (aka - Nightmare Arete)
description: overhanging arete

name: Ulu Traverse
description: Variation of Ulu (VB). Start on right of the wall with the Ulu crack and traverse left until you reach the crack. Finish on Ulu.  Beta Vid (starts a few moves in)

name: Ninja Squirrel
description: thin crimps up face - arete is off

name: Bulgur Hay
description: So many problems on such a little section of rock! Thats okay, theyre all good!    This one starts underneath the small roof on the crack in the back. Starts the same as The Perch. Reach around to the low crimps on the face and head up to the slopers, the same as you would with The Perch. From here, traverse right into Light Shag and finish it up.

name: Light Shag
description: under overhanging roof start hold is a jug out to lip of roof, onto short face and straight up to top. Same start as Turkish Blend v5

name: The Perch
description: SDS in the crack on the left side underneath the roof. Reach around the small roof to a crimp at the lip. Continue upward to slopers. From here, head up and left to a good flake. Top out above.

name: Turkish Blend
description: under overhanging roof start hold is a jug out to lip of roof, onto short face via sloper, top out above

name: Throwing Oranges At the Eskimos
description: Sit start from left facing flake, up face, past sloping dish

name: Catching Flies
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: The Fin
description: Climb the prow being careful not to touch intrusively close tree, making way to top ledge across face and topping out to left.

name: Funky Butt Flies
description: Start as for "Catching Flies", but traverse left into the start of "Funky Butt Love" utilizing a high heel and a right hand side-pull crimp. Slap around the arete to the seam, then slap to the lip and top out.     Not sure if this has been climbed before or is described elsewhere, so feel free to update FA / grade.

name: Funky Butt Love
description: Start with a seam for your left and sidepull for your right.  Hike up your feet throw for the lip and top out.  Mind the tree, hence the name.

name: Main Squeeze
description: The leftmost line on the wall. Grovel up and over the buldge.

name: Moss Clod
description: Tenuous layback up a flake

name: Pete's Butt Swing
description: Start with both hands on a good hold, go to the top slopers and top out.

name: The Tainted Orb
description: Sit Start with crimps under the bulge, and feet on the detached rock. Climb up into Main Squeeze. Be careful with the loose start hold.

name: Before the Forum
description: Climbs the prow. Start down in the pit, slightly around the corner on a horizontal crack. Trend leftwards out around the prow then straight up.

name: Black Angus
description: SDS with a large sidepull. Climb up past a gaston, a pinch, a two finger slot, and finally the thin seam on the slab.

name: Bovine
description: Between Gumball (L) and Black Angus (R). Use left arete and the seam of Black Angus. WIDE arms.

name: Gumball
