description: Sit down start on a good sidepull and sloping hold.  Move up to a small crimp in the middle of the face and to a weird pocket/shallow sidepull.  Make a big move up to a good edge, and then to a pinch and top out.

name: Happy Cow
description: Start on a jug on the right of the boulder and traverse left on the lip using small edges, turn the corner of the boulder and top out.

name: In the Face of Danger
description: This climb is prominent, inspiring, and a little bit dicey, with great moves! To start it, step off the big platform onto the start holds (low left hand slopey sidepull, right hand incut but small crimp) above a very dangerous gap in the platform. Climb up through a small horn and a gaston to a jug near the tree, then a fairly moderate topout.Important: have an attentive spotter ready to push you *away* from the boulder onto the pads, to avoid the pit (maybe throw a pad down in the pit anyway in case you slide down). I felt fairly safe on it because you are pushing away from the pit to move upward, but the feet are very bad so a slip is possible.

name: Line Graph Traverse
description: Start on jug and traverse right across boulder on good crimp rail with a few small feet

name: Shredder
description: Climb the overhanging crack to the juggy rail then over the top of the overhang.

name: Bubblegum
description: Start on two jugs down low and work left to a good horizontal then up to a diagonal crimp, move right to a gaston (easier) or bring the right hand up to a good jug and top out.

name: Bubblegum Face
description: The standard warmup problem for the area, start on two sidepulls and follow big holds to the finish.

name: Bubblegum Face Sit
description: Start on low undercling with a good left foot and move up into Bubblegum Face

name: Bubblegum Variation
description: Same SDS as Bubblegum. Go to first good horizontal and straight up from there to a crimp and then huge jug. Top out.

name: Cave Crack
description: Climb out the cave left of Bubblegum.  Strenuous topout with high dab potential.

name: Meeker SDS
description: Sit down start as low as possible.  Squeeze the overhanging prow to the top.

name: Meeker V5 Variation
description: Start sitting on the boulder.  Squeeze the overhanging prow to the top.

name: Bypass
description: Looking directly at Patoggan Run, start in the rounded dihedral near the left arete with a good edge on the arete. Smear up into the dihedral and traverse right to join Pattogan Run.

name: Escalator Traverse
description: If you are looking directly at Patoggan Run, it's the right side of the boulder.  Start on the left side of the face with a good low foothold, just right of a dead tree stalk. Traverse right along the face with good footholds in the low crack. Link into Paddle Prow at the right arete.

name: Paddle Prow
description: Climb the blunt, slabby arete to the right of the V6 slab.

name: Patoggan Run
description: Climb the steep slab.

name: V2 by Meeker
description: Climb the face to the slopey top out up and left.

name: The Moon is Down (Stand)
description: Start on underclings and move up left to a series of good sidepulls.

name: The Press
description: SDS with a jug on the prow. The right arete is off. Reach up to an edge, then to the terrible flat gaston sloper. Match it, and continue up edges on the left face.

name: scoop
description: S.D.S. matched on a protruding hold down low. Use a couple incut sidepulls to reach a jug on the lip. Top-out directly above.

name: Unnamed V1 (Little Roof)
description: Short and easy roof climb. Get as low as you can to SDS on good sidepulls/underclings, then fire out, up , and over on jugs. Not much to it, but it is one of the few easy roof climbs (nearly horizontal) to be found at Haycock.

name: Unnamed V2
description: Sit down start on the right side of a fairly large boulder, with a rail and the prow for hands. Move up to a good jug, then continue trending left up the arete to top out.

name: Duck Dive
description: Climb the right side of the slab.

name: Noodled
description: Start on edges, move up and right to a long crimp rail then up to a good U-shaped hold one foot below the lip.

name: Over the Falls
description: Not sure of the exact details... climbed this problem while on a trip to Haycock. Great arete problem if I recall correctly.

name: Swan Dive
description: Start on small edges and stemming in a subtle corner, move up on small edges and top out.

name: Tsunami
description: Crimpy face to the right of Over the Falls

name: Uncle Muscles Power Hour
description: Start at the big footholds, move up to opposing sidepulls and make a big move for the top.

name: Unnamed V0
description: Start at the right side of the face and traverse the lip.  Top out around the left arete.

name: Savage Hand Orgy
description: Fun sit-down-start and make a huge move or dyno to an obvious sloper and top out above

name: Ankle Biter
description: Sit down start.  Climb the face left of the arete without using the arete.

name: Bombora
description: SDS matched on jug and climb several small crimps to tenuous top out.

name: Bone Yard
description: Stand start on jug and climb up jugs and good slopers to easy top out.

name: Unknown3
description: SDS on two good crimps with a good left foot, stand and reach to good sloping edge and then up to another crimp.  Tricky top out.

name: Birdnest
description: Start with high left on the left arete and a low right hand crimp. Move up and out to the left to top out.  https://vimeo.com/64966772#t=3m57s

name: Stonemaster
description: Start matched on a large jug in the center of the face and move up.    vimeo.com/64966772#t=0m56s

name: Chiba
description: SDS with your right hand on the horn and your left hand on a sidepull. Pull up to the slopy sidepull, match, and tension over to holds on the arete. Top out after reaching the big crimp rail up high.

name: Hobo
description: Was originally V10 but a small crimp broke and got better! Since, the problem hasn't seen enough ascents for everyone to agree on a grade.  Start on a good right hand and medium incut crimp.  Climb the overhang with side pulls, a decent crimp and a big pop to a sloping edge. Tricky top out.

name: Pipeline
description: Start on good jug and follow slopers straight up and top out in the depression at the top of the boulder.

name: The Throw
description: SDS on low jug and campus up to high jug or use a slopey intermediate.  Easy top out after reaching the high jug.

name: The Wink
description: Same start as Hobo but trend right and low on good holds to an easier top out

name: Cup of Tea
description: Climb the overhanging arete in the pit. Make a huge throw to a slopey rail.

name: Riding the Elephant
description: Like many of the classic lines at Haycock, this is all about compression.     SDS on obvious, yet low, jug. Dyno up to slopers on the faint lip and then trend leftwards. Climb up the prow and then trend back right slightly towards the topout finish.

name: Squeezing Your Mom
description: Another powerful compression line. This one might definitely be height dependent as you'll need every possible inch to span this boulder.     SDS squeezing the prow and work your way up the left and right arete until its possible to mantle over the top.

name: The Amoeba
description: Start on the obvious jugs down low. Climb up the shallow dihedral using small crimps. Pull yourself up over the rounded topout.

name: Baby Doe
description: Start on Jane Doe Ledge and finish/topout on John Doe bucket. Maybe FA, idk, crossing lines is fun and worth doing.

name: Jane Doe
description: Start on giant ledge on the left side of the Doe Boulder face. Move left to sloping arete, up to right crimp--continue along the good side arete to finish top.

name: Jon Doe
description: Unique boulder full of underclings, side pulls, toe hooks, good feet, a challenging arete and good finish. Cool find.  The beginning sequence feels weird until its sequenced--there are many ways to start the problem. (Knee bar, heel-toe cam left, heel-toe cam right).  Start with a left hand sidepull and a right hand undercling triangle pinch. Climb up the face using edges, good feet and the arete.

name: The Eye
description: Starting with a high lefthand sidepull on the face and a very low righthand sidepull on the arete, work your way up using the arete and the eye!

name: The Pod
description: Start somewhat low in the crack on a really good sidepull. Follow the crack up and left to a good hold and then dyno for the top. The left arete is off.    A SDS to this line has been done, but the holds down low are somewhat pliable and are ready to explode!

name: 45 Degree Arete
description: Start with a high right hand pinch and a left hand sidepull. Climb up and over the rounded arete.

name: 45 Degree Wall
description: In the center of the wall is a L shaped hold at the top of a scar that runs up the middle. The L shaped hold is easy to spot, its formed by a right hand ledge and a left hand sidepull. Find feet and establish on this L shaped hold. Fire up for the lip. Trend rightwards across the lip and mantle on to the slab above. Careful on some of the higher portions of this slab, certain sections are fragile and prone to breaking.

name: Observable Differences
description: This is the lower start to the 45 Degree Wall. Start directly below the L shaped hold that defines the start of the 45 Degree Wall on two somewhat parallel edges/sidepulls. Work some tricky foot beta and find your way up in to the 45 Degree Wall start hold. Fire for the lip, trend right, and mantle on over.

name: Proximity Infatuation
description: This one is WAY out there. If youre up for some bushwacking, then this one is for you. Its well worth the effort to get out to this location.     Start on the right side of the boulder and follow the prominent seam. Continue working leftward until its possible to hit the small crimp leading up the face. Hit the second seam and continue up the slabby top to the finish.

name: Under My Thumb
description: Are you looking for a roof problem at Haycock?! If so, then this is the line you'll want to check out. Interesting moves lead you out this cave. If you refrain from researching the beta, you'll have a fun time trying to decipher the odd yet fun moves that will lead you to higher ground!    Start in the back of the cave on a flake and work your way towards the prominent notch. Figure out how to get around the lip and up through the little chasm. Hit the final seam and revel in the fact that you just did some acrobatic moves to get there!  The easiest way to get to this problem is by coming from the Caves. Once you hit the caves, go around the backside and scramble up along the talus. Under My Thumb is about 150 yards uphill. Its somewhat hard to spot.

name: Peligro
description: Time to hone in your dyno skills! This one has seen a bit of crumbling on the start hold so a community censuses on the grade is probably needed. Start with both hands on crimps in the seam. From here, dyno to the sloping lip. You'll trend right around lip and mantle up on to the face.

name: The Tri-Force
description: The long traverse spans the boulder starting in a shallow dihedral on the far right side. The start isnt too well defined and you'll find yourself scratching your head looking for the best way to start this. Either way, start with low holds in the dihedral and work your way leftward. Using the prominent gaston and long seam, continue working leftwards and mantle on to the upper section of the boulder.

name: Deviled Egg (Sit)
description: SDS squeezing where you can on the bottom of the egg shaped boulder. The kickplate underneath is on for feet. Find a way to pull on and up to the starting sloper for The Deviled Egg.

name: The Deviled Egg
description: Rather conditions dependent because of the slopers on this one!     Start with a right hand crimp just left of center on the boulder and your right hand on a sloper dish. While the finish is a mere 3-4 feet away, find the ability to hump your way up the bulging arete. A bit deceiving but fun to figure out.

name: The Flaming Moe
description: climb the fairly tall crimpy face, without using arete.

name: Fun Boulder Slab
description: Left side of the slab.

name: Huggles Arete
description: Sit down start on the overhanging side of the right arete.

name: The Mantel
description: Start on the slopers above the bulge and mantle.

name: Open Book
description: Climb the subtle open book in the middle of the slab face.

name: Air
description: Climb the middle of the face.

name: Disco Stew
description: Climb the arete.

name: Bump and Drag
description: Sit down start with hands on either side of the block, slap your way up the block to easier ground and follow the left angling crack to top out.

name: Googy
description: Traverse the slopey lip to top.

name: Into the Picnic
description: A great link up of Tit Toss and Teddy Bear's Picnic. Start on Tit Toss and traverse right on good holds until you have to make a big reach to gain access to Teddy Bear's Picnic. Top out Teddy Bear's Picnic.

name: Jeff's Route
description: A technical climb, start on a sidepull and a good crimp under the perched boulder and move right on small edges.  Reach a good jam and position your feet higher to reach positive holds at the lip.

name: Show Me Yours
description: Start on the Into The Picnic traverse holds between Teddy Bear's Picnic and Tit Toss and dyno up to a sharp edge below the lip, or skip it and go straight to the top.

name: Teddy Bear Picnic
description: Teddy Bear Picnic is the leftward angling crack on the backside of the teddy bear area main boulder.  Begin the problem standing on the low boulder to gain a good finger lock and follow the crack using jams and small edges for feet to a slopey top out.

name: Tit Toss
description: Start on good edges and climb 2 moves up before the holds stop, slap for the lip and find the good jug and top out.  The slopers to the right on the arete are off.  A V0 variation to this problem allows use of the arete.

name: Twin Cracks
description: From Char Fetterolf's "Haycock Mountain Bouldering" guidebook:   "Start with your choice of holds and climb the vertical seams.  Tough to get started."

name: Polar Bear Crack
description: Its easy to see that this line is always overlooked. The top will almost always have to be cleaned off and the same will have to be scrubbed from all the debris that built up from no one touching it for months (or years). Despite the fact that its unnamed and only a v3, its a rather fun line nonetheless.     SDS in the pit. Left hand on a low but good crimp and right hand in the seam. Work your feet and follow the seam up to the lip. A few tension moves and good foot placements will see you hitting the lip and doing the fun topout. Just try to avoid the vegetation that has grown a few inches thick on top of this one!

name: Unknown
description: Offwidth crack, a tad bigger than most male fists.

name: The Broiler
description: Starting in the pit located between this boulder and the next one uphill, follow the diagonal crack to a slab below the bulge and top out directly above.

name: V0 wide crack
description: Climb the wide vertical crack/flake system (second crack from the right) and top out in the gap. Great introduction to kinda-highball boulders; it's consistently easy movement the whole way up, with solid feet, the occasional hand jam, and a simple top out move. Recommend walking up the backside of the boulder first and locating the hidden jug on the top out.

name: V2 crack
description: Climb the vertical crack on the right hand side of the downhill face of the boulder. Then follow the diagonal crack up and to the left, and top out in the gap. Walk around to the top and check to make sure the diagonal crack is clean before climbing it, this doesn't see much traffic.

name: Hematoma
description: Stand start on jugs and climb seam up the slab.

name: R2-D2
description: Start in the crack in the back of the cave on the leftside of the little corridor that separates The Wookie and Witch Hazel. Start the same as The Wookie, in the crack at the back of the cave. Work your way up the crack and up on to the overhanging left face and reach around to the slab. Finish straight up.

name: Witch Hazel
description: Climb into the cave and SDS on the prominent undercling. Work you way up the rail and the right arete until its possible to turn onto the face. Brace yourself for a somewhat tricky and elusive topout.     Careful not to dab, this one gets a bit tight.

name: The Wookie
description: In the cave on the right hand side of the small corridor lies the Wookie! Start in the crack at the back of the cave. Traverse leftward across the left overhanging face. Work your way through a heinous gaston and then out to the lip. Round the lip and make your way up the slab.

name: The Never Ending Biscuit
description: Using the left arete and the dihedral, make some interesting moves moves up to the top.     Although this problem is on the short side, its a v4 in the Top Rocks section worth checking out.

name: Pyramid Crack
description: Low angle small hands size crack.

name: Iron Lion
description: Climb arete under Top Rock starting on large blocky rock. highball with pinches, pockets, slopers.

name: Lovers Quarrel
description: A big boulder with an obvious west-facing line.

name: Mighty Mouse
description: Start up on the ramp with solid hand jams in the overhanging crack.  Climb over the roof as the crack gets thinner.  Might seem harder if you cant jam

name: Puff Puff Pass
description: An arete line on the south edge of the boulder marked by 'VAPE' graffiti.

name: Snake in the Eagles Shadow
description: This is the big block just to the right of Iron Lion. Walk into the little corridor that houses Mighty Mouse.    This route is the arete just next to the big tree. Start with both hands in the horizontal crack and climb the left arete. When the arete gets close to the tree, youre able to trend rightwards a bit on edges then up to the top.

name: Trade Marked
description: A low seam that starts wide on the right then thins up as you traverse left; top out above the 'TM' graffiti and don't dab on the  blocks to the left. Depending on the beef of your hands, may feel harder than the grade.

name: E Honda
description: If lowball topouts is what youre searching for, then look no further. This odd shaped rock proves that even lowballs can be tricky.    SDS on jug on right side and work your way out!

name: Lolos
description: This one doesnt usually see much action, so if youre trying to find it by looking for previously chalked holds, it might be impossible to find. Make sure to bring a brush too, just incase there is some moss buildup.     SDS underneath the boulder on prominent crimps. Work your way out and up using compression and more crimps.

name: Blowhole
description: Start matched on the lowest rail on the left. Bump up to the lip, find a nice round pocket, and top out.  There was a recent break on this problem so beware that some of the rock above the start may be loose.

name: Early 70s Gymnastics
description: Start on a nice left edge and the right arête. Move up to a tiny rail and small nubs. Reach back for a better hold and top out. Kinda strenuous. Beware the dab.  Beta Vid

name: Raining Blubber
description: Start on a left sidepull and a right crimp in the face. Move up to slopers and top out with a crimpy gaston.  Project: Start on the lowest section of the left sidepull and the right crimp in the face. The feet at this angle are rough, probably a V3.

name: Unicorns in Paradise
description: Start on good edges in the middle of the face with smeary feet. Triple bump to the top on the left. Throw a heel then reach for a sloper on the right. Top out.  Beta Vid

name: Behind the Bank
description: Sit-down start with a left crimp and a right pinch on the arête. Climb up on slopers, gain the lip and top out.

name: Electric Squid
description: Sit-down start with a left hand jug and a right pinch in the center crack. Throw a heel and move up the arête.

name: Project
description: SDS with the same finish as Surfer.

name: Project
description: Climb left along the slopey ledge to the left arête and top out.

name: Surfer © Teen Confronts Fear
description: Start with the right arete and a high left side pull. Move up and right then top out.   Beta Vid  From the main trail, walk down the hill towards the river. There will be a dam and some large flat rocks on the right. The boulders are to the right of the dam along the bank.

name: Indian Creek Traverse
description: SDS on the far left, traverse right avoiding the top lip then top out. This a pretty long climb and you could make it a V2 with some eliminations.

name: Droplet
description: SDS with left sidepull jug and right crimp. Make one big move to gain the lip and top out.  Beta Video

name: Happy Birthday Arête
description: Stand start with jugs, climb the short arête. A SDS seems possible but the small tree makes it pretty awkward.  Beta Video

name: Purell
description: SDS on right side of overhang. Traverse left and top out.  Beta Video

name: Social Distancing
description: Start matched on the far left end of the lip. Traverse right and top out around the corner.  Beta Video

name: Virulence
description: SDS with left sidepull jug and right crimp. Gain the lip and transverse right as far as possible before topping out. The two large blocs at the base are off for feet.  Beta Video

name: Dr. Strangelove
description: Start matched in a small pocket at the bottom right. Move left onto the arête with a flakey right jug. Move left past a mossy shelf to the second arête. Make a big move up to the rail along the protruding block. Traverse to the nose and topout.  Take a moment to do your best Slim Pickens.  The large shelf under the start and the wall to the right is off. The loose pointed block between the arêtes and the loose right side of the rail are also off.

name: Junk Dunk
description: Start matched in a small pocket at the bottom right. Move left onto the arête with a flakey right jug. Move left past a mossy shelf to the second arête. Make a big move up to the rail along the protruding block. Traverse to the nose.  The large shelf under the start and the wall to the right is off. The loose pointed block between the arêtes and the loose right side of the rail are also off.  Beta Vid

name: V Zorro
description: Start on the low shelf with smeary feet. Move up to the central jug and match at the top to finish.  Beta Vid

name: Zorro Dyno
description: Start on the lower ledge and move up to the central jug. Dyno to the top. Left undercling and right end of ledge are off.

name: Heel yourself Marieke
description: The crux starts after two moves from the lowest section of the route. The good thing about this climb is the fact that it is really low off the ground. The not so good quality of the climb is that you have to keep yourself off the ground half way into the climb at its lowest section. This route requires alot of heel hooks and some toes. The crux requires a pretty strong left heel hook while bumping right hand up followed by left hand.

name: Kelly Drive Boulder traverses
description: It's fun if you like V0 traverses in direct sun with a lot of background noise and traffic.

name: Kelly Krack
description: Follow the juggy crack towards the highest point of the boulder. Trend left at the top to avoid a dirty top out. Highball on good holds.

name: Low pockets to dyno direct
description: Begin at the bottom of the smaller right crack (at the bottom of the little ramp) on an obvious chalked start hold.  Traverse left before the large rail on thin pockets. Dyno from the low small pockets to the big low flake.  Move up right of the main crack on small crimps to the upper flake. Downclimb to the left or right (both cracks are easy downclimbs – if you climb here, you most likely warm up climbing on them both).

name: Orion's Belt
description: On the far left side of the boulder, close to the bike trail, sit start on a low slopper in the overhanging rock. Proceed left up the arete and finish with a slabby top out. The large crack to the right is off.

name: Orion's Dagger
description: Sit start at the furtherest left point where you can still be sitting on grass (nearly on the bike path). Left hand on a fat pinch, right hand on a jug. Solid feet on a lower block. Move up and right through a series of jugs and gain a positive jug on the arete to link with Orion's Belt.

name: Thin Fin
description: Traverse left using the namesake flake. Gain the lip  via good edges to your left and make the crux top out. The rock has a bit of caked on dirt but should clean up quickly. A fun problem that varies from the jug hauls to the left.

name: Ten Thousand Feet Up Mega-Traverse
description: There are many ways to play on this wall but we do one very long traverse that keeps you low, eliminating the need for crash pads. This route begins V-easy and ends V-hard (but I usually climb with ropes so I'm not that familiar with bouldering grades. Open to suggestions.) Start standing on a coffee table size rock. Pretend you are standing on a ledge ten thousand feet up. Proceed through the easy Orangutan/Jungle Traverse, which is an excellent warm-up. Stem through the dihedral. Throw a calf up and around the corner and step up high to keep things easy or stay low around the corner for a challenge. Down-climb or stay low to continue traversing through some wide reaches until reaching another good resting spot. Breeze through a long easy section and then take a rest before the cave. Continue into the cave, being aware of the sharp boulder under your back. Climb up and out of the cave to the right, watching for loose blocks. Try to gain a comfortable stance and rest as if you are ten thousand feet up until you are ready to do it all in reverse!

name: High AF
description: Test your bravery by getting high af. Difficulty is mostly in your mind.

name: Infinity Traverse
description: Start either on the stone wall or on the grassy side. The route wraps around the column infinitely, how many times around can you go?

name: Slabs & Cracks
description: This one requires lots of crimps and creative grips. Footholds here are hard to find, but very rewarding.

name: Some Crimping Required
description: A fun little crimp and balancing traverse that ends a little high in the sky. Definitely have a pad handy for the end of it.

name: Take the L Traverse
description: Traverse from the right end of the underpass wall, around the corner--in an "L" shape--all the way to the yellow paint / edge of MLK drive.

name: Easy Shoobie
description: Stand start and climb the jugs on the right arête.  Beta Video

name: Hazy Summer
description: Sit down start on a rock on left side. Grab slopers above, throw high, right and back, match, and top out.  Beta Video  (from rockclimbing.com)

name: Lazy Summer
description: Sit down start with an undercling above the low ledge in middle of face. Traverse right to join the left-slanting crack. Follow the crack up and top out.  Beta Video  (from rockclimbing.com)

name: Palmtius Pilate
description: Start below the shallow arête with a left side pull and a right sloper. Traverse right following the footholds in the horizontal crack. Move up and topout on the right. Holds on the shallow arête are off.  Beta Video

name: Tannhäuser Gate
description: Begin standing with a left hand on the arête and a low right sidepull. Move up to a curved edge on the face. Slap up the arête and top out.  If you can't reach the low right sidepull, you can use the lower right crimp on the face or stand start with only a left hand on the arête.  Beta Video

name: Vangelis
description: Climb the shallow arête that runs diagonally up the left of the slab. Grab the undercling/side pull and top out over the block left of the arête.

name: Basic Member
description: Stand start on the left end of the long juggy crack. Traverse right and move up to top out.

name: Cache Money
description: Sit down start with the upside down V crack. Traverse right to the long sloping shelf. Continue along the shelf until you reach the large vertical sidepull. Mantle up onto the shelf or top put with a hold high on the large sidepull.  Beta Video

name: First To Find
description: SDS with the lowest part of the large side pull and a slopey feature to the right on the bulge. Bump your right to a jug and move up on crimps at the top.Beta Video

name: Muggle Toes
description: Start low on the upside down V shaped crack and move up and left along jugs on the overhanging. Make a wide move to the jug left of the overhang. Move up and left to the top with tricky feet. The top of the overhang is off.Beta Video

name: Nano Standstart
description: Standstart matched on the large side pull. Use the large crimp to step up onto the left slab and move up.Beta VideoVariation V0: Same SDS as First to Start but set left onto the slab using the crimp.

name: Neocacher
description: Start low on an upside down V shaped crack and move up and left along jugs on the overhang. Top out directly above the overhang.Beta Video

name: Pocket Query
description: Same start as First to Find - SDS with low left side pull and right sloper. Move up and right to the long juggy crack. Traverse the crack and top out to the right. Positive holds and tricky feet make for some great climbing.Beta Video

name: Smurfs 292
description: Sit down start with the upside down V crack. Move right to a curved edge, throw to the lip and top out above.Beta Video

name: Don't Be A Flake
description: Flakey route straight up the boulder avoiding the moss to the right.

name: Green Moss Escape Plan
description: Start at the far right side, traverse under moss growth about 10 feet, top out between moss patches.

name: Angus Scrimm
description: SDS and start matched on overhanging sidepull. Move straight up face to the left of the large vertical crack to an easy top out. Cool moves but the surface of the rock is heinously spiky.  Beta Video

name: Charles Gitout
description: SDS with low left jug. Climb up and right along the overhanging arête. Round the corner and top out on jugs.

name: Dark Horse Arête
description: SDS with low sidepull jug. Climb the arête.

name: Garfield Minus Garfield
description: SDS with jugs on the right.  Head straight up and top out.

name: Stone Age in America
description: A boldering spot tucked up above Kelly Drive near Boathouse Row.

name: Strawberry Rock
description: The rock is on the hill side just south of Strawberry Mansion Bridge.  It features multiple diagonal shelves and deep roofs.  It is well concealed, heavily guarded by poison ivy and despite its proximity to the Schuylkill River Path offers some center city solitude.  Much like "Stone Age in America" the crop is on the East side of Kelly drive and not frequently trafficked.

name: No Smoking
description: shitty urban boulder problem

name: Roadkill
description: Route is a good up to the roof (beware of choss on the ledge below the roof, ask your belayer to stay clear) which requires some boulder style moves to top.  Route is fun to practice laybacking, downside is the choss under the roof and poor rock quality there.

name: Art Museum Buildering
description: vertical fingertip splitter on the parking garage at the Philadelphia Museum of Art.  It's building, its wacky but its a climb.

name: Centre the Dragon
description: SDS, layback on the excellent crack and work up to the etched letters, move right and top out on the metal awning. The rail above the etched letters as well as the electrical boxes on the right are off.

name: Cross Town Traffic
description: Bouldering over maintained grassyness. But bring your ropes and anchor lead gear off iron bars. Fat-security-dupe will peak around the corner soon after your partner has begun to second and clean gear. At this point every member of the party is obligated to stay still and make no noise. Once hes gone, continue climbing as usual.

name: Square Pants Traverse
description: Shimmy up the column to a solid rail and move right, top out on the metal awning. Smoking sign and letters are on.

name: Unknown
description: outdoor bolted sport climbs near center city located near the train tracks and kelly drive

name: Council Rock Traverse
description: Start with large jugs on the far left. Traverse right using the lowest holds and exit right onto the lower ledge.

name: Teedyuscung
description: Start on large jugs on the left and traverse up and right across the face. Climb up on jugs on the right side of the face and top out over the highest point.

name: Unnamed
description: Start on the obvious hold on the lower left. Work your way up and to the left. Top out over the left side.

name: A Monkey in the Park?
description: Start with a large jug and high feet over the water's edge. Throw to good holds along the top of the boulder. There are plenty of foot options for those who like to smear or throw in heel and toe hooks. Once both hands are on the main horizontal crack in the boulder, throwing the right hand to a high sharp crimp will be the crux. Tall climbers will be able to skip this intermediate crimp and should throw their right hand in to a slightly farther jug just past the crimp. Rock over the high right foot and reach up to the last two top out jugs to stand up.

name: Social distance
description: Flakey jugs with slippery feet due to lichens. Largest flake is loose but it can be easily skipped. I identified it in the pictures. Some vines and plants growing out of cracks. I gave it a quick cleaning and plan on tidying it up a bit more.

name: Through the Leaves Traverse
description: Start at the very left of the boulder and traverse left past the tree and then head straight up. The Arete is off.

name: William's Roof
description: Start directly underneath the roof and work your way up using various cracks. Reach up to the lip of the roof, swing your feet out left and mantle over the roof.

name: Luther's Alley
description: SDS with two sloper edges in the middle of the face. Climb straight up with crimps and slopers. Keep off of the far right arête.

name: Mola Mola
description: SDS on slopers at the far left end of the lip. Climb the lip on slopers and crimps, top out at the peak.

name: Requiescence
description: SDS with a left hand in the horizontal crack and a right hand undercling/sidepull. Stand up and gain the lip. Traverse left to the peak and top out. Barely a warm-up.

name: Resurrect Dead
description: SDS with two extremely low jugs. Climb straight up and top out.

name: Second Wave
description: SDS on far left side of overhang. Traverse right and top out over the corner. Excellently formed holds make for fun climbing.

name: Tranquility
description: SDS with a left hand in the horizontal crack and a right hand undercling/sidepull. Stand up, reach for the lip and top out straight up. Barely a warm-up.

name: Boltax
description: This problem is only 3 moves, but they are pretty fun ones. Stand start on two parallel holds below the end of Lushes Lip, and climb the face to the right of the arete, using a gaston and nice sculpted sidepull. Finish by matching the top of Rich's Arete.

name: Edges and Ledges
description: Sit start at the beginning of the crack system and bust a move up to the prominent jug ledge above the end of the crack. Keep following the good holds into the finish of The Rainbow.

name: The Gaston Classic
description: Start at the base of the crack and climb it until it peters out (juggy ledges to the left of the crack are off). Move up to a good sloping pocket and then to a sharp crimp pocket above it. Make a big move with the right hand to the small but positive gaston, then fire up for a crimp just below the lip. Finish on the juggy lip.There are three variations/eliminates for this problem; here is a beta video from Rich showing which holds are on.

name: Iron Cross
description: Start with hands on the big chalked-up ledge. Move right into the crimpy pocket and execute the iron cross into the juggy left-facing flake (the higher crimp between the pocket and flake is off). Finish on The Rainbow.

name: Iron Toss
description: Fun variation of Iron Cross. Start on the same big ledge and make the same initial moves as Iron Cross, but once you are situated in the pocket, move up into the crimp and make a toss for the big ledge directly above you. Finish on Poison Ivy (traverse the ledge right, into the finishing jug for The Rainbow).

name: Jugs
description: Start on the prominent jug farthest to the right. Move up and left on jugs to reach a long shelf. It's a real choose your own adventure kinda thing here, plenty to choose from. Continue traversing left to the same finish as The Rainbow for a V2.  Beta Vid

name: Lushes Lip
description: Start matched on the horn on the far right. Traverse left along the lip as far as possible then top out. The rock on the bottom left is off.  Beta Vid

name: Poison Ivy
description: Start on the big chalked-up ledge and make a big move up to a good hold. Ride the rail rightwards, crossing into the finish of The Rainbow.

name: Pot of Gold
description: Start at the bottom of the crack and make a move or two up it. With your right hand established somewhere amongst the very chalked bulge where the crack splits, get yourself set up for a big throw left to the massive left-facing flake. Go big with the left hand, cut feet for style points, and bring your right hand over to match the flake. Finish with a big and easy toss up to the the big ledge directly above the flake, or finish on the Rainbow.The big jug ledge near the end of the crack is off.

name: The Rainbow
description: Start matched on the prominent jug in the middle of the face. Follow the flake up to the right using only the holds along that seam. The shelf at the top is the finish. If you really have something to prove you could probably top it out for a V2 :)

name: Rich's Arete
description: A fun arete sit starting on the slab, climbing the water streak.

name: Zigg then Zagg
description: Start on the two obvious crimps moving left horizontal to the two other crimps. Finding good footing to start is good for right foot, but suspect for the left foot.Throw left hand up to mini jug and work your way up to large jug that's left and up. Find some feet then head up and right to crimps then a far right to ledge (crux is these last few moves mentioned). From there top out with by throwing a heal up and moving a little further to the left and over. If you don't go over the top no worries, has lots of vegetation so can be muddy and slippery.  Contrived problem, but some good heal hooks and crux at the end. Most problems are easy on this wall, but a pretty decent one for the area. This may already be a problem, but because of all the "not in plays" it may not have been.

name: Forbidden Boulder (traverse)
description: Hop on either end of the boulder with the Battle of Germantown memorial plaque on it. Traverse the path of least resistance for an introductory V0ish route. Take other lines or eliminate holds for more tougher problems, or to avoid seeping mud and moss in spots. You'll get similar reactions as on the Kelly Drive Boulder since it sees a bit of foot and bike traffic.

name: The Slab
description: Walk up the slabby right-hand face of the boulder. Easy, a good place for new outdoor boulderers to build confidence and practice footwork.

name: The Squeaky Hinge
description: Start on a left sidepull and right sloper. Traverse left with an undercling and make a reachy move to a prominent sidepull jug. Move up and left on slopers to a solid top out.  Beta Vid

name: Straight Up
description: Start on the jug and feet out right. Goes straight up on bad slopers. Gets slick in the sun, plan accordingly.

name: The Cleaver
description: Start on the far right and climb the arete then traverse. There are some nice crimps on the rock face along the way as well. Solid skinny topout at end of the boulder.

name: Deepest Bluest
description: SDS with jug. Move up to crimp rail, gain the lip, move right to an easy top out.

name: Moon Pool
description: Stand start matched on the far left end of the lip. Traverse right along the ridge to an easy top out.

name: My Hat Is Like A Shark's Fin
description: SDS with sidepull jugs. Move straight up to an easy top out.

name: Tsunami
description: Follow the weakness under the roof. Exit climbers right and heel hook traverse to a low jug.

name: Double Rainbow
description: Sit start where the left side of the cave meets the ground, not in the cave but on the outside as it begins to wrap around the corner. Traverse right over the opening of the cave. At some point you'll need to switch feet from one side to the other while your hands are towards the center of the top of the "rainbow" arch. Continue the traverse until you're fully to the right of the arch, then follow the crack up to the top edge of the rock (top rock is a bit dirty / overgrown), and follow that edge back over the cave until you're fully wrapped around the left side of the rock formation.

name: Hips and nips
description: Sit start using the lower crack with sloping handholds.  Lay back and find foot holds inside the cave.  Traverse the cave opening by swiveling your hips to find footholds on lower left side of cave wall.  Proceed to obvious top out.

name: Up schist creek
description: Start on right side of lower rock formation and traverse left along obvious upper jug.  Lower crack provides secure feet.  Top out is slightly around the left side but be aware some rocks may be loose.

name: Wu-han
description: Start inside the cave about 4 ft in to the right. Two hand start on most obvious overhanging hold (it's well chalked).  Continue out to the lower right area of cave entrance and stay low with hands while moving to the lower left of cave entrance. My finish was a prominent hold to the left of entrance where I could firmly place two hands with relatively good footing. There is also an obvious top out variation that's still in the V3-category.

name: Wrastlin'
description: Start with hand jams at about chest height in the lower left of the diagonally running hand crack. Follow the crack up and right where it flares out. The crux is getting from the flare to the upper lip of the boulder and there are two ways to go about it. Either make a reachy dynamic throw to the lip, or calf hook into the flare and use an undercling to wrestle your way into an insecure heel/toe cam then reach for the lip. Either method is very committing and having a spotter would be very nice psychological pro. The topout is easy enough but not a "gimme" so exercise caution as it would be a nasty fall coming off of the top.

name: Das Fraulein
description: Far side of left face. From Dave R.: "Yes, the crack to the left, called Das Fraulein, is an easier way to finish, but if you do it, hang your top route on bolt anchors directly above it to avoid a pendulum. "

name: Directissima
description: Start with a few moves to get up the roof. Climb the arete up, and slightly left, to the top of the rock. The last move is a long one.

name: Lammy Pi (a.k.a. the 5.10)
description: It starts directly in front of the man hole, the same place as the nine but break left. Climb through the small roof and go up the face. Stay well right of the arete. There are some small horizontals and side pulls up the bulge. I think it's on the harder side of 5.11 - a solid V3 boulder problem.

name: Standard
description: Logged by Jim Fiore on theCrag.com. I'm not sure where he got the name, or the specific line or eliminate it is.

name: Stevens
description: Finger crack left of Regular. This route name is from Curt Harler's "Climb Pennsylvania" book, which is the only place I've seen it used so far.

name: V1 traverse
description: Eliminate traverse problem, trending uphill, with surprisingly consistent little crimps and interesting footwork. Start on the uphill portion of Livezey rock, just right of the crack/flake system for the rightmost toprope climb. Crack/flake is off, for full effect on the start. Move vertically a few moves (but not to the top of the face) then traverse right until the rock ends in the hillside. Recommend 2 crash pads, not because of the height but because there's a big log and a rock in the landing that you need to protect.

name: Zig Zag
description: Start with a few moves to get up the roof. "Zig" or traverse to the left and move up to the face. "Zag" right around an arete and up a gradually climbing set of holds well marked with chalk. Move up and "zig" back left to the anchor.

name: Mordor
description: Begin as far out to the right as you can on the overhang. Traverse left until you get to the jugs at the far left and top out.  Beta Vid

name: Mayday
description: The V6 is called Mayday, climbed mid-90's by Colby Barth. climbs the sit, from the far left, follows a seam up and right. (thanks Matt S.)    Rated 5.13 and V7 on this route's first ascents on toprope (1980s) and unroped (1999), it now generally rated 5.12/.12+ and V5+/V6-.

name: Unnamed
description: The overhanging chimney crack to the right of Vital Juices... is 5.9.

name: Light of My Life
description: Climb up the numerous jugs and shelves to a scrambly top out.  On the right side of the large loner boulder.  GPS: 40.06817, -75.22234

name: Saucer Traverse
description: A nice long overhang traverse. Start as far left as possible and traverse the overhang. Top out with a mantle at the far right.

name: The Nose Right
description: Stand start on a left hand Gaston, and a right hand side pull. Cross to the highest crimp and bump left. Use some heel compression and finish up with a bomb for the lip.  The top is harder since a hold broke off.

name: Unnamed Left
description: Sit start on the left side of the nose.  Pull two easy moves finishing with either a Dyno to the lip or a dead point to a slopey  jug. Top out is mellow.

name: A very good cool-down problem
description: Start at the base of Ben Franklin and moves up and right to the obvious positive (and very sharp) horizontal. Follow the progressively smoother and smaller holds moving right to the obvious finish rail. Nice traverse for waiting out the rain.

name: Ben Franklin
description: Sit start with a left heel, reach up to the crack and move right. Solid top out.  Beta Vid

name: Dirty Dish Traverse
description: Sit start with hands on the sloping rail at the right end of the boulder. Make your way left to the "dirty dishes" holds and keep going (crux) until you hit the arete. Top out as for Ben Franklin.

name: Dirty Dishes Variation
description: Sit start on crimps in center face. Move up to a jug then work up and right to a large slot without using the jugs out left. Top out above.

name: Dirty Lobsters
description: Start as for Dirty Dishes [V3] and bust right using some awkward body tension cross moves. Finish as for I'm Bringing Lobsterbacks [V2].

name: Dishless Traverse
description: It's an eliminate, but hey, this is the Wiss. Sit start with hands on the sloping rail at the right end of the boulder. Move left, through textured slopers and the perpetually-soggy crimps and into the big jug underneath the "dirty dishes" holds, without using the dishes. Keep traversing left to the big sharp jug on the arete, or save yourself the pump and shoot directly to the good holds above the jug on the arete. Top out as for Ben Franklin.

name: Fishbowl
description: Start on the huge jug at the base. Boulder at the base is on. Throw straight up to the lip and top out. Far right jugs and arête are off.  Beta Vid

name: Fishy Arete
description: Start on the jug at the base. Boulder at the base is on. Throw a right heel and move left on frictiony holds. Use the arete and crimps to get up and top out.  Beta Video

name: Fishy Dyno
description: Start on any of the chalked up blocks below the fish. Feet on the kicker block. Dyno to the lip and pull hard to stick it. Easy top out.

name: I'm a Man Cheetah
description: I believe this is a FA. start with left hand on crimp, and right hand on the obvious hold. Go directly up and over the bulge of the boulder to top out.  Beta Vid:

name: I'm Bringing Lobsterbacks
description: Start with a hand on the lip and a hand in the tiny but incut crimp under the lip. Make a hard starting move to a juggy flake and then follow jugs up and right.

name: Mind the Gap
description: Sit start with hands on the slopey start and toes hooked around the arete as seen in the picture. Move up and top out over the lip. Make sure to have a spotter as a fall could send you tumbling down the hill.    Beta Video:

name: Pinsor
description: Start on the jug under the boulder. Toe hook to start, the kick boulder is off. Bump to a good right hand and kick around to a hand foot match with a right heel. (Hard not to dab) Use slopers to get to the Arete, then make a match on a wide pinch. Exit out to left of the Arete and start hold. Mellow topout

name: Skeletons in the Closet
description: Sit start on a jug and work up and right on good holds. Figure out a way to reach the crack on the face above the roof, and then manage the scary and insecure topout. A key hold on the lip is hollow sounding and flexing, might break off after another winter freeze/thaw.

name: The snack that smiles back
description: Start on the jug below boulder and move straight up the face. Do NOT use the block.

name: Squishy Fishies
description: Start on jug below the boulder. Move on ledge right until top out. Do not use the detached block for feet.

name: A Walk In the Park
description: Start on the right side of the boulder with a low left jug and right edge. Climb up to the ledge, reach for a high right jug then top out.  Beta Video

name: Limerence
description: Start with large edge on the right corner at about chest height. Follow the diagonal crack up and left to the peak of the left arête. Traverse left along the lip and top out on the far left. Fun moves and a lot of mileage on this one.  Beta Video  A harder variation avoids the the lip, following the crack as far as possible before topping out.

name: Sunday Stroll
description: Start on the right side of the boulder with a low left jug and right edge. Move left to large holds on the face. Top out over the arête without exiting right onto the large shelf.  Beta Video

name: Unnamed
description: SDS on the arête and traverse along the jugs under the roof. At the dihedral, move up to the jugs under the second roof and traverse back to the right ledge and topout.

name: Unnamed
description: SDS on the arête and climb up to jugs on the face. Top out on the right shelf. Boulder to the right of the arête is off.

name: The Dirty Crack
description: Start matched on a jug to the right of the prominent crack in the middle of the face. Move left and climb the crack/flake. A bushy top out is possible, watch for poison ivy.  Beta Vid

name: Fully Torqued
description: A classic 3 move power boulder, if only it wasn't an eliminate!  Start as per torque, make a long move to the mail slot directly from the start, skipping all other intermediates. Match the mail slot reset feet and dyno to the torque finish. Those under 5' 10" need not apply.

name: Gem of a Stem
description: Start on the far right near the remains of wheatpased sign a LARPer put up to warn of the overwhelming strength of his spells (this is actually what the sign said before it faded...). Traverse left along the dihedral until you reach the left arête. Climb up until you're done, a bushwhacking top out is possible but not that fun.

name: Karmic Retribution
description: Start on far right corner and traverse across the dihedral to the arete, staying low. Head around the corner and make a reachy move to a small left crimp. Move up the crimpy face. Topping out is possible but not that fun. Basically Gem of a Stem plus the left side of the Mixed Up arête.

name: Locked Down
description: Sit start matched in the low crimp rail. Use  a Gaston and some fancy hips and make the move to a geometric hold. Finish on the upper section of breaking my heart, avoiding the arete cave feature.

name: Slap Happy
description: One of the best moderate boulders in the park, with great holds and fun movement on an obvious feature. Sit start with your hands matched on the perfect edges at the bottom of the overhanging corner, and open with a powerful blind throw left to the sloping edge. Follow obvious holds up the arete and into the mail slot, and quest up over the lip on good holds until you hit a two-handed finishing jug about two feet above the lip. I dropped down from here as the problems in this area don't top out, but you probably could top out and make things difficult for yourself if you want to prove a point.As of September 2020 there was zero chalk on anything above the mail slot, but the holds are all there, you just need to do a little looking. Get on this thing, it's amazing!

name: Bodily Fluid Dynamics
description: Right most sport line

name: The Deficator
description: 2nd bolted line from the left . noted single anchor . Share with Bodily Fluid dynamics if doing on TR   Shared Start to bodily Fluid Dynamics make your way left to the separate bold line and anchor

name: Plumber's Crack
description: Warm up crack climb,  3 pieces of gear needed and then chains at the top.  Helpful to have something big to avoid a run out .  Helpful to have a large hex to make the 3rd placement .

name: The Urinator
description: It's called the Urinator, and it's 5.12+ when you actually clip the chains.

name: All Toads Go To Heaven
description: SDS as low as possible with your choice of great holds. Move up over the bulge and top out. Great warm out.

name: The Cubicle
description: Begin on crimps on the slab at the base. Move up between the two walls and top out.

name: The Dirty Betsy
description: Start on the lower crack and move up/across the overhang and top out on the right side. Side rock is on for V0, but can make it more challenging by skipping that feature. Avoid the dirt on the right!

name: Pumpers Better Than Tumblers
description: SDS matched on the left arête. Traverse right along the sloping lip. Round the corner and continue right as far as possible. Throw a heel and top out.  Beta Video

name: Quartz Crimp Traverse
description: Start as far left as possible on jugs in the wall. Traverse right without using holds on the lip. Top out on the right.  Beta Video

name: Aladdin Vein
description: SDS and climb the crack to a solid top out. Sadly, the holds in the crack have some serious mud so beware if it's rained recently.  Beta Video

name: Garnet
description: SDS with a large left sidepull and a low right crimp. Bump to higher jugs and cruise on up to an easy top out. Only a warm up, but we all gotta warm up somehow.  Beta Video

name: Log Lady
description: SDS on the face to the left of the cave with a small left edge and large right jug. Climb straight up and top out in the space next to the tree.

name: Rampage
description: Right in between the rifle and the long lady. This time you are sending it all the way too the top. Have plenty of pads and spotters!

name: Rifle
description: Start low in the shallow cave and move up and right along a system of jugs. Top out over the lower ledge on the right side of the face. The difficulty level will probably depend mostly on how deep in the cave you begin.

name: Gneiss Dreams
description: Start on the far left and traverse right as far as possible before topping out. The top ledge is off.

name: Kirlian Auras
description: SDS with crimps at the bottom left. Move up on a sloper to a horizontal crack midway up. Keep moving and top out. Most holds are pretty clear of lichen already but you may have to brush a few holds.  Beta Video

name: Ollivander's
description: Start on the far left and traverse right as far as possible before topping out. The top ledge is on.

name: Rip Torn
description: SDS matched on the sharp arete in the middle of the wall. Move up to friendlier jugs in a crack on the right. Top out above.  Beta Video

name: Took a lichen to
description: Sit start with feet swept out to the left. Low crimpy holds and a heel hook may be useful beta. Make 1 or 2 powerful moves (height dependent) up to the contoured pocket and jug on the right. Match feet in the pocket and proceed to top out.

name: Belly Up
description: SDS with two nice edges. Climb straight up to an easy top out.

name: Crawlspace
description: SDS with sidepull jugs on far left. Heel hook and traverse your way across the face without using the lip or jugs on the lip. Top out once you reach the large jug on the far right.

name: The Delaware
description: SDS at the base of the large crack. Climb up the crack to an easy top out.

name: Dueling Snakes
description: Stand start with opposing sidepulls in the middle of the face. Work your way up the serpentine cracks and top out.

name: Roof Deck
description: Start matched on the far left lip. Traverse right along the lip as far as possible before topping out.

name: Tributaries
description: Long, low traverse with interesting moves if you take it into the overhung/cave section. Standing start on the top lip on the left side of the face. Proceed right along the central cracks, and transition into the overhang and cave before finishing at the downed log.

name: Wissahickon Hermit Boulder
description: Start your way up by using the first obvious sloper. Work your way up by using the small finger slots or the other slopers.The climb is finished at the very last hold.

name: Falling
description: A roof problem on the detached outcrop at the top of the descent trail.  Pull the roof w/o using cheater blocks.  Often top roped due to the bad landing.

name: Orvie Direct
description: Begin below the steep, narrow est face of the Practice Face marked with "Orvie" graffiti.     Straddle the left arete. A few bouldery moves get you to the large ledge. The rest is easy, but the huge hold near the top is super dirty. Somewhat contrived in that the difficulty depends partially on whether a nice layback right of the arete is used.

name: Crank N' Up
description: Reach up for the jug and climb the arete for 5 feet to a stance.  Escape left.  Use only the overhanging arete for feet.

name: Finger in the Dike
description: Climb the smooth face between the cracks of Ivy Leaf (20 feet left) and Practice Climb (8 feet right) past a short crack and left-facing corner.  Continue more or less straight up through the small overhangs/bulges to the top.

name: Ivy Leaf
description: Climb the crack in the center of the Practice Face to its end.  Move up and left past a notch to a small ledge, then up to the top.  A variation (also 5.4) moves up and right from the end of the crack to the top.    A Variation of this climb follows the main crack until it ends before the overhangs, then follows another crack up to the right. Ivy Leaf shares a double bolted chain anchor with "Triple Overhang" (route to the left of Ivy Leaf). However, there is a different double bolted chain anchor for the variation.

name: Mickey's Mantle
description: Pull the overhang onto an awkward, sloping ledge.

name: Practice Chimney
description: Climb the obvious damp, dark chimney to the top.

name: Practice Climb
description: Climb the obvious wide, broken crack to the top.

name: Shit Face
description: There are numerous variations, from about 5.9 to 5.11a, depending on where on the face you decide to climb.    Climb an overhnag to a small ledge, then up the center of the face to another small overhang.  Reach over the hang to find good holds, then step right and up and climb the right side of a short face to the top.  The outside corner to the right is off if you want the full 5.10b grade.

name: Triple Overhang
description: Climb the leftmost seam, then straight up through the overhangs to the top.  Perhaps a bit harder than the rating.  Climbing the center seam (var. 1) makes the climb 5.8 and climbing the face between the right most seam and the next crack to the right (Ivy Leaf) makes the climb 5.9 (var 2).

name: Warmup Traverse
description: Begin at the Practice Chimney and climb down and right below an overhanging bulge.  Continue right just above the ground until you reach the grungy section at the Weeping Wall.

name: Bootbuster Ceilings
description: Climb the left-facing inside corner to a ceiling, then up the face and corner right of the Neanderthal bombay chimney to the ceiling just right of the crux notch of Neanderthal.  Pull the ceiling (crux) then up to the large ledge (Neolithic Ledge) and the bolted belay.

name: Bootwear
description: Climb the blank face betwen two cracks to a small ledge at 13 feet.    The cracks and adjacent holds are off route.

name: Neanderthal
description: A popular classic.  P1 - Climb a crack into the obvious bombay chimney 25 feet up. Step left out of the chimney to a stance below the crux ceiling. Climb the ceiling at the notch up to the large ledge (Neolithic Ledge) to a bolted belay.  P2 - Climb the left-facing corner above the belay to the top.  This route was rated 5.9 at least through 1983. I think 5.9 will always be a realistic rating of this climb. Lou Lutz told me it was 5.9 the first time I ever climbed at Stover

name: Route 1
description: P1 - Climb the right side of the Neolithic Wall to a bolted belay on the large ledge (Neolithic Ledge).    P2 - Move up and left to a pie piece-shaped overhang.  Pass the overhang on the right to a pine tree and then to the top.    Perhaps a bit harder than the grade ?

name: Route 2
description: P1 - Climb the crack to a small overhang with an old pin.  Step up through the notch in the ceiling to the large ledge (Neolithic Ledge).  Belay at the bolted anchor.      P2 - Climb a left-facing corner to another ledge, then climb another corner to a crack and overhang.  Step righ to bypass the overhang at the "H-shaped" cracks.  This pitch is dirty and almost never done.    Starting in the easier crack 8 feet further right on P1 makes the climb 5.5.

name: Airy Route
description: P1 - Climb the crack then move into a "cave-like" crack (crux).  Step up and right to a belay (same as Tango).    P2 - Traverse right around a corner and up to a ledge.  Either scramble easily off right to a belay at a tree or climb up the face to the top.

name: Crummy Rotten Crack
description: The first 5.10 route established at High Rocks.     Start as for Gorilla, then move right at the top of the initial corner to a thin overhanging crack just left of an outside corner.  Climb the crack past an old piton, avoiding the corner to the right, to the top

name: Gorilla
description: Climb the short right-facing corner or the overhangs to the left to a large corner with a piton.  Move up to the large overhang.    From here the original route had a 5.7 finish.    A freeze in winter 2005 removed a giant block from the Tango Roof, inadvertently upgrading Gorilla to a 5.11+ finish.

name: Gorilla Slabs (R.I.P. 1978-2005)
description: Note: This route was apparently destroyed when a large piece of Tango ceiling fell in 2005.    Climb Gorilla to the first large ceiling (=Tango ceiling).  Traverse left on the face out to the left edge of the face, then continue up, passing another ceiling on the left.  Move back right and up to the top.

name: Hummingbird
description: P1 - Climb the crack approximately 20 feet to a small ledge and a band of crappy rock.  Climb past the shaley rock up a face to a bolt, then work up past more poor-quality shaley rock until you can move right to a nicve belay ledge (same as Tango).    P2 - Move a bit left, then up several "steps" to a large ceiling (easier than it looks).  Climb through the notch in the ceiling to the top.  Large cam helpful at the ceiling.

name: Tango
description: P1 - Climb the left-facing corner to a small shelf below the huge overhang and some fixed pitons (shifting rock, potential rockfall hazard).   Traverse left along the shelf until you can pull into the left-facing corner above (crux, harder if short).  Continue up and right to a belay ledge.    P2 - Climb straight up the steep left-facing corner to the ceiling.  Clip the bolt, then surmount the ceiling on the right and up to the top.

name: Tango Super Direct
description: Climb the crack and continue up the face to a bolt.  Surmount the small overhang (crux, long reach) then finish on Tango or traverse right under the Violent Femmes overhang and finish on Gorilla.

name: New Generation
description: The first pitch is fun and challenging.  The second pitch is a 4th-class scramble and not worth doing.    P1 - Start behind the tree and climb a dihedral that begins 5 feet off the ground, then move right to a stance.  Move back left to a nicet face and climb it to a bolt.  Continue up the smooth steep face with small holds to a ceiling, step right (or pull straight through at a notch, harder) and up to a ledge and a bolted rap/belay anchor.    P2 - (almost never done) Follow a 4th-class gully on the left to the top.

name: Blockhead
description: P1 - Climb the corner to the ledge 12 feet up as for Loose Block.  Continue in the main corner until you can step right to a large ledge (optional belay).  Climb the steep dihedral to a ledge with a cedar tree (same as for Loose Block Direct).    P2 - (Same as Loose Block Direct).  Climb a short face past the piton to the top.

name: Cramped Thumb
description: P1 - Climb the nice face just left of the small corner past an old, bent pin, then move up and right to an overhang.  Clear the overhang at a notch, then follow a groove to a small ledge with old pitons and the original belay.  Traverse left around a corner to a better belay (#2 Camalot).    P2 - Traverse way right under the overhang to a left-facing corner and bypass the overhang using awkward moves.  Follow a dirty crack up and left to the top.    Can be done in one pitch and this avoids the odd belay position.  Long slings or double ropes helpful.

name: Cramped Thumb Direct
description: Follow Cramped Thumb to the first overhang and notch just below the original belay.  Veer up and right to a notch in the next overhang (right of the notch for Director Overhang) with numerous pitons.  Clear the overhang at the notch and climb the steep exposed face festooned with pitons.

name: Director Overhang
description: Follow Cramped Thumb to the narrow ledge with pitons (original belay for Cramped Thumb).  Climb straight up from there to the overhang and clear it at an obvious notch.

name: Higher Than I
description: Dirty and uninspiring, even by Stover Standards.   P1 - Climb the cracks to a dirty ledge.  Walk left about 25 feet to a belay tree at the right edge of the Cramped Thumb face.    P2 - Climb the left-facing corner directly behind the tree to the ceiling.  Clear the ceiling (old piton above) and continue up the grungy face to the top.

name: Loose Block
description: Climb the broken corner to gain a ledge 12 feet up.  Continue up the corner and crack (crux) to a stance.  Angle up and left following the easiest path to the summit.

name: Loose Block Direct
description: P1 - Start as for Loose Block, climbing the corner to a ledge 12 feet up.  Continue up the corner to a large belay ledge.    P2 - Continue up the corner to another ledge with a tree.  Climb a short face behind the tree past a piton to the top.

name: Shalestorm
description: P1 - Climb the corner to the ledge 12 feet up as for Loose Block. Climb the steep face of the left-facing corner above, passing much friable rock to a ledge below the ceiling (or climb Loose Block to this point, better and safer with better rock). Continue through the overhang and follow 4 bolts up the face to a large belay ledge with a tree (same as Loose Block Direct and Blockhead).    P2 - Climb the short face past a piton to the top.

name: Dean's List
description: Start in an easy dihedral, the crux comes above the second bolt with some small holds and making a dynamic move to an ok hold on the arete, a few jugs lead to a small ledge where a good rest out right can be obtained.  The top is more sustained climbing on small holds.  If you blow it at the top, there is a chance you could hit the tree.

name: Dean's List (arête variation)
description: Start in an easy dihedral, and follow the bolts to the anchor. Use the arête for a 5.9 climb; avoiding it will yield a 5.11 crux instead.

name: Open Book
description: This is usually free solo'd to setup TR's for Tales and Deans if you're not up to leading on the old/sparse bolts. You can traverse into the book on blocky ledges. During the summer, the top part where the book meets the ledge is overgrown with lots of Poison Ivy.

name: Tales from the Crypt
description: The climb is on the Great Buttress, it's the obvious bolted line on the left.  A little runout and pumpy at the top. BE KIND TO THE CACTI!!! Did the upper pitches once with 3 good friends and a couple cold beers in tow. Worth the effort of tricky gear and route finding through questionable rock. I only remember one bolt after the cactus ledge and then making a skecthy belay on the next large ledge. I ended up getting a couple pieces in and clearing a beautiful crack out of vegetation on the final slab to the top.  Belay off the fence at the top and answer questions from non-climbers while bringing your partner(s) up.     P1: 5.10a PG. 60 feet, 3 bolts.   P2/3: 5.7? R. 60 feet?, 2 bolts?.

name: Three Buttresses (first pitch)
description: A blocky start leads to a left slanting crack capped by a roof which is bypassed on the right up to a ledge with a tree.  The ledge is part of the cactus ledge but is so covered in Poison Ivy and Brush that you can't get across it.  There are 2 more pitches, though they are rarely done.    This is the standard route. It traverses right as soon as a ledge can be reached on that side, by learning across and mantling onto it (or stepping wide if you're stretchier than I am). This traverse happens several moves below the roof, which is referred to in some guidebooks as "variation 1."

name: Three Buttresses (first pitch, variation 2)
description: Climb to the open book about 8 feet above the trail, then follow it to below an overhang. Hand traverse right under the overhang (instead of  mantling onto the lower ledge in the original version), and reach a cedar tree belay station.

name: The Long Chimney
description: The first technical climb done at Stover by Joe Walsh and friends from the Philadelphia Trail Club.    Climb the obvious chimney on the right side of the Open Face to the top.

name: Open Face
description: Climb the obvious chimney/gully to the top.

name: Open Face Slab
description: slab line to the right of prominent Open Face gully. Couple bolts throughout where pro placements are non existent. Allegedly led not using bolts by unknown party in 1980s according to P.Nick's guide.

name: Dirty Sanchez
description: A tall bolted route on the left middle section of Orangutan Buttress. A stiff start up a short shallow open book under the first bolt, followed by an interesting jaunt up the face. Three quarters of the way up the cliff is a roomy ledge with a pair of belay/rappel chains. From there, combine finesse and brute force to tackle the roof immediately off the deck - don't kick your ledge partners in the helmet - then haul over the bulge up the steep short second pitch to the top. If you're lucky you'll surprise a hiker around Cedar Overlook.    P1: 5.7, 7 bolts to anchor, ~80 feet.   P2: 5.9+, 4 bolts to anchor, ~30 feet.    From Nancy: "The first pitch is a 5.7, 7 bolts to a 2 bolt anchor and needs a 50m to rappel. The second pitch is 5.9+/10a 4 bolts to a 2 bolt anchor and needs a 70m to rappel from the top or 2 rappels with a 50m or 60m. This route is well protected and should not need a R rating. As far as the history goes, people have been climbing at RS since the 1940's and I'm sure at some point this line has been climbed, however there is no documented accent of the first pitch in any of the old guidebooks. The second pitch however, was a old top rope variation of orangutan rated 5.9+. "

name: Orangutan
description: The original of Orangutan continues to see little traffic.    P1: 45 feet, 5.3 R   P2: 30 feet, 5.8 PG    Starts in a 9' corner, 25 feet right of the Long Chimney on Open Face. Go up three ledges using easy rock, keeping right towards the end to belay. Pitch 2  keeps right and goes through the so-called "Crack of Doom."

name: Man of Science
description: Left most sport climb on the overhanging wall at the top of the Great Zawn gully.

name: The Problem
description: The right-hand sport line on the Great Zawn.

name: Crack Magic
description: A crack in a left-facing corner near the far right end of the Hawk's Nest area.

name: Cramped cosmonaut
description: Recently bolted face just to the right of Crack Magic. This was previously a TR only line; the grade comes from the guidebook. I don’t know who bolted it but they used closely spaced glue in bolts with a non-shiny finish. (This was a nice touch - they are less obvious and less visually disruptive for nonclimbers enjoying the cliff)

name: Hawk's Neck
description: Climb up easy rock to the roof of the cave. Go over the roof, roughly following a thin crack, then up the rock above to two anchor bolts on a ledge.

name: Hawk's Nest (P1)
description: The first pitch of Hawk's Nest is a fun, quality climb for its grade and location. Climb up a dihedral to a ceiling, and traverse left a short distance to its end. From there, follow a crack straight up, and traverse left along a ledge to a bolted belay directly over Hawk's Neck (if you don't see it at first, look on the left/far side of a rock protrusion - then there's no missing it).    "The opening moves often have wet feet. These can be bypassed and protected, but it ups the ante a little bit. After the seep, it's the best gear and best climb of it's grade at Stover." [-Larry S]    Three variations for the section pitch wait above.    Both pitches can also be combined into one pitch with a 60 m rope.

name: Hawk's Nest (P2 left)
description: From the bolted belay over Hawk's Neck and Hawk's Nest pitch 1, climb up and keep left wherever possible. This is the blue line in the route photo.

name: Hawk's Nest (P2 middle)
description: From the bolted belay over Hawk's Neck and Hawk's Nest pitch 1, climb up the roof past an old piton. Above it you'll have 15 to 20 feet of runout before the next pro, with a ledge close below. Climb carefully. This seems to be the variation done on the first ascent of Hawk's Nest. It's the purple line in the route photo.

name: Hawk's Nest (P2 right)
description: From the bolted belay over Hawk's Neck and Hawk's Nest pitch 1, traverse right.    This variation follows an erosion gully full of loose dirt and trash (your standing on this crap).     Go up to the pitch 2 chains. This is the yellow line in the route photo.

name: Welcome to Stover
description: Short hard sport route up a steep ceiling.

name: The Hearth
description: Slightly overhanging and fun, but also dirty and not often climbed.

name: Noncensus Direct
description: A recently bolted line that appears to be a direct start to Noncensus by climbing the overhanging face on good holds, mantling onto the ledge halfway up the route seemed to be the crux, then delicate vertical climbing past a bolt to the chains.  The bolts are closely spaced by stover standards.    - I do not know who bolted this, I only climbed it.

name: Oh Promise Me
description: Follows an inside corner into a chimney which spits you out onto a small ledge. Takes OK gear.

name: Beautiful Loser
description: First climb short bulging face. The crux is after the first ledge. When you pull the overhang on to the steep slab, the book notes that if you fall from the steep slab the bolts won't stop you from hitting the ledge. You now can top rope this with new chains and bolts at top.

name: Chain Reaction
description: We start this a little different then the book describes by simply starting off the trail. Go straight up first block to nice ledge where the Nameless Arete starts. Continue straight up the graffiti section about 10 feet off ledge is the crux you pull and awkward mantel then reach for small crimpers above you. Continue straight up to big roof. Holds are there but sometimes you have to reach and get keep them feet on.

name: Deaf and Dumb
description: These climbs are just around the corner from Chain Reaction. The inside corner is the 5.4 with var. on the facing wall both moving a little more left each time. The corner and first var. are easy to protect although the corner is a a little dirty at times. Fun in general.

name: Deaf and Dumb (variation 1)
description: Variation 1 is on the wall left of the 5.4 route, moving a little more left as it climbs. It goes left to the final overhang, then angles right to the notch to the right.

name: Nameless Arête
description: Climb up to the ledge with the stump and crank out the crimpy moves past 3 bolts culminating with a deadpoint to a jug, the difficulty then backs off, pass a two shuts anchor on a ledge and continue 10 feet to the top and clip the chains.

name: No Self Control
description: Follows a large corner, sometimes sharing it with a little trickling water or toxic foliage. Halfway up is a ledge with a tree, and it tops out through a notch, slightly to the right in a small overhang.

name: Wham, Jam, Thank You Cam
description: Walk a short way up a faint use trail on the far left side of Chain Reaction Buttress (left of Nameless Arete). Go up a left-facing dihedral for most of the cliff; near the top, traverse left to a tree, then top out.

name: Dead Tree
description: Starts a little left of Obnoxious Partner crack. Climb right-facing corner under a roof, traverse left past it, and up to a ledge. Climb a crack up to a cedar tree belay.

name: Obnoxious Partner Crack
description: Apparently a classic for the area.  Follows the obvious overhanging fist crack to a pod.  Then an airy step and up to the top.

name: Old Chimney
description: Climb the dirty Chimney immediately to the left of "Run Out of Favors" and 15' to the left of "Dead Tree".

name: Run Out Of Favors
description: The first Crux is climbing the bulge past the first bolt and gaining the large ledge, the second crux is at the second bolt gaining the small ledge while avoiding the large loose flake.

name: Broken Heart
description: This problem is found on the main boulder on the right side. The side resembles a heart. It is a simple crack problem. Its a short crack climb that starts with right foot out on a small rock in the ground and then a wide left foot on the base of the main boulder. Start with hands in the crack then cross hands up further on the crack and then bring right foot over to left foot and back flag the left. Move up the crack crossing hands and then pull up on top of boulder to top out.

name: Ridleys Gap
description: This problem starts with two feet on a smaller rock and two hands low on the first part of the boulder. Cross with your right hand further up on the same part you started on and then match hands. Throw a heel hook with your left foot to the edge. Put your right foot up onto the second part of the boulder and push up to grab with your right hand to the top part of the second part of the boulder and match hands. Then work your way up to the top using the edge of the boulder for feet. Top out.

name: Ridleys Oyster Shell
