description: Start with a hang start with feet on small rock under the first ledge. Cross left hand to small crimp swing out to grab a crimp on the other side of the ledge with right hand. While hanging throw a heel hook with right foot while flagging with left. Crank up and grab the point of the second ledge. Step up and top out.

name: Two Humps
description: Its a shorter problem if you have a crash pad bring it!

name: Finger Hand Fist
description: Start on good but small hands on the ledge below the crack, left foot smear and right foot on a small edge. Use the flaring crack to work hands up and then feet. This is a good problem for someone looking to get practice with different crack sizes. Although the crack is short if so inclined you could get 6-7 jams in before topping out (I did it in 3, a finger, hand, and fist jam)

name: Run Train
description: Start with feet on large angling boulder on the right end of the cave and hands on underclings of the top boulder. Work feet up the bottom and hands up the top until you can bump out left and let feet loose. Get a heel hook on the lip and make a scary mantle then scramble the slabby featured face to top out.

name: Whoever Killed That Tree, Your Mom's a Hoe
description: Start low and let on the end of the crescent shaped crack on incut small holds, feet on the base of boulder on good feet. Bump hands right along shallow crack (watch out for the corpse of the baby tree growing in the crack) and adjust feet on base. Either follow thinning fingertip sidepulls up the crack and an arduous high right foot to top out, or get yourself set on a good right hand and lunge up with the left for a sloper, heel hook and top out. Both ways are difficult, maybe v3. Please be careful to not lay your pad in such a way that you will stress the small tree at the back of the landing.

name: Chaos
description: Start matched semi-far to the right. Use heel hooks to not dab while traversing slightly to the left, and then going up for the top out.

name: Ladder
description: SDS on whatever holds you like, sometimes I start on the block to the right as well. There is a tree and ladder (hence the name) positioned above the boulder, which are fun to play around on.

name: Mythos
description: Start low on two extremely sharp crimps. Pull hard for a difficult throw upwards onto better holds, then top out.

name: Barefoot Traverse
description: Start with hands as shown in the picture or wherever there are dry holds, and head up and to the right quite aways before topping out.

name: Bob-ombs
description: Start with both hands matched on the basketball sized ball. You can go up either left or right, either way it's juggy slab climbing.

name: Colony
description: Start low on the right side of the outcropping with hands as shown in the picture. Head up and over the bloc containing the start holds for the topout.

name: Electra
description: Start with both hands matched at the far right end of the undercling rail (pictured). Slap out right, using the fins to the right and a bomber kneebar to get holds high overhead, and then topout to the left. I would wear a kneepad or long pants

name: Gengar
description: Low start at the left end of the steep overhang on a high right hand pinch and a low sloper left hand, climbing all the way out under the tree to the right.

name: Gengar Low
description: Start with both hands matched on the leftmost jug. Climb a few moderately difficult moves into the starting position of Gengar.

name: Hiangle
description: Start matched on a crimp rail on the lower detached bloc. After some delicate moves to get to the lip, traverse left. I probably would not want to fall from the top, since the hill is steep and there is a possibility of hitting the bloc below.

name: Icarus
description: Start somewhere on the right side of the boulder, and head up and to a little to the left before topping out.

name: Le Fin
description: Super cool feature. This boulder is a thin flake of black rock with big jugs, making it a  good warmup.

name: Nascar
description: This climb starts by sitting down against the tree at the far left, matched on a good jug. Continue climbing the arete (using the holds on the roof too) all the way around to the right end. I didn't top it out because it was raining, but it's probably possible.

name: Spike
description: Start on any of the numerous juggy holds on the left side, and go up and to the right for the topout.

name: Swarm of Eels
description: Start towards the left side of the outcropping, with hands as shown in the pictures. Avoiding the detached bloc below to the right of the start, go up and to the right for the top out.

name: Tardis Cave
description: This climb starts with a high left hand and lower right hand inside the cave. Follow the arete and avoid dabbing since it's so low, finishing matched on the hold at the far right end.

name: Tardis Cave Low
description: Lay down start all the way to the left with the hands as indicated in the pictures. Climb a few fairly difficult moves into the start position of the regular Tardis Cave and finish the same way.

name: Tunnel Vision
description: SDS with both hands matched on a slopey sidepull. Go up and to the left for a few moves before topping out.

name: Chubby chaser
description: Sit start left side with feet just under Boulder work your way upward on a slight angal till get around to the over hanging side then make your way up and over

name: Cobra
description: Sit start undercling crack boost up to the upper ledge follow vertical crack and nice crimps to top.

name: Detour
description: Start the same as you would for pinacle point problem but edge right and climb through the bulge.

name: Ledger
description: The start is a compression move with two side pulls (Picture shows starting position). Then your hands will work up to the multiple ledges until you reach the top. The top is sloppy and somewhat of a struggle to get on top.

name: Overhang
description: Low hanging start on a good ledge (Shown in picture). Power move to the second ledge then match. Another powerful move to a sloppy crimp with a thumb. Move up to a side pull, then reach to the top.

name: P Diddle
description: 1st area

name: Pinacle Point
description: sit start one crimp and undercling crimp continue up to two crimps above bring feet up and make a big fun move to a slopey yet good hand hold above from there edge left to the pinnacle point.

name: Pinacle Point Street Side
description: Sit start on slopey ledge with right foot under overhang continue up to another sloped ledge and a crimp you will need all you can purchase from this as the feet are scarce. Continue up to better ledges and traverse around the point top out is same as pinnacle point problem.

name: Pocket Pull
description: Either sit or stand start on flakey crack. Work up to overhang and traverse right. Reach for good ledge. Hold on in slopey pocket and topout directly above. Rocks to the right are off. Assuming a first ascent because route isn't on MP, but I'm sure it's been climbed before.

name: Sidewinder
description: Start on two, right facing, incut crimps. Move up and right under a small bulge and finish just right of the bulge.

name: Simply
description: Start on a low side pull. Reach up to decently sized crimp. There are a few holds to grab onto before the large ledge. You can either grab the sloper or grab more tiny crimps. I prefer tiny crimps. Move your feet up and make a move to the ledge. From there, work your way to the top.

name: Sobriety Check
description: Sit start on left crack. Work your way up to right good sloper. Continue up over high point.

name: Touch of faith
description: Sit start, starts to the right of over hang on ledge move to two finger pockets above ledge move toward the over hang to a knob then up to the top useing a few small crimp type holds keep your feet off big ledge under over hang

name: Viper
description: Starts above a small block at the base of the boulder about 15 feet to the right of Sidewinder. Climbs straight up on generous edges and pockets to a rounded top out.

name: walk on the moon
description: really nice holds on this route stand start on double handed crack to left right move to another great side pull. follow crack on right center to top out.

name: Dark and Slopey
description: Sit Start, Keyhole shaped pocket for the left hand and a good crack for the right. Work your way up and left into the mid section of the climb then use some deep pockets to get onto a pretty slopey top out.

name: Finger Hanger
description: BETA: Start on a really good flake (Shown in Photo). Bounce up to a small edge and match. Reach out to a crimp that you can either match or use other crimps around it. After the crimpy section, move your hands along a few slopers in till you reach the last hold. The last hold is a good sloper. During the whole climb, your legs are underneath the rock and your hands are in the middle of the face.  WARNING: Do not go high and to the left. The rocks are flaky there. Also, DO NOT go farther underneath the rock!! There is a huge flake that could come off. The boulder route does not go near there, so it is safe.

name: Social Anxiety
description: BETA: Starts on a really good ledge (Shown in picture). Bounce up to the next ledge where there are multiple good holds. From there, reach for a protruding rock that has a nice jug. Make your way to the top with a few more good holds. The top hold is a bit slopey.  WARNING: Do not go to far to the right or up. The rocks to the right and up are flaky and ready to break off.

name: Beginner's Crack
description: Beginner's crack is a fairly straight forward climb. Just follow the crack with both hands and walk your feet up the sides.

name: Crack full of fingers
description: Climb up the crack couple crimps to the right to help stabalize top out.

name: crock gators
description: Start below the the small boulder at the bottom making this problem a little longer, continue along the arete through pretty awesome divot features in the rock.

name: Dirty harrey
description: Start on crack follow towards the the top to few nice hand holds then a step over the top

name: Hedge stone
description: This climb is in area 3 on the wall start left on corner move up and right you will find a sloppy hold big enough for two hands from there you will keep moving upward and right to a more crimp hold work your feet up as you look for the next crimp which is a bit farther of a reach then the last few holds where it closer to the top and a little right from the last hold then final and slap over the top as u climb up for top out

name: High and Dry
description: This route is named after the pond that forms beneath it in the winter and spring. Sit start with left hand in pocket right hand on the arete. Continue up till you get to a round two handed crimp, cross over the face to a large pocket and little pinches and crimps up to the top.

name: Mount. Direct
description: This rock can have multiple paths from the right or left; however, this route goes directly up the center. Start with both hands on a small ledge in the bottom crack. It helps to hold onto the crack if you do a bicycle with your feet. Powerful move to a right hand crimp. Move left hand to a small under cling, then bump up to a small crimp. Move right hand to a small ledge and move left hand to a really bad side pull. From here you have to dyno to the top because there are no holds in between.

name: Short and sweet
description: Sit start with your feet towad the right side of the Boulder with your hand on a real nice side pull make your next to the ledge work left on it then work your up to the point

name: Simple but Sharp
description: Start in the obvious, big pocket with both hands. Move your hands up and get your feet on the big sloper ledge. Work your feet across the ledge and top out left. There is still lichen and moss on the boulder, but the key holds are clean enough.

name: Adam fall lowball Mantle
description: Sit start straddling the front corner. go right to get below the overhang. heel hook and mantle from underneath without the sidewall.

name: Adam fall lowball Traverse
description: To the right: Start on far left side on slopy crimp work all the way around stem outcut and push to stand.(V2)   To the left:Start Stemmed in the outcut work all the way around until a tree blocks the path.(V3)   Front corner is crux move both ways

name: Adam fall lowball under-over
description: Start Stemmed below overhang work right to vertical face then topout

name: Dog face rock V1
description: Start low on left side where underhang begins below crack climb straight up.

name: Dog Slobber
description: Start on right side of boulder one foot under the low shelf hand matched on the second shelf. go left all the way below the flat front face and top out.

name: No hand toe slab
description: FEET ONLY. start on lowest two crimps balnce to top using feet

name: Wibbly Wobbly Rocky Wocky
description: Start at left side where overhang begins hands below the crack feet low. Work all the way under the flat front upper face, top out.

name: 3-Layer Cake
description: Start on the low ledge an work your way up to the second ledge. The second ledge to the third ledge is the crux. I find it easiest to bring your right leg up to the ledge and turn your hips into the wall. This allows you to freely move your hands without falling. There are crimps and some better holds on top. Top out is a little tricky.

name: Unforeseen
description: Sit start with some very good pockets and holds. make your way directly to the top. Topping out is the crux move. The top is very slopey and there are no holds. Use your feet to push above the top.

name: Dimer
description: Start on two separate holds, one is an undercling and the other is a pinch. Do a big move to a good jug and reach up to a side pull. Move again to either another side pull or to another jug. From there you can reach the top. I did not use the the arete or the wall to the left. If you use these, then the grade is lowered.

name: Eave
description: Start with left hand on the arete and right hand on a small side pull. I stick my foot in the bottom crack to help stabilize. Bump the right hand to another side pull higher up. Then prepare for a dyno move to good hold with the right hand again. Then bring the left hand up and top out. The wall to  the right is off limits. Do not use.

name: Swiss Cheese
description: Start on a low undercling, then move up to a solid hold. The rest of the way is quite simple, since there is a variety of holds. The top out is easy because of a nice crack on top of the boulder. I did not use the arete, so the grade is without the arete. If you use the arete, the grade is lower. It does not matter much in this climb.

name: Sylphlike
description: You can either sit start or stand start. The grade does not vary between the two starts and is pretty simple. Follow the very thin crack till you top out.

name: Voluminous
description: Fairly simple climb straight up the wall. Just a warm up.

name: Butterball
description: Start on a pretty slopey hold. Traverse right to a really good pocket and match. From there, reach out right to a side pull. Move feet to a triangle sticking out. Put left hand in the side pull as well. Transfer weight from left side to right side. This is the crux section. Reach out right to the last hold. It is a bit slopey. Do not use the top ledge for this boulder problem. Otherwise it is a V0.

name: 52 card pick up
description: Easy problem that goes up a seam in this 13 foot high pillar that sits on top of a section of the crag.  There are more difficult problems up different parts of the pillar, this will be the easiest way up.  The top makes for the perfect spot to take a break and get some sun.  Climb up but be prepared to climb down, the down climb is easy though.

name: Ain't No Thang
description: An easy boulder problem just off the main path below the Western side of the crag.  Problem goes up the center of the stone with a slightly positive pitch on meaty juggy holes and some seams and under hooks in the rock, work your feet to make an easy send to top out and scamper down the other side of the rock.  Really great problem for beginners.     17 feet high measured

name: Chicken wing on a string
description: Easy climb up decent sized boulder.

name: Chub Rub
description: A dirty, wet, moss-covered, but rediculously fun chimney with good hands and feet the whole way up. Top out to complete. Bring a spotter. They won't be able to help you much if you fall in the chimney but they can keep you from rolling down the hill and over the cliff.

name: Collateral Damage
description: This is a pretty short easy boulder problem. Follow the obvious holds up the face and use the generous lip to top out. While helping Dan establish the problem I smashed my finger moving a loose boulder at the bottom of the project. Hence the name.

name: Cool Runnings
description: 17 foot high slightly angled flat side of this boulder with some cracks and shallow dimples.  Give those toes a work out as you make your way up this flat slick slab.  Might make 2 problems out of it, one that goes up a few feet then left to the edge, work edge to top out and one that continues up the center of the boulder.  Time will tell.

name: Cross Hatch
description: Cling to the scarred holds of this boulder as you make your way up the over hung arete, work for an interesting top out.  Hold on tight ; )

name: Don't Forget Your Towel
description: Sit start this high ball just inside the mouth of a low roof cave.  Work up for a match on the large corner hold.  Pull some magic with your feel and go far right before pulling up the seam.  If your fingers are narrow and or you are better than I at jamming this section could go easy for you.  Continue up to where the rock come out just a bit and work left and up for what looks like an easy last half.  Know your limits and the art of the down climb, no room for error.      (See photos for exclusion)     Projecting and piecing sections together on this problem is quite a treat as the large tree just 2 feet away from the rock face makes for a great resting/cheating post ;)     May be possible to start way inside the cave following the right wall seams out adding another 10-15' of length upping the difficulty and creating a new problem.

name: Double dutch don't pop the clutch
description: Start under the roof, on the right. Hands on the chest high sloping edge at the end, feet on the flake directly below, go up to and across the top crack to the end of the flake, then up for the top ledge.

name: Exclusion Delusion
description: Small boulder that has a little angled overhang.   Sit start in the low corner with feet under the overhang, work up and out of the over hang.  Anything besides the overhang is off.  No smearing the vertical flat or using anything far right.  See photos for details.

name: Frosted Flakes
description: Fairly high boulder problem directly on the main trail just down the hill from the main crag.  Problem goes up the center of the high nearly vertical rock on lipped flake like holds.  Be cautious of thin flakes and don't pull out as much on the holds as you pull down, they can be brittle.  Lots of options for holds, do what works for you, keep your feet in comfortable positions on some of the narrower sharper holds to prevent discomfort work up the rock to the lip on the right for quick rest before pushing out the last few feet towards the left.  Top out and straddle the top of the rock and throw your hands up in the joy of success then scamper your way down the slopey other side.    20 feet high measured

name: The Great Migration
description: Sit start in the same vertical seam as "You must find a shrubbery" Once you are up, and at the horizontal seam start working your way right under the roof.  Continue under the roof on an amazing mix of holds in the roof and off the lip, utilizing the horizontal seam when necessary for 10-15" until you can pull the roof on the far right.  Knock out the last 8 or 9 vertical feet to top out for one amazing journey.  Guess on grade until it's completed.

name: High Step Scramble
description: High feet and good hands to a top out on this natural staircase. A fall might cause you to roll down the hill to the cliff's edge so a spotter is recommended. There is also a nasty rock in the ground at the base so cover it with a pad to protect your ankles.

name: Lute's Delight
description: Follow the crack system up to the roof. A fall would be dangerous but it's easy climbing. The block itself in the middle feels loose and wobbled a bit so beware if you pull on it. Fortunately it's possible to do without using that part. Go Lutes!

name: Mad Gab
description: Stand start on the round knob at foot level and move up into pockets while matching hands on the palm smear at head height or a little higher (I'm tall so it might be a little above your head if you're of average height). There are two really great hidden plate holds that are super fun to find so I won't spray beta. You'll just have to search to find them. Pull on the plates until you top out in the moss.

name: Mad Gab's Mouth
description: Match hand's on plate hold, feet on back wall. Work hands left, feet right to front wall then pull for the crease and work out of the cave and up to the big sloper.

name: Monkey Face
description: This boulder stands at full salute at the bottom of the crag near the main wall.  Work the arete and friction holds to reach the tip...errr top.  (problem formerly known as "just the tip")  renamed after a first send.  Will update name mentions in time, like on the location topo.

name: Monkey Shuffle Traverse
description: Start on the horn to the left where the crack begins. Match hands along the crack keeping feet low. The first crux is near the peace sign on the wall. Match feet on the wall below the "MAD" graffiti and then stem your right foot below the peace sign. Keep moving right until you get to "We'll See" and heel hook just right of the word "See" and start to move out onto the roof. There is a nice heel hook up and to the left of the monkey's face for your right heel after you match feet on the "See" hook. Follow the seam on the roof flake and continue right. The protection gets really sketchy here and you will NEED a spotter over the rocks. Continue until the route naturally terminates above those nasty sharp rocks on the ground. You hands will run out but your feet will end on the corner. It runs horn to horn.

name: Over the Rainbow
description: Sit start in a seam near the middle of the the cave/tunnel created by the main wall and boulder.  Just above the sit start seam is a large juggy hole that is your first move. (tall people might be able to reach it from sit start, encouraged to start on lower holds).  After you are up work your way out of the cave/tunnel (both sides are on for this problem).  Once out work your way up the main wall and up the slight over hang to a ledge.  Work right on the ledge and climb your way back down an easy decent to end up on top of the boulder you were originally underneath.

name: Perdy Mouth
description: This grimacing problem goes up the Western side of this large boulder.  (Stand start) Find your right foot then initiate the climb and bump your way to a thumb hole and index/middle finger pinch, or however you want to hang on it. Find your feet and figure out your next move, may seem daunting at first but goes fairly easy.  Get up to the angled seam and prepare to do your last few moves to top out this highball with a sketchy landing.  (currently a project of mine, more to come)

name: Pink Patchouli Flower
description: The route sit-starts on the obvious flake to the right of the boulder (see pictures) and follows an arc up and over toward your left. The problem terminates in one of two places: You can either downclimb back to the ground or top out on top of the boulder following the same route that you would use for Collateral Damage.

name: Pink Patchouli Flower Power up
description: Sit start with left foot low right foot flagged, left hand on right crimp closest to the flake, right hand on the bottom of that flake. Get feet in the right pocket and hand's up the flake grab jug with left and arete with right get a high left foot and go for the top of the right arete.

name: Proboscis
description: Sit start this tall knife like boulder and work a few holds and some easy moves to get up on some solid footing.  From there do what you gotta do to make it go which may or may not include using the large nose like hold the problem derives it's name from.  Adjacent boulder is off.

name: Ruffles Have Ridges
description: Sit start in the cave/tunnel in the same seam as "Over The Rainbow" on the crag side of the tunnel.  Hit the same first move but then work your way right instead of left.  Boulder that creates other side of cave/tunnel is off.  Work your way around and up the ridge of the large potato chip flake until you reach the over hang.  Pull the small roof and head up "most likely left" for a top out.  Guess on grade, until it is finished.

name: Scissor Me Timbers
description: A fun little problem, work up left, then stretch those legs to come back over to the right before topping out.

name: Scratching Post
description: Sit start just inside on the right wall of the small cave created by these two large boulders.  Work your way up the available holds towards the outside arete.   Continue working your way up between the boulder and the tree just beside it to top out where the two boulders meet.  (adjacent boulder is off)

name: Staircase to Nowhere
description: Start out just right of "Ain't No Thang" at the bottom of the natural staircase. You will see a really clear side pull off to your right and a jug that looks like part of a stylized mountain range (if you use some imagination). Place your right hand on the sidepull and your left hand on the "hump" of the mountain range. Place your right foot turned inward (this is important) on the only little wavy vertical bacon on the rock that it looks like it might hold about ten to twelve inches up from the ground. The tricky part of this climb is the first few super-technical moves that will require speed because your foot placement will not hold for long. Place your weight on that right foot and as your body moves up take your right hand off of that sidepull and reach up for the palm smear directly above your head. As you pull that with some friction move your left foot out to the wavy bacon to your left and stand up enough to tuck your toes on your right foot into that sweet little pocket (you'll know the one). As you do transition your right hand up onto the pinch above your head to the right a little and your left hand to the pocket just to the left of the pinch. You'll have to pull that pocket a little bit like and undercling (almost). Pull yourself up a bit and slap the moss on the top with whatever hand you can be free of for a few precious moments. You're done! Now go grab a beer you sexy beast. You've earned it.

name: Stuck like penit butta
description: Match hands on far right plate, feet high on left wall. Work hands left get a foot to the start hold and pull for the sidecut crease then out to the top. Right wall is off limits, stick to the roof.

name: Supernumerary
description: Start way back in the cave on a right-hand undercling and a slightly donky flake. Move through iron bands to arete and up face.

name: Tony the Tiger
description: The start is the same as Frosted Flakes, but after your first couple moves up the boulder you to traverse to the right, to top out on the far right ledge. You won't run short of holds on this quick, fun climb

name: Under the rhodo shelf
description: Stand start on crimps below the shelf, left of where the lower incut meets the ground.  go straight up through the overhang then left to the arete to top out.

name: Varicose Veins
description: (Stand start) On the left front face of the boulder start this great problem out on an under hook and shallow 2 finger hole (or whatever works for you) work some magic with your feet and do some rearranging to hit a phenomenal 2 hole pinch and from there find your way to the vein like features the problem gets it's name from.  Work for a fairly solid yet high top out and find your way down the backside of the boulder.     20 feet high measured.

name: Wait, that's not....right?
description: Stand start both hands in crack under the first roof flake, workup to roof pocket lay out and reach hard for the left edge of the crack. Finish in the bushes on the ledge above.

name: Why So Serious
description: Great problem, may seem more difficult than V1 if you don't see the move but once you see it, figure out how to hit it, it all falls into place.  Could go softer? IDK?     Breeze up the rest of the problem to where the last move to top out goes a bit un easy.  On less than solid footing and odd angle left hand hold make a big reach with the right for the far top right of the rock and hope you find a hold... it's there :)

name: Workin The Corner
description: grade lowered based on new start position.  Stand start on the corner.  Left foot low, right hand low right and left hand in corner undercling.    Work your feet and get situated to transition up the arete for a solid top out.  Boulder is around 17 feet high, entire problem runs close to 20 feet or slightly more, second half of the problem goes easy.

name: Yankin' Yoda's chin
description: Sit-start matched on right flake with feet on lower opposite facing flake. Work hand's up under overhang, then over to the "chin" of the second yoda head up. Finish up "Ain't no thang"

name: You must find a SHRUBBERY!
description: Fun little problem,  Sit start in the seam how ever you want,  Only one way that i found that worked well.  Pull one big move to hit the big lip/horizontal crack.  Work your way up on a mix bag of fun holds.  Once up on the 2nd layer of rock work your way left then up for a top out.  You can continue straight up as opposed to going left but sooner or later the bushes get the better of you and you run out of rock.

name: Your Other Left
description: Stand start with your hands in the seam near the "W''s (graffiti) and work your way up to some solid holds on the next layer of rock.  Position yourself to match the crack/hole in the middle of the roof and then throw for the seam a foot or so up on the outside of the roof on the vertical.  Work some magic with your feet and then top out last easy bit of this high ball that all makes for a great problem.

name: 1. Dirty Crack
description: Sit start on big jug flake on the far right of the small roof. Climb up the name sake crack to the top.

name: 10. Niners
description: Sit starting on the same right facing crimp rail as SAMCRO, move up into undercling feature. From here you want to go up and right to the large gash on the face; there is two ways to do that. One is dyno with your left on a good sidepull and right still in the undercling all the way to the lower part of the gash, but the hold you're going for is sharp. The other is make a few smaller moves using the tiny crimps out right. It's easy after you gain the large gash.

name: 11. SAMCRO
description: Near the center of this large overhanging face, at the lowest point, sit start matched on a right facing sidepull crimper. Make a big first move to juggy gaston, and match in the feature as an undercling. From here SAMCRO goes left a bit through pinches and pockets. Then climb up on bad crimper flakes to a monster move aiming for a big left sidepull. Continue up a few more moves to the easy topout.

name: 11a. Nomads
description: A link up of SAMCRO into Niners, this climb starts as SAMCRO, but after climbing up and left where you would normally do the big move to the left facing jug, climb up and right using a single slopey biscuit to meet up with the giant gash of Niners.
Start under Samcro on big holds, climb up and left on more big holds to the top.
Climb the overhang with many hold options that you see on your way in.

name: 14. Liar Liar
description: in the hole on the left side of this boulder, start low on left crimp and right hand wide with a right heel hook. Get out of the pit and topout.

name: 15. The Golden Bough
description: Could be the best line in SWPA. Start low down in the pit matched on a large left-facing flake. Climb up the gently overhung face on perfect coral-esque crimps. Unlock the right sequence and you'll get to the heady but easy topout.

name: 16. Last Stand of the Space Cowboys
description: Start low, climb the face, topout left of the hanging block.
Often dirty, climb the thin slab to the top

name: 18. Missionary Direct
description: Sit start just left of the arete and crimp your way up this overhanging face to the top.

name: 19. Missionary Arete
description: Sit start on arete, and follow it up until you can make a big move to gain the slab. Topout.

name: 2. Main Bloc Pocket Problem
description: Left of the jug flake, sit start on decent holds with a high right foot. Climb out short but steep roof using sharp/shallow pockets to a slopey mantle finish.

name: 20. Subtlety
description: Sit start on the right side of this slab. Climb straight up on slopers, avoiding the wall and arete to the right.

name: 21. Doritos
description: Climb the orange wall on fragile iron features to the top. Kind of sketchy. It's a shame because it looks cool.

name: 22. Getting Out of the Hole
description: Underneath Doritos, you can crawl in a hole; this climb starts at the base of the roof on a slopey ledge and climbs out said hole to an amazing slopey topout and slab finish.
On the right side of the overhang, start low and topout. That's all the info i got on this one.

name: 24. Cherry Picking
description: Sit start down under the roof on good holds. Follow line of holds under roof and on the face to climb up and left. Meet up with jugs on left side of the face, and topout.

name: 25. Shirley Temple
description: Sit start, more like lay down in the hole under the roof on good holds. Climb out roof to the center of the face above, then follow crimp ledges to the top.
Clibm the right arete.

name: 27. Tsunami Arete
description: Left of the easy arete, sit start matched on a small crimp ledge. Climb up weird features, avoiding the arete to your right. Topout.

name: 28. Boxing
description: Sit start and climb the short overhung face on crimps, just left of Tsunami Arete.

name: 29. Boxed In
description: Left of Boxing around a tree, start low and climb out small dihedral feature and topout the bulge.

name: 30. Pequod
description: uphill from the beginners slab climbs, you will find an arete facing you that is part of the cliffline. Sit start on left side pull on the leftish part of the blunt arete. Climb up to top.

name: 3a. Main Bloc Arete
description: There are many ways to do this arete; Stand start about half way up with a good foot edge on the arete. Climb to the point and topout.

name: 3b. Main Bloc Arete Sit
description: There are many ways to do this arete; Sit start matched on the good foot chip that you would use for the stand start. Climb out arete to the point and topout.

name: 3c. Main Bloc Arete Full
description: Sit start at lowest point on arete. Climb out to the point but instead of topping out here, continue right on slopers to the same mantle topout as Main Bloc Pocket Problem.
Right of the arete, climb the often wet overhang.

name: 5. Tee Pee Right
description: On the rightish side of the Tee Pee face, stand start on crimps and climb up and right to the top.

name: 6. Project
description: Probably not crazy hard, it's never been done to my knowledge because it's pretty high. Climb straight up the gut of the Tee Pee boulder.
Climb the small overhanging dihedral feature to the top.

name: 8. Mayans
description: On the right side of the wall standing up on some small boulders, stand start on large sketchy looking flake. Climb up, then right following the line of holds just below the orange/irony section. A big move guards the end just before the lip.

name: 9. Project
description: Start same as Samcro and Niners, but traverse right through thin cruxes to the same topout as Mayans.

name: Cranberry Bog
description: Start on the obvious handlebar and the jug to the left, and chug up easy moves for the first couple feet. Stab with the right hand to a slot facing the wrong way, and make a blind move with the left hand to a dimpled black pocket. Make one more move and finish in the black jug at the top. A gimme if you’re tall.

name: (13) Cannabis
description: Appears to be run out at first glance but well protected.    While this route, like its next-door neighbor (Touch of Green, 5.6), is not especially interesting to climb, the view from the anchors is the best at Breakneck. (And they're the only ones that get consistent sun!) Oh, and the evenly dispersed array of small pockets make Cannabis, like Eclipse (5.6), a less height-dependent route than most of the problems on the Main & Right walls and thus a similarly good choice for a first lead attempt by novice sport climbers (especially on a busy day when the upper area is mobbed).

name: (14) Touch of Green
description: A route similar to Cannabis. This one is the right of the three routes on this block.  5.5 seems a fair rating, as this route is easier than Eclipse (5.6). While neither of these lower routes are particularly exciting climbs, the view from the anchors is the best at Breakneck. And they're the only ones that get consistent sun!

name: Apartment 19
description: This is the most climber friendly and easiest lead at Breakneck.  It is reasonable for the grade with secure holds and stances.  Much less committing than Eclipse and easier than the three climbs on the front side of The Cannabis Boulder.  There are a good variety of moves and body positions as you work your way through the different sections of this short but very fun route. A great addition to this area.

name: Don't PAT the Tree
description: Most likely the best of the 3 climbs on this face.  If you use the large flake behind the tree the grade is a little easier.

name: Old Spice
description: Fun juggy line.

name: The Right Spice
description: A great addition to breakneck! Pumpy and juggy with a fun crux.

name: Convergence
description: Begin just left of "High Hanging Fruit." Climb up to the small rooflet half way up the route and then follow the right facing flake to the top.  This route shares anchors with "High Hanging Fruit."

name: Divergence
description: This route has the same start as Convergence. Climb up to, and over, the same rooflet, but then head up and left on a rising diagonal and head to the set of anchors on the left side of the wall.

name: High Hanging Fruit (A.K.A. Legends of the Green)
description: There is a very sequential 5.9 section on the bottom of this route that is protected by two bolts.  The hand crack on the top is not more than 5.6.  The bolts on the face below will allow a new trad leader to feel safe as they work on their gear game.

name: M&M
description: You can avoid the first crux on the bottom half of the route by skirting slightly to the right before rejoining the route.  This drops the rating a couple letters.

name: The Undeterred
description: Although this is a very short route, it stays real from the first move until the last.  Please be careful at the top.  Because it is so short and only has 2 bolts, the combination of an inattentive belay and a leader falling while trying to clip the anchors could be very bad --thus the R rating.  There has been discussion about adding a 3rd bolt a move or two from the anchors to avoid this scenario.

name: (1) Old School
description: Climb starts on the small ledge up around the left side of the cliff. Climb up the arete to the ledge at the top of Mosquito. Can use the shuts of mosquito to lower or bring up a second.

name: (10) Grab Your Balls
description: A tricky start off the ground or easier if started from the rock to the right. Climb up easy ledges to a committing crux near the top.    A steady 5.7 climb sandwiched by two legit 5.9 cruxes, one at the bottom (from the ground) and one at the anchors. The ground start is particularly vulnerable to a sketchy PG13+ landing (more than a pad can cover), especially on lead without a stick-clipped first bolt, so people seem to skip it and come at it from the right instead. The hardest stretch is that portion coming up the face from the ground to the first clip, so it's probably a 5.9- (mostly 5.7ish climbing) without it.

name: (2) Mosquito
description: Second line of bolts from the left climb up to the small ledge 8' off the ground. Follow the bolts up to a small ledge. Climb up through a bulge to another ledge and the shuts.

name: (3) Mosquito Variation
description: Climb the start of Mosquito, but from the ledge above midpoint move right to a bolt and flake. Climb left from the flake to the ledge and the same shuts as Mosquito.

name: (4) New School
description: Climb up to the small ledge 8' off the ground. Continue straight up face moves to a bulge. From the bulge it is possible to go left, direct, or right. Left and right are 10a variations. Direct is the most difficult at 10d.

name: (5) Bowling Ball
description: Starts up to the easy ledge. From the ledge climb thinner face moves to the now famous bowling ball hold. Continue up through the crux to the good horizontals and a rest. Finish on the slopers above to the shuts.

name: (6) Transfusion
description: The interesting start with a rocky landing well warrants a stick clipped first bolt. Once through the opening crux, work your way up the face to the bulge pull the bulge and find easier climbing to the top.

name: (7) Burning Balls
description: Another thin start with a bad landing, stick clipping the first bolt here isn't a bad idea either. climb up the thin face to the bulge pull the bulge and find a balancy top section.

name: (8) Diesel
description: Start to the left of the eclipse route/crack. Climb up through a flake system to a rest ledge continue up the thin face to the shuts.

name: (9) Eclipse
description: This is the route for any beginning sport climber. Start up the right side of the offwidth 2/3 of the way up start to stem and lay back off the left wall to the shuts.
Unknown bolted route with unknown rating but has been guessed at 10b.

name: Crimp Fest
description: Climb through a relatively easy beginning on slabby slopers, then commit to a crimpy crux at the top that is unique for breakneck.

name: Do You Like Apples
description: The direct start to Revisited, and the right most climb on the main wall. Jump start to funny looking hole jug. Climb straight up on crimpy underclings, meeting up with revisited at the third bolt.

name: Gas on the Fire
description: In between Diesel and Eclipse; start off on easy terrain reaching a crux at the second bolt. Definitely a bit of a squeeze job, but all the holds you use are independent of Diesel and straying too far right towards the crack risks a weird fall. A good addition to Breakneck; it's worth noting that the little rusty nubs near the anchors were the original anchors placed by Dave Lynn and friends all the way back in the early 2000s.

name: Revisited
description: A reachy crux at the first bolt leads to fun climbing up and right on a blunt slopey arete.

name: Bio-fear
description: This is the right line on this face, moderate face climbing to the top.

name: Finger Crack (TRAD)
description: finger crack listed as 17a on the topo. start in the center of the wall at the crack and follow it to the bolted anchor at the top of bio fear or top out to the right of the bolts

name: Fool's Gold
description: Left most sport climb on the right wall. Hardest of the three

name: Nemosis
description: The Left of the two bolted lines on this face. Seldom climbed and moderate.

name: Tee Pee Tim
description: Start on the right end of the face. Work your way up the steep lip passing 2 bolts to the chains.

name: New River Problem
description: Starts 8' right of PUR Pocket Power on the obious jug flake system.  Using jugs, climb your way out to the crux at the lip.  Pull the lip and finish.  Drop down to the pads

name: PUR Pocket Power
description: SS start on obvious flakes, make a left throw to a 2 finger pocket at the lip.  Traverse left to a right facing flake.  Pull lip to ledge.  Jump down to pads.

name: Fancy Nancy
description: Recommended, This slab problem seems to be very friction dependent.  Start standing, hands up to where rock changes angle. finish direct to top.  Note: Larger left corner is off limits except starting left foot.  It'll make sense when on the problem.

name: Lucky 7's
description: SS, left of Fancy Nancy.  Follows left leaning sloping faces up arete to top.  F.A. 7/7/07

name: Silly Sally
description: Up edges direct to top.

name: Hot Wax
description: SS, Starts up center of block.  Right of large jugs(off). Climb up the flake, make a move to the large center ledge.  Work up into the HotWax holds.  Finish with a topout.

name: Weeping Vagina
description: SS, begins on the right side of the Hotwax face.  Use vertical slits as start.  Work up though several moves to the large horizontal. Move left and finish up Hotwax.

name: Jimminy Cricket
description: Climb right diagonal crack from sit start on uphill face of block. Mantle topout.

name: Sleeping, Snoring, Sampson
description: SS. Climbs long overhanging arete. Bad landing on ledge below.

name: King Kong
description: Crux is at midheight on the crimpy right facing rail.  Match on the rail, highstep and move up high to the arete.

name: Ground Round
description: SS with feet under overhang using slopers work your feet up onto the face, continue to the top.

name: Pocket Full of Kryptonite
description: SS on left side.  Moves right through pockets topping out to the right side.

name: Unbridled Spirit
description: Sit start in front of the downed tree.  Work up using pockets to an undercling.  Finish by topping out on the sloping lip.

name: Firesticks
description: Starts in corner under roof and follows out seam and face until possible to pull the overhang and topout.

name: Good in a pinch
description: SS, follow short arete to a low topout. Another problem to do while at the Mouse Hole

name: Project
description: Follow line out center of steep face of Mouse Hole Block.  Use crimps and small features.  Get to the lip and top out.

name: Joel's Line
description: First done around a decade ago, this heinous crimp line used to be considered Joel's V9, but has yet to see a repeat. To the right of Silver Tongue, sit start on the face matched on the only obvious jug. Climb up and left through micro crimps to a big move to catch the lip, and it's still not over.

name: Orange Crush
description: To the right of Pinnacle and left of the crazy white blankness, cruise the iron feature up and left all the way to the top.

name: Pinnacle
description: On the left side of the "vaccum sealed" boulder, climb up just right of the arete using side pulls and big moves.

name: Silver Tongue
description: Sit start at the base of the obvious overhanging compression arete. Slap up to be able to gain the right side, then using crazy toe hooks come in and match. Cruise the right side to the point and topout.

name: Sunset Arete
description: Sit start on a right facing crimpy flake. Climb the arete to the top using some small crimps to a tricky topout.

name: Turkey Vulture
description: Sit start matched on a decent crimp with a good left foot. Make a hard move up and left, then keep it together for a few more moves to topout.

name: The Unbearable Lightness of Being
description: Sit start and climb the right side of this amazingly pure arete all the way to the top.

name: Establishmentarianism
description: Just right of the left arete, climb the coralesque face on crimps up and right to the top.

name: Moose Squat
description: Sit start and do the first few hard moves to get into easy climbing all the way to the top.

name: Project
description: Phenomenal iron crimps lead all the way up a vertical face.

name: The Dojo
description: The right most climb in the Ceilings, start on a juggy seam. Move through decent holds on the roof to a crazy lip encounter using the only real hold- a bad sloper. Drop off after you've gained the slab, or cruise the V1ish highball to the top.

name: Minecraft
description: Stand start on obvious huge triangular shaped jug. Climb straight up through the large dihedral on jugs and cracks. Dropoff from the jug halfway up the slab, or topout bush-wack style.

name: Moe
description: Sit start in the middle of the boulder matched in a slanted rail. Climb slightly up and left to the most amazing horn jug, then climb up and right to a tricky topout.

name: No Ceilings
description: Start way low and left down in the largest part of the ceilings matched on an undercling. Do a V7 crux right off the bat, then follow the obvious features up and right to another V7 mid way. Finish matched on the last jug before the roof completely blanks out.

name: Bees in the Trap
description: Probably the best V2 at Colls. Center of the highball face on the Bees boulder.

name: Flight of the Moon
description: Sit start and climb the pure crack feature until it blanks out, then do some big moves to establish on the jugs at about 12-15 feet and drop off.

name: Hot Hot Pockets
description: Sit start in pockets, climb short bulge using sidepull pockets to a sloper and topout onto the ledge. Drop off from here.

name: Hotter Pockets
description: super pure line of shallow pockets up a vertical face.

name: Lord Lizardly
description: Sit start and climb the roof encounter arete on compression tufaesque features to an obvious drop off jug.

name: Mutumbo
description: Under an always dry roof, sit start on right sidepull and left gaston with crunched feet. Get up into the sidepull seams and dyno up and right for a bad hold just beneath the roof. Match and drop off, or continue climbing for another 15' up a monster roof with a sketchy landing for a first ascent.

name: Par 3
description: Aesthetic slopey bulge with an obvious and pure sequence.

name: The Donedoozler
description: Under the dirty roof, sit start on left facing jug flake (same as Furious Sky) but this aim right towards a large sloper pocket, finishing with a big move to the jug ledge. Drop off.

name: Furious Sky
description: Sit start on left facing jug flake.  Move up to a bad right hand, then figure out a way to get to the next good holds way up and left. Drop off at jug ledge before dirty roof.

name: Make It Rain
description: One of the few lines actually worth stopping here for. Stand start on good holds. Climb the gently overhanging face well into the scarry zone. Topout at only spot that is cleaned off.

name: The West Wind
description: Right of Donedoozler, awkwardly sit start on two large pockets. Avoiding anything too big and too far to the right, climb straight up and get into the undercling rail. Match in the jug before the roof and dropoff.

name: Deforestation
description: Sit start on bad undercling. Move through a few good incut holds, encounter the buldge, and topout.

name: Iron City
description: Stand start on good holds, follow more good holds to a topout at the point.

name: Meat Grinder
description: Sit start on iron holds. Move up to the only hold on the face, a super sharp knife blade iron crimp, and make a big move to a sharp jug. I know, doesn't sound too fun does it? But it is!

name: Africa
description: Nice easy highball. Low crux after second or third move leads to jugs along a large flake.

name: Bhante Pema
description: The "little black" project has fallen to local legend Joel Brady. Start low with both hands in good underclings. Climb up and right to a good vertical seam, then hit the top and topout.

name: Bindi the Jungle Girl
description: Climb the slab to the right of Croc Hunter (V6).

name: Bloody Hatchet
description: Stand start on the "turtle back rock" with hands on the reach starting pockets. Campus out to the edge of the "hatchet" and then topout on the point.

name: Continental Divide
description: Stand start and finesse your way up a deceptively hard crack feature which doesn't really allow for jamming but requires the use of sloping crimps.

name: Croc Hunter
description: Start low on blunt arete with bad feet. Climb up and left through slopers to the top.

name: Extra Credit
description: Start on a rounded flake and move up to the interesting roof encounter and mantle/pull over it to the slab. Get your extra credit by going all the way to the top.

name: Hide Your Kids
description: Sit start on awkward sharp holds. Bump up to the immaculate iron crimp/pinch hold, and then mantle up onto the somewhat sloping ledge. The topout is easy after standing up on the mantle ledge, but the mantle itself is full value.

name: High and Far Out
description: Climb the dihedral feature to a tricky topout. Fun stemming movements at the beginning culminate in a big reach for a sloper before the topout.

name: Horny
description: Start on the jug to the right of the sassafras tree, and then use jugs on the overhanging face to through over the top of the bulge to get a solid hold (crux) before topping out.

name: Johnny Dunbar
description: Sit start and climb the right side of the striking white gritstone arete.

name: Like the Dickens
description: Start as low as you can on the rail feature under the roof, with a right heel on. Move into crux holds, fire a big shouldery move, try not to dab, then mantle onto face. No topout necessary, just be standing on your feet. Many variations exist on this boulder and will be described in better detail in the future.

name: Lion Turtle
description: Start low on good holds. Climb the tall beautiful face on a series of slopey crimp rails. The aretes are off on both sides, but its still pure.

name: Loreal Pits
description: Start from the same jug Snake starts on, but head straight up through pockets. Topout might be dirty -- it might be best to just drop down after you are fully standing on the slab (judge for yourself)

name: Mic Jagger
description: The low start to Stevie Wonder starts with right hand in a double pocket, left hand on the arete. Slap up blindly to the sloper pockets of Stevie Wonder and topout.

name: Mr. Yuk
description: The description I saw for this problem gives it a V4, but it felt incredibly soft. I'm leaving it as is until others give their input.  Start on the obvious underclings in the middle of the left face. Shoot up and mantel the obvious feature about halfway up the face and then continue the easy face climb to the top.

name: Oatmeal
description: Sit start on your choice of crimps. Move up to bad crimps, use more worse crimps, and hit the top. If you didn't get it by now, you better be good on crimps for this one!

name: Penetrating the Weakness
description: Sit start low on an obvious diagonal rail near a tree and move up and left along the feature to a technical award top out.

name: Pickled Sausage
description: From the pre-guide, "Classic Coll's Cove highball slab! Start of blank face with left foot on a good seam. Keep finding hidden feet till a crux at the top." Trust me, bring a strong mental game for this one, but the immaculate gritstone slab is well worth the reward.

name: Plate Tectonics
description: Hand and fist jams in SW PA? Look no further! Follow the crack up to an easy top out. You probably could find some jugs in or around the crack, but come on... use the hand jams!

name: Reallyreally Good
description: Sit start with left hand on pointy undercling and right wherever. Using the detached boulder to your left for feet, maneuver up the overhanging arete using holds on both sides.

name: Reallyreally Good Direct
description: Start same as normal, but do not use the detached boulder for feet. Makes it harder and a bit awkward, but its still amazing!

name: Sacrilege
description: Start with a good left high sloping rail and a decent right hand side-pull, smear with good feet and then bump up to the juggy arete you will follow to the top.

name: Slander
description: Sit start and work your hands up the slopey feature. The first move is the toughest.

name: Slopey Seconds
description: Start as low as you can on the slopey lip, with a good left hand and right hand under the roof. Get a left heel on and start slappin your way to the point.

name: Snake in the Hand
description: Climb up the left side of the beautiful white slab perched on the sketchy edge. Ideally don't fall, because if you pop too far off then you will plummet another good 10 feet past the small ledge to the ground. Good holds throughout though. This problem provides an awesome view from the copout.

name: The Snake
description: Start with a left heel and hands matched on a jug. Bump over to the right leaning crack feature and continue to climb up it till you can find some ok feet before reaching some positive overhanging jugs towards the top. From there, traverse right until you can top out.

name: South America
description: Climb the blunt aerie that resembles the namesake continent. Start on a good crimp line. Bump to the aerie, and then figure out high feet and the right hand sequence to top out way above your crash pad.

name: Stevie Wonder
description: Start left hand on the lowest sloper on the lip, and right hand on good undercling. Make blind moves up amazing sloper pockets to a casual topout using the left arete.

name: Stingray
description: Sit start on obvious sloping jug. Use crazy core tension to climb the side pull system up and right to the jug of the stand start and finish from there.

name: Stingray Stand
description: Start matched on the L shaped jug flake in the middle of the face. Power up through slopey crimpers to the top and mantle out.

name: The Switch
description: Easy first couple moves up to a mono pocket on the left and a big reach to the top.

name: Thrill of the Chase
description: Start right on a good pinch, and feet in a hard-not-to-dab spot. Move through pinches and crimps to the easier jug haul which leads up and over the point A tall proud line with a bad landing.

name: Thumb Wrestling
description: Sit start matched in vertical seam. Use a variety of techniques to reach the ledge and mantel. Continue to topout.

name: Trailside V3
description: Sit start on the lowest seam. Climb the diagonal seams up the face finding decent footholds as well. Top out, and then down climb left.

name: Triple X
description: Start matched on a jug on the detached block and then make long reaches and balancy moves through the awkward top out.

name: Wheres the Elks
description: Sit start on right side of the boulder with right hand on a small pinch. Move up to a large slopey sidepull, then follow crack feature up and left to the same mantle ledge as Thumb Wrestling. The right arete is off, but you wouldn't use it anyway.

name: White Lightning
description: THE best V2 in the whole boulder field. Stand start low in the white-lined crack feature. Move up through a few jugs, then tech the crux using a variety of small shallow pockets to an easy mantle.

name: White Thunder
description: Same start as White Lightning, move up and traverse across the obvious ledge.  At the end of the traverse, use the pocket to move up and to the right to complete the topout on the far right of the boulder.

name: Try Hard
description: Not many good lines exist all the way back here, but this is probably the best. Climb out a 40 degree roof on edges and slopers to a classic slopey topout.

name: 21 Gun Salute
description: Start under the roof of BB Gun on a rough right hand jug, left crimp, and left foot on a chip facing out of the cave. Climb into the start jug of Sharp Shooter, do the move, then traverse left into Medal of Honor and finish up on that. If you consistently climb 5.13s you might think this is a bit easier..

name: B B Gun
description: The best V3 in this small area. Sit start below Sharp Shooter on the jug rail. Follow the crack feature up and right through a slopey section and topout on good holds.

name: Barracks Traverse
description: A fun techy traverse. Start on left most holds and traverse quality rock to meet up with Basic Training and topout. The obvious jug rail above is off.

name: Basic Training
description: Stand start on some good holds and tech your way through easy climbing to the top out.

name: Blunt Trauma
description: Start with low right hand sidepull, left on slopey arete, and a high right foot. Pull on and slap up the blunt arete to the top.

name: Drafted
description: Get up to the jug rail on your first moves and move right and up around the right side of the bulge overhang.

name: Dreaming of Mussoorie
description: Start on the right side of the obvious overhung golden face. Navigate a few easy moves out left on a crimpy rail and then throw out further left to not-so-great crimps. Hold on, find some insecure feet and power up to the positive lip and mantle your way out of there.(I cleaned this problem up, but didn't get a chance to send it yet. If anyone gets on it before I get back to it, I'll update the FA info and change the name if you want. It's a great looking line on exceptionally beautiful stone. I am speculating about the grade, but think it's pretty accurate. So get after it.)

name: Joint Effort
description: Start matched in juggy pocket. Use the thin seam to your left and slopers to your right to get your weight up onto the slabby face. Stand your way to the top.

name: Medal of Honor
description: Sit start on left biscuit and right on your choice of undercling/sidepull. Make a hard first move to the deceiving jug, then use tiny sloping crimps to reach a slanted top. Using the small detached boulder for your left foot at the topout is legit.

name: PTSD
description: Start same as Sharp Shooter, but use the beautiful crescent feature as a gaston to go way up and left to another gaston. Topout straight up.

name: Sharp Shooter
description: The area's name sake for a reason! Start matched in the jug above BB Gun. Power up to the closest pocket, and continue basically straight up to an easy topout. Very low percentage!

name: Steel City Traverse
description: Start matched on the leftmost side of the thin horizontal flake/edge that cuts across the slightly overhung face. Navigate sharp but positive fingertip edges as you traverse right. You start with some less than decent feet, but they disappear about halfway through so you have to smear and get funky high and wide feet at times. Once the edge/flake disappears power straight up through a wide crack-like feature and top out.

name: Colonel Sanders Arete
description: A mossy arete that is straddled to ascend. Fun, plus the moss shields your hands from the sharpness of the rock

name: Fat Bottomed Girls
description: Fun, Sharp climb on chickenheads that goes up next to "Lightning Strikes Twice" and actually finishes on the same place. It will rip up your hands however, because of some sharp crimps and jugs.

name: Handicap Accessible
description: On the far left edge of the boulder, there is a ramp. Use the iron rails and edge of the boulder to stem against the ramp until you top out.

name: Head of the Basilisk
description: Use the crack (same as Lightning Strikes Twice) for your right hand and the nubbins to the left for your left hand. A lot of smearing for footholds, Work your way up, topping out just to the left of the block on top of the boulder.

name: It's a Triangle
description: Using some pockets and rails for footholds, haul yourself up over the overhanging "triangle", then edge up, using the various rails as you go up, to the top out.

name: Lightning Strikes Twice
description: Follow the Flake up the face of the boulder, smearing for footholds. At the top of the boulder, where the tree is, transition to the chickenheads to the right of the flake for the finish, and top out on to the boulder.

name: Stegosaurus
description: Start pulling a crimp with your right hand and reaching for the first "spine" on the top of the boulder with your left hand. Pull yourself up until both hands are on the top edge of the boulder, using any little nub or ledge possible for foot holds. Edge along the "spines" on top and end on the bug rounded "spine", with a hand on either side of it.

name: 3-D
description: Sit start on a rock to the right slightly down hill of the flakey overhang. Work from this rock (which is in a different plane than the main section) onto the main section and then cling to the flakes with leg and heel hooks to support your weight as you climb the rungs to the top. after you reach the last hold and pull your upper body up as far as you can (with footing or not if you are hardcore :) ) and then hang and drop for completion (landing is on a hill so just be careful)  to top out is difficult and sketchy, no holds beyond the last over hang lip

name: Cha-Cha
description: Feet only. The "mantle" is the crux.

name: The Din of Silence
description: Start matched on a low leaning shelf heel-hooking a lower blunt section of the same feature. Pull up right through positive shelves and decent heel-hooks. Once matched on the obvious large middle shelf throw for a sloper to the middle right of the blunt arete. Find good feet and mantle the top out.

name: Eh Spicy Meatballs
description: Easy problem.  High feet to reach a rock for the topout

name: Handsy Cha-Cha
description: Easy slab boulder.  Cha-Cha with hands

name: My Little Friends
description: Start on the right most jug with your feet on the back side of the cave. Work your hands and feet towards the left and eventually grab the jug in the middle of the boulder. From there, move through several slopers and top out by the left most side of the boulder. The face of the boulder directly right of the start is not in.

name: Rhino Rampage
description: Work hands left from start, far left foothold. Work hands up and right to next crack.  High left heel-toe cam. Left hand to small ledge, right hand to 2 finger pocket. Right foot up to small crack and shift weight over left foot, (crux).  Walking top out.  **Disclaimer**: I have no experience outdoor climbing, so my grade may be off.

name: Side Shuffle
description: Easy traverse with feet on ledge to second crack, and up from there.

name: Silent Rhino's
description: Start the same as Rhino Rampage, but top-out where Din of Silence, The tops out.

name: I saw a groundhog
description: Start on the two crimps, grab the edge and mantle.

name: 5.10 Crack
description: The crux is making it from the ground to the first hand jam.  From here, jam your way to the top.

name: Grillers in the Mist
description: This is a really cool route, and if you like crack climbing, it's worth aiding through the crux just to reach the crack above.   Start by stemming your way up to reach the 2nd bolt.  Make a dyno to a poor hold and then clip the 3rd bolt (crux).  From here head right to the point where the arete meets the crack above.  Follow the crack to the top.  As of 8/10, these are still the original bolts.  The bolt protecting the crux is a spinner, use caution.

name: Unknown, 5.9
description: Climb the steep crack.  It begins to widen toward the top.  The crux is where it gets wide.   Caution:  I've seen a well placed #3 camalot track out when a climber fell at the crux and the red alien below kept his head inches from the ground.   Back this up if you can, the rock is not well traveled and tends to have a fine layer of loose grit on the surface.   Nice climb though, especially if you enjoy cracks.

name: Fun Four
description: Undercling right curving flake, straight to top. One of the old guys from the gym at pitt for places to place a bunch of nuts. From the ground, placement looks suspect. Route is grossly weathered, ie loose.

name: Fun One
description: This is likely the easiest route to the top of this block and would serve as a nice first lead for beginners.  Easy climbing with lots of gear.  Start on the face, just to the left of the arete.  Climb up the face to reach a horizontal and small overhang, traverse right to gain a large stance on the arete.  Climb the short hand crack to the top.

name: Fun Three
description: Short crack to ledge, straight up

name: Fun Two
description: Boulder start between cracks, straight to top

name: Crack Project
description: This crack has not yet seen a clean ascent, however it will go and can be done so on traditional pro.  It's likely 5.12, and on the high side of the grade.  Start at the base of the crack and undercling up to reach a variety of flared hands and finger locks.   Reach the obvious bottle neck slot and follow the flared crack until it tapers.   From here, find horizontals to the top.       Beware, the large rock overhanging this route is not attached.  Do not pull on it!

name: Gagging On The Shag
description: Start at angled letterbox jug, straight up

name: Oriental Lickmaster
description: Overhanging corner on arete.

name: Under Cling Peach
description: Crux is the middle between the two rails. Can be set as a TR after you climb up Way up

name: Way Up
description: Start just to the left of the mossy edge of the arete.   Climb up passing 2 horizontal cracks to reach a nice stance at the base of a short and dirty slab.  Get gear just below the slab, it's the last pro before the top.   Top it out.

name: Can I Touch It
description: Start just behind the large tree and climb up passing a horizontal to reach the first bolt.   Continue climbing up to reach the 2nd bolt.  The crux is the moves above the second bolt.  A small cam can be be placed before reaching the top.

name: I Think I Soloed That
description: Good horizontals up steep face.

name: Never Kissed On the Lips
description: Face up to small tree

name: Pinch Me I'm Dreaming
description: Start by climbing directly up the arete to reach a horizontal on the arete (crux).  Continue up to reach the bolt.  From here, the climbing eases up a bit.  You can get another piece of gear before topping out.   Really nice rock and fun moves!

name: The Amoebob
description: Climb up the slab aiming for the long horizontal crack about 15 feet up.   Place gear here.  Climb up and get a stance to clip the bolt.  Now make a few thin moves and head to the top between a small clearing in the rhodys.   If you like, gear can be placed in a dirty horizontal crack out left just before topping out, but it's really not worth the trouble of fiddling with the placement.       The best descent option is to walk along the top of the block to the right and lower from the shuts above Terror of Tiny Tom.

name: Crack Up
description: Climb the face passing 2 horizontals to reach the obvious crack.  Follow the crack to the top.  If you try Hard Corey and can't pull the crux, you can easily traverse over to the crack on this climb to get to the top.

name: Dead Ringer
description: Climb up passing a few shallow horizontals to reach the flake system.  Follow the flake system to its end.  Gain the short flaring vertical crack and top it out (crux).

name: Hard Corey
description: This is a great route!  Start by climbing up to reach a horizontal.  You can place gear here or make a reach up and clip the 1st bolt.   Continue climbing up passing another horizontal crack and then a slot.  You can place gear in both of these features.   Continue climbing up as the holds begin to thin and clip the 2nd bolt.  Now the crux begins.  Very thin moves to the top on gritstone sloppers.  It's best to try to send this route in cool conditions as the crux is fairly friction dependent.

name: Idiots Rule
description: Most people would only do this route to set up a top rope, as it is the easiest way to gain access to the top.

name: Mr Green Genes
description: Balancey at the top; all friction with no ideal holds

name: Mungo Jelly
description: Start to the right of the arete and climb up passing a few horizontal cracks.  They take great gear.   Continue to reach a stance on the arete, just below the bolt.   Clip the bolt and make a few thin moves to reach the horizontal crack at the top (crux).   Doing the moves above the bolt feels a little committing, however the hardest part is just setting off from the good stance.  Trust the friction!    The best descent option is to walk along the cliff to the right and lower off the new shuts above Terror of Tiny Tom.   You can also bushwack straight back across the top of the block and lower from the chain anchors above Terror of Tiny Tim.

name: Take a Stab
description: This is a nice climb, but somewhat of a hassle to set belay or get back down.   Start at a crack about 10 feet to the left of the obvious flake that is about 15 feet up.   Climb the crack, traverse right to gain the large flake and follow it straight up to the finish.

name: Terror of Tiny Tim
description: This is probably one of the hardest established lines at The Knobs, however there's potential for much harder if someone was motivated.   Start on the overhanging left facing dihedral.  Climb up the dihedral passing the first bolt and keep going to get somewhat of a stance to clip the second bolt.   From here, follow the dihedral as it becomes much less positive and head slightly right aiming for the next horizontal crack (crux).  You can place gear in this horizontal, but you're still only a few feet away from the bolt, but it's recommended because since the route is so steep, a fall doesn't put you more than a body length off the ground.   Continue straight up aiming for the next horizontal.   You can place gear here too.   From the horizontal, head up and left looking for pockets until you can reach the chain anchors.

name: Terror of Tiny Tom
description: Start to the left of the arete and climb up to reach the first bolt.  From here, climb up passing 2 horizontal cracks and then traverse left until below the 2nd bolt.   Place gear anywhere in these horizontal cracks.  Climb up and clip the bolt, then make a few thin moves to reach the top (crux).  The top can be a bit dirty, but the necessary holds are usually clean.

name: Crescent Crack
description: Climb the crescent shaped crack to the top.

name: Easier Done Than Said
description: Climb through the overhang, Finish on the arete and slab above.

name: Heir Rider Equipped
description: Sport route on The Bob Block.  The rating on this route might be a touch soft.  There is a single move crux and the rest of the route is probably only 5.8.  Young Michael did his first drilling on this route, hence the name.

name: High Performance
description: Climb the face 12' left of the corner climb up and get a good cam in the horizontal. Continue up on face holds to the slab above. Clip the two bolts and finish.  Feels like a sandbag at 5.9, especially if you are short.

name: Horizontal Bop
description: Climb the route directly across from The Corner. Use the appropriately spaced horizontals to gain access to the top.

name: The Puzzler
description: Climb the face across the corridor from Snip, Snip, Snip. Follow the route diagonaling left from the base to the top.

name: Brutal Access
description: This used to be a sketchy solo to access Brutal Block.  Now a single bolt allows for safer access.

name: Brutal Orangutan
description: This climb starts on the right side of the arete and moves along a left leaning diagonal to under the roof and then straight up.  Young Adrien got the FFA on this 5.12 as he placed his first piece of gear, ever!

name: Chip Off the Old Rock
description: Climb the thin, pumpy face to the sidepull on the left and a long reach. Finish on slopers at the top.

name: The Face of Reality
description: Start just right of the loose blocky rock in the corner. Climb the face past 2 bolts to the shuts.  Consensus is that this route is a 12a.

name: The Matrix
description: Climb directly under the left side of the roof. Pull the small roof to gain access to the obvious inside corner. Finish on the corner.  Consensus is this is an 11b/c.

name: Project
description: Jump start, rock stack, or climb the maple tree to reach the good edge at the lip of the cave. Climb a short 5.11+ sequence to a break, then use the arete to do a powerful static sequence or just dyno to the top...both sequences are likely around v8. Or....sit start at the back of the cave, trend slightly left, and then boulder through the head-height double digit roof problem, with a couple possible sequences, using tenuous toe hooks and finishing with a giant toss (either left or right) to the good edge at the lip. Drop off and claim the v11 tick or continue up the route and start clipping bolts. You'll definitely want a couple pads and a spot for the boulder.Initial boulder: v11?Route without initial boulder: 5.13b?Boulder into route: 5.13+All three remain projects.

name: Urban Orangutan
description: Start just left of the rear access point of the corridors. Climb up and lunge for the large edge below the arete. Clip the second bolt and work the face and the arete right to get the third bolt and shuts.

name: Vini Vidi Vici
description: Climb the face 8' right of Brutal Orangutan corner. Pass the first bolt and continue to the large horizontal where you can get a gear placement.  Finish by climbing the thin face above with the last bolt and to the shuts.

name: Water Streak
description: Climb the green grungy face past three bolts to the shuts.

name: Green Wall Right
description: Start just left of a rotting stump. Climb up the short technical face to a ledge and the first bolt. Make a move off the ledge passing the second bolt. Move right to the thin face holds and the third bolt, continue up to the shuts.  Like its two neighbors to the left, this route will most likely need brushed some more.

name: Immortal
description: Tricky getting to first bolt, crux at top.  May need brushed.  Very good route that sees little activity.

name: Kiwi Dreams
description: This arete starts with some big moves coming off the ground. Start under the overhang pulling through to gain the arete. The remainder of the route is more chill to the anchors.

name: Last Man Standing
description: Start just 10' left of Lichenville.  This climb was named for Dick Watson, Bob Dodson and Tom Brooks ... all legendary Pittsburgh climbers who have stepped up and been of great help in the recent surge of stewardship in the region.  The three of them together have over 100 years experience climbing in SWPA.  Appropriately enough, all three of them spent a good bit of time helping to clean and drill holes for this particular route.  They all continue to inspire us.    "I don't wanna be the last man standing, on second thought, maybe I do" --Willie Nelson

name: Lichenville
description: Origianly a trad line.  Never saw any activity until bolted in early 2000.  Now a popular route at the Lost Crag.  Near corridor that blows cool air in summer and FRIGID air the rest of the time.  Great on hot days.

name: Lucky Charm
description: This route climbs just to the left of the arete on the right hand side of the face of Bulge Block that is parallel to the trail (#9 in the new guide).  Like it's neighbor, "Puckered Green," misinformation led us to mistakenly put bolts on this route that had been previously climbed on gear.  We have offered to remove the bolts but it appears that they will stay.  For those who want to practice trad, (perhaps with the security of back up bolts?) start under the overhanging right corner of this block.
